window.DV_CORPUS=[{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Qualitative & quantitative data","text":"Before you can analyse anything, you have to know what kind of data you're holding — and why you bothered to collect it. This is the first decision in every data project, and examiners love it because it's the one students rush. Key knowledge: types and purposes of qualitative and quantitative data , including data generated through interactions with digital systems — such as interviews, surveys, sensor data, census or demographic data, time-series data and AI-generated data. The word “including” matters: everything that follows it is examinable. Know each source and be able to say whether it gives you words or numbers, and what job that data does.","id":0},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Qualitative & quantitative data","text":"Meet StepUp — a wellbeing app three Year 11 students built for their school. Every student wears it during the term. It counts steps, asks how people feel, runs focus groups, and even has an “AI coach.” We'll use StepUp the whole way through, because a single app quietly produces every type of data in this dot point . Spot them as we go.","id":1},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Words or numbers?","text":"All data splits into two families. The fastest way to tell them apart is to ask one question: can I count or measure it, or am I describing it?","id":2},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Quantitative NUMBERS","text":"Answers how many , how much , how often Can be added, averaged, ranked and charted Objective and easy to compare at scale Weak at explaining the why behind a number","id":3},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Qualitative WORDS","text":"Answers what kind , why , how does it feel Rich, detailed, captures context and emotion Must be read, grouped and interpreted (coded) Harder to summarise or compare across many people","id":4},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"A memory hook that actually sticks","text":"The N stands for Numbers . If you can do maths with it — sum, average, plot it — it's quantitative. The L stands for Language . If it's words, opinions, descriptions or images, it's qualitative.","id":5},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"The thermometer & the diary","text":"Imagine a friend has a fever. Two tools tell you different things:","id":6},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"The thermometer → quantitative","text":"“38.9 °C.” A precise number you can track over hours, compare to normal, and chart. But it can't tell you they feel miserable.","id":7},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"The diary → qualitative","text":"“Aching all over, couldn't focus, just wanted to sleep.” It captures the human experience the number leaves out — but you can't average it. Neither is “better.” Good data analysis usually combines both : the numbers tell you how much , the words tell you what it means and why . Remember that line — it answers half the exam questions on this dot point.","id":8},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Become the data source","text":"Theory sticks faster when you generate the data yourself. Two quick tasks: count something — you'll produce a number — then describe something — you'll produce words . That's the whole distinction, made by your own hands. Did you feel the difference? Counting forced one exact number . Describing opened up many possible words . That's why the two types answer different questions — and why good analysis usually needs both.","id":9},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Why collect data at all?","text":"The dot point says “types and purposes .” Students remember the types and forget the purposes — then lose marks when a question asks them to justify a choice . Data is collected so an organisation can do one of these jobs:","id":10},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Describe","text":"Capture what is happening right now — a snapshot of users, behaviour or conditions.","id":11},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Compare","text":"Set groups, times or options side by side to see differences.","id":12},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Find patterns","text":"Spot trends, clusters or relationships hiding in the raw data.","id":13},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Explain","text":"Understand the reasons behind a behaviour or result.","id":14},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Predict","text":"Use what's happened to estimate what's likely next.","id":15},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Decide & persuade","text":"Back a recommendation with evidence others will trust.","id":16},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Type follows purpose","text":"Notice the pattern: if the purpose is to compare or predict , you usually want quantitative data you can chart. If the purpose is to explain or understand why , you usually need qualitative data. The purpose chooses the type — not the other way around.","id":17},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Six places data comes from","text":"These are the six sources named in the study design. Tap each to see what it produces inside StepUp, whether it's qualitative or quantitative, and the purpose it serves.","id":18},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Interviews","text":"A researcher asks open questions and follows up on the answers. The result is rich, detailed and personal — and impossible to reduce to a single number.","id":19},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Surveys","text":"The classic trap. A survey can collect both types at once. Closed questions (multiple choice, Likert scales, yes/no) give quantitative data; open questions (“tell us why…”) give qualitative data.","id":20},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Sensor data","text":"Devices measure the physical world and output numbers, continuously and without a human typing anything. Step counters, heart-rate monitors, GPS, temperature probes.","id":21},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Census / demographic data","text":"Structured facts describing who people are — age, year level, location, household size. The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) Census is the national example. Mostly counted and grouped.","id":22},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Time-series data","text":"Not a different kind of number — a different shape . The same value captured at regular intervals (daily, hourly) so you can see how it changes. Time is always one axis.","id":23},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"AI-generated data","text":"An AI model produces new data — a written summary (qualitative), a predicted number (quantitative), or a synthetic dataset. Useful, but it's generated , so it can be biased, wrong or invented. Always treat it with caution. ↪ The quality of all this data — accuracy, bias, reliability — is the next dot point (KK03). Here we only classify it and name its purpose.","id":24},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"The StepUp data stream","text":"Every source feeds the same app. Tap a source — on the buttons or the orbiting node itself — to send its data flowing into StepUp's core. Cool / cube tokens are quantitative ; warm / round tokens are qualitative . Sources that produce both emit a mix.","id":25},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Sort it: words or numbers?","text":"Drag each piece of StepUp data into the right bin — or tap it, then tap a bin on touch screens. Watch the trap cards: a number isn't always quantitative.","id":26},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Key terms","text":"Tap a card to flip it. These are the words examiners expect you to use precisely. Data expressed as numbers — countable or measurable. Answers how many / how much. Data expressed as words, images or descriptions. Answers what kind / why / how it feels. A question with set responses (yes/no, scale, multiple choice). Produces quantitative data. A question inviting a free response in the person's own words. Produces qualitative data. Numeric data generated automatically by hardware measuring the physical world. The same measure captured at regular intervals so change over time can be seen. Structured facts describing a population — age, location, year level, etc. Grouping and labelling free-text responses so qualitative data can be summarised.","id":27},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"“It's a number, so it must be quantitative.”","text":"Not always. A student ID like 047 , a postcode, or a jersey number is a label , not a measurement. If averaging it is meaningless, it's acting as categorical (qualitative-style) data.","id":28},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Treating a survey as one type only.","text":"A survey is a method , not a data type. The same form can collect both — closed questions give numbers, open questions give words.","id":29},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Forgetting the “purposes” half.","text":"The dot point is types and purposes . If a question says “justify” or “explain why,” naming the type alone won't score full marks — you must link it to the job it does.","id":30},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Calling qualitative data “just opinions” / less valid.","text":"Both types are legitimate evidence. Qualitative data is the only way to capture the why . Dismissing it shows a shallow understanding.","id":31},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Trusting AI-generated data automatically.","text":"AI output is generated, not observed. It can be biased, outdated or fabricated. It still counts as data, but it needs verifying.","id":32},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Confusing a Likert scale's feeling with its data.","text":"“Rate your motivation 1–5” is about a feeling, but the data captured is a number — so it's quantitative.","id":33},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"Quick quiz","text":"Instant feedback. No marks counted here — it's a warm-up for the real practice below.","id":34},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure , not length. Use Point · Evidence · Link : state the type, give a concrete example, link it to the purpose. Name the data type clearly. Give a specific example from the scenario. Tie it to the purpose / why it suits the goal. [Point] The team should collect qualitative data. [Evidence] For example, they could run short interviews or use an open survey question asking students to describe what made them stop walking. [Link] Qualitative data is suited to this purpose because it captures the reasons and feelings behind behaviour — the “why” — which a step count or rating alone could never explain.","id":35},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Four questions, 15 marks. Try each one on paper first. Then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide — and mark your own work using the dock in the corner.","id":36},{"file":"u1o1-kk01.html","nav":"u1o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Qualitative & quantitative data","head":"The whole dot point on one screen","text":"Quantitative = numbers you can count/measure (how many, how much). Qualitative = words/descriptions (what kind, why). Type follows purpose. Source Type Best for Interviews Qualitative Understanding why; rich detail Surveys Quant + qual Scale (closed) + ideas (open) Sensor data Quantitative Objective, continuous measurement Census / demographic Quantitative Segmenting & comparing groups Time-series Quantitative Trends and change over time AI-generated Quant + qual Summaries & predictions (verify!) Watch for: numbers used as labels aren't truly quantitative · a survey collects both · always pair type with purpose · AI data needs checking.","id":37},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Characteristics of data types","text":"Every value you store has a type — and the type you choose decides what you're allowed to do with it. Pick the wrong one and your phone numbers lose their leading zeros, your dates become nonsense, and your totals quietly break. Across Victorian schools, students log wildlife sightings into one shared dataset — a spreadsheet that feeds a relational database . Every field forces a data-type decision. We'll use it the whole way through. Field Example value What it really is observer_id 00742 TEXT ID with a leading zero species Eastern Grey Kangaroo TEXT string count_seen INTEGER whole number air_temp_c 14.6 FLOAT decimal sighted_at 2026-03-14 06:48 DATE/TIME expert_confirmed TRUE BOOLEAN yes/no","id":38},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"A data type is defined by what you can do with it","text":"It's tempting to think a data type is just \"what the value looks like\". It isn't. The VCAA glossary defines a data type as the forms data can take, characterised by the kind of operations that can be performed on it . That single idea answers almost every exam question on this dot point.","id":39},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Operations: join, search, slice","text":"You can concatenate (join) strings, search inside them, and pull out characters. You cannot meaningfully add or average them.","id":40},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Operations: + − × ÷, compare","text":"You can do arithmetic, find averages, sort by size and compare magnitudes. Choose this only when the maths actually means something.","id":41},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Operations: AND, OR, NOT","text":"Holds only TRUE or FALSE. Built for logic and filtering — \"show me sightings where expert_confirmed = TRUE \". The same value can be stored differently depending on whether you're in a spreadsheet or a database . The skill VCAA wants is choosing a type that suits both the data and the tool — and being able to justify it with the operations you need.","id":42},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"An analogy: kitchen containers","text":"Think of data types as containers in a kitchen. A measuring jug is built for liquids you'll pour and measure (numeric). A labelled spice jar holds a name you'll read, never pour (text). A light switch is simply on or off (Boolean). You could pour milk into a spice jar — but you've lost the ability to measure it. Choosing a number type for a phone \"number\" is exactly that mistake: it fits, but you've thrown away what made the container useful.","id":43},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The type sorter","text":"Each chip below is a real value from the CritterCount dataset. Send it to a bin and watch what operations that type unlocks. The goal isn't \"which bin will accept it\" — it's \"which bin lets you do the job you need\".","id":44},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Text — character and string","text":"Text data is stored as characters. The study design names two forms:","id":45},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Character (char)","text":"A single symbol — one letter, digit, or punctuation mark. In CritterCount, a size_band field might store S , M or L — exactly one character.","id":46},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"String","text":"A sequence of characters of any length — words, sentences, codes. species = \"Eastern Grey Kangaroo\" is a string. Most real-world text is a string. CritterCount gives every observer an ID like 00742 . Phone numbers, postcodes and member IDs are the same. They look like numbers but you never add them — and storing them as numeric silently deletes the leading zero, turning 00742 into 742 . Rule: if the \"number\" isn't used in calculations — phone, postcode, ID, ABN — store it as text/string . The interactive below makes the zero physically fall off.","id":47},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Numeric — integer, floating point, date/time","text":"Numeric types are for values you'll actually do maths with. The study design lists three sub-types.","id":48},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Integer","text":"Whole numbers, no decimal point. count_seen = 7 . You can't see half a kangaroo, so a count is an integer.","id":49},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Floating point","text":"Numbers with a decimal fraction. air_temp_c = 14.6 , or a GPS latitude like -37.8136 . Use it whenever precision below 1 matters.","id":50},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Date/time","text":"A special numeric type. sighted_at is stored as a number under the hood, so you can sort chronologically and subtract two dates to get a duration. If you stored 14/03/2026 as plain text, sorting would put 14/03 before 2/04 alphabetically — wrong order. A real date/time type stores it as a number, so \"earliest first\" actually works and you can calculate \"days since first sighting\".","id":51},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Boolean — true or false, nothing else","text":"A Boolean holds one of exactly two values: TRUE or FALSE (sometimes shown as Yes/No, 1/0, or a tick-box). In CritterCount, expert_confirmed is Boolean — a sighting either has been verified or it hasn't. Why not just store the word \"yes\" as text? Because Boolean unlocks logical operations . You can filter WHERE expert_confirmed = TRUE , combine conditions with AND/OR, and count flagged records instantly. Text \"yes\"/\"Yes\"/\"y\"/\"YES\" would be inconsistent and far harder to filter reliably. If a question can only ever be answered yes or no — \"Is it nocturnal?\", \"Was a photo attached?\", \"Confirmed?\" — it's a Boolean. The moment a third option appears (\"maybe\", \"pending\"), it's no longer Boolean.","id":52},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The same value, matched to the chosen software tool","text":"This dot point specifically says data types are matched to the chosen software tools . A spreadsheet and a relational database name their types differently, even for the same value. Knowing the mapping is worth marks. CritterCount value Generic type In a spreadsheet (Excel/Sheets) In a database (Access/SQL) Eastern Grey Kangaroo TEXT Text format Short Text / VARCHAR 00742 TEXT Text format (or value forced text) Short Text INTEGER Number (0 decimals) Number / INTEGER 14.6 FLOAT Number (decimals) Number (Double) / FLOAT 2026-03-14 06:48 DATE/TIME Date/Time format Date/Time TRUE BOOLEAN Boolean (TRUE/FALSE) or checkbox Yes/No (Boolean) If a question names a tool (\"…in the spreadsheet\" or \"…in the database\"), use that tool's type names and justify the choice by the operations the data needs. Don't just say \"number\" — say \"Number formatted with no decimal places, because counts are whole values that will be summed\" .","id":53},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Number or text? Make the call","text":"For each CritterCount field, decide whether it should be stored as a number or as text . The test is always the same: will you do arithmetic with it? If not, it's text — even when it's made of digits.","id":54},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Calling everything made of digits a \"number\"","text":"Phone, postcode, observer ID, ABN, credit-card — digits, but never added. Store as text/string to keep leading zeros and full length.","id":55},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Giving no example","text":"The 2023 report noted students lost higher marks because they stated the rule but gave no concrete example . Always anchor with one: \"e.g. a phone number 0431… loses its leading zero\".","id":56},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Confusing character with string","text":"A character is exactly one symbol; a string is many. A size band M is a character; the species name is a string.","id":57},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Storing dates as text","text":"Text dates sort alphabetically and can't be subtracted. Use a real date/time type so chronological sorting and date arithmetic work.","id":58},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Defining a type by its appearance, not its operations","text":"\"A number is something with digits\" earns little. Define by the operations allowed — that's the glossary definition and the mark-winning angle.","id":59},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Ignoring the named software tool","text":"If the question says spreadsheet or database, use that tool's type names (Short Text, Number, Yes/No), not generic words alone.","id":60},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"For any \"justify the data type\" question, structure the answer as Point → Evidence → Link . It forces in the example examiners reward.","id":61},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Name the type + tool format","text":"\"Store observer_id as text (Short Text in the database) .\"","id":62},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Operations + example","text":"\"IDs are never used in calculations, and a numeric type would drop the leading zero — e.g. 00742 would become 742 .\"","id":63},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Back to the requirement","text":"\"So every ID stays complete and unique, which the matching of observers to sightings depends on.\" \"Store observer_id as text. IDs aren't used in calculations and a numeric type would drop the leading zero (00742 → 742), so storing it as text keeps every ID complete and unique for matching records.\" — that's a full-mark justify response in three sentences.","id":64},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Practice questions","text":"SAC/exam-style questions in VCAA command-word style. Try each in your head or on paper, then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide. Award yourself marks — the dial bottom-right tracks your total. (Units 1 & 2 are school-assessed, so these mirror the style your teacher will use.) Define the term data type and give one example of a data type. CritterCount stores each observer's mobile number, e.g. 0431 251 902 . Justify the most appropriate data type for this field. Distinguish between the character and string data types, using a CritterCount field for each.","id":65},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Practice questions","text":"The CritterCount team will record count_seen , air_temp_c , sighted_at and expert_confirmed in their spreadsheet . State the most appropriate data type for each and briefly say why. A teammate argues \"we should just store everything as text — it never breaks.\" Explain two problems this would cause for CritterCount's analysis, referring to specific fields. Total available: 15 marks . Be honest with the marking guides — examiners reward the named example and the lost operation, not just the right type word.","id":66},{"file":"u1o1-kk02.html","nav":"u1o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Recap","text":"A data type is defined by the operations you can perform on it — not by how the value looks. Text : character (one symbol) and string (many). For values you read, join or search — never add. Numeric : integer (whole), floating point (decimal), date/time (numeric under the hood). For values you calculate, compare or sort. Boolean : TRUE/FALSE only, for logical filtering. Match the type to the software tool (spreadsheet vs database) and use that tool's type names. The big trap: digit-strings you never calculate with (phone, postcode, ID) are text — numeric drops leading zeros. In a justify , always give a concrete example . It's the difference between mid and full marks.","id":67},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"The quality of data & information","text":"A data visualisation is only ever as trustworthy as the data underneath it. This module unpacks the five factors VCAA uses to judge that trust — accuracy , bias , integrity , relevance and reliability — and the sub-factors hiding inside one of them. Ava , a Year 11 student, is building a data visualisation for the Student Representative Council. The question: “How do students actually want to use the courtyard at lunchtime?” She runs an online survey and pulls in some secondary data — canteen till sales, library logins, the weather. Every quality factor in this module shows up somewhere in Ava’s project, so each idea has a concrete home.","id":68},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Quality data → quality information","text":"The study design separates two words on purpose. Data is the raw, unprocessed facts Ava collects — 147 , \"basketball\" , TRUE . Information is what those facts mean once they’re organised, analysed and presented — “most Year 9s want the courtyard for ball sports.” The visualisation is information; the survey responses are data. Here’s the catch examiners love: you cannot fix bad data with good presentation. A beautiful chart built on rubbish numbers is a beautiful, convincing lie. Quality has to be protected at the data stage, before it ever becomes information.","id":69},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Quality data → quality information","text":"Data is your ingredients; information is the finished dish. A brilliant chef cannot rescue a meal made from spoiled ingredients — they can only plate the spoilage attractively. Programmers say the same thing more bluntly: garbage in, garbage out (GIGO) . VCAA assesses quality against five named factors. They overlap a little in real life, but in an exam you’re expected to name them, define them, and apply them to a scenario — so we’ll treat each one precisely.","id":70},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"What makes data trustworthy","text":"Tap a card to flip it. The front gives the exam definition; the back shows how the factor plays out in Ava’s PulseCheck data and how she’d check or improve it.","id":71},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Accuracy","text":"A student types their year level as 91 instead of 9.","id":72},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Bias","text":"The survey only reached the basketball team's group chat.","id":73},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Integrity","text":"Rows get duplicated when copied into the spreadsheet.","id":74},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Reliability","text":"Two hand-counts of the same recess differ by 40. Read the first letters as a question you ask of any dataset: A·B·I·R·R — “ Are Biases In Records Real? ” It’s clunky on purpose, which is exactly why it sticks. Accuracy, Bias, Integrity, Relevance, Reliability.","id":75},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Accuracy is not reliability","text":"Students lose marks every year by treating these as synonyms. They’re not. Accuracy means data is close to the true value . Reliability means data is consistent and repeatable — you’d get the same result again. A measurement can be one without the other. Picture darts on a target. Hitting the bullseye every time is accurate and reliable . A tight cluster in the top corner is reliable but not accurate — consistent, but consistently wrong (that’s a systematic error, often bias ). Darts scattered around the bullseye are accurate-ish on average but not reliable .","id":76},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Accuracy is not reliability","text":"All over the board is neither. Use the buttons to throw each pattern. “Ava’s hand-tally of courtyard users was reliable — she always counted the same way — but not accurate , because she stood too far away and consistently undercounted by about ten. Reliable data can still be systematically wrong.”","id":77},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Inside data integrity","text":"Integrity means the data has been maintained and kept intact and unaltered across its whole life — from the moment it’s collected, through storage, all the way to the visualisation. If a value gets corrupted, duplicated, or quietly edited along the way, integrity is broken even if every other factor looks fine. Think of how a courtroom treats evidence: it’s logged, sealed, and tracked so nobody can tamper with it between the crime scene and the trial. Data integrity is the same unbroken chain — from Ava’s survey form, into the spreadsheet, into the chart.","id":78},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Inside data integrity","text":"One unsealed link and the whole conclusion is doubtful. Here’s the part that trips people up — and it’s a documented exam weakness. The study design lists its own set of factors for integrity specifically , and it is not the same as the five quality factors. The integrity sub-factors are: Quality of data & information = accuracy, bias, integrity, relevance, reliability (5) . Integrity of data = accuracy, authenticity, correctness, reasonableness, relevance, timeliness (6) . A past VCAA multiple-choice question hinged on spotting that “completeness” is not an integrity factor.","id":79},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Inside data integrity","text":"Note the two overlaps that examiners exploit: accuracy and relevance appear in both lists. Integrity sub-factor Breaks in PulseCheck when… How Ava protects it Accuracy A student fat-fingers their year level as 91 instead of 9 . Range validation on entry (7–12). Authenticity A prank account fills the survey pretending to be staff. School-login (SSO) gated form. Correctness A date arrives as 13/30/2026 . Type / format checking on the field. Reasonableness “Hours in courtyard per week” comes back as 200 . Sanity bounds + flag outliers. Relevance She also collected favourite colour — useless to the question. Drop fields that don’t serve the aim. Timeliness She reuses last year’s survey after the courtyard was rebuilt. Collect current data each time.","id":80},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Spot the quality problem","text":"Each card describes something that went wrong in a PulseCheck-style project. Drag it into the quality factor it most directly damages. Some are deliberately close calls — that’s where the marks live.","id":81},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Exam traps, collected","text":"Five quality factors (A·B·I·R·R) vs six integrity factors (accuracy, authenticity, correctness, reasonableness, relevance, timeliness). “Completeness” belongs to neither official list. Keep them in separate boxes in your head. Accurate = close to true. Reliable = consistent / repeatable. Always give an example of the gap (a scale that’s always 5 kg over is reliable but not accurate) — examples are where the second mark hides. Bias means the data is systematically skewed by how it was collected — e.g. only sharing the survey in the basketball team chat. Don’t define it as “someone being unfair.” Name the source of the skew.","id":82},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Exam traps, collected","text":"This dot point is the quality of data (trustworthiness). The next one — characteristics of data & information (size, structure, accessibility, clarity, context) — is different. If a question says “quality,” answer with A·B·I·R·R. A documented examiner note: criteria or explanations written as a single word score zero. A quality criterion must be a measurable statement — “at least 90% of survey records fall within the valid year-level range (7–12),” not just “accurate.”","id":83},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong extended responses follow Point → Evidence → Link : name the factor, ground it in the scenario, then connect it back to what the question actually asked. Write a response below and watch the meters react to the moves examiners reward.","id":84},{"file":"u1o1-kk03.html","nav":"u1o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The quality of data & information","head":"Practice questions","text":"Attempt each in your notebook first, then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide. Mark yourself honestly — the dock bottom-right keeps your running total. Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · U1·O1 Data Analysis · KK03 — Quality of data & information Aligned to the VCAA VCE Applied Computing Study Design 2025–2028 · Single-file, fully offline · en-AU","id":85},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Characteristics of data & information","text":"Six properties decide whether a dataset is actually fit for the job : size, structure, relevance, accessibility, clarity and context . Get them right and raw data becomes useful information. Get them wrong and even \"correct\" data is useless. Maya , a Year 11 student at Riverbend Secondary College, exports a full year of her music-listening history from her streaming app. She wants to turn it into an infographic — \"My Year in Sound\" — for a Data Analysis task. The export is a giant file of play events: timestamps, track names, artists, genres, how many milliseconds she listened, the device she used, and whether she skipped.","id":86},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Characteristics of data & information","text":"Every characteristic in this module is something Maya has to judge before she can trust her data. We'll follow her file all the way through.","id":87},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"First: data is not information","text":"You cannot describe the characteristics of \"data and information\" until you can tell the two apart. The study design lists them together for a reason — context is the bridge between them.","id":88},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Data","text":"Raw, unprocessed facts and figures with no meaning on their own. A value, a string, a timestamp. 237411 is data. So is \"Skip\" .","id":89},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Information","text":"Data that has been processed, organised and given context so it answers a question and supports a decision. \"You listened for 4 hrs less in winter\" is information. Try it. Below is a raw value from Maya's export. Add context and watch data become information:","id":90},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"The six characteristics — see each one","text":"Click each characteristic. Maya's dataset (the cube cloud) transforms to show what that property actually does to data. One concept, one visual, every time. Now the detail — definition, what it looks like in Maya's SoundCheck file, and the question each one answers:","id":91},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Structure: the three states of data","text":"Structure is the characteristic students lose the most marks on, because it has named categories examiners expect you to use: State What it means In Maya's file Structured Organised into a fixed model — rows, columns, defined data types. Easy to sort, filter, query. The play-events table: timestamp · track · artist · genre · ms_played . Semi-structured Has some organising tags or markers but no rigid table — e.g. JSON or tagged fields. The raw JSON the app actually exports before Maya converts it to a spreadsheet. Unstructured No predefined model — free text, images, audio. Powerful but hard to analyse with formulas. A free-text review Maya typed for some tracks: \"loved this one, summer vibes\".","id":92},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"The \"relevance\" trap: KK03 vs KK04","text":"Relevance appears in both dot points, and so does the word \"information\". Students mix them up under exam pressure. They are different lists answering different questions: KK03 · Quality KK04 · Characteristics Asks Can I trust this data? Is this data usable / fit for purpose ? The list accuracy · bias · integrity · relevance · reliability size · structure · relevance · accessibility · clarity · context Mindset Trustworthiness & correctness Shape, usability & meaning Memory hook: quality is about whether the data is right; characteristics are about whether the data is right for you .","id":93},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Sort the situations","text":"Each card describes something that went wrong (or right) with Maya's data. Drag it to the characteristic it best demonstrates. On a touchscreen, tap a card then tap a zone.","id":94},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"How to write a characteristics answer: P · E · L","text":"Extended-response marks are lost when students name a characteristic but never connect it to the scenario. Use P·E·L for every characteristic you discuss:","id":95},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"Common exam traps","text":"✕ Listing quality factors (accuracy, bias, reliability) when asked for characteristics . Wrong list. ✕ Defining a characteristic but never linking it to the scenario — that's the missing mark almost every time. ✕ Treating size as \"always more is better\". Too much data is slow and noisy; too little is unrepresentative. Describe the effect both ways. ✕ Confusing accessibility (can the right people get and use it?) with security (keeping the wrong people out). They pull in opposite directions. ✕ Saying data \"is information\". Until it is processed and given context , it is only data. ✕ Mixing up clarity (is it understandable?) with accuracy (is it correct?). Data can be perfectly clear and still wrong.","id":96},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide . Then self-mark — your score updates the dial in the corner. 1 mark: a definition that links context to the circumstances/meaning that make data usable. “Background” alone is too vague — it must convey that context provides meaning . 1 mark: correct distinction (data = raw/unprocessed facts; information = processed + given context/meaning). 1 mark: a valid example of each drawn from the scenario. Size is not the difference — that's a common error. 1 mark: a valid benefit of large size tied to the scenario (representativeness / reliable patterns).","id":97},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 mark: a valid drawback (performance / handling / noise). “More is always better” scores 0 — size has trade-offs in both directions. Up to 2 marks per characteristic: 1 for correctly naming + defining a KK04 characteristic, 1 for an effect on the visualisation tied to the scenario. Must be characteristics (structure, relevance, accessibility, clarity, context) — the weak answer used quality factors (accuracy, reliability) and earns no marks here. Two characteristics required; a single very detailed one caps at 2. 1 mark: defines relevance as how closely data relates to the purpose/question.","id":98},{"file":"u1o1-kk04.html","nav":"u1o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Characteristics of data & information","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 mark: applies it — identifies relevant vs irrelevant fields in the scenario. 1 mark: explains the consequence of including irrelevant data (noise / cluttered or misleading visualisation). 2 marks per problem, to a maximum of 4: 1 for identifying a problem tied to the named characteristic, 1 for a sensible way to address it. Answer must use the named characteristics (accessibility, structure, clarity), not generic “PDFs are bad”. A clear address/solution is required for each problem to score the second mark.","id":99},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Australian Privacy Principles","text":"When someone hands you their personal data, you don't own it — you hold it in trust . The Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) sets out 13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) that say how organisations must handle that trust. Your study design zooms in on three of them. Drag the scene to explore. Three duties orbit the data you're protecting: non-identification (APP 2), primary purpose (APP 6) and security (APP 11).","id":100},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"You're not just crunching numbers — you're handling people","text":"In this outcome you collect, manage and communicate data to build a visualisation. The moment your dataset contains anything that can be tied back to a real person — a name, a student ID, a survey response, a photo, even a postcode plus a birthday — it becomes personal information , and the law has something to say about how you treat it. That's why the APPs live right here, next to data types and data quality. A brilliant dashboard built on data you collected unlawfully isn't a good solution — it's a liability. The exam expects you to apply the three named APPs to the acquisition , management and communication of data, not just recite them.","id":101},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Acquisition","text":"How you collect the data. Do you need to identify people at all? (APP 2)","id":102},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Management","text":"How you use and store it. Only for the purpose you collected it for (APP 6), and kept secure (APP 11).","id":103},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Communication","text":"How you share or publish findings. Don't disclose beyond the original purpose; protect it in transit (APP 6 & 11).","id":104},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"The Privacy Act 1988 and the 13 APPs","text":"The Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) is the federal law that protects the personal information of individuals. It contains 13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) — a single set of rules covering the whole life-cycle of personal information: how it's collected, how it can be used and disclosed, how it must be kept accurate and secure, and a person's right to access it. The Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC) regulates it. You don't need all 13. The study design names three , one for each stage of the data life-cycle:","id":105},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"The Privacy Act 1988 and the 13 APPs","text":"APP Plain-English name The one-line rule PulseCheck question it answers APP 2 Non-identification (anonymity & pseudonymity) People must have the option of dealing with you anonymously or under a pseudonym, where practical. Do we actually need the student's name on the survey? APP 6 Primary purpose (use or disclosure) Information collected for one purpose can only be used or disclosed for that purpose, unless an exception applies. Can we hand the stress answers to the year-level coordinator? APP 11 Security (of personal information) Take reasonable steps to protect the information from misuse, loss and unauthorised access — and destroy/de-identify it when no longer needed. Where is the spreadsheet stored, and who can open it?","id":106},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"You are a custodian, not an owner","text":"Here's the mental model that makes the APPs click. Think of personal information like a coat handed to a cloakroom . APP 2 — the masked guest. A guest can attend the event wearing a mask. If the cloakroom doesn't need to know who they are to do its job, it shouldn't demand a name. Collect identity only when you truly need it. APP 6 — the coat is for collecting, not wearing. You handed your coat in for one purpose: to get it back later. The cloakroom can't wear it, lend it to a friend, or sell its details to a tailor.","id":107},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"You are a custodian, not an owner","text":"Data collected for one purpose can't be quietly repurposed. APP 11 — the locked back room. While the coat is in their care, it must be kept in a secure room — not left on the front counter for anyone to grab. Reasonable steps to protect what you hold. Carry this through the whole module: a good custodian takes only what they need, uses it only for the agreed job, and guards it while it's in their care.","id":108},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Non-identification — anonymity & pseudonymity","text":"APP 2 gives individuals the option of not identifying themselves , or using a pseudonym (a made-up name or code), when dealing with an organisation — wherever it is lawful and practical . The default question a custodian should ask is: \"Do I actually need to know who this is to do the job?\" Often, the answer is no.","id":109},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"The survey doesn't need names","text":"PulseCheck is about patterns across the year level — average sleep, the spread of screen-time, how stress trends by week. None of that needs Jordan's name attached. So the form collects anonymous responses, or at most a pseudonym/code (e.g. \"respondent 042\") if you need to let someone update their own entry.","id":110},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Anonymous vs pseudonymous — don't blur them","text":"Term What it means PulseCheck example Anonymous No identifier is collected at all. Nobody — not even you — can link the response to a person. A paper drop-box survey with no name field. Pseudonymous A code or fake name stands in for the real identity. The data isn't directly named, but a re-identification key could exist. \"Respondent 042\" — with a separate, secured list mapping codes to students so they can edit answers.","id":111},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Primary purpose — use or disclosure","text":"APP 6 says personal information collected for a particular primary purpose may only be used or disclosed for that purpose — unless an exception applies. The primary purpose is the main reason you collected it in the first place . Using it for anything else is a secondary purpose , and that needs justification.","id":112},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"What you may do","text":"PulseCheck's primary purpose is building a wellbeing visualisation for the assembly . Calculating averages, charting screen-time, and presenting de-identified trends all serve that purpose. Green light.","id":113},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"What needs an exception","text":"Handing the raw \"I feel stressed every day\" responses to the year-level coordinator to follow up individual students is a different purpose . It may be defensible, but only via an APP 6 exception — not by default.","id":114},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"The exceptions you can cite","text":"A secondary use/disclosure is allowed when, broadly: Exception Meaning PulseCheck angle Consent The person agreed to the new use. The form said \"results may be shared with wellbeing staff\" and students opted in. Reasonable expectation The secondary purpose is related to the first and the person would reasonably expect it. Showing the chart to the same assembly audience it was always for. Required/authorised by law A law compels the disclosure. A court order — rare in a class project. Serious threat Needed to lessen a serious threat to life, health or safety. A response disclosing immediate danger may be escalated to protect that student.","id":115},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Security of personal information","text":"APP 11 requires an organisation to take reasonable steps to protect personal information from misuse, interference and loss , and from unauthorised access, modification or disclosure . It also says: when you no longer need the information, take reasonable steps to destroy it or de-identify it .","id":116},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Where does the spreadsheet live?","text":"\"Reasonable steps\" scales with how sensitive the data is. PulseCheck stress data is sensitive, so reasonable steps might include: storing the file in the school's access-controlled drive (not a shared USB), using strong passwords / MFA , limiting who can open it, encrypting if exported, and deleting the raw responses after the assembly once only the de-identified chart is needed.","id":117},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Physical","text":"Locked rooms, devices not left unattended, secure disposal of printouts.","id":118},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Software","text":"Passwords/MFA, access permissions, encryption , up-to-date anti-malware, backups.","id":119},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Procedural","text":"Who's allowed to access, training, a routine to delete data once it's no longer needed.","id":120},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"The Custodian's Desk","text":"A PulseCheck response just arrived at your desk. Make three custodian decisions and watch the privacy outcome respond live. The 3D shield around the data strengthens or cracks with each choice. Aim for all three duties green . Notice that each duty is independent : you can collect perfectly (anonymous) but still fail by selling the data (APP 6) or leaving it in a public folder (APP 11). Compliance is the weakest link, not an average.","id":121},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Which APP is at stake?","text":"Drag (or tap, then tap a bin) each scenario into the principle it relates to most. Some are deliberately tricky — one is a distractor that isn't really about these three APPs at all.","id":122},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Named exam traps","text":"These are the specific mistakes that cost marks on APP questions. Learn them as a checklist.","id":123},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Build a full-mark answer with P·E·L","text":"VCAA rewards structured legal reasoning. Use P·E·L : name the Principle , give the Example from the scenario, then state the Link back to the question. Try it below — the checklist lights up as your answer hits each element. Prompt: \"PulseCheck plans to email the full list of named survey responses to a local gym that sponsored the project. Referring to one Australian Privacy Principle, explain why this is a problem.\" (3 marks) This breaches APP 6 (use or disclosure) of the Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) [Principle] . The responses were collected for the primary purpose of building a wellbeing visualisation for a school assembly;","id":124},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Build a full-mark answer with P·E·L","text":"sending named responses to a sponsoring gym is a secondary purpose the students did not consent to and would not reasonably expect [Example] . Because no APP 6 exception applies, disclosing the data this way is not permitted and PulseCheck must either obtain consent or only share de-identified results [Link] .","id":125},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Five questions, 19 marks total, climbing from define to evaluate . For each: try it, then reveal a weak response (with why it loses marks), a strong response, and the marking guide . Self-mark honestly — it feeds the score dial. \"It protects your privacy on the internet.\" → Too vague; doesn't say whose information or what kind , names no principles, and wrongly limits it to \"the internet\". 0–1 marks. \"The Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) protects the personal information of individuals — data that identifies or could identify a person.","id":126},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"It contains the 13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) , which set out how organisations must collect, use, secure and disclose that information.\" 1 mark — identifies it protects personal information of individuals . 1 mark — names the Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) (accept \"13 APPs\"). \"They shouldn't ask for your name because of privacy.\" → Names no principle, no reasoning about whether identification is needed , no remedy. 1 mark at most. APP 2 (anonymity & pseudonymity) gives users the option to deal with an organisation anonymously or under a pseudonym where lawful and practical.","id":127},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Viewing a public library doesn't require identifying the user, so demanding a full legal name is unnecessary. The app should let users browse anonymously (or with an optional pseudonym/account) and only request identity when a feature genuinely needs it. 1 — names APP 2 / the anonymity-pseudonymity option. 1 — reasons that identification is not necessary/practical for browsing a public library. 1 — states the remedy: allow anonymous/pseudonymous access. \"No, that's spam and it's against the law.\" → Right instinct, no APP 6 reasoning, no primary/secondary purpose language, and no condition given.","id":128},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Caps low. Under APP 6 , personal information may only be used or disclosed for the primary purpose it was collected for. The emails were collected to send report cards , so using them to advertise the fete is a secondary purpose . Parents may not reasonably expect marketing from a report-card list, so by default this is not allowed . It would become permissible if the school obtained the parents' consent for promotional emails (or the use fell within another APP 6 exception, such as a related purpose the parents would reasonably expect).","id":129},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 — identifies the primary purpose (report cards). 1 — labels the marketing use as a secondary purpose . 1 — concludes it is not allowed by default under APP 6. 1 — gives a valid condition ( consent / reasonable-expectation exception). \"Use a password and don't lose the file.\" → One generic step, no justification, no mention of access control or disposal. Reads as a list, not reasoning. Step 1 — store on an access-controlled drive with MFA: because stress data is sensitive, limiting access to the project team with multi-factor authentication reduces the risk of unauthorised access , a core APP 11 requirement.","id":130},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Step 2 — delete the raw coded responses after the assembly: APP 11 requires destroying or de-identifying information once it's no longer needed ; keeping sensitive stress data beyond the project's purpose creates ongoing, unnecessary risk. 1+1 — two valid, distinct reasonable steps (access control/MFA, encryption, restricted sharing, secure disposal…). 1+1 — each step justified against sensitivity/context (not just stated). Award the disposal point only if it links to \"no longer needed\". \"Yes, because no names means no privacy problem.\" → Accepts the claim uncritically, ignores re-identification, says nothing about APP 6 or 11, no judgement weighed.","id":131},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Evaluate = weigh both sides. Removing the name column helps with APP 2 , reducing direct identification, but it is not sufficient . Under APP 2 , combined fields (year level, team, suburb) can re-identify individuals, so the data may not be truly anonymous. The claim also ignores APP 6 : privacy obligations cover how the data is used and disclosed , not just publication — if the raw responses were repurposed or shared beyond the assembly, that's a breach regardless of the name column. Finally, APP 11 obligations continue for the stored raw data:","id":132},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"it must be secured and then destroyed when no longer needed. Overall , the claim is overstated — de-identification is one part of meeting APP 2, but full compliance also depends on lawful use (APP 6) and ongoing security and disposal (APP 11). 1 — credits that name-removal partly addresses APP 2 . 1 — challenges it via re-identification risk. 1–2 — explains APP 6 still applies (use/disclosure beyond publication). 1 — explains APP 11 (security + disposal of stored raw data) still applies. 1 — reaches a weighed judgement that the claim is overstated. (Top band needs all three APPs + a clear verdict.)","id":133},{"file":"u1o1-kk05.html","nav":"u1o1-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Australian Privacy Principles","head":"Five-card recap","text":"That single sentence, plus a scenario-specific example for each principle, is a confident full-mark spine for any APP question in this outcome.","id":134},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Ethical issues around data & information","text":"Data isn't just numbers in a spreadsheet — it's people . This dotpoint is about the line between what you can do with data and what you should do. Ethical issues that arise from the acquisition, storage, analysis and communication of data and information, including : transparency; inaccurate or incomplete data; ownership and control of data and information; the misuse of personal data; and the repurposing and sharing of data and information by artificial intelligence. In VCAA language, including means every item that follows is examinable. So all five issues above are fair game — and the AI one is the one students most often forget. Learn all five by name.","id":135},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Your running scenario: PulseCheck","text":"You and three classmates run PulseCheck , a Year 11 wellbeing project. You survey 200 students about their sleep, stress, screen time and mood , then analyse the responses and build visualisations to present to staff. It feels harmless — until you realise you're holding 200 people's private feelings in one spreadsheet. Every ethical issue in this module shows up in PulseCheck. We'll use it the whole way through.","id":136},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Data vs information — quick reset","text":"Data is the raw stuff you collect (a student ticks \"3 hours sleep\"). Information is what you get after analysis gives it meaning (\"Year 11 students average 5.8 hours sleep on school nights — well below the recommended 8–10\"). Ethical issues live at both ends: how you gathered the raw data, and what you do with the information you produce.","id":137},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Legal is the floor. Ethical is the ceiling.","text":"This is the single idea examiners reward most — and the one weak answers miss. Legal means \"the law allows it.\" Ethical means \"it's the right thing to do.\" They overlap, but they are not the same question. In Unit 1 you study the Australian Privacy Principles (KK05) — that's the law . KK06 sits one level up: even when the Privacy Act permits something, you still have to ask \"should we?\" Use this 2×2 to keep them apart: You ask for consent, explain the purpose, anonymise results, store data securely and delete it when done.","id":138},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Legal is the floor. Ethical is the ceiling.","text":"PulseCheck done right. The fine print technically lets you reuse the wellbeing data to rank students — but it's not what anyone expected or agreed to. Where most exam questions live. Leaking that the data was being secretly sold, to protect students — breaks a rule, but defends people. Whistleblowing tension. Selling identifiable student mental-health data to an advertiser without consent. Wrong on every count. If a question uses the word ethical , do not answer \"because it breaks the Privacy Act.\" That's a legal answer. Talk about fairness, honesty, harm to people, trust and consent — the should , not the allowed .","id":139},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Five ways to interrogate any dataset","text":"Think of each ethical issue as a lens you hold up to a dataset. The same PulseCheck spreadsheet looks different through each one. Tap a lens below (or click a ring in the scene) to focus it.","id":140},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Transparency","text":"Transparency means people can see and understand what's happening to their data: what you're collecting, the purpose, where it's stored, who sees it, and how your analysis turned their answers into a conclusion. The opposite is a \"black box\" — data goes in, claims come out, and no one can check the working. For a data analyst, transparency also covers your visualisations . A chart with a chopped-off axis or a cherry-picked date range can be technically \"true\" yet deeply misleading. Hiding your method is a transparency failure even if every number is real.","id":141},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Transparency","text":"Privacy is about keeping data from the wrong eyes . Transparency is about being honest with the right people — the ones whose data it is. You can be private and still sneaky.","id":142},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Inaccurate or incomplete data","text":"There's a quality side to this (that's KK03) and an ethical side (that's KK06). The ethical problem is what happens when you present shaky data as if it were solid , and real people get judged or affected by a conclusion that the data can't actually support. Inaccurate = the values are wrong (typos, jokes, lies, broken sensors). Incomplete = there are holes (people skipped questions, only some groups replied, the sample is too small to represent everyone). Either way, the information you build on top is untrustworthy — but a slick chart can hide that completely.","id":143},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Ownership and control of data & information","text":"Ownership asks: whose data is this? Control asks: who gets to decide what happens to it? These come apart all the time. The student feels their survey answer is theirs — but the organisation that collected and stored it may be the one holding the keys. That tension is the ethical issue. Good practice gives people meaningful control: the right to see their own data, correct it, withdraw it, and have it deleted. The questions to ask: Can a participant pull their data back out? Who keeps the dataset when the project ends? Can it be handed to someone else?","id":144},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Misuse of personal data","text":"Personal data is anything that can identify a person or reveal something private about them. Misuse is using it beyond the purpose it was given for — sometimes called function creep , where data quietly slides from its original job into a new one no one signed up for. Misuse includes: profiling and labelling people, surveillance, singling individuals out, combining datasets to re-identify \"anonymous\" people, and disclosing or selling data. The harm is the point — misuse erodes trust and can hurt the very people who shared their data in good faith.","id":145},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Misuse of personal data","text":"Stripping names off data feels safe, but combining it with other details (timestamps, class, age, suburb) can re-identify people. \"Anonymous\" data is only anonymous until someone joins it to something else.","id":146},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Repurposing & sharing of data by AI","text":"When you paste data into an AI chatbot or generator, you may be handing it to a third party . That data can be stored on their servers, used to train future models, and effectively shared beyond your control — repurposed for something completely different from your project. AI also repurposes data in a second sense: it can combine sources, infer new facts about people, and re-identify individuals — generating conclusions people never consented to. The convenience of \"just ask the AI to summarise it\" hides a one-way door: once personal data leaves your hands, you can't pull it back.","id":147},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"🧭 The five lenses, one breath","text":"T ransparency · A ccuracy & completeness · O wnership & control · M isuse · A I repurposing & sharing. A memory hook: \"TAOMA — Tell the truth, About the data, Own it together, Misuse never, AI with care.\"","id":148},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Ethics is about who gets hurt","text":"The strongest exam answers don't just name an issue — they trace the harm to real people . In the centre is a PulseCheck decision. Around it sit the people affected. Trigger an ethical lapse and watch the ripple reach them. \"It's a misuse of data\" = 1 mark, maybe. \"It's a misuse of data because students shared mental-health answers to get help, and instead they're individually flagged to staff — eroding trust and discouraging honest responses in future\" = full marks. Always follow the ripple to a person.","id":149},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Which lens is this?","text":"Read each PulseCheck moment and pick the ethical issue it best illustrates. Some are sneaky — they could touch more than one, but choose the primary one.","id":150},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Flip cards","text":"Define it in your head first, then tap to check. These are the exact phrasings to have ready in the exam.","id":151},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Where marks quietly vanish","text":"Every one of these comes straight from how this dotpoint is actually marked. Read them like a checklist before you write.","id":152},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Answering \"ethical\" with a law","text":"Writing \"it breaches the Privacy Act\" when the question asks about an ethical issue. That's a legal answer to an ethics question.","id":153},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Naming an issue with no harm","text":"\"This is a transparency issue.\" Full stop. A bare label with no explanation or stakeholder barely scores.","id":154},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Forgetting the AI issue","text":"Listing only four issues. The repurposing and sharing of data by AI is examinable and the one most often left out.","id":155},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Confusing transparency with privacy","text":"Treating them as the same. Privacy is keeping data from the wrong eyes; transparency is being honest with the right people.","id":156},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Mixing up KK03 quality with KK06 ethics","text":"Listing data-quality factors (accuracy, bias, integrity) instead of the ethical impact of acting on bad data.","id":157},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Saying \"anonymous = safe\"","text":"Assuming stripping names makes data harmless. Combining it with other details can re-identify people.","id":158},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Vague \"it's wrong / bad\"","text":"Emotional verdicts with no reasoning. Markers can't award \"it's just bad.\"","id":159},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"The P·E·L method for ethics answers","text":"Ethics questions reward structure. Name it, explain the harm, tie it back to the case. Hit all three and you cover what the marking guide looks for.","id":160},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"Command words decoder","text":"The verb tells you how much to write. Match your effort to the marks.","id":161},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Six questions, 26 marks. Try each before revealing. Use 👎 to see a common weak answer, 👍 for a strong one, and 📋 for the marking guide — then self-mark to feed the score dock.","id":162},{"file":"u1o1-kk06.html","nav":"u1o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Ethical issues around data & information","head":"📨 New case for Q2–Q6: StepUp","text":"A local gym, StepUp , gives members a free fitness-tracker app. Members log workouts, weight, heart rate and sleep. StepUp's analyst studies the data to design class timetables. Recently, management asked the analyst to (a) email each member a \"fitness score\" ranking them against others, and (b) paste the member data into an AI tool to auto-generate personalised marketing. Just like the exam, the issues are the same — only the scenario is new.","id":163},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","text":"When you use someone else's data, words or ideas in a data-analysis project, you have to say where they came from. The APA system is the agreed way to do that — so your reader can trust your work and trace every source. “Techniques and conventions for referencing primary and secondary data and information using the APA referencing system.”","id":164},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"References are receipts for ideas","text":"Imagine you're audited and asked, “Where did this number come from?” If you kept the receipt , you can prove it instantly. A reference is that receipt: it proves the data isn't yours invented out of thin air, and it shows exactly where to buy the same “item” again.","id":165},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"The receipt analogy","text":"A receipt records who you bought from, when , what the item was and where the shop is. An APA reference records the same four things about a source — Author, Date, Title, Source. Lose the receipt and you can't prove anything; lose the reference and it looks like you stole the idea.","id":166},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Chain of custody (for the forensics crowd)","text":"In digital forensics, every piece of evidence needs an unbroken record of where it came from and who handled it — or it's thrown out of court. Referencing is the chain of custody for information : an unbroken trail from your conclusion back to the original source, so anyone can verify it held up. Hold onto the four words WHO · WHEN · WHAT · WHERE . Every APA reference is built from them, and you'll see them again in the 3D builder below.","id":167},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Why we reference at all","text":"“To make it look professional” is not a mark-earning answer. Referencing exists for four concrete reasons:","id":168},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Acknowledge intellectual property","text":"Data, writing and images are someone's intellectual property. Referencing gives legal and ethical credit to the creator.","id":169},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Avoid plagiarism","text":"Presenting others' work as your own is plagiarism — an academic integrity breach that can void an assessment.","id":170},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Let readers verify","text":"A reader can follow the reference to the original source, check your data is real, current and not misrepresented.","id":171},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Build credibility","text":"Well-sourced findings are trustworthy. Referencing shows your conclusions rest on evidence, not opinion.","id":172},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Primary vs secondary sources","text":"The study design names both , so examiners love asking you to tell them apart. The test is simple: did the data come straight to you, first-hand, or had someone already collected and reported it? Data you collect yourself, for your specific purpose, that didn't exist before you gathered it. A survey you run on student canteen choices An interview you conduct and record Temperature readings from your own sensor Observations you make and log Data someone else already collected, published or analysed, that you re-use in your project. ABS census figures from a data repository A journal article reporting a study A news report, textbook or website A Kaggle / data.gov.au dataset","id":173},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Try it: sort these sources","text":"Click a card to send it to the bin you think it belongs in.","id":174},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"The anatomy of an APA reference","text":"Every reference is four blocks snapped together: WHO wrote it, WHEN , WHAT it's called, and WHERE to find it. Spin the model, then tap a block to light up its part in the live reference below. Switch the source type to watch the same four blocks describe a website, a journal article, a dataset or an AI tool.","id":175},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"The two halves: in-text + reference list","text":"APA always works as a pair . A short pointer sits in your writing; the full details live in a list at the end. Every in-text citation must have a matching entry in the reference list, and vice-versa. A brief signpost inside your sentence — usually just author and year — so the reader knows that claim came from a source. The full details at the end, under a References heading, alphabetical, with a hanging indent.","id":176},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"APA formats for the sources you'll actually use","text":"You don't memorise these character-by-character, but you must know the order (Author → Date → Title → Source) and what gets italicised . Italics go on the title of a standalone work (book, journal, report, dataset, site) — never on an article/chapter title. The VCAA explicitly points to APA's method for acknowledging AI. If a tool helped generate or summarise content, you reference it like any other source — and note in your method how you used it.","id":177},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"APA citation builder","text":"Pick a source type, type in the details, and watch a correctly-formatted APA reference assemble. Great for revision: cover the output, build it in your head, then check.","id":178},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Citing inside your writing","text":"Two flavours: parenthetical (everything in brackets at the end) and narrative (the author becomes part of your sentence). Note the small but examinable difference: use & inside brackets, but the word and in narrative text. Situation Parenthetical Narrative One author (Chen, 2023) Chen (2023) found… Two authors (Chen & Okafor, 2023) Chen and Okafor (2023)… Three or more (Chen et al., 2023) Chen et al. (2023)… Organisation (ABS, 2024) The ABS (2024)… Direct quote (Chen, 2023, p. 14) …“…sleep” (Chen, 2023, p. 14). No date (ABS, n.d.) The ABS (n.d.)…","id":179},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Reference list rules","text":"Alphabetical order by the first author's surname — not the order you used them. Hanging indent — the first line is flush left, every line after it is indented. Italicise the standalone work — book / journal / report / dataset / site title. Article and chapter titles are not italicised. Sentence case for article and book titles — capitalise only the first word, the first word after a colon, and proper nouns. Journal and newspaper names keep Title Case. Ampersand & between authors in the list (and in brackets); the word and in your sentences. Heading “References” , centred and bold, on its own.","id":180},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"“It looks professional” as the purpose","text":"Vague and unmarked. Fix: name a real purpose — acknowledge intellectual property, avoid plagiarism, or let readers verify the source.","id":181},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Calling a reporting source “primary”","text":"A textbook or news report about a study is secondary. Fix: primary = collected first-hand by you or the original researcher.","id":182},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Reference list not alphabetical","text":"Listing sources in order of use loses the “correct conventions” mark. Fix: sort A–Z by first author surname.","id":183},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Italicising the wrong thing","text":"Italics belong on the journal / book / dataset name, not the article title. Fix: italicise the standalone work only.","id":184},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Mixing “&” and “and”","text":"& in brackets and the list; and in narrative sentences. Fix: match the form to the position.","id":185},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"A missing component","text":"Dropping the date or source breaks the reference. Fix: check all four — WHO, WHEN, WHAT, WHERE — are present (use n.d. if there's truly no date).","id":186},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Structure an answer: Point · Evidence · Link","text":"Short-answer marks come from structured responses, not single words. P·E·L keeps you on track: state the Point , back it with an Example/Evidence , then Link it to the question's context.","id":187},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Make the claim","text":"Answer the actual command word directly in one clear sentence.","id":188},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Show an example","text":"Give a concrete instance, format or rule that proves the point.","id":189},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Tie to context","text":"Connect it back to the scenario, data or consequence in the question. Worked example. “Explain why a student must reference a dataset downloaded from a repository.” (2 marks)","id":190},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"Reveal a weak and a strong response for each, read the marking guide, then mark your own attempt. Your score feeds the dial in the sidebar. Primary is your own data and secondary is other people's data. Like a survey or the internet. Primary data is original data the analyst collects first-hand for their specific purpose — for example, a survey the student runs on canteen preferences. Secondary data is data already collected and published by someone else and then reused — for example, ABS population figures downloaded from a data repository.","id":191},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark: a correct definition that contrasts first-hand collection (primary) with reused/published data (secondary). 1 mark: a valid, distinct example of each that fits a data-analysis context. No mark for examples that don't match the definition (e.g. calling 'the internet' secondary without specifics). So they don't get caught copying. They need to put the website and the name. They must reference it to acknowledge the intellectual property of the organisation that created the data and to avoid plagiarism, since it is secondary data they did not collect. An APA reference must include the author/organisation and the year (and the dataset title and source), allowing the assessor to verify the data.","id":192},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark: a real purpose — acknowledging IP / avoiding plagiarism / enabling verification. 1 mark each (max 2): two correct components from author–organisation, year (date), title, [Data set] label, publisher/URL (source). Cap at 2 marks if no purpose is given. Referencing is important so your work looks professional and you get better marks. It is ethical because copying is bad. First, referencing acknowledges the intellectual property of those who created the data, giving fair credit. Second, it lets readers verify sources by tracing each claim to its origin, which supports trustworthy findings.","id":193},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"Ethically, referencing enacts transparency and respects ownership and control of data — the analyst is open about where information came from rather than presenting others' work as their own. 1 mark each (max 2) for two distinct, valid reasons (IP acknowledgement, avoiding plagiarism, verification, credibility). 1 mark for a clear ethical link (transparency / ownership / respect for creators). 1 mark for explanation quality — reasons developed, not just listed. 'Looks professional' / 'better marks' alone earns nothing. It's wrong because it has no brackets and no full stops. Fix the spelling.","id":194},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"Error 1: the year is not in parentheses — it should read (2023). Error 2: the author needs initials and punctuation — Chen, L. Error 3: the journal name should be Title Case and italicised — Journal of Youth Studies. Corrected: Chen, L. (2023). Screen time and adolescent sleep. Journal of Youth Studies (italicised). 1 mark each (max 3) for identifying AND correcting: (a) year not in parentheses → (2023); (b) author format → Chen, L.; (c) journal not capitalised/italicised → Journal of Youth Studies in italics. Identifying without correcting earns half credit only if the correction is implied.","id":195},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"Volume/issue/pages absence may be noted but the three primary errors above are the target. They should say they used AI somewhere so they don't cheat. They should reference the AI tool in APA form — e.g. OpenAI. (2024). ChatGPT (version) [Large language model]. URL — with an in-text citation (OpenAI, 2024), and describe in their method how it was used. This acknowledges the tool's role transparently and maintains academic integrity, since the summary was not solely the student's own work. 1 mark: correct acknowledgement method — APA reference to the tool and/or describing its use in the method.","id":196},{"file":"u1o1-kk07.html","nav":"u1o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Referencing primary & secondary data with APA","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark: a valid reason — transparency / academic integrity / not passing AI output off as one's own. General 'just say you used it' without an APA form or reason earns 1 max.","id":197},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Your running scenario FreshStats","text":"The school canteen manager, Ms Tran , hands your team a spreadsheet of last term's sales and food-waste data and asks for a dashboard she can read at a glance. You don't get to invent the job — you interpret the requirements she gives you , then design and build a data visualisation . Every example in this module comes back to FreshStats.","id":198},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Think of it as a renovation brief","text":"Four words sound abstract until you map them onto something physical. So picture renovating a kitchen.","id":199},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🔧 Requirements = the job list","text":"Functional = the things the kitchen must do : cook, store food, wash up. Non-functional = how well : the bench must take a hot pan, the lights must be bright enough to read a recipe. For FreshStats: F \"show a bar chart of sales by day\" · NF \"load in under 3 seconds on the canteen tablet\".","id":200},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🧱 Constraints = the walls you can't move","text":"Your budget , the size of the room, the plumbing already in the floor, building codes. You must design inside them — they're set by the world, not by you. For FreshStats: C \"no money for new software — use the school's Excel licence\" · C \"student purchase data must be de-identified ( Privacy Act 1988 )\".","id":201},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🚧 Scope = the line around the worksite","text":"Renovating the kitchen — not the bathroom, not the garden. The boundary tells everyone what's in and what's out , so nobody expects a new deck for the same price. For FreshStats: in weekly sales dashboard · out live till integration, predicting next term's sales.","id":202},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"⭐ Why bother being precise?","text":"Vague briefs cause arguments later. \"Make it nice\" can't be ticked off; \"labels must be readable on a 10-inch tablet\" can. Precise requirements are testable — and in the exam, precise wording is what earns the marks. Hold this analogy — we'll unpack each idea with FreshStats next.","id":203},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Functional requirements — what it must do","text":"A functional requirement describes a specific action, feature or behaviour the solution must perform. If you can picture the solution doing it — taking an input, processing it, producing an output — it's functional. The reliable test: a functional requirement almost always starts with a verb — calculate, display, sort, filter, import, export, search, validate . It's something you could later tick off as \"built\" . FreshStats functional requirements: Import the weekly sales CSV Ms Tran provides. Calculate total sales for each menu item. Identify the five best-selling items. Display a bar chart of sales by day of the week. Filter the dashboard by a selected week. Export the summary as a PDF for Ms Tran.","id":204},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"The IPO clue","text":"Functional requirements map cleanly onto Input → Process → Output : Input Process Output Sales CSV Sum per item Totals table Totals Rank & pick top 5 Top-5 list Daily sales Group by weekday Bar chart If you can write it as a row of this table, it's a functional requirement.","id":205},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Non-functional requirements — how well it must do it","text":"A non-functional requirement describes a quality or standard the solution must meet. It doesn't add a new feature — it sets the bar for how the features behave. They're the \"-ilities\": usability, reliability, accessibility, maintainability, plus performance and security.","id":206},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"⚡ Performance","text":"How fast / responsive. \"Dashboard loads in < 3 seconds.\"","id":207},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"👁️ Usability","text":"Easy to learn and read. \"Ms Tran can find top sellers in one click.\"","id":208},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"♿ Accessibility","text":"Works for all users. \"Colours are distinguishable for colour-blind users.\"","id":209},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🔒 Security","text":"Protects the data. \"Only canteen staff can open the file.\"","id":210},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🛡️ Reliability","text":"Doesn't fall over. \"Charts still render if a day has no sales.\"","id":211},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🔧 Maintainability","text":"Easy to update later. \"A new month's data can be added without rebuilding.\"","id":212},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Functional vs non-functional — the one-question test","text":"Students lose easy marks mixing these up. There's a single question that sorts almost every case.","id":213},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🧭 Ask: is it a thing it does , or how well it does it ?","text":"Functional Non-functional Describes An action / feature A quality / standard Answers \"What does it do?\" \"How fast / safe / usable / reliable?\" Starts with A verb (display, sort…) An \"-ility\" or a measure Tested by \"Did the feature work?\" \"Did it meet the standard?\" FreshStats \"Display a sales bar chart\" \"…that renders in under 3 s\" Notice the last row: the same feature carries both. The action is functional; the standard attached to it is non-functional.","id":214},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Constraints — the limits you must work inside","text":"A constraint is a restriction on how the solution can be designed or developed — a boundary set by the outside world, not a feature you choose. You don't get to ignore them; you design around them.","id":215},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"💰 Economic","text":"Money, time, licences, hardware budget. \"No budget for new software — use existing Excel; finished before end of term.\"","id":216},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"⚖️ Legal","text":"Laws you must obey. \"Student purchase data must be de-identified — Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth).\"","id":217},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🖥️ Technical","text":"Available tech, formats, compatibility. \"Must run on the canteen's old 10-inch tablet; data only comes as CSV.\"","id":218},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"👥 Social","text":"People, culture, expectations. \"Canteen staff aren't tech experts — it must be simple to use.\"","id":219},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🤝 Usability","text":"What users can reasonably operate. \"Must work with touch only — no mouse at the counter.\"","id":220},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"🧠 Remember","text":"Constraints come in five flavours: economic, legal, technical, social, usability . A deadline and a budget both sit under economic .","id":221},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Scope — the boundary of the solution","text":"Scope defines exactly what is included (in scope) and what is excluded (out of scope) . It draws a line around the project so everyone agrees where the solution ends — and what they shouldn't expect.","id":222},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"✅ In scope (FreshStats)","text":"Weekly sales dashboard from the provided CSV Bar chart of sales by weekday Top-5 selling items Food-waste summary (kg per week) Filter by week · export summary to PDF","id":223},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"⛔ Out of scope (FreshStats)","text":"Live integration with the POS / till Predicting next term's sales A separate mobile app Online ordering for students Automatically ordering stock","id":224},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"How the four fit together","text":"These aren't four separate lists — they describe one solution from four angles. Read a brief and you should be able to pull each one out. Requirements say what the solution is and how good it is. Constraints say what you must work inside. Scope draws the line around the whole thing. Lens The question it answers Functional What must the solution do ? Non-functional How well must it do it? Constraints What limits bound the work? Scope Where does the solution stop ?","id":225},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Seven traps that cost real marks","text":"Every one of these is a mistake examiners see year after year. Knowing them is the cheapest mark on the page.","id":226},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Calling a non-functional requirement a constraint","text":"\"Easy to read\" is a quality you want → NFR . \"Must use Excel because it's all we own\" is an external limit → constraint . Ask: could the team have chosen differently? If no, it's a constraint.","id":227},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Writing scope items as if they were requirements","text":"Scope is a boundary (in / out), not a list of actions. \"Export to PDF\" is a functional requirement; \"the project does not include a mobile app\" is a scope statement. Phrase scope as included / excluded.","id":228},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Vague, untestable non-functional requirements","text":"\"Fast\", \"good\", \"user-friendly\" can't be measured or marked. Attach a number or standard: \"loads in under 3 seconds\".","id":229},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Listing only functional requirements","text":"If a question says \"requirements\" and you only give actions, you've answered half of it. Always consider non-functional ones too.","id":230},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Treating the deadline or budget as a requirement","text":"\"Finish by the end of term\" doesn't describe the solution — it limits the project. That's an economic constraint.","id":231},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Confusing the data with a functional requirement","text":"\"Sales data\" is an input/source. A functional requirement is what the solution does with it. Lead with a verb: \"calculates total sales\".","id":232},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Saying scope = the whole project","text":"Scope isn't everything — it's specifically the boundary of what's in and out. Don't define scope by restating the project title.","id":233},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Write for the command word, structure with P·E·L","text":"Marks follow the command word. Match your depth to the verb in the question, then structure each point so an examiner can find the marks fast.","id":234},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"The P·E·L spine","text":"Every extended point can be built from three moves. Try it on this question:","id":235},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Practice questions — weak vs strong, then self-mark","text":"Try each in your head (or on paper) first. Reveal the weak answer to see the trap, the strong answer to see the ceiling, and the marking guide to award yourself marks. Your total tracks in the dock. 1 mark: a correct functional requirement with a FreshStats example. 1 mark: a correct non-functional requirement with a measurable FreshStats example. Full marks require the distinction (action vs quality/standard) to be explicit. 1 mark: a valid technical constraint with FreshStats detail. 1 mark: explaining it is an external limit the team must work within.","id":236},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Practice questions — weak vs strong, then self-mark","text":"1 mark: a valid legal constraint (named law strengthens it). 1 mark: explaining it is imposed externally, not a feature/quality chosen by the team. 1 mark: identifies the request is out of the agreed scope. 1 mark: names this as scope creep. 1 mark: explains the consequence (deadline/resource/quality risk) and/or the value of a defined boundary. 1 mark: a re-write that is specific and measurable (a number or testable standard). 1 mark: it genuinely captures usability (not just speed). 1 mark: justification explicitly links measurability to being testable in evaluation.","id":237},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Practice questions — weak vs strong, then self-mark","text":"1 mark each, (a)–(d): F, C, S, NF respectively. No part marks for a correct label with the wrong reason if working is shown. 1 mark: benefit of clear requirements (right features / testable standard). 1 mark: benefit of stating constraints (avoids impossible/illegal work). 1 mark: benefit of defined scope (prevents scope creep / protects deadline). 1 mark: a synthesising benefit (less rework, aligned expectations, basis for evaluation).","id":238},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"The KK08 cheat sheet","text":"If you remember nothing else walking into the exam, remember this.","id":239},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Functional","text":"What the solution does — an action/feature. Starts with a verb; can be ticked off as built.","id":240},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Non-functional","text":"How well it does it — a measurable quality (the \"-ilities\").","id":241},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Constraints","text":"External limits you must work inside: economic, legal, technical, social, usability.","id":242},{"file":"u1o1-kk08.html","nav":"u1o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Requirements, constraints & scope","head":"Scope","text":"The boundary — what's in and out. Stops scope creep.","id":243},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Design tools for solutions","text":"Four ways to plan a data solution on paper — an IPO chart , a mock-up , an annotated diagram and a query design — so the database, spreadsheet and visualisation you build are the right ones , the first time.","id":244},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Why would you draw a solution before you build it?","text":"Imagine being told to build a house. You wouldn't start pouring concrete and hope it works out. You'd get a blueprint first — a plan everyone can read, check and agree on before a single brick is laid. Data solutions are no different. Before you create a database, a spreadsheet or a data visualisation , you produce design tools : small, readable plans that show what the solution will do and what it will look like. They let you (and your teacher, and your client) catch problems while they're still cheap to fix — on paper — rather than after you've spent three lessons building the wrong thing.","id":245},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Why would you draw a solution before you build it?","text":"A good design tool passes the blueprint test : could someone else build your solution from it without asking you a single question? If yes, it's detailed enough. If they'd have to guess, it isn't.","id":246},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Where these tools sit in the problem-solving methodology","text":"Every solution in this course moves through four stages. Design tools live squarely in the second one. Analysis works out what the solution must do (the requirements). Design works out how it will do it and what it will look like — that's where your four tools live. Only then does Development build it, and Evaluation checks it against the original requirements. Design tools split neatly into two jobs. Some describe functionality — the behaviour, the data flow, the logic (IPO charts and query designs). Others describe appearance — the layout, colours and labels a user will see (mock-ups and annotated diagrams). Strong students always know which job each tool is doing.","id":247},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"The four tools at a glance","text":"Each tool answers a different question about your solution. Learn the one-line job of each — it's the difference between naming a tool and explaining it.","id":248},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"IPO chart","text":"A three-column table — Input · Process · Output — that maps what data goes in, what is done to it, and what comes out. Plans functionality .","id":249},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Query design","text":"A written plan for a question you'll ask the data — which fields, which conditions, which sort/total — for a database , spreadsheet or visualisation . Plans functionality .","id":250},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Mock-up","text":"A sketch of the layout — where the title, charts, tables and buttons go on screen or page. A picture of the finished look. Plans appearance .","id":251},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Annotated diagram","text":"A mock-up (or other diagram) with callout notes explaining each design choice — colours, fonts, alignment, chart type — usually tied to design principles . Plans & justifies appearance.","id":252},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Try it: sort the design jobs","text":"Drag (or tap, then tap a bin) each job onto the tool that does it. Four belong to each tool — get them home.","id":253},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"IPO charts — input, process, output","text":"An IPO chart is the simplest way to plan what a solution does . Three columns, read left to right: what goes in , what happens in the middle , what comes out . Input = the fruit and milk you tip in. Process = the blending. Output = the smoothie. You don't see how the blades spin — you just describe the transformation. That's exactly the level of detail an IPO chart works at.","id":254},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Worked example — the StepUp leaderboard","text":"The coordinator wants a leaderboard that ranks home groups by total steps. Here's the IPO chart for that process: Input Process Output Daily step file ( StudentID, Date, Steps, Homeroom ) exported from the fitness app 1. Remove rows with blank or negative Steps 2. Sum Steps per Homeroom 3. Sort home groups from highest to lowest total 4. Assign rank 1–6 Ranked leaderboard table: Rank, Homeroom, Total steps","id":255},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"See it move — the IPO machine","text":"Press Run to push the raw StepUp data through the machine. Watch the messy input get cleaned, summed and ranked into the output. This is the mental model: data is transformed , not just moved.","id":256},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Mock-ups — a picture of the finished look","text":"A mock-up is a sketch of the layout : where the title, charts, tables, buttons and labels will sit. It shows a client what they'll actually see — before you build it. A mock-up shows the arrangement — the furniture in the right places — but the content can be placeholder. Real data isn't needed yet; XX,XXX steps or grey boxes stand in for charts. You're designing the frame , not filling it.","id":257},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Worked example — the StepUp foyer dashboard","text":"Here's a mock-up of the data visualisation that will run on the foyer screen. Notice it's a layout plan — blocky, labelled, placeholder content: You can't open design software in a written exam. If asked to \"draw a mock-up\", produce a neat, labelled hand sketch with a ruler. Markers reward clear regions and labels — not artistic shading. Always note the orientation (portrait/landscape) if it matters.","id":258},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Annotated diagrams — a mock-up that explains itself","text":"An annotated diagram is a mock-up (or other diagram) with callout notes pointing at each part, explaining the design choice — usually by naming a design principle or a format/convention . If a mock-up says \" here is the layout \", an annotated diagram adds \" …and here's why each part looks like this \". The annotations are where you show the examiner you understand design principles — not just where boxes go.","id":259},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Query designs — planning the questions you'll ask the data","text":"A query is a question you put to your data: \" which home groups beat 50,000 steps? \". A query design plans that question before you build it — naming the fields, the conditions, the sort and any totals. Queries appear across all three Data Analysis tools, and the design looks a little different in each:","id":260},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Database","text":"Plan the fields to show, the criteria (conditions), and the sort order . Often written as a QBE grid or an SQL-style statement.","id":261},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Spreadsheet","text":"Plan the filter conditions and the functions that summarise — SUMIF , AVERAGEIF , COUNTIF — and which range they cover.","id":262},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Visualisation","text":"Plan which queried fields feed which chart — e.g. \"ranked totals → bar chart\", \"daily totals → line chart\". The query shapes the picture.","id":263},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Worked example — three StepUp queries","text":"The same data, three different questions, planned three different ways:","id":264},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Try it: design a database query","text":"Pick the fields, a condition and a sort. Watch the SQL-style design assemble — and the StepLog rows that would match light up. This is the plan ; the real query comes later in Development. StudentID Homeroom Steps Date S214 11A 12,840 2026-03-04 S118 11B 8,460 2026-03-04 S377 11C 15,120 2026-03-04 S045 11A 6,230 2026-03-05 S260 11C 9,980 2026-03-05 S501 11B 11,200 2026-03-05 S088 11A 3,110 2026-03-06 S412 11C 13,760 2026-03-06 Marks are for the plan — fields, criteria, sort — written clearly enough to build from. You don't need real output rows. Equally, \"find the best home group\" is too vague : name the field ( SUM(Steps) ), the condition and the order.","id":265},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Appearance vs functionality — what your annotations target","text":"When you annotate a design, you're commenting on one of two things: how it looks (appearance) or how it works (functionality). Examiners love asking you to do both.","id":266},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Appearance — how it looks","text":"The visual design the user sees. Judged with design principles such as:","id":267},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Functionality — how it works","text":"The behaviour and usefulness. Judged with factors such as: StepUp design choice Appearance or functionality? Principle / factor Largest, boldest text is the dashboard title Appearance Hierarchy, contrast Bar chart chosen to compare home groups Functionality Correct chart type Step totals all right-aligned with commas Appearance Alignment, conventions Leaderboard updates as new data is added Functionality Usability, data flow High-contrast colours so it reads across the foyer Appearance Contrast, accessibility","id":268},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Choosing and combining the right tool","text":"No single tool plans a whole solution. A real design uses several together — each covering a part the others can't. If you need to plan… Reach for… Because How raw data becomes a result IPO chart Maps input → process → output clearly A specific question for the data Query design Names fields, criteria and sort What the screen/page looks like Mock-up Shows layout and placement Why each visual choice was made Annotated diagram Ties layout to design principles","id":269},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"The full StepUp design, tool by tool","text":"A complete design for the StepUp solution combines all four: Part of the solution Tool(s) used Database of step readings IPO data in/clean/store · Query top groups Spreadsheet leaderboard IPO sum & rank · Query AVERAGEIF Dashboard visualisation Mock-up layout · Annotated design reasons","id":270},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Exam traps students fall into","text":"These are the avoidable mistakes that quietly cost marks on design-tool questions. Learn to spot each one in your own answers. \" I would use a mock-up \" is not a mock-up. If the command word is construct, design, draw or produce , you must actually create the artefact , not describe that you'd make one. The process column describes the actions (clean, sum, sort). The output is the result (the ranked table). Students often put the answer in the process column and leave output blank. \"This looks nice\" earns nothing.","id":271},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Exam traps students fall into","text":"Every annotation must name a design principle (contrast, hierarchy, alignment…) or a convention , and say why it helps the user . \"Find the top group\" hides the design. State the fields , the condition and the sort — e.g. SUM(Steps) GROUP BY Homeroom ORDER BY DESC . If a question asks for an appearance annotation, don't write about how the leaderboard updates (that's functionality). Read which one is being asked — sometimes both, clearly separated. A mock-up plans the layout , so use placeholders ( XX,XXX , grey bars).","id":272},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Exam traps students fall into","text":"Filling it with calculated totals turns a design tool into a half-built product and misses the point. Choosing a bar chart to compare groups or a line chart for a trend is a functionality decision worth marks — but only if you say why that chart suits that data.","id":273},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Command words & the P·E·L method","text":"Half of exam success is reading the command word correctly, then structuring your answer so a marker can find every point.","id":274},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Decode the command word","text":"Name it. No explanation. \"It is an IPO chart.\" Say what it is and a feature/how it works. Give reasons — why or how , with a because. State a clear difference between two things — use \"whereas\". Actually produce the artefact — the chart, mock-up or query. Add labelled notes naming principles & reasons. Argue why your choice is the best one. Weigh strengths and weaknesses, then conclude.","id":275},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Structure with P·E·L","text":"For \"explain / justify\" answers, three moves keep you on track: State your claim directly. \"A mock-up plans the layout.\" Give the reason or evidence. \"…because it shows where each chart sits before building.\" Tie back to the scenario / question. \"…so the StepUp coordinator approves the look early.\"","id":276},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Practice questions — mark yourself","text":"Five VCE-style questions on the StepUp scenario, 18 marks total. Attempt each, reveal the weak vs strong responses and the marking guide, then award yourself a score. Your total tracks in the dock. 1 mark — naming each correct tool (max 1 for naming). 1 mark — stating what each plans (functionality vs appearance, or a correct specific job). Accept IPO, mock-up, annotated diagram, query design. 1 mark — Input names the actual fields of the file. 1 mark — Process lists clear ordered steps (clean → sum → sort → rank).","id":277},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Practice questions — mark yourself","text":"1 mark — Output is the specific ranked leaderboard (not just \"data\"). 1 mark — correct description of a mock-up (layout/appearance). 1 mark — correct description of an annotated diagram (mock-up + explanatory notes). 1 mark — a clear point of distinction (\"whereas…\"). 1 mark — a relevant StepUp example for each. 1 mark — correct fields shown (Homeroom + total of Steps). 1 mark — the > 50,000 condition (HAVING/criteria). 1 mark — sort highest→lowest (ORDER BY DESC). 1 mark — a valid reason a query design helps before building.","id":278},{"file":"u1o1-kk09.html","nav":"u1o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Design tools for solutions","head":"Practice questions — mark yourself","text":"1 mark each (×3) — a clear annotation that names a design principle/factor and the reason it helps the user. 1 mark — at least one appearance and one functionality annotation present. 1 mark — annotations clearly tied to specific parts of the StepUp dashboard.","id":279},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"One spreadsheet becomes a mess. A relational database keeps it clean.","text":"When the student council started selling hoodies online, they kept everything in one giant spreadsheet. By week three it was a disaster — Maya's email was spelled three different ways and nobody could update a price without breaking something. This module shows how splitting that chaos into tables joined by keys fixes it for good.","id":280},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"What you're accountable for","text":"Key knowledge: “the structural characteristics of relational databases, including tables, primary keys, foreign keys and queries.” Because the dot point uses the word “including” , every item after it — tables, primary keys, foreign keys and queries — is directly examinable. You must be able to identify each one, explain what it does, and read a small database to spot them. A relational database stores data in separate tables that are linked together through keys . Software that manages one of these is called a relational database management system (RDBMS) — Microsoft Access, MySQL and the database behind almost every app you use are all RDBMSs.","id":281},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"What you're accountable for","text":"The whole idea rests on one principle: store each fact once, in the table where it belongs, and link to it everywhere else. Get that, and tables, keys, relationships and queries all click into place. We'll build the intuition with MerchLine — the student council's school-merch shop — then drill it with exam-style questions. Scroll top to bottom — each section unlocks the next idea. The 3D scenes are draggable : spin them, click the records, watch the links light up. Finish with the practice exam and self-mark dock (bottom-right) to track your score.","id":282},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"The “one big spreadsheet” trap","text":"Here's how MerchLine started — one flat table with a row for every sale. It looks fine at first. Look closer at what repeats. Buyer Email Item Price Size Date Maya Okafor maya.o@stu.edu Hoodie $45 03/05 Jack Chen jchen@stu.edu Cap $18 03/05 Maya Okafor maya.o@stu.edu Bottle $22 05/05 Maya Okafor maya.o@stu.edu Hoodie $45 06/05 Sam Patel spatel@stu.edu Hoodie $45 07/05 Maya's name and email are typed out three times . The hoodie's price sits in three rows. This duplication — storing the same fact in many places — is called data redundancy , and it causes three classic problems examiners love:","id":283},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"The three update anomalies","text":"Update anomaly — the hoodie price rises to $48. You must find and change every hoodie row. Miss one and your data now contradicts itself. Insertion anomaly — you want to add a new product (a tote bag) that nobody has bought yet. But this table only has rows for sales , so there's nowhere to put it. Deletion anomaly — Sam cancels his only order and you delete the row. You've just lost the only record that Sam is even a customer. Imagine every student carried a full photocopy of the school rulebook.","id":284},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"The three update anomalies","text":"Change one rule and you'd have to recall and reprint 1,200 copies — and you know some would slip through with the old rule. A relational database is the opposite: one master rulebook in the office, and everyone just holds a slip that points to it. Change the master once, everyone's up to date.","id":285},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Tables, records & fields","text":"The fix is to split the data so each table describes exactly one kind of thing (one “entity”). MerchLine needs three: the people, the products, and the orders that connect them. Every table is built from the same two parts: A field (a column) is one characteristic — e.g. Email or Price . A record (a row) is one complete entry — all the fields for a single student, product or order. StudentID 🔑 FirstName Surname Email S-014 Maya Okafor maya.o@stu.edu S-027 Jack Chen jchen@stu.edu S-031 Sam Patel spatel@stu.edu Now Maya appears exactly once .","id":286},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Tables, records & fields","text":"Her email lives in one cell. Spell it right here, and it's right everywhere it's used. That single move — one fact, one place — is the heart of the whole topic. A spreadsheet also has rows and columns, but it's one loose grid with no enforced links between sheets. A relational database enforces structure: defined fields, keys, and relationships the software actively protects. Saying “a database is just a spreadsheet” loses marks.","id":287},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"See the schema in 3D","text":"Here are MerchLine's three tables floating in space. The Orders table in the middle is the connector — it holds two foreign keys that point back to the primary keys of Students and Products. Click an order to fire the links and watch a single order resolve into a real person and a real product.","id":288},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Primary keys — the unique handle","text":"A primary key is a field (or combination of fields) whose value uniquely identifies every record in a table. No two records can share it, and it can never be empty. Your school has two students both called Jack Chen . Names collide. But each Jack has a different student ID number — that's the primary key. The office never looks you up by name; they look you up by the number that can only ever mean you .","id":289},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"What makes a good primary key","text":"Unique — no duplicates, ever. The RDBMS will reject a second record with the same key. Not empty (no nulls) — every record must have one. A record with no key can't be reliably found or linked. Stable — it shouldn't change. People change surnames and emails; an ID like S-014 stays put, so links never break. Names repeat (two Jack Chens). Emails change when someone switches providers — and if the email is the key, changing it breaks every order linked to it. That's why databases use a dedicated ID field as the key: it's guaranteed unique and never needs to change.","id":290},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Foreign keys — the link","text":"A foreign key is a field in one table that holds the primary key value of a record in another table . It's the actual wire that connects two tables. In MerchLine, the Orders table has two foreign keys: OrderID 🔑 StudentID 🔗 ProductID 🔗 Size Date 1001 S-014 P-01 03/05 1002 S-027 P-02 03/05 1003 S-014 P-03 05/05 You hand your coat to the cloakroom and get a ticket stub: #47 . The stub in your pocket is the foreign key . Coat #47 hanging on the rack is identified by its primary key .","id":291},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Foreign keys — the link","text":"The stub doesn't contain your coat — it just points to exactly which coat is yours. Lose the rack and the stub is useless; that's why the link must always point at something real. The RDBMS enforces a rule: a foreign key must point to a primary key that actually exists . You can't create an order for StudentID = S-099 if no such student exists. This protection is called referential integrity — it stops “orphan” records that link to nothing.","id":292},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Relationships & cardinality","text":"The relationship between two tables describes how many records on one side connect to records on the other. This is the cardinality , and it's a favourite exam target. Pick one and watch the links form. Databases can't store a raw many-to-many link directly. One student buys many products; one product is bought by many students. The fix? A junction table in the middle (Orders!) that turns one M:N into two clean 1:M relationships. That's literally why the Orders table exists.","id":293},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Queries — asking questions of the data","text":"A query is a question you ask the database to pull out exactly the records you want. The power of the relational model is that a query can join tables together using their keys — combining the person, the product and the order into one readable answer. Pick a question: OrderID Item Size Date 1001 Hoodie 03/05 1003 Bottle 05/05 You don't walk the whole library re-reading every shelf. You ask the librarian a precise question — “all books by this author, published after 2020” — and they hand back just those.","id":294},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Queries — asking questions of the data","text":"A query is that question; the database is the librarian who knows exactly where everything is because of the keys. A query doesn't store data — it produces a view of data that already lives in the tables. Run it again tomorrow after new orders arrive and you'll get an updated answer. Calling a query “a table” in an exam costs marks.","id":295},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Sort it: which part is which?","text":"Drag each example into the correct structural component. This is exactly the “identify the feature” task the study design names.","id":296},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Definitions worth memorising","text":"Tap a card to flip it. These are the exam-ready definitions — learn the wording, not just the gist. A database that stores data in separate tables linked together through keys, so each fact is stored once and referenced everywhere else. A structure that stores data about one kind of thing, organised into records (rows) and fields (columns). One complete entry in a table — all the fields belonging to a single item, e.g. everything about student S-014. One characteristic stored for every record in a table, e.g. Email or Price.","id":297},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Definitions worth memorising","text":"A field (or set of fields) whose value uniquely identifies every record in a table. It must be unique and can never be empty. A field in one table that holds the primary key value of a record in another table, creating the relationship between them. A request that retrieves and combines records matching set criteria, often joining tables by their keys. It produces a view, not a stored table. The rule that a foreign key must always point to a primary key that actually exists, preventing orphan records.","id":298},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Six ways students lose easy marks","text":"It can't — uniqueness is the whole point. Two records with the same primary key would be impossible to tell apart. Fix: state it must be unique and never null. In a one-to-many relationship the foreign key always lives on the many side. StudentID belongs in Orders, not a list of orders crammed into Students. Fix: foreign key goes on the “many” table. A spreadsheet is one loose grid; a relational database has multiple tables with enforced keys and relationships. Fix: name tables, keys and relationships as the difference. A query produces a temporary view of data that lives in tables — it doesn't store its own copy.","id":299},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Six ways students lose easy marks","text":"Fix: say a query retrieves/combines data; it doesn't store it. “Many students to one order” is wrong — one order has one buyer. Read it both ways before answering. Fix: test the relationship in both directions. “A primary key is a special field” earns nothing. The mark is in uniquely identifies each record . Fix: always include the identification function.","id":300},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"Instant-feedback check","text":"Multiple choice, in the style of VCAA Section A. Pick an answer to see why it's right or wrong.","id":301},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"The P·E·L method for written answers","text":"Short-answer database questions reward a tight structure: make a Point , ground it in an Example from the scenario, then Link back to what the question asked. Pick a concept to see it modelled, then try your own.","id":302},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"CourtBook is the system that manages bookings for the school's sports courts. It uses three tables: Members (everyone allowed to book), Courts (court 1, court 2, the gym hall…) and Bookings (who booked which court, when). Use this scenario for all questions below. Attempt each question on paper first. Then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer, and the marking guide — and use the dock to self-mark honestly. A primary key is an important field in the table. A name is no good because it's too long. A primary key is a field whose value uniquely identifies each record in a table.","id":303},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"A member's name is unsuitable because two different members could share the same name, so it would not be unique and could not reliably identify one record. 1 mark — primary key uniquely identifies each record in a table. 1 mark — a reason based on uniqueness (names can repeat, so not unique / can't reliably identify a record). Accept also: names can change, breaking links. A foreign key connects the two tables so you know who made the booking. It's in the Bookings table. A foreign key is a field in the Bookings table that stores the MemberID — the primary key value of a record in the Members table.","id":304},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"By matching that value to the primary key in Members, the database links each booking to the one member who made it, without copying the member's details into the Bookings table. 1 — foreign key is a field in Bookings (the ‘many’ side). 1 — it holds the primary key value (MemberID) of a record in Members. 1 — matching the values links each booking to one member / avoids duplicating member data. It had lots of repeated data which was messy. Using more tables makes it neater and easier to read.","id":305},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"Problem 1 — redundancy: a frequent booker's name, email and phone were stored again in every one of their booking rows, wasting space and inviting inconsistency. Problem 2 — update anomaly: if that member changed their email, staff had to edit every booking row, and missing one left the data contradicting itself. Solution: splitting into a Members table and a Bookings table stores each member's details once in Members, with each booking holding only a MemberID foreign key that links back. Now a detail is changed in a single place and every linked booking reflects it automatically.","id":306},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"2 marks — two correct problems named and described with the scenario (redundancy / update anomaly / insertion / deletion anomaly). 1 mark — restructuring stores each member's details once in a Members table. 1 mark — Bookings links via a MemberID foreign key. 1 mark — a change is then made in one place / integrity maintained. It's a one-to-many relationship. The foreign key goes in a table. The relationship is one-to-many: one court can appear in many bookings, but each booking is for exactly one court. The foreign key — CourtID — should be placed in the Bookings table, because the foreign key belongs on the ‘many’ side.","id":307},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"Storing CourtID in each booking lets many bookings each point to one court record, whereas a single Courts record could not list an ever-growing number of booking references in one field. 1 — identifies one-to-many. 1 — states the direction (one court → many bookings; each booking → one court). 1 — foreign key (CourtID) placed in the Bookings table. 1 — justification: foreign key sits on the ‘many’ side / a single field can't hold many references. You'd run a query to search for the bookings from last week and it would show the names and courts.","id":308},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"A database is good at this. A query would join three tables: Bookings, Members and Courts. It uses the foreign keys in Bookings — MemberID and CourtID — to match each booking to the correct record in Members (via its MemberID primary key) and in Courts (via its CourtID primary key). The query filters bookings to last week's dates, then returns the member's name from Members and the court name from Courts for each matching booking. This is easier in a relational database because each member's and court's details are stored once and the keys make the links explicit, so the query assembles the answer automatically.","id":309},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"VCE-style questions · 20 marks","text":"In the original single table the name and court were re-typed in every row, so the same data could be inconsistent and a reliable, de-duplicated list would be far harder to guarantee. 1 — query joins Bookings with Members and Courts. 1 — uses foreign keys MemberID and CourtID in Bookings. 1 — matches them to the primary keys in Members and Courts. 1 — filters to last week / returns member name + court name. 1 — relational advantage: data stored once, links explicit, assembled automatically. 1 — contrast: flat table repeated data → inconsistency / harder to guarantee a clean list.","id":310},{"file":"u1o1-kk10.html","nav":"u1o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Relational Database Structure","head":"One-screen summary","text":"Term One-line definition MerchLine example Table Stores data about one kind of entity, as records (rows) and fields (columns). Students, Products, Orders Primary key A field that uniquely identifies every record. Unique, never empty, stable. StudentID = S-014 Foreign key A field holding another table's primary key value — the link between tables. Orders.StudentID → Students Query A question that retrieves/combines records; produces a view, not a stored table. “All orders Maya placed” Relationship How records link across tables — most often one-to-many. 1 student → many orders Store each fact once in its own table, give every record a unique primary key, link tables with foreign keys, and ask questions with queries. Everything in this module is a detail of that sentence.","id":311},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","text":"Every chart, total and dashboard you'll ever build in this course starts life as a grid. Before you can analyse data, you have to know exactly how a spreadsheet is built — because the structure is what makes data findable, sortable and safe to calculate with. This dot point is about that architecture: the parts of the grid and the names examiners expect you to use precisely. VCAA scope, exactly. The study design lists the structural characteristics of spreadsheets , such as rows , columns and cells . That's the whole job of this dot point — the anatomy of the grid.","id":312},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","text":"Building formulas, validating and charting come later (KK12); calculating averages and standard deviation comes later again (KK13). Keep your answers here about structure . Our running scenario — “BoothBoss”. Maya and Jayden run the bubble-tea booth at the PVCC school fete. Every cup sold gets logged into a Google Sheet called booth-sales . We'll use that one sheet to name every structural part as it appears — so the theory always has something concrete behind it.","id":313},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"A spreadsheet is a stadium seating plan","text":"Imagine the booth profits paid for everyone to go to a concert at Marvel Stadium. Your ticket doesn't say “somewhere on the left” — it says Row 24, Seat F . Two facts, and only one seat in the whole stadium matches both. That is exactly how a spreadsheet finds a single piece of data.","id":314},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Seat letter → Column","text":"The lettered direction (Seat A, B, C…) is the column . It tells you which kind of place you're in.","id":315},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Seat row → Row","text":"The numbered direction (Row 1, 2, 3…) is the row . It tells you which one in that sequence.","id":316},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Your actual seat → Cell","text":"The single seat where the row and the letter cross is the cell — one spot, one person, one value. So when a spreadsheet says cell C7 , it means the same thing as “Seat C, Row 7”: go across to column C , down to row 7 , and there is exactly one box waiting for you. Hold that picture — the rest of this module is just naming the parts of that stadium.","id":317},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Columns — the vertical strips","text":"A column is a vertical strip of cells running from top to bottom. Columns are labelled with letters along the very top: A, B, C … then after Z it continues AA, AB, and so on. In a well-built sheet, each column holds one kind of fact about every item — one attribute . In BoothBoss, column C only ever holds flavours; column F only ever holds prices. Because everything in a column is the same kind of thing, you can sort it, total it or chart it sensibly. One column = one attribute.","id":318},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Columns — the vertical strips","text":"Think of a column as a labelled jar: the jar marked “Flavour” should never contain a price. Mixing kinds of data into one column is the classic beginner mistake — and it breaks every calculation later. BoothBoss column Holds (one attribute) Example value Sale ID Time 12:18 Flavour Taro Size Large Topping Pearls Price ($) 6.50","id":319},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Rows — the horizontal strips","text":"A row is a horizontal strip of cells running left to right. Rows are labelled with numbers down the left edge: 1, 2, 3 … In a well-built sheet, each row holds everything about one item — one complete entity . In BoothBoss, row 7 is the full story of a single sale: its ID, time, flavour, size, topping and price, read across the columns. Add a new sale and you add a new row. One row = one record. A row is like one receipt: it pulls together all the facts about a single sale into one line.","id":320},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Rows — the horizontal strips","text":"The first row ( row 1 ) is usually a header row — it stores the column titles, not real data. Remember the directions. Columns are like the columns of a building — they stand up tall (vertical, letters). Rows are like rows of seats — they stretch sideways (horizontal, numbers). Get this right and half the exam traps disappear.","id":321},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Cells — the atom of the spreadsheet","text":"A cell is the single box formed where one column crosses one row . It is the smallest unit of a spreadsheet, and the golden rule is: one cell holds exactly one value — one number, one piece of text, one date, one Boolean. That “one value per cell” idea is what keeps data atomic and easy to calculate with.","id":322},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Every cell has an address","text":"A cell reference names a cell by combining its column letter then its row number — always in that order. So the flavour of sale #6 lives in cell C7 : column C (Flavour) meets row 7 (sale #6, because row 1 is headers).","id":323},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"The active cell","text":"The one cell you've currently clicked is the active cell . Its reference shows in the Name Box (top-left of the spreadsheet), and whatever you type lands there. Only ever one active cell at a time. Order matters. A cell reference is always letter-then-number: C7 , never 7C . Writing it backwards is a quick way to lose an easy mark.","id":324},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Lab: light up the structure","text":"Here's the BoothBoss grid rebuilt in 3D. Use the buttons to highlight a single cell , a whole row , a whole column , or a rectangular range — and watch how each one selects a different shape of the grid. Drag the grid to spin it. Notice the difference in shape : a cell is a single block, a row is one line across, a column is one line down, and a range is a rectangle of cells named by its top-left and bottom-right corners (here, C2:C9 ).","id":325},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Ranges","text":"A range is a block of cells named by its top-left and bottom-right corners with a colon between them. F2:F41 means “every price from row 2 to row 41”. Ranges are how you point a future total or chart at a whole column of data at once.","id":326},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Worksheet vs workbook","text":"A workbook is the whole file ( booth-sales ). Inside it, each tab is a worksheet : Maya keeps Sales , Stock and Summary sheets in the one workbook. A full address can name the sheet too — Sales!C7 . The structure is a hierarchy. Workbook → Worksheet → (Columns & Rows) → Cell. Zoom all the way in and you always land on a single cell holding one value; zoom out and that cell sits inside a sheet, inside a file. Every structural term names one level of that ladder.","id":327},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Try it: the live BoothBoss sheet","text":"This behaves like the real thing. Click any cell to see its reference appear in the Name Box, and read what column (attribute) and row (record) it belongs to. Or use the buttons to select a whole row, column or range. Sale ID Time Flavour Size Topping Price ($) 11:02 Taro Reg Pearls 5.50 11:09 Mango Large Jelly 6.50 11:15 Matcha Reg Pearls 5.50 11:23 Brown Sugar Large Pearls 6.80 11:40 Mango Reg None 5.00 12:18 Taro Large Pearls 6.50 12:31 Matcha Large Jelly 6.80 12:47 Brown Sugar Reg Pearls 5.80 13:02 Mango Large Pearls 6.50","id":328},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Don't mix it up with a database","text":"The next dot point (KK10) covers relational database structure. The two look similar — both are grids — but they use different vocabulary , and exams punish students who swap the words. If the question says spreadsheet , use columns , rows and cells . If it says database , use fields, records and tables. Idea Spreadsheet term Database term The whole thing Workbook / worksheet Database / table One vertical strip (an attribute) Column Field One horizontal strip (an item) Row Record One single value Cell Field value Pointing at a block Range (C2:C9) Query result Guaranteeing uniqueness — (not built in) Primary key The deeper difference.","id":329},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Don't mix it up with a database","text":"A spreadsheet is a free-form grid — you can type anything anywhere. A relational database enforces its structure with defined fields and keys that link tables together. That extra structure is exactly why databases handle large, related datasets more reliably (more in KK10).","id":330},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Reversing the reference","text":"It's column-letter then row-number: C7 , not 7C . Always letters first.","id":331},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Letters across, numbers down — backwards","text":"Columns are vertical and lettered; rows are horizontal and numbered. Swapping which is which is the most common slip.","id":332},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Calling a cell “a row and a column”","text":"A cell isn't a row or a column — it's the single intersection of one row and one column, holding one value.","id":333},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Database words in a spreadsheet answer","text":"If the question says spreadsheet , don't write “field”, “record” or “table”. Use column, row, cell.","id":334},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Workbook = worksheet","text":"The workbook is the whole file; a worksheet is one tab inside it. One workbook can hold many worksheets.","id":335},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Two facts in one cell","text":"“Taro Large” crammed into one cell breaks the one-value-per-cell rule. Split it into a Flavour column and a Size column.","id":336},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Writing trainer: Point · Example · Link","text":"Short-answer marks come from structured writing, not just naming a term. Click a structural feature and see it written up as a model P·E·L response — Point (define it), Example (show it in BoothBoss), Link (why the structure matters). Then practise rebuilding the pattern in your own words.","id":337},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Practice: VCAA-style questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total. For each: try it on paper first, then reveal a weak answer (and why it loses marks), a strong answer, and the marking guide. Mark your own work honestly — your score saves to the dial in the corner.","id":338},{"file":"u1o1-kk11.html","nav":"u1o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Spreadsheet structure: columns , rows and cells","head":"Key-term recap","text":"If you can define each of these in one clean sentence and point to it in the BoothBoss sheet, you've nailed KK11. Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · Unit 1 Outcome 1 (Data Analysis) · KK11 — Structural characteristics of spreadsheets. Built for Year 11 & 12 revision. Scenario “BoothBoss” is fictional. Aligned to the VCAA VCE Applied Computing Study Design 2025–2028; always confirm examinable wording against the current study design.","id":339},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Manipulating & validating data","text":"Raw data is almost never ready to use. Before it can tell a story, you have to manipulate it into shape, validate that it's clean, and test that everything you built actually works. These are the engine-room skills of data analysis.","id":340},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Where this fits","text":"KK12 is the \"make it work\" dot point — the hands-on middle of the Data Analysis outcome. You've already learned what data is (KK01–KK04), how to judge its quality (KK03), and how databases and spreadsheets are structured (KK10–KK11). KK12 is where you finally do things to the data : reshape it, guard it against errors, and prove your work is correct. KK13 then narrows in on the specific statistics — average, median, count, standard deviation — so keep this dot point about the broad techniques , not those particular calculations.","id":341},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Where this fits","text":"\" Functions and techniques to manipulate , validate and test data, including formulas and functions, charts and graphs, and Structured Query Language (SQL) queries. \" Because the wording uses including , all three tool-sets — formulas/functions, charts/graphs and SQL queries — are directly examinable.","id":342},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Meet the running scenario: SnackTrack","text":"Mia is a Year 11 student who runs the data behind her school canteen's SnackTrack loyalty app. Every Friday the till exports a messy file of lunch orders. Across this module, Mia will manipulate that file into insight, validate it so next week's orders stay clean, and test that her formulas, queries and charts are right. Same dataset, three jobs.","id":343},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Three jobs, one dataset","text":"Manipulate, validate, test — they sound similar but answer three different questions.","id":344},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"🔧 Manipulate","text":"\"Reshape it.\" Change the data's form or pull out a subset so it answers your question — calculate, sort, filter, query, chart.","id":345},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"🛡️ Validate","text":"\"Is it reasonable?\" Check incoming data is sensible before it's accepted — existence, type and range checks stop garbage getting in.","id":346},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"✓ Test","text":"\"Did it work?\" Prove your solution behaves correctly using a test table of expected vs actual results, and verify charts match their data.","id":347},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"The kitchen analogy","text":"Manipulating is the cooking — chopping, mixing and plating raw ingredients into a dish. Validating is the quality check at the door — rejecting a delivery of off milk before it ever reaches the kitchen. Testing is tasting before you serve — confirming the dish is actually what the recipe promised. Skip any one and a customer gets a nasty surprise. Validation happens at the point of entry and asks \"is this value reasonable ?\" — it can never guarantee a value is true . A perfectly reasonable quantity of 3 still passes validation even if the student actually bought 5 . Testing happens after you build, and asks \"does my solution produce the expected result?\"","id":348},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Lab A · The data pipeline","text":"Watch a raw order travel through all three stations. Click a machine to see its job.","id":349},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Manipulating data","text":"Three tool-sets do the heavy lifting — and the study design names all three. To manipulate data means to change its form, organisation or content so it answers a question. In VCE Applied Computing you do this with three software tool-sets, each suited to a different job:","id":350},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"ƒ Formulas & functions","text":"Inside a spreadsheet . Calculate new values, combine text, look things up, sort and filter rows.","id":351},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"⌗ SQL queries","text":"Inside a relational database . Select exactly the rows and columns you need from large tables — fast.","id":352},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"▦ Charts & graphs","text":"In a spreadsheet or visualisation tool . Turn rows of numbers into a shape the eye can read instantly. A real workflow usually chains them: SQL pulls the right slice out of a big database → you import it into a spreadsheet → formulas refine and calculate → a chart presents the finding. Mia uses exactly this path below.","id":353},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Formulas & functions","text":"Mia's raw export, refined one column at a time. A formula is any expression you type into a cell that starts with = . A function is a named, built-in operation (like SUM or IF ) you use inside a formula. Here is Mia's raw SnackTrack export — the till gave her quantity and unit price, but not the line totals she needs. Click any amber cell to see the formula that built it: A · Item B · Qty C · Unit $ D · Line total Sausage roll 3.50 10.50 Juice box 2.00 10.00 Muffin 3.00 6.00 Water 1.50 6.00 TOTAL 32.50 The four manipulation moves you'll be expected to recognise:","id":354},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"① Calculate","text":"Derive new values: =B2*C2 for a line total, =SUM(D2:D5) for a grand total, =D2/$D$6 for each item's share.","id":355},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"② Combine / look up","text":"=CONCAT(A2,\" ×\",B2) builds a label; =VLOOKUP(A2,menu,3,0) fetches a price from the menu table.","id":356},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"③ Decide with logic","text":"=IF(D2>10,\"Big order\",\"Small\") tags rows by a rule — the spreadsheet equivalent of an if statement.","id":357},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"④ Sort & filter","text":"Reorder rows by line total (descending) to surface top sellers; filter to Category = Drink to focus a question. When Mia copies =D2/$D$6 down the column, D2 shifts to D3 , D4 … (relative) but $D$6 stays locked on the total (absolute). Mixing these up is the single most common spreadsheet bug — and a favourite exam target.","id":358},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"SQL queries","text":"When the data lives in a database, you ask for what you want in Structured Query Language. A spreadsheet is fine for a few hundred rows, but a term's worth of orders lives in a relational database . SQL (Structured Query Language) lets Mia request exactly the rows and columns she needs without scrolling. Every query you'll meet at this level is built from four clauses: Try it on Mia's orders table. Change the clauses and watch both the query and the result update live: item category qty Pie Hot Juice box Drink Water Drink Sausage roll Hot Muffin Bakery Apple Fruit Say it as a sentence:","id":359},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"SQL queries","text":"\" Select these columns from this table where this condition is true, ordered by this column. \" If you can narrate a query in plain English, you can usually write one. Watch out for the string-vs-number rule: text values need quotes ( WHERE category = 'Drink' ) but numbers do not ( WHERE qty > 3 ).","id":360},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Charts & graphs","text":"A chart is a manipulation too — it turns a column of numbers into a shape you read in a second. Once the totals are calculated, Mia builds a chart so the canteen manager can see top sellers at a glance. Choosing the right chart matters: a bar/column chart compares categories, a line chart shows change over time, and a pie chart shows parts of a whole. Toggle the data below and watch the bars rebuild in 3D:","id":361},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Validating data","text":"Three checks decide whether a value is reasonable enough to let in. Validation is the process of checking that data entered into a solution is reasonable, complete and sensible — done at the point of entry , before the value is stored. It can't prove a value is true ; it only blocks the obviously wrong. The three techniques you must know by name:","id":362},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"∃ Existence check","text":"Is there a value at all? A required field can't be left blank. \"Item name must not be empty.\"","id":363},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"# Type check","text":"Is it the right kind of data? Quantity must be a number , not text. \" five is rejected; 5 is accepted.\"","id":364},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"⟚ Range check","text":"Is the value within sensible limits? \"Quantity must be between 1 and 50.\" Blocks -2 and 999 . Validation only catches the unreasonable . If Mia types 3 sausage rolls when she really sold 5 , every check passes — the value is reasonable, just wrong. Catching that kind of error needs verification (e.g. double-entry or proofreading against the source), which is a different idea. In a spreadsheet you set it with Data Validation rules (whole number, between 1 and 50). In a database you set field properties and validation rules on the table, so bad records are rejected on import. Same three checks, two homes.","id":365},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Lab B · The validation gates","text":"Build an order record, then send it through three gates. Will it survive? Set the three properties of an incoming order, then press send . The record (a glowing cube) flies toward three gates — Existence, Type, Range. A green gate lets it pass; a red gate bounces it back. Make it through all three and the record is accepted into the database.","id":366},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Testing data","text":"A formula that runs isn't the same as a formula that's right . Prove it with a test table. Once Mia has built her formulas, queries and chart, she has to test them. The standard tool is a test table with four columns. You choose deliberate test data — including tricky edge cases — work out the expected result by hand, run it, and compare. Test # Description Test data Expected Actual Line total multiplies correctly Qty 3 × $3.50 10.50 10.50 Grand total sums all lines 10.50+10+6+6 32.50 32.50 Range check blocks too-large qty Enter 999 Rejected Accepted Boundary:","id":367},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Testing data","text":"qty = 50 (max allowed) Enter 50 Accepted Accepted T3's mismatch is the whole point of testing: it exposed that Mia's range rule was set to <1000 instead of <=50 . Without the test, that bug ships.","id":368},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Choose test data on purpose","text":"Cover valid (normal), invalid (should be rejected) and boundary (right on the limit — 0, 1, 50, 51) cases. Boundaries catch the most bugs.","id":369},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Expected before actual","text":"Work out the expected result by hand first . If you fill it in after running the solution, you're just copying the output, not testing it. Validation guards the input at entry time. Testing checks the whole solution after you build it. A range check is validation; confirming that range check actually fires is testing.","id":370},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Lab C · Verify the chart","text":"Testing isn't only for formulas — a finished visualisation must match its data too. Mia's chart software re-typed one value by mistake, so a bar no longer matches the spreadsheet. Verifying a visualisation means checking every bar against its source value — exactly the kind of question VCAA loves. The data table is correct. Click the bar that doesn't match its number. Item Source value Sausage roll 10.50 Juice box 10.00 Muffin 6.00 Water 6.00","id":371},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Exam traps","text":"The mix-ups that quietly cost marks. Learn the name, dodge the trap.","id":372},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"\"Validation\" used to mean \"make it correct\"","text":"Validation only checks data is reasonable , never true . Fix: say validation \"checks data is sensible at entry\"; use verification for checking against the real source.","id":373},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Naming the wrong three checks","text":"The trio is existence, type, range . Students invent \"format check\" or \"length check\" (real, but not the named three). Fix: memorise existence · type · range.","id":374},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Confusing manipulate / validate / test","text":"They answer different questions: reshape it · is it reasonable · did it work. Fix: tie each to its question before you write.","id":375},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"SQL string quotes dropped","text":"Text values in WHERE need single quotes ( = 'Drink' ); numbers don't. Fix: quote text, leave numbers bare.","id":376},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Filling \"Expected\" after running","text":"Copying the output into the expected column proves nothing. Fix: always calculate expected by hand first .","id":377},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Forgetting boundary test data","text":"\"Test it works\" with one normal value misses the bugs. Fix: include valid, invalid and boundary cases (0, 1, max, max+1).","id":378},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Structure every short-answer like an examiner: P oint · E xample · L ink. Pick a concept to see it modelled. Markers award the Point (the definition/term), the Example (it proves you can apply it — usually worth its own mark) and the Link (ties it back to the scenario, which separates a C from an A). Most students give only the Point and cap themselves at half marks.","id":379},{"file":"u1o1-kk12.html","nav":"u1o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Manipulating & validating data","head":"Exam practice","text":"Five VCAA-style questions · 20 marks. Read each, attempt it, then reveal a weak and strong response and self-mark. Distinguish between validating data and testing a solution. Name and describe three validation techniques. For each, give an example based on a canteen order quantity. Mia's orders table has columns item, category, qty, price . A bar in Mia's finished chart shows a value that does not match the spreadsheet it was built from. Mia exports a raw file of Friday's canteen orders. Describe how she would manipulate , validate and test this data to produce a reliable \"top sellers\" chart. Refer to specific functions or techniques for each stage.","id":380},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Descriptive statistics","text":"Turning a pile of raw numbers into a few honest summary figures — using spreadsheet functions to calculate the average , median , count/frequency and standard deviation , and knowing which one actually answers the question. Use spreadsheet functions to calculate average, median, count/frequency and standard deviation . The skill examiners reward is twofold: pick the right statistic for the question , then interpret what the number means for the data — not just quote a formula.","id":381},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Meet the scenario: Sip — Leo's school cart","text":"Leo , a Year 11 student, runs Sip , a smoothie & coffee cart at PVCC's Friday markets. For one busy morning he records the wait time in seconds for each customer and the drink they ordered. He wants to answer four questions — and each one needs a different statistic: We'll use Leo's data the whole way through, so every formula has a real reason to exist.","id":382},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Why summarise at all?","text":"Leo served 11 customers before recess. Their wait times (seconds), already sorted, were: Customer Wait (s) 215 You could hand someone all 11 numbers. But nobody reads a spreadsheet to \"get a feel\" for it. Descriptive statistics compress a dataset into a handful of figures that describe it — its centre, its spread, its counts — so a human can understand it at a glance. The catch: different summaries tell different stories , and a careless choice can mislead. A film with 40,000 reviews shows you one star rating — say 4.2.","id":383},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Why summarise at all?","text":"That single number is a descriptive statistic: it summarises 40,000 opinions so you can decide in a second. But it hides whether everyone agreed (all 4s) or the crowd was split (half 1s, half 5s averaging to 4.2). Centre (average) and spread (standard deviation) together tell the real story. Leo's morning is exactly this problem in miniature.","id":384},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Average (the mean)","text":"The average — properly the mean — is the balance point of the data. Add every value, divide by how many there are. In a spreadsheet: For Leo's 11 customers: 38+39+…+215 = 652 , divided by 11 = 59.3 seconds . Ten of Leo's eleven customers waited under a minute . Yet the mean says \"59 seconds\" — because the single 215-second catering order drags the balance point to the right . Every value tugs on the mean, so one outlier (an extreme value) can pull it well away from where most of the data actually sits.","id":385},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Average (the mean)","text":"That's the whole reason the median exists. Picture each wait time as a child sitting on a see-saw, at the position of their value. The mean is where you'd put the pivot so the plank balances . Move one child far out to the end (the 215 catering order) and the pivot has to slide a long way toward them to keep balance — even though nobody else moved. The next lab lets you feel exactly that.","id":386},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Lab · the balance beam","text":"Each ball is one of Leo's wait times sitting at its value along the beam. The amber pivot auto-slides to the mean (the balance point). The blue ball is the median (the positional middle). Drag the slider to grow that one catering order and watch what happens.","id":387},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Median","text":"The median is the middle value when the data is sorted in order. It cares only about position , not size — so an extreme value can't drag it around. Odd count (Leo's 11 values): the median is the single middle one — the 6th value = 44 s . Even count (say 10 values): there's no single middle, so you average the two middle values .","id":388},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Mean = 59.3 s","text":"Pulled up ~15 s by one catering order. If Leo reports this as \"typical wait\", customers think the cart is slow.","id":389},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Median = 44 s","text":"Half waited less, half waited more. A fairer \"typical wait\" because the rare big order can't distort it. When data is skewed or has outliers , the median is the better measure of \"typical\". When data is roughly symmetric with no extreme values, the mean uses all the data and is usually preferred. Saying which and why is where the marks are.","id":390},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Count & frequency","text":"Centre statistics answer \"how big\". Count and frequency answer \"how many\". They sound the same but examiners separate them:","id":391},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Count","text":"How many entries in total (or how many meet one test). Leo had 40 orders all morning.","id":392},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Frequency","text":"How many fall into each category . Split those 40 orders by drink type → a frequency table .","id":393},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Leo's morning, by drink","text":"Drink (category) Frequency Spreadsheet function Smoothie =COUNTIF(C2:C41,\"Smoothie\") Coffee =COUNTIF(C2:C41,\"Coffee\") Juice =COUNTIF(C2:C41,\"Juice\") Total orders =COUNTA(C2:C41) COUNT counts numbers only (ignores text). COUNTA counts any non-empty cell (text or numbers). COUNTIF counts cells that meet a condition — the engine of every frequency table. Mixing these up is a classic lost mark. Count is the bouncer's clicker at the door — total people in. Frequency is the cloakroom tally — how many coats, how many bags, how many umbrellas. Same crowd, sorted into buckets.","id":394},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Standard deviation","text":"The mean tells you the centre. Standard deviation (SD) tells you the spread — on average, how far the values sit from the mean. A small SD means the data is tightly clustered ( consistent ); a large SD means it's widely scattered ( unpredictable ). You will never hand-calculate SD in this course. You choose the function, then interpret the result . That's the examinable skill.","id":395},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Same average, totally different experience","text":"Two of Leo's helpers each served 8 customers. Both averaged exactly 43 seconds. The mean alone says they're identical — but they're not: Helper Wait times (s) Mean Feel Mia 40 42 44 46 43 45 41 43 43.0 2.0 Steady, predictable Sam 20 66 38 48 25 61 30 56 43.0 17.3 A lottery Two players both average dead-centre. One lands every dart in a tight cluster (low SD); the other sprays them around the board but they happen to average to the bullseye (high SD). The average score is the same; the consistency is night and day. SD is the size of the cluster.","id":396},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Lab · the spread-o-meter","text":"Every dot is a wait time, floating around the fixed mean line (43 s) . Drag the slider to spread the dots out — the ±1 SD band grows and the SD readout climbs, while the mean never moves . That's the point: spread and centre are independent .","id":397},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Choosing the right statistic","text":"This is the part exams actually test. Match the question being asked to the statistic that answers it honestly . Strong analysis rarely uses one statistic. Mean + SD describes a clean dataset (\"typical and how spread\"). Median + range describes a skewed one. Frequency turns categories into charts. Examiners love a response that reports a centre and a spread and explains the choice.","id":398},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Spreadsheet function reference","text":"The exact functions for KK13, plus the close companions examiners expect you to recognise. Function Returns Example Leo's result AVERAGE Mean of numbers =AVERAGE(B2:B12) 59.3 s MEDIAN Middle value (sorted) =MEDIAN(B2:B12) 44 s COUNT How many numbers =COUNT(B2:B12) COUNTA How many non-empty cells =COUNTA(C2:C41) COUNTIF How many meet a condition =COUNTIF(C2:C41,\"Coffee\") STDEV.S SD of a sample =STDEV.S(B2:B12) 51.8 s STDEV.P SD of a whole population =STDEV.P(B2:B12) 49.4 s SUM Total =SUM(B2:B12) 652 s MAX / MIN Largest / smallest =MAX(B2:B12) 215 / 38 ① Write the = sign — a formula without it is just text.","id":399},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Spreadsheet function reference","text":"② Reference the cell range ( B2:B12 ), never retype the numbers, so it updates live. ③ When you copy a formula, use $ to lock a cell you don't want shifting (e.g. =B2/$B$13 for a percentage of total).","id":400},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Named exam traps","text":"Quoting the mean for skewed data (Leo's 59 s) and calling it typical. → Spot the outlier/skew, switch to the median, and say why . Using STDEV.P on a sample (or vice versa) and giving no reason. → Measured everyone = population ( .P ); measured some = sample ( .S ). VCE data is usually a sample. Using COUNT on a column of drink names and getting 0 — because COUNT ignores text. → Text? Use COUNTA (any non-empty) or COUNTIF (by category). Answering \"how many of each drink\" with a single total instead of a per-category breakdown.","id":401},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"Named exam traps","text":"→ \"Of each\" = frequency = a value per category, not one grand total. Writing \"SD = 51.8\" with no units and no meaning. → Add units and interpret: \"SD ≈ 52 s — very high, so wait times were inconsistent (driven by the catering order).\" Listing every statistic instead of the one the question asked for. → Read the command word. Calculate wants a value; justify/explain wants the value and the reasoning.","id":402},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure , not length. Use P·E·L : make a Point , give a concrete Example from the data, then Link back to what was asked. Click a statistic to see a model paragraph.","id":403},{"file":"u1o1-kk13.html","nav":"u1o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Descriptive statistics","head":"VCAA-style practice questions","text":"Five questions, 17 marks total. Try each in your head or on paper first, then reveal the weak response, the strong response, the examiner's note and the marking guide. Self-mark honestly — your score builds in the dock.","id":404},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Why are you making this chart?","text":"Before a single colour is chosen or a single bar is drawn, every good data visualisation answers one question: what is it for? This module is the 14th key-knowledge point of the Data Analysis chapter — the purposes of data visualisations . \" The purposes of data visualisations — to educate, entertain, inform and persuade an audience. \" All four are examinable. You must be able to identify the purpose of a given visualisation and justify your choice using its design features. GreenLoop is a student-run sustainability program at a secondary college.","id":405},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Why are you making this chart?","text":"The data team has one spreadsheet — a term's worth of waste & recycling data (bins weighed each week, by building and material). Watch how that single dataset becomes four completely different visualisations, depending on who's looking and why. Same numbers. Different jobs.","id":406},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Purpose is decided before you design","text":"A common beginner mistake is to make a chart and then ask what it's for. The study design flips that. Purpose is part of the solution requirements — it's settled in the Analysis stage of the problem-solving methodology, long before you open the software. Purpose then drives every later design choice: chart type, colours, fonts, how much text, how the data is framed. Think of a film director. They don't film random footage and then decide whether it's a comedy or a documentary. They decide the genre first, and every shot serves it. Your visualisation's purpose is its genre. Pick it first; let it command the rest.","id":407},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Purpose answers two questions","text":"Who is the audience (their knowledge, their stake)? and what do you want them to walk away with — understanding, a feeling, the facts, or a decision?","id":408},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"One visualisation, one dominant purpose","text":"A visualisation can do a little of several things, but in an exam you name the primary purpose and justify it. \"It informs and persuades\" without choosing a dominant one usually loses marks.","id":409},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"The four purposes","text":"Memorise these four — and crucially, the difference between them. A quick hook: \"Every Eager Intern Persuades\" → E ducate, E ntertain, I nform, P ersuade.","id":410},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Change minds or behaviour","text":"Educate = \"now I understand it.\" Entertain = \"that was fun.\" Inform = \"now I know the facts.\" Persuade = \"now I want to act.\" If you can finish the sentence the audience would say, you've found the purpose.","id":411},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Lab — the Purpose Prism","text":"Here is the central idea in one picture. The GreenLoop dataset (left) enters a prism and splits into four outputs — one per purpose. Choose a purpose below and watch the same data get reshaped for a different job. Notice: the numbers never change; the design does.","id":412},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Lab — how a fact becomes a weapon","text":"The line between inform and persuade is the most-tested idea in this dot point — and it often comes down to one design choice: where the axis starts. Below is GreenLoop's recycling rate for four weeks: 62%, 64%, 66%, 69%. A real, modest rise. Toggle the y-axis baseline and watch the same numbers go from \"honest\" to \"dramatic\". A truncated (cut-off) axis isn't always \"wrong\" — but it shifts the purpose toward persuade , because it's chosen to create an impression rather than to report neutrally. If a question asks you to evaluate whether a visualisation informs , a misleading axis is your evidence that it leans toward persuade instead.","id":413},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"The subtle pair — educate vs inform","text":"Both deal in facts and aim to be accurate, so students mix them up. The split is about what the audience does with it.","id":414},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Educate → teaches","text":"Builds understanding of how/why. The audience comes away able to do or explain something. Tends to be sequenced, annotated, with the \"mechanism\" shown. Tell-tale: arrows, steps, labels explaining a process; \"here's how it works\".","id":415},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Inform → reports","text":"States the current facts / state of affairs. The audience comes away knowing what is , not necessarily how it works. Tends to be a snapshot or trend. Tell-tale: dashboards, status charts, \"here's where things stand right now\". Educate: a flow showing how a plastic bottle is sorted, washed, shredded and re-pelletised. Inform: a chart showing how many bottles were collected each week. One teaches the process; the other reports the count.","id":416},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"The dangerous pair — spotting persuade","text":"Persuade is the purpose with an agenda . The data may be accurate, but it's framed to push you toward a viewpoint or an action. Learn the design \"tells\" — these are exactly what examiners reward you for naming.","id":417},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"① A point of view","text":"It's clearly \"for\" or \"against\" something. Inform stays neutral; persuade takes a side.","id":418},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"② A call to action","text":"\"Switch now\", \"Vote yes\", \"Bring a reusable\". An explicit ask to the audience is a dead giveaway.","id":419},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"③ Emotive language & colour","text":"Alarming reds, big bold words, shock numbers (\"9,000 bottles!\") chosen to make you feel .","id":420},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"④ Selective / framed data","text":"Truncated axes, cherry-picked time ranges, \"1 in 3\" framing — the data that supports the case is foregrounded. A persuasive visualisation can be completely truthful. Persuasion is about intent and framing , not falsehood. When framing crosses into distorting the facts, it becomes misleading — but the underlying purpose is still to persuade.","id":421},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Name that purpose","text":"Eight real-world style visualisations. Read each, then tap the purpose you think dominates. You'll get instant feedback and the examiner's reasoning. Every correct answer adds to your score dock.","id":422},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Match the design choice to the purpose","text":"Purpose drives design. Tap a design choice on the left, then the purpose it best serves on the right. Correct pairs lock in.","id":423},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Quick-recall cards","text":"Tap to flip. Use these for last-minute revision the night before an exam.","id":424},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Educate","text":"\"Now I understand how/why it works.\" Teaches a concept or skill with steps and annotations.","id":425},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Entertain","text":"\"That was fun!\" Playful, personalised, emotion-first — precision is secondary.","id":426},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Inform","text":"\"Now I know the current facts.\" Neutral, accurate, lets the audience judge.","id":427},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Persuade","text":"\"Now I want to act.\" A viewpoint + call to action, framed to move you.","id":428},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Inform vs Persuade","text":"A call to action or selective framing → persuade. Neutral, balanced, honest axes → inform.","id":429},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Where is purpose decided?","text":"Analysis. Purpose is part of the solution requirements and drives every later design choice.","id":430},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"Six exam traps","text":"The mistakes that quietly cost marks. Read them now so you don't make them under pressure. Confusing inform and persuade because both \"show data\". Saying a visualisation \"does all four purposes\" to play it safe. Treating educate and inform as identical because both are factual. Thinking persuade means the data is fake or wrong. Identifying a purpose but giving no evidence from the visualisation. Forgetting entertain exists, so labelling a playful \"Wrapped\"-style card as inform.","id":431},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"\"Identify and justify the purpose\" questions reward a tight structure. Use P·E·L : Point (name the purpose) → Evidence (a design feature you can see) → Link (how that feature serves that purpose for that audience). Draft each part; the meter fills as your answer gains the keywords examiners look for. GreenLoop releases a bright red poster reading \"9,000 bottles wasted this term. Bring a reusable — start Monday.\" with a giant arrow to a pledge form. Identify the purpose of this visualisation and justify your answer with reference to its design. (3 marks)","id":432},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Five questions, 17 marks total. Try each yourself first. Then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide — and self-mark honestly. Your total tracks in the dock. 1 mark for naming two correct purposes. 2 marks for naming all four: educate, entertain, inform, persuade. No marks for descriptions like 'to look nice' instead of a named purpose. 1 mark: correctly identifies the purpose as inform. 1 mark: first valid design feature (e.g. neutral/honest axes, plain labels). 1 mark: second valid feature OR explaining the absence of persuasion (no call to action/emotive framing).","id":433},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Identifying inform with no design evidence caps the answer at 1 mark. 1 mark: A identified as educate. 1 mark: design feature of A linked to educating (steps/labels teaching how). 1 mark: B identified as persuade. 1 mark: design feature of B linked to persuading (call to action / emotive shock figure). Top answers note the same data serves different purposes. 1 mark: identifies the axis as truncated / not starting at zero. 1 mark: explains the visual effect (small change exaggerated). 1 mark: links this to a shift in purpose toward persuade (away from inform).","id":434},{"file":"u1o1-kk14.html","nav":"u1o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Why are you making this chart?","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"1 mark: states the risk — misleading the audience / distorted decisions / lost credibility. 1 mark: judgement that the statement is incorrect / too absolute. 1 mark: explains persuade is a valid purpose based on framing/intent, not falsehood. 1 mark: gives a supporting example (truthful but persuasive). 1 mark: acknowledges persuasion CAN become misleading, distinguishing framing from distortion.","id":435},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Three ways to show the same story","text":"You've cleaned the data, run the stats, found the pattern. Now comes the decision that earns marks: which type of data visualisation do you actually build? The same numbers can become a tall scrolling infographic , a wall of posters , or a live dashboard — and picking the wrong one for the audience loses the message. This dot point is about the types of data visualisations used to present findings to an audience: infographics (long-form) , a series of infographic posters , and dashboards . You need to describe each one, tell them apart, and — most importantly — choose and justify the right type for a given audience and purpose.","id":436},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Three ways to show the same story","text":"A Year 11 Applied Computing class surveys 180 senior students about their weekly screen time , the app categories they use, and how it affects their sleep . Same dataset, three audiences: the whole school at assembly, a \"Digital Wellbeing Week\" corridor display, and the wellbeing coordinator who wants to watch the numbers as surveys keep arriving. Each audience needs a different type of visualisation — that's this whole module.","id":437},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Same ingredients, three different dishes","text":"Think of your dataset as a basket of ingredients. The purpose (KK14 — to inform, persuade, educate or entertain) is why you're cooking. The components (KK16 — charts, tables, text, graphics) are the ingredients . This dot point, KK15, is the dish you serve — the overall form the visualisation takes. Same eggs and flour can become a cake, a stack of pancakes, or a buffet of small plates. Choosing the dish is choosing the type . Two questions decide the type almost every time. Slide each one in your head when a scenario lands:","id":438},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Same ingredients, three different dishes","text":"A printed poster freezes the data the day you publish it. A dashboard can update as new data arrives and let the viewer filter and drill in. If the user needs to interact or the data keeps changing , you're heading toward a dashboard. A long-form infographic is one cohesive story read top-to-bottom. A series of posters breaks the story into separate, self-contained pieces that can be spread across a space or shown one at a time. Need it to live as independent chunks ? That's a poster series. Read it — a long-form infographic you scroll or read down in one sitting.","id":439},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Same ingredients, three different dishes","text":"Walk it — a poster series you walk past, each poster a stop. Watch it — a dashboard you keep an eye on as the numbers change. If you can decide which verb fits the audience, you've picked the type.","id":440},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Long-form infographic","text":"A single, usually tall, static graphic that tells one complete story from top to bottom. It blends short text, statistics, icons, images and a few charts into one continuous flow. You meet these every day: the tall posts that fill your social feed, a \"year in review\", a public-health poster on a wall. › One continuous narrative — a clear start, middle and conclusion, read in order. › Static — fixed once published; the data doesn't update and the viewer can't filter it. › Self-contained — text, stats, images and charts together so it stands alone with no explanation.","id":441},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Long-form infographic","text":"› Tall layout — usually vertical, designed to be scrolled or read down a single page. Best when: you want to broadcast one message to a wide audience in a single hit — and you don't need them to interact. ScreenWise use: the student leaders build one tall \"Where did our week go?\" infographic to post on the school socials and show at assembly.","id":442},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"A series of infographic posters","text":"Instead of one tall graphic, you split the story into a set of separate posters , each carrying one sub-theme or angle. They share a look and feel so they read as a family, but each poster works on its own. Think of a museum exhibit or a corridor campaign where each panel is its own stop. › Modular — a collection of standalone pieces, not one continuous scroll. › One idea per poster — each focuses on a single trend so it's digestible at a glance. › Consistent style — shared colours, fonts and layout tie the set together as one campaign.","id":443},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"A series of infographic posters","text":"› Spread across space or time — displayed along a corridor, around a room, or as a slideshow. Best when: the audience encounters the message in pieces, in different places or over several days, and you want each piece to land on its own. ScreenWise use: a \"Digital Wellbeing Week\" set — Monday's poster is total hours, Tuesday's is top apps, Wednesday's is the sleep link — one per day down the senior corridor.","id":444},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Dashboard","text":"A single screen that brings several views of the data together as panels (or \"widgets\") so you can monitor everything at a glance. Dashboards are usually dynamic : they refresh as new data arrives and let the viewer filter, switch date ranges or drill into detail. Think of a car's dashboard, a sports scoreboard, or the analytics screen behind a YouTube channel. › Multiple coordinated panels — several charts and key numbers tiled on one screen. › At-a-glance monitoring — designed to be scanned quickly and often, not read once.","id":445},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Dashboard","text":"› Dynamic & interactive — updates with live data; viewers filter, sort and drill down. › Audience of decision-makers — built for someone who acts on the numbers regularly. Best when: the data keeps arriving and a person needs to track it and make ongoing decisions. ScreenWise use: the wellbeing coordinator opens a dashboard that updates as more students submit — average hours, top apps, a sleep gauge — and filters by year level whenever she likes.","id":446},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Dashboard ≠ \"must be a computer screen\"","text":"Most dashboards are digital and live, but the defining trait is multiple coordinated views for monitoring , not the device. Don't define a dashboard by saying \"it's on a screen\" — define it by what it does: pulls several panels together so you can watch the whole picture at once.","id":447},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Pour the data into a different mould","text":"Below is one dataset — the coloured blocks are the screen-time , app-usage , sleep and mood fields from ScreenWise. The numbers never change. Press a button and watch the same blocks reorganise into each type. That reshaping is KK15: one dataset, three visualisation types.","id":448},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"The three types, side by side","text":"This table is your exam anchor. If a question asks you to compare two types or pick between them, every row here is a point of difference you can lean on. Feature Long-form infographic Poster series Dashboard Structure One tall, continuous graphic A set of separate, linked posters Many panels tiled on one screen Static or dynamic Static — fixed when published Static — each poster fixed Usually dynamic — updates live Interaction None — you read it None — you walk past it Filter, sort, drill down Story shape Single narrative, start to end One idea per poster Whole picture at a glance Audience Wide public, one-time read Audience moving through a space Decision-makers, repeat viewing Best verb Read it Walk it Watch it ScreenWise Assembly + socials post Wellbeing Week corridor Coordinator's live monitor","id":449},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"The decision tool","text":"Answer the two axis questions and the tool names the type — and, just as importantly, the reason . Exam answers that name a type without a reason cap out fast; the reason is where the marks live. A fixed message split into standalone pieces suits a set of posters — one idea each, spread across a space.","id":450},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Now sort the scenarios","text":"Drag each brief into the type you'd recommend. They snap back if they're in the wrong bin — read the brief for the two clues (live-or-fixed, one-story-or-many).","id":451},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Confusing the type with the purpose","text":"KK14 is purpose (inform, persuade, educate, entertain). KK15 is the form (infographic, poster series, dashboard). \"It informs the audience\" answers the wrong dot point. Fix: name the form, then link it to the audience.","id":452},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Calling everything \"an infographic\"","text":"A dashboard is not an infographic, and a poster series is not \"one infographic\". Use the precise term the study design uses. Fix: long-form infographic / series of infographic posters / dashboard — say which.","id":453},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Naming a type but not justifying it","text":"\"A dashboard\" on its own is usually one mark of several. Examiners want why this type suits the audience . Fix: tie the choice to a feature — \"live updates suit ongoing monitoring\".","id":454},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Forgetting to say why the other type is unsuitable","text":"\"Select and justify\" questions often need you to rule out the alternative too. A past exam awarded full marks only when students said why the rejected option didn't fit. Fix: add one line — \"an infographic is static, so it can't show the live updates the coach needs\".","id":455},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Describing components instead of the type","text":"Listing \"it has charts, a title and some text\" describes KK16 components, not which type it is. Fix: describe the overall structure — tall single graphic vs. set of posters vs. tiled panels.","id":456},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"Defining a dashboard by its device","text":"\"It's on a computer\" isn't the defining trait. Fix: define it by multiple coordinated panels for at-a-glance, ongoing monitoring.","id":457},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure, not length. Use P oint → E xample → L ink. Click each step to build a full-mark answer to: \"The wellbeing coordinator wants to monitor screen-time results as surveys arrive. Recommend a type of data visualisation and justify your choice (3 marks).\" If the question says… It wants you to… Identify / Name / State Just give the correct type — one or two words. No reason needed. Describe Say what the type is and its key features (structure, static/dynamic). Compare / Distinguish Give points of difference between two types — use both sides.","id":458},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Recommend / Select & justify Pick a type, give reasons it fits the audience, and often why the other doesn't. Explain why Link a feature of the type directly to the audience's need.","id":459},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Try each one yourself first. Then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide. Mark your own attempt — your score builds in the dock. 1 mark — long-form = single static graphic, one continuous narrative. 1 mark — dashboard = multiple panels, dynamic/interactive, for monitoring. A genuine point of difference is required, not just naming both. 1 mark — recommends a long-form infographic. 1 mark — feature-based justification (single, static, self-contained story). 1 mark — links the choice to the wide, one-time, shareable audience. 1 mark — describes the poster series (modular, standalone, one idea each).","id":460},{"file":"u1o1-kk15.html","nav":"u1o1-kk15.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK15","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Three ways to show the same story","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 mark — describes the long-form infographic (single continuous story). 1 mark — relates both to the corridor / five-day display context. 1 mark — states and justifies the poster-series choice. 1 mark — recommends a dashboard. 2 marks — justification: multiple coordinated panels, dynamic/updating, interactive filtering, tied to ongoing monitoring (1 each, max 2). 2 marks — explains the infographic is static/fixed and non-interactive, so it cannot show live updates or allow filtering (1 each, max 2). (a) 1 mark type + 1 mark justification (single static broadcast). (b) 1 mark type + 1 mark justification (modular, met in pieces). (c) 1 mark type + 1 mark justification (live, filterable monitoring). Justifications must link a feature of the type to that audience's need.","id":461},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"The three things every visualisation is built from","text":"Open any infographic , dashboard or poster and pull it apart. Underneath, it is always made of the same three component families: text & graphics , tables , and charts & graphs . Knowing what each one is for — and when it is the wrong choice — is what the exam rewards.","id":462},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"A visualisation is an assembly, not a single object","text":"Meet Theo , a Year 11 student. The canteen manager asks him to make a one-page “Canteen Wrapped 2026” — a single visual that sums up the year of canteen sales for the whole school to see on the noticeboard. Theo doesn't reach for \"a chart\" or \"a table\". He reaches for a toolbox of components and chooses the right one for each job on the page. Key knowledge: “components of data visualisations , including text and graphics , tables , and charts and graphs .” You are expected to identify these components, explain the purpose of each, and justify which component suits a given communication purpose and audience .","id":463},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Text & graphics","text":"Tell the reader what they're looking at and what it means.","id":464},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Charts & graphs","text":"Show the pattern, trend or comparison at a glance. Say it with text & graphics · Store it in a table · Show it with a chart. If you can name which of the three jobs the question is really asking about, you can name the right component.","id":465},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"The Assembly Bench","text":"Here is Theo's blank canvas, exploded into its layers. Add each component family one at a time and watch the empty page turn into a finished visualisation. A page with only a chart is a mystery; a page with all three is a message.","id":466},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Text & graphics — the voice of the page","text":"This family does the talking. Without it, a chart is just coloured shapes and a table is a grid of mystery numbers. Text & graphics carry meaning, context and wayfinding . Titles & headings · subheadings · axis labels · data labels · legends/keys · captions · annotations & callouts · units of measurement · source citation · body text. Icons & pictograms · photographs & images · logos & branding · illustrations · arrows/connectors that guide the eye · deliberate use of whitespace. A title, axis labels and a legend are not decoration — they are text components .","id":467},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Text & graphics — the voice of the page","text":"Examiners routinely show a chart with a label missing and ask what's wrong. The answer names the missing text component and the effect: the reader can't tell what is being measured or in what units.","id":468},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Analogy — signposts in a shopping centre","text":"A shopping centre full of shops (the data) is useless without signage. The directory map is your title, the level labels are your axis labels, the colour-coded zones are your legend, and the \"You are here\" dot is an annotation. Remove the signage and shoppers wander lost — exactly what happens to a reader facing an unlabelled chart. Graphics have a job (wayfinding, meaning, accessibility, tone). A graphic that carries no communication purpose — a stock photo of a salad slapped behind the numbers — is chartjunk and counts against the design, not for it.","id":469},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Tables — the exact record","text":"A table arranges values in rows and columns with header cells. Its superpower is precision : the reader can look up one exact figure, or scan many categories across several attributes at once. The audience needs the exact number · values must be auditable / referenced · you're comparing many items across several columns · precision matters more than \"shape\". You want the reader to see a trend or pattern at a glance . A 40-row table hides the story — the eye can't spot the peak. That's a chart's job.","id":470},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Same data, two jobs","text":"Here is part of Theo's weekday sales. The table answers \"exactly how much on Wednesday?\" ; the bars answer \"which day is busiest?\" — neither replaces the other. Notice you spotted \"Friday is biggest\" instantly from the bars, but you had to read the table to learn Wednesday was exactly $534. That's the whole distinction in one picture.","id":471},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Charts & graphs — the picture of the data","text":"Charts turn numbers into position, length, angle and colour so the eye can read patterns the brain would never spot in a table. The skill examiners test is matching the chart type to the question being asked.","id":472},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"The chart types VCAA expects you to know","text":"Compare → bar. Over time → line. Of a whole → pie. Distribution → histogram. Relationship → scatter. Pick the chart whose shape answers the reader's question.","id":473},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Right tool for the job","text":"This is the exact judgement the exam tests. Read the communication goal, then click the component that does that job best. Get instant feedback — and a reason.","id":474},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Which family does it belong to?","text":"Drag (or tap, then tap a bucket) each item from Theo's page into the component family it belongs to. Then check your answers.","id":475},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"The one-line job of each component","text":"Tap a card to flip it. Front = the component; back = its job, when to use it, and when not to.","id":476},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Text & graphics","text":"Give meaning, context and wayfinding — titles, labels, legends, icons, annotations. Always — every chart and table needs labels to make sense. It's decorative only and carries no message (chartjunk).","id":477},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Tables","text":"Present exact values in rows & columns for precise lookup. The audience needs the precise figure or many attributes side by side. You need a trend or comparison seen at a glance.","id":478},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Charts & graphs","text":"Reveal patterns, trends, comparisons and proportions visually. The reader needs the \"shape\" of the data fast. Exact values are required — read-off precision is poor.","id":479},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Wrong tool for the purpose","text":"Using a chart when the reader needs an exact figure , or a giant table when they need the pattern . Fix: match the component to the stated communication purpose and audience — and say so in your answer.","id":480},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Confusing chart types","text":"Calling a histogram a \"bar chart\", or using a pie chart for change over time . Fix: bar = compare categories; histogram = distribution (bins touch); line = trend over time; pie = parts of a whole at one moment.","id":481},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Forgetting labels are components","text":"Treating a title, axis labels and legend as \"just formatting\". They are text components with a job. Fix: if asked what a chart is missing, name the missing text component and its effect on the reader.","id":482},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"\"Graphics = decoration\"","text":"Dismissing icons, images and whitespace as fluff. Fix: graphics aid wayfinding, accessibility and meaning — but only when they carry a purpose. Purposeless graphics are a fault, not a feature.","id":483},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Mixing up component and type","text":"Answering \"a dashboard\" when asked for a component . A dashboard, infographic or poster is a type of visualisation (KK15). The components inside it are text&graphics, tables, charts&graphs (KK16). Fix: read whether the question asks about the whole artefact or its building blocks.","id":484},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Naming without justifying","text":"Writing \"use a bar chart\" with no reason. Identify questions want the name; justify/recommend questions want the name plus why it fits the purpose and why alternatives are weaker. Fix: always tie the component back to the audience's need.","id":485},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Quick-fire quiz","text":"Five questions. Pick an answer to lock it in and see why.","id":486},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"VCE justify/recommend answers score best with Point → Explain → Link . Write a response to the prompt below; the trainer lights up as you include the ideas a marker looks for.","id":487},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Practice questions","text":"A fresh scenario, the way the exam does it. Attempt each in your head or on paper, then reveal the weak vs strong responses and the marking guide. Use the dial (bottom-right) to track your self-marked total out of 22 . The school library is building “ReadRadar” , a one-page visual for students summarising the year's borrowing: total loans each month, the share of loans by genre, and the top-borrowed books. The audience is students glancing at it in the library foyer, plus library staff who need exact figures for their annual report.","id":488},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Practice questions","text":"Identify / State = name it, no reason needed · Describe = name + detail · Explain = give the why/how · Justify / Recommend = choose + defend, ideally noting why alternatives are weaker · Evaluate = weigh strengths against limitations to a judgement. 1 mark for correctly naming all three families (text & graphics; tables; charts & graphs). 1 mark for a valid example of each drawn from the scenario. 1 mark — recommends a table. 1 mark — justifies with exact-value lookup / precision for the report audience.","id":489},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark — explains a chart is less suitable because it shows approximate, not exact, values. 1 mark — line graph for the monthly trend; 1 mark — justified (continuous/time data, shows change). 1 mark — bar/column chart for genre comparison; 1 mark — justified (discrete categories, compares size). 1 mark — identifies the missing elements (title, axis labels, legend). 1 mark — classifies them as text components / text & graphics. 1 mark — explains the impact: reader can't interpret what/units/categories. 1–2 marks — identifies genuine roles of graphics (wayfinding, recognition, tone, accessibility, whitespace).","id":490},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark — acknowledges purposeless/decorative graphics (chartjunk) can be removed. 1 mark — reaches a balanced judgement (keep purposeful, cut purposeless). 1 mark each (×3) — a valid, scenario-specific use of text & graphics, a table, and charts/graphs. 1–2 marks — explains the distinct job each does that the others can't. 1 mark — links the combination to serving the mixed student/staff audience better than any single component.","id":491},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"The three component families","text":"Component Job — one line Reach for it when… Text & graphics Say it — meaning, context, wayfinding Always: titles, labels, legends, icons, annotations Tables Store it — exact values, precise lookup The audience needs the precise figure / many attributes Charts & graphs Show it — patterns, trends, comparisons The reader needs the \"shape\" of the data at a glance","id":492},{"file":"u1o1-kk16.html","nav":"u1o1-kk16.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK16","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"The three things every visualisation is built from","head":"Pick the chart by the question","text":"Question Chart Compare separate categories? Bar / column Change over time? Line graph Parts of a whole? Pie / donut Distribution of one variable? Histogram Relationship between two variables? Scatter plot Golden line for the exam: name the component, explain the job it does, and link it to the audience's purpose — then, for justify questions, say why the alternatives are weaker.","id":493},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Formats & conventions","text":"The same data can look professional and instantly readable — or messy and confusing. The difference is rarely the numbers . It's the rules you apply consistently : how you name things behind the scenes, and how you use colour, fonts, images and icons out front. Mia is turning two terms of reef species sightings into a one-page infographic for the conservation group's AGM. She has a database of sightings, a spreadsheet of monthly counts, and a blank canvas for the visualisation. Her data is solid — but her first draft is a mess of Sheet1 tabs, six different fonts and clashing colours. We'll follow Mia as she applies the formats and conventions that turn a rough draft into something the audience trusts.","id":494},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"The scope, in plain words","text":"In the VCAA Study Design, this is the final key-knowledge point of Unit 1 Outcome 1. It reads as formats and conventions applied to improve the effectiveness of solutions , and it splits cleanly into two halves:","id":495},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Naming conventions","text":"Consistent, meaningful names for the parts of your databases (tables, fields, queries) and spreadsheets (sheets, ranges, columns). Nobody in the audience sees these — but they make the solution easier to build, read and maintain.","id":496},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Colour · fonts · images · icons","text":"The visual conventions the audience does see. Used consistently, they guide the eye, signal meaning and make the visualisation look credible. Used randomly, they fight the message. A convention is just a rule you choose once and then apply every time . Effectiveness comes from the consistency, not the specific choice. Mia could pick blue for fish or green for fish — what matters is that fish are always the same colour on every chart.","id":497},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Think of a sports club's gear shed","text":"Imagine the storeroom at a footy club. If every jumper is labelled in the same way — Senior_Home_07 , Senior_Away_07 — anyone can grab the right one in seconds. If they're labelled jumper , the blue one , #7?? , you waste the whole afternoon. That's naming conventions . Now picture the club running onto the ground. Matching guernseys, one logo, club colours everywhere: the crowd reads \"that's one team\" instantly. If half wore random colours and three different logos, you couldn't tell who was who. That's colour, fonts and icons — visual identity that lets an audience read meaning at a glance.","id":498},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Think of a sports club's gear shed","text":"Exam-ready link: conventions reduce the effort the user spends decoding your solution. Low decoding effort = high effectiveness. That sentence works in almost any KK17 answer.","id":499},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Naming databases & spreadsheets","text":"A naming convention is a shared rule for what you call things. The audience never sees a field name — but consistent naming makes a solution faster to build, easier to read, and far easier to fix later. Mia's golden rules: Be descriptive, not generic. sightingDate tells you what it holds; Field3 and Sheet1 tell you nothing. Pick one style and stick to it. Either camelCase ( speciesName ) or snake_case ( species_name ) — just never both in one solution. No spaces or odd symbols in field, sheet or range names.","id":500},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Naming databases & spreadsheets","text":"They break formulas and queries. Use an underscore or a capital instead. Prefix by object type so things sort together: tbl for tables, qry for queries, frm for forms in a database. Stay consistent with case and units — if one field is lengthCm , don't make the next one WidthMM . Watch Mia's reef database clean itself up. Toggle the convention on and off:","id":501},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Colour that means something","text":"Colour is the fastest signal a visualisation has. Used well it codes categories , draws the eye to what matters and reinforces a brand. Used badly it becomes noise. The conventions: Consistent colour-coding: one category, one colour, everywhere. If fish are blue on the bar chart, they're blue on the pie chart and the map too. Limited palette: a handful of colours, not a rainbow. More colours = more for the eye to decode. Enough contrast: text must stand off its background, and adjacent bars must be distinguishable — including for colour-blind viewers (avoid red/green as the only difference). Purposeful accent: use one stand-out colour to highlight the key finding, not for decoration.","id":502},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Fonts: hierarchy, not variety","text":"Beginners reach for lots of fonts to look \"creative\". Designers do the opposite. The convention is restraint plus hierarchy : One or two typefaces, maximum. One for headings, one for body is plenty. Build a clear hierarchy with size and weight: big bold title → medium subhead → smaller body. The reader's eye should know the order instantly. Readable sizes & consistent alignment. Body text large enough to read across a room if it's a poster; everything aligned to the same edges. Match tone to audience — a clean sans-serif suits a conservation report; a novelty font undermines its credibility. ✗ Three clashing fonts, no hierarchy ✓ One family, clear hierarchy","id":503},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Images & icons: one visual language","text":"Images set context; icons compress an idea into a glance. Both follow the same convention — consistency of style and meaning : One icon set / one style. All line icons, or all filled — not a mix. A jumbled set looks unprofessional and slows reading. Each icon means one thing. If a fish icon stands for \"fish sightings\", don't reuse it elsewhere for \"ocean\". Consistent size & placement. Icons the same size, aligned the same way; images cropped to the same shape and resolution. Relevant & properly sourced. Images must support the data and be credited (ties back to KK07 referencing) — decorative clip-art that adds nothing is clutter.","id":504},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Spot the inconsistency","text":"✗ Three different icon styles in one row — line, filled, heavy. The eye notices the style change before the meaning. ✓ One consistent line style, one size, evenly spaced.","id":505},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Mia's infographic: before & after","text":"Identical data. The only thing that changed is whether formats and conventions were applied. Flip between them: Colour: one consistent colour per category, instead of random clashing fills. Fonts: one family with a clear title→body hierarchy, instead of three novelty fonts. Icons/images: a single line-icon style at one size. Naming (unseen): the underlying sheets and fields were renamed MonthlyCounts / sightingDate , so the build is maintainable.","id":506},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Write it down: a style guide","text":"Conventions only help if they're applied consistently — and the way professionals guarantee that is by writing a short style guide before they build. The VCAA teaching activity for this dot point literally asks students to act as an organisation and agree a shared set of formats and conventions. Mia's looks like this: Naming: camelCase fields; tables prefixed tbl , queries qry ; spreadsheet tabs named by content. Colour: Fish ● · Coral ● · Inverts ● · Algae ● — used identically on every chart. Fonts: one sans-serif family;","id":507},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Write it down: a style guide","text":"22 px bold titles, 13 px body. Icons: single line-icon set, 28 px, one icon per category. In an exam, \"the organisation should agree a style guide / set of conventions and apply it consistently\" is a high-value sentence — it shows you understand why conventions exist, not just what they are.","id":508},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Read the verb before you answer","text":"KK17 questions live or die on the command word. Match your response length and depth to it:","id":509},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Structure an \"explain\" the examiner can mark","text":"For any \"explain how a convention improves effectiveness\" question, write three moves: Point → Example → Link . Tap through Mia's model answer: Your turn — write an \"explain\" for a font or naming convention. The detector lights up as your answer hits each move:","id":510},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"VCE-style questions with model responses","text":"Attempt each in your head or on paper first, then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide. Award yourself a mark with the self-mark buttons — your total tracks in the dock.","id":511},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Naming conventions","text":"Descriptive, not Field3 / Sheet1 One case style — camelCase or snake_case No spaces / special characters Prefix by type: tbl , qry , frm Consistent units & case across fields","id":512},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Colour","text":"One colour per category, everywhere Limited palette Enough contrast (colour-blind safe) One accent for the key finding","id":513},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Fonts","text":"One or two typefaces max Clear hierarchy: title → subhead → body Readable size, consistent alignment Tone matches the audience","id":514},{"file":"u1o1-kk17.html","nav":"u1o1-kk17.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK17","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Formats & conventions","head":"Images & icons","text":"One icon set / one style One icon = one meaning Consistent size & placement Relevant, good resolution, sourced \"A convention is a rule chosen once and applied consistently; the consistency lowers the effort builders and audiences spend on a solution, which is what makes it more effective.\"","id":515},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","text":"Programming used to mean typing every line yourself. Now you can describe what you want in plain English and a model writes the code. That changes how we build software — but not whether we still have to understand it. This module shows you the trends, the tools, and the one skill examiners care about most: judging whether AI-written code is actually correct.","id":516},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"What this dot point is asking","text":"“ emerging trends in programming languages and AI-based code generators ” Unit 1, Outcome 2 (Programming). The supporting teaching activity is explicit: you are given code created by an AI code-generation tool and asked to evaluate its correctness and compare it to a manually written solution . So this is not just “name some tools” — it’s a thinking-and-judging skill. Break the dot point into three examinable threads. Everything below hangs off these:","id":517},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"📈 Trends","text":"Where programming languages are heading — higher abstraction , readability-first design, and low-code / no-code platforms.","id":518},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🤖 AI generators","text":"Tools like Copilot, ChatGPT and Gemini that turn a plain-language prompt into code — what they do well and where they quietly fail.","id":519},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🔍 Judgement","text":"The examinable skill: read AI-written code and decide if it is correct, readable and maintainable — or not. Maya is in Year 11 and is building QuizQuest — a small quiz app for her Applied Computing class. She’s on a deadline, so she uses an AI code generator to scaffold it fast. It feels like magic… until a classmate scores exactly 50 and the app marks them as failed. We’ll use Maya’s build to make every idea on this page concrete.","id":520},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Why programming keeps changing","text":"Every few years, programming gets a new layer that lets you say more with less . Punch cards became assembly; assembly became high-level languages; libraries hid the hard parts; and now AI lets you describe intent in English. This single direction — rising abstraction — is the spine of this whole dot point. Think of it like cooking. You can grind your own flour and butcher your own meat (machine code), buy ingredients and follow a recipe (a high-level language), use a meal kit with everything pre-portioned (a framework), or just tell a chef “something warm and Italian” (AI).","id":521},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Why programming keeps changing","text":"Each step up trades fine control for speed and convenience . None of them removes the need to know whether the meal is any good. An emerging trend isn’t just “a new app”. In this study it means a shift in how software gets built — a new level of abstraction (low-code), a new kind of tool (AI generators), or a new design priority (readability and maintainability over raw cleverness).","id":522},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Lab 1 — The Abstraction Tower","text":"Here is the same task — “add two numbers and show the result” — expressed at six levels of programming history. Click any rung to see how the code changes. Watch the technical detail melt away as you climb. That melting-away is the trend.","id":523},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Abstraction Tower — click a rung","text":"Words and symbols people understand. Portable across machines. This is where you write Outcome 2 code. Notice: the bottom rung is unreadable to humans but tells the machine exactly what to do; the top rung is effortless to read but leaves the machine (and the AI) to fill in a lot of assumptions. More abstraction means more is hidden — which is exactly why you still have to check what the tool produced.","id":524},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Trends in programming languages","text":"You don’t need to memorise version numbers. You need to recognise the directions languages are moving in, and be able to give an example of each.","id":525},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🐍 Readability first","text":"Languages like Python are popular because they read almost like English. Clear code is faster to write, easier to fix, and easier for a team to maintain.","id":526},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🧱 Object-oriented by default","text":"Most modern languages are OOP — code is organised into objects that bundle data with the methods that act on it. This is the language family Outcome 2 expects you to use.","id":527},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🧩 Low-code & no-code","text":"Drag-and-drop builders and visual logic (think App Inventor, Power Apps, Scratch-style blocks) let people build working apps with little or no typed code.","id":528},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🤖 AI-assisted by default","text":"Editors now ship with an AI generator built in. Writing code increasingly means prompting, reading and correcting as much as typing. “A current trend in programming languages is the move toward greater readability and maintainability (e.g. Python) and toward higher abstraction through low-code platforms and AI-based code generators, which let developers produce working solutions with less hand-written code.”","id":529},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"What an AI-based code generator is","text":"An AI-based code generator is a tool that produces source code from a natural-language description or from surrounding code. You’ve almost certainly met one: GitHub Copilot , ChatGPT , Google Gemini , Claude, Cursor, Replit Ghostwriter.","id":530},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"How it actually works (and why that matters)","text":"This is the part most students get wrong in exams. An AI generator does not understand your program or “know” it is correct. It is a prediction engine : trained on enormous amounts of existing code, it predicts the most statistically likely next tokens for your prompt. It’s a phenomenally good autocomplete — not a tester, and not a guarantee. An AI code generator answers “what does code like this usually look like?” — never “is this code right for your exact problem?” That gap is where bugs live. Because it’s predicting “usual” code, it’s brilliant at common, well-known tasks and shaky at anything unusual, brand-new, or specific to your data. It can also hallucinate — confidently invent a function or library that doesn’t exist.","id":531},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Lab 2 — The AI Code Inspector","text":"Maya asked an AI generator for a function that decides if a quiz mark is a pass. Here’s what it returned: # the pass mark at Maya's school is 50 — a mark of 50 should PASS It reads cleanly and runs without errors — so it’s tempting to trust it. Don’t. Launch the test probes below. Each probe carries a mark; it turns green if the AI’s answer matches the correct answer, and red if it doesn’t.","id":532},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🤖 What AI wrote","text":"if mark > 50: A mark of exactly 50 is excluded, so a genuine pass is marked as a fail. A classic boundary error — the code runs perfectly and is still wrong.","id":533},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"✅ The manual fix","text":"if mark >= 50: Comparing against the manually written, correct version is exactly what the study design asks you to do. One character — >= instead of > — fixes it. “Runs without errors” is not “correct”. Only testing against known inputs — especially boundary values like the pass mark itself — exposes the kind of subtle mistake AI generators love to make.","id":534},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"⚡ Speed & scaffolding","text":"Boilerplate, loops and standard structures appear instantly, so you spend time on the hard, specific parts instead of typing routine code.","id":535},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🎓 Learning & examples","text":"Seeing a worked solution — and asking “why?” — can teach syntax and patterns, especially for a beginner stuck on where to start.","id":536},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🧹 Readability & refactoring","text":"Generators can rename variables, add comments and restructure messy code, improving readability and maintainability — a benefit the study design names directly.","id":537},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"♿ Lower barrier to entry","text":"With low-code and AI together, people who can’t yet write much code can still produce a working solution, widening who gets to build software.","id":538},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🐞 Subtle, silent bugs","text":"As Lab 2 showed, code can run cleanly and still be wrong (boundary errors, off-by-one, wrong operator). You must test, not trust.","id":539},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"👻 Hallucinated code","text":"It can invent functions or libraries that don’t exist, or use ones incorrectly — confidently and convincingly.","id":540},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🔒 Security & privacy","text":"Generated code may carry insecure patterns; pasting private or school data into a public tool can breach privacy and IP rules.","id":541},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"©️ IP & licensing","text":"Output is trained on others’ code and may resemble licensed work, raising ownership and copyright questions (the focus of KK06).","id":542},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🧠 Skill erosion / over-reliance","text":"Lean on it too early and you may never build the understanding needed to spot when it’s wrong.","id":543},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🎯 No real context","text":"It doesn’t know your requirements, constraints or data — only what code “usually” looks like.","id":544},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Low-code & no-code approaches","text":"Low-code platforms let you build most of an app visually (drag-and-drop screens, point-and-click logic) and drop into written code only when you need something custom. No-code aims to remove typed code entirely. Both are part of the same trend as AI generators: get a working solution with less hand-written code.","id":545},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"👍 Strong fit","text":"Quick prototypes, simple business apps, forms and dashboards, people without a coding background, tight deadlines.","id":546},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"👎 Poor fit","text":"Complex or unusual logic, fine performance tuning, anything the platform doesn’t support — you hit a wall the platform’s authors didn’t plan for. Trade-off to remember: low-code buys speed and accessibility at the cost of flexibility and control — the same bargain you make every step up the Abstraction Tower.","id":547},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Readability & maintainability gains","text":"The study design singles these two out, so define them precisely:","id":548},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"📖 Readability","text":"How easily a human can understand what code does — clear names, sensible structure, helpful comments.","id":549},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🔧 Maintainability","text":"How easily code can be changed or fixed later without breaking things. Readable code is far easier to maintain. AI tools can push both up (cleaning and commenting code) or down (spitting out clever, dense, uncommented code nobody on the team understands). Same input scenario, two outcomes:","id":550},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🙈 Harder to maintain","text":"Works, but what is f ? What is x ? Six months later, nobody knows.","id":551},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"🙌 Easier to maintain","text":"Same logic, named and commented. Anyone can read, test and change it.","id":552},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Evaluating AI-generated code","text":"This is the heart of the dot point. When you’re handed AI code in an exam, work a quick checklist rather than eyeballing it for vibes: Correctness — does it produce the right output for normal inputs and boundary inputs? (Build a small test table, as in Lab 2.) Requirements fit — does it actually do what the brief asked, including constraints and edge cases? Readability — clear names, structure and comments, or a cryptic one-liner? Maintainability — could another student safely change it next term? Compare to a manual solution — how does it differ from how you’d write it by hand? Which is better, and why?","id":553},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Sort it — benefit or limitation?","text":"Tap a card to drop it into the right bin. Each is a real feature of AI code generators — decide whether it helps Maya or hurts her.","id":554},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"“It ran, so it’s correct.”","text":"Running without errors only proves the syntax is valid. Correctness is about output , proven by testing. → Always mention testing, especially boundary values.","id":555},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Saying AI “understands” code","text":"It predicts likely tokens from training data; it has no understanding or guarantee of correctness. → Describe it as a prediction/pattern tool, not a thinker.","id":556},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Only listing benefits (or only risks)","text":"“Discuss/evaluate” questions need both sides plus a judgement. → Give benefits and limitations, then a reasoned conclusion.","id":557},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Confusing readability with maintainability","text":"Readability = easy to understand now; maintainability = easy to change later. Related, not identical. → Define each separately if both are asked.","id":558},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"“Low-code = no skill needed”","text":"Low-code still needs logic, design and testing; it removes typing , not thinking . → Frame it as less hand-written code, not no expertise.","id":559},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"Vague answers with no example","text":"“AI is fast and helpful” scores little. Name a tool, a trend, a concrete benefit/limit. → Anchor every point to a specific example.","id":560},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure , not word-count. Use P·E·L — Point, Example, Link. Make your point, prove it with a concrete example, link it back to the question. Click each tab for a worked sentence on “a limitation of AI code generators”. Make a clear, examinable claim. No hedging. Anchor the point in something concrete and specific. Tie it back to the command word (here, a limitation’s consequence).","id":561},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Attempt each on paper first. Then reveal the weak vs strong responses and the marking guide, and self-mark — your score feeds the dock in the corner.","id":562},{"file":"u1o2-kk01.html","nav":"u1o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Programming","title":"Emerging trends & AI in programming","head":"One-screen cheat sheet","text":"Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · U1·O2 Programming · KK01 Single-file & fully offline · Three.js r128 inlined · en-AU · Built for Year 11 & 12.","id":563},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Characteristics of data types","text":"Every value your program touches has a type — and the type silently decides what the computer is allowed to do with that value. Pick the right one and the right operations just work. Pick the wrong one and you get bugs that no error message warns you about. Showing a static view — turn on your browser's hardware acceleration for the animated 3D. Every activity below works either way.","id":564},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Straight from the study design","text":"VCAA · VCE Applied Computing · Unit 1 Outcome 2, key knowledge: “characteristics of data types: text (character, string), numeric (integer, floating point, date/time) and Boolean.” You must be able to name each type, describe what it holds, and justify the most appropriate type for a given field in a software solution.","id":565},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Our scenario: Lockr","text":"Priya , a Year 11 student, is building Lockr — an app to book and pay for school lockers — as her Unit 1 Outcome 2 software solution. Before she writes a line of code she has to decide the data type for every piece of information Lockr stores. Get those decisions right and the whole app behaves. Get them wrong and lockers won't open. We'll use Priya's choices to make every data type concrete.","id":566},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"A data type is a contract, not a label","text":"When you declare a variable, you're not just naming a box — you're signing a contract that fixes three things at once.","id":567},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"① What fits","text":"The set of values the variable is allowed to hold. A Boolean can only ever be true or false . An integer can't hold 3.5 . Try and the language either rejects it or quietly mangles it.","id":568},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"② How much memory","text":"A Boolean needs about a bit; an integer a few bytes; a long string grows with its length. The type tells the computer how much room to reserve.","id":569},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"③ Which operations are legal","text":"You can do arithmetic on numbers but not on text. You can join (concatenate) strings but not Booleans. The + symbol even means different things depending on the type — that's the trap that catches the most students. Think of a school canteen form. The “how many?” box only accepts whole numbers — you can't order 2.5 sausage rolls. The “name” box accepts any text. The “gluten free?” box is a tick or no-tick — nothing in between. Nobody wrote rules on the form for fun: each box's type stops nonsense getting in and tells the canteen what it can do with each answer. Data types are exactly that, enforced by the computer instead of a canteen lady.","id":570},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The one sentence to remember","text":"The data type you choose decides what operations the computer will let you perform on that value. Almost every exam mark on this dot point comes back to that idea.","id":571},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The Type Foundry","text":"Pick a real Lockr value below. Watch it drop into its matching container, then read what that type can hold, how much memory it needs, and which operations it unlocks. Try the 0042 chip — it hides a classic trap.","id":572},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"🏭 Cast a Lockr value into its type","text":"Each chip is a field Priya must store in Lockr. Choosing a value reveals its data type and everything that follows from it.","id":573},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Text types","text":"Text data is anything made of letters, digits-as-symbols, spaces and punctuation. The study design splits it into two: character and string .","id":574},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"char Character","text":"Exactly one symbol — a single letter, digit, space or punctuation mark. In Lockr the locker block is one of A – F , so Priya stores block as a character. Holds: 'C', '7', '?', ' ' · Quoted: usually single quotes","id":575},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"string String","text":"A sequence of characters of any length, including empty. A student's name, an email, a 4-digit PIN — all strings. \"Priya Nair\" is one string of 10 characters. Holds: \"\", \"C\", \"Block C – Level 2\" · Quoted: usually double quotes","id":576},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Digits aren't always numbers","text":"A phone number, a postcode, a PIN and a student ID all look like numbers but should be strings . Why? You never do arithmetic on them, they can start with 0 (which an integer throws away — 0042 becomes 42 ), and they can be too big for a numeric type. Rule of thumb: if you'd never add or average it, it's text. A character is a single Scrabble tile. A string is the whole word you build by laying tiles in a row. A word can be one tile long, or twenty, or zero (an empty rack). That's the only real difference: a character is one tile; a string is the row.","id":577},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Numeric types","text":"Numeric data is data you genuinely do maths on. The study design lists three numeric forms, and choosing between them is a favourite exam question.","id":578},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"int Integer","text":"Whole numbers , positive or negative, no decimal point. Counting things. Lockr stores lockerNo = 47 and lockersLeft = 12 as integers. Holds: -3, 0, 47, 100000","id":579},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"float Floating point","text":"Numbers with a decimal/fractional part. Money, weights, percentages, sensor readings. Lockr stores dailyFee = 1.25 as a floating-point number. Holds: 1.25, -0.5, 3.14159, 99.0","id":580},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"date Date/time","text":"A specialised numeric type for points in time. It knows that the day after 31 Dec is 1 Jan, and it can be subtracted to find durations. Lockr stores bookedUntil = 12 Sep 2026 . Holds: 12/09/2026, 08:45, full timestamps","id":581},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Integer vs floating point — the decider","text":"Ask: “Can this value ever have a fraction?” A count of lockers can't (you never have 12.5 lockers) → integer . A fee, a temperature or a weight can → floating point . Choosing integer for money silently rounds $1.25 down to $1 and Priya loses 25c on every booking. An integer is a staircase — you can only stand on whole steps, 1, 2, 3. A floating point is a ramp — you can stop anywhere, including 2.37 of the way up. Counting people? Stairs. Measuring how full the water tank is? Ramp.","id":582},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Why “floating point” is named that","text":"The decimal point can “float” to represent very large or very tiny numbers — 0.000123 or 4 500 000.0 — but that flexibility costs precision. Floats are tiny approximations, so 0.1 + 0.2 can come out as 0.30000000000000004 . That's why serious money systems sometimes store cents as integers instead. You don't need the deep maths for Units 1–2, but knowing floats are approximate is worth a mark.","id":583},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Boolean — the decision type","text":"A Boolean holds one of exactly two values: true or false . It's the smallest, simplest type — and the one your program's logic runs on. Named after mathematician George Boole. Lockr uses Booleans for every yes/no fact: isPaid , isOverdue , isMember . These feed straight into if statements — the value of a Boolean decides which branch the program takes. Flip the gate below and watch the path change.","id":584},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Why a whole type for true/false?","text":"Because branching is the heart of programming. if (isPaid) openLocker() else showPayment() reads almost like English. Storing “paid?” as the string \"yes\" instead would force messy comparisons and let typos like \"Yes\" or \"y\" break the logic. A Boolean makes the decision crisp and impossible to misspell.","id":585},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The same symbol, different jobs","text":"This is the single most-tested misconception on this dot point. The + operator does addition on numbers but concatenation (gluing end-to-end) on strings. Same key on your keyboard, completely different result.","id":586},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The Lockr bug this causes","text":"Priya reads a quantity from a text box and writes total = qty + 1 . Text boxes hand back strings , so if a user types \"2\" , she gets \"21\" , not 3 . The fix is to convert (cast) the string to an integer first. No error appears — the program just silently does the wrong thing. That's why understanding types prevents bugs you'd otherwise never spot.","id":587},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Picking well — Priya's data dictionary","text":"In the SAC you'll be asked to state and justify the most appropriate type for a field. Run every field through two questions: “Will I ever do maths on it?” and “Can it have a fraction or a leading zero?” Tap a card to reveal Priya's decision and her reasoning.","id":588},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"The decision routine (memorise this)","text":"1. Yes/no fact? → Boolean . 2. A point in time? → date/time . 3. Will you do arithmetic on it? If no → text (string, or character if always one symbol). 4. If yes, can it have a decimal? Yes → floating point ; No → integer .","id":589},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Sort it — drag each value to its type","text":"Drag (or tap on touch) each Lockr value into the correct type bin, then hit Check . Wrong ones go red so you can rethink them.","id":590},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Six ways students lose marks here","text":"Every one of these is something examiners' reports flag year after year. Open each, learn the fix.","id":591},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Write answers that earn the marks","text":"Half the battle is reading the command word and answering in its shape. Then structure justifications with P·E·L — Point, Example, Link.","id":592},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Six fast questions","text":"Instant feedback. These are the “do you actually know it” reps — no marks recorded, just self-test.","id":593},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"VCE-style practice — mark your own","text":"Five questions, 16 marks total, written in VCAA's voice. Attempt each on paper first, then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide. Award yourself marks — your score follows you in the dock.","id":594},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"The whole dot point on one screen. Screenshot it the night before. Type Holds Lockr example Choose it when… character one single symbol block = 'C' the value is always exactly one letter/digit/symbol string a sequence of characters (any length) name = \"Priya Nair\" text, or digits you never do maths on (PIN, phone, ID) integer whole numbers, no decimal lockerNo = 47 counting; the value can never have a fraction floating point numbers with a decimal part dailyFee = 1.25 money, measurements, anything fractional date/time a point in time bookedUntil = 12/09/2026 dates, times, durations to compare or subtract Boolean true or false only isPaid = true any yes/no fact that drives a decision","id":595},{"file":"u1o2-kk02.html","nav":"u1o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Programming","title":"Characteristics of data types","head":"If you remember nothing else","text":"Type = a contract fixing what fits, how much memory, and which operations are legal. · Digits you never add are text. · Fraction possible → float, else integer. · + adds numbers but glues strings.","id":596},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Data structures","text":"One-dimensional arrays, lists and records — the three ways a program groups related data together, and how to tell them apart in an exam. The study design says you should “demonstrate the use of data structures, such as one-dimensional arrays, lists and records, and then describe the differences between them.” So this dot point is really two jobs: (1) know what each structure is and when to use it, and (2) be able to compare them. The detail in brackets — varying data types, field index — is about records , and examiners love it.","id":597},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Our worked example for the whole module","text":"Meet DeckHand — a phone app a Year 11 student is building for the (made-up) collectible card game Hexlings . Everything we cover lives inside this one app, so the three structures stay concrete:","id":598},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"🎴 The battle board","text":"A duel always has exactly 5 lanes . Lane 0, lane 1 … lane 4. The number never changes.","id":599},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"📚 Your collection","text":"Open a pack and it grows ; trade a card and it shrinks . Could be 12 cards or 1,200.","id":600},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"🪪 One single card","text":"One card has a name , an attack , a cost , an element , and whether it’s a foil — all different types.","id":601},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Why not just use lots of variables?","text":"Imagine storing five cards on the board with five separate variables: This works for 5, but it falls apart the moment you want to loop, count, sort, or have a changing number of things. A data structure is a container that holds many related values under one name , so you can reach them with an index or a field and process them in a loop. A data structure is an organised way of storing a collection of related data under a single identifier so it can be accessed and processed efficiently.","id":602},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Why not just use lots of variables?","text":"The three you must know for Units 1 & 2 are the one-dimensional array , the list , and the record . The next three sections take them one at a time — each with a 3-D lab you can play with.","id":603},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"One-dimensional array","text":"A one-dimensional array is an ordered collection of elements that are all the same data type , stored under one name, and reached by a numeric index . Its size is fixed when you create it.","id":604},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Same type","text":"Every slot holds the same kind of value — e.g. all strings, or all integers. (homogeneous)","id":605},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Fixed size","text":"You declare a length and that’s it. A 5-lane board has lanes 0–4. There is no lane 5 .","id":606},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Index access","text":"Reach any element directly by its position: board[0] , board[3] . Indexes start at 0 .","id":607},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"3-D Lab · The 5-lane battle board","text":"A 5-element array has indexes 0,1,2,3,4 — not 1–5. Asking for board[5] is an “index out of range” error. Off-by-one bugs come straight from forgetting arrays start at 0.","id":608},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"List","text":"A list is also an ordered collection reached by index — but unlike an array its size is dynamic . You can append , insert and remove items while the program runs, and it grows or shrinks to fit.","id":609},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Dynamic size","text":"Starts empty or small, then grows on demand. Perfect when you don’t know how many items there’ll be.","id":610},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Add & remove","text":"collection.append(card) adds to the end; collection.remove(0) takes one out.","id":611},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Re-indexing","text":"Remove item 0 and everything after it shifts down — the old item 1 becomes the new item 0.","id":612},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"3-D Lab · Your growing collection","text":"Array = fixed size, set at creation. List = dynamic size, changes at run-time. If a question mentions an unknown or changing number of items, that’s a flag for a list . If it’s a known, fixed count, an array fits.","id":613},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Record","text":"A record is different in kind. Instead of many items of the same type, it groups together fields of varying data types that all describe one thing . You reach a value by its field name (or its field index ) — not by hunting through a list.","id":614},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Mixed types","text":"One field is a string, the next an integer, the next a Boolean. (heterogeneous)","id":615},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"One entity","text":"All fields belong to a single item — one card, one student, one booking.","id":616},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Field name / index","text":"Access by name card.attack or by field index card[1] — field 0 is name, field 1 is attack…","id":617},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Describe the differences","text":"This is the half of the dot point students drop marks on. Learn this table cold — every row is a sentence you can write in an exam. * In many languages a list can technically hold mixed types, but for VCAA the examinable contrast is fixed (array) vs dynamic (list) size — that’s the difference graded. 1. Same type or mixed types? Mixed → record . Same → array or list. 2. Does the count change? Fixed → array . Changes → list .","id":618},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"The structures combine — a list of records","text":"Real apps nest structures inside each other. In DeckHand, your collection is a list , and each element of that list is a card — a record . That’s a list of records : the single most common pattern you’ll meet in this course. So collection[0] uses the list’s numeric index to grab a record, and [\"name\"] uses the record’s field name to grab a value. Two access styles, one line — and a perfect thing to point at when an exam says “describe the differences.” When you build your own small solution, you’ll almost always store “a bunch of things, each with several fields” — students with their marks, products with prices, bookings with times. That’s a list (or array) of records . Recognising the pattern is half the design.","id":619},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Choose the right structure","text":"Drag each scenario into the structure that fits best — or tap a chip then tap a bin on touch screens. Think: same/mixed types? fixed/changing count?","id":620},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"“An array can grow when you need more space.”","text":"No — an array is fixed at creation. Fix: that’s a list. Use “fixed (array) vs dynamic (list)” to mark the difference.","id":621},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Calling a record “an array of different types.”","text":"A record holds the fields of one entity , accessed by field name — it isn’t indexed like an array of many items. Fix: say “one entity, varying data types, field name/index.”","id":622},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Indexing from 1.","text":"A 5-element array has indexes 0–4 . board[5] is out of range. Fix: remember the first element is index 0.","id":623},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"“List and array are basically the same.”","text":"They share index access, but the graded difference is size: fixed vs dynamic . Fix: always name that difference explicitly.","id":624},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Naming a structure but not justifying it.","text":"“Use a record” earns little. Fix: link it to the scenario — “a record, because a card has several attributes of different types.”","id":625},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Forgetting the “field index” detail for records.","text":"VCAA explicitly lists varying data types and field index . Fix: mention that a field can be reached by its name or its position (field index).","id":626},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"The verb tells you how much to write. Tap to expand.","id":627},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Quick quiz","text":"Instant feedback — pick an option to see if it’s right and why.","id":628},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong written answers follow Point → Example → Link . Pick a structure and see a model sentence built in that shape — then copy the pattern in your own answers.","id":629},{"file":"u1o2-kk03.html","nav":"u1o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Programming","title":"Data structures","head":"Practice questions","text":"Five VCAA-style questions, 19 marks . Try each on paper first, then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide. Mark your own work — your score saves automatically.","id":630},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","text":"Before a single line of code is written, four questions decide whether your software succeeds: what must it do , how well must it do it , what limits hem you in , and where is the edge of the job . Read them wrong and you build the wrong app perfectly.","id":631},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Why this dotpoint matters","text":"In Outcome 2 you interpret a teacher-provided brief and build a working program in an object-oriented language. You are not inventing the problem — you are decoding it. Every brief, no matter how short, can be split into the same four buckets. VCAA literally asks you to read a short case study and write a table listing the functional and non-functional requirements , the constraints, and the scope. Get fluent at that table and you’ve nailed a guaranteed chunk of marks.","id":632},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"F Functional","text":"What the solution must do — its actions and behaviours.","id":633},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"NF Non-functional","text":"How well it must do it — the qualities and standards.","id":634},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"C Constraint","text":"A limit you must work within — not chosen, imposed.","id":635},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"S Scope","text":"The boundary — what’s in the job and what’s out.","id":636},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Ordering a pizza","text":"You don’t need to be a developer to already understand all four ideas — you use them every time you order food. Picture phoning a pizza shop. “Make a large pepperoni, cut into 8 slices.” “…and I want it hot and here in 30 minutes .” “The shop has one oven and shuts at 9pm.” “Pizza only — no, you can’t add a haircut.” Notice the relationships: the constraint (one oven, closes at 9) is exactly why the non-functional “30 minutes” is hard to meet, and it’s why “also wash my car” falls out of scope . The four lenses aren’t separate facts — they pull on each other.","id":637},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"FUNCTIONAL What it must do","text":"A functional requirement describes a specific action, behaviour or function the software must perform. The cleanest test: could you tick a yes/no box that says “the software did this”? If yes, it’s functional. Functional requirements are almost always written as a verb the program performs on some data : calculate , store , display , sort , validate , add , delete .","id":638},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"PixelBoard — functional requirements","text":"▸ Let a player enter three initials after a game ends. ▸ Store the player’s score with their initials and the date. ▸ Sort all saved scores from highest to lowest. ▸ Display the top ten scores on the leaderboard screen. ▸ Reset the leaderboard when the teacher enters a passcode. Each one is a behaviour you could demonstrate to the Tech Club and they could nod “yep, it did that.” Notice how testable they are — that testability is what makes them functional.","id":639},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"NON-FUNCTIONAL How well it must do it","text":"A non-functional requirement doesn’t add a new behaviour — it puts a quality standard on the behaviours you already have. Same job, higher bar. These describe the experience and the standard , not the function. Most non-functional requirements are an “-ility” . Memorise the family and you’ll spot them instantly:","id":640},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Usability","text":"Easy to learn and use. PixelBoard: a Year 7 can enter their initials with no instructions.","id":641},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Reliability","text":"Works consistently without crashing. No saved score is ever lost between games.","id":642},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Response time / performance","text":"Fast enough. The leaderboard redraws in under 1 second.","id":643},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Security","text":"Protected from misuse. Only the teacher passcode can wipe the board.","id":644},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Portability","text":"Runs in different places. Runs on the cabinet’s old browser and a laptop.","id":645},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Maintainability / robustness","text":"Easy to fix; survives bad input. Typing “12” for initials doesn’t crash it.","id":646},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Sort the lens: drag each spec into its bucket","text":"Here are real lines from a PixelBoard brief. Drag each into the right bucket — or tap a chip then tap a bucket on touch screens. You’re training the reflex examiners reward.","id":647},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"CONSTRAINT The limits you can’t change","text":"A constraint is a restriction or limitation imposed on the solution — by money, technology, the law, time, or people. The key word is imposed : you don’t choose a constraint, you’re stuck with it, and it shapes every decision. VCAA groups them into recognisable types:","id":648},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"SCOPE Where the job stops","text":"Scope defines the boundary of the solution — the line between what the software will do (in scope) and what it won’t (out of scope). Writing scope is mostly about saying no on purpose, so everyone agrees on the edges before you build.","id":649},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"In scope ✓","text":"✓ Saving a score with three initials ✓ Showing the local top-ten ✓ A teacher reset with a passcode","id":650},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Out of scope ✗","text":"✗ Online accounts & global leaderboards ✗ Syncing scores between machines ✗ Running the arcade game itself","id":651},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Examine PixelBoard through four lenses","text":"One product, four ways of looking at it. Switch lenses to recolour the cabinet and reveal what that lens captures. The point: the same software answers all four questions at once — they’re views of one thing, not four different things.","id":652},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"What PixelBoard does","text":"The behaviours the cabinet performs — each one testable yes/no. Enter three initials Store score + date Sort high → low Display the top ten Teacher passcode reset","id":653},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"The spec table examiners want","text":"When VCAA hands you a case study, the safest move is to build the four-column table . Here’s the full PixelBoard brief reduced to one. If you can produce this from a paragraph of text, you can answer almost any question on this dotpoint.","id":654},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Name that constraint type","text":"Constraints trip people up because you also have to name the type . Read each line from a new brief (a school excursion-booking app) and pick the constraint type. Instant feedback explains the call.","id":655},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ Calling a quality a behaviour","text":"Writing “the app is fast” as a functional requirement. Speed is a standard, not an action.","id":656},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ Vague non-functionals","text":"“It should be user-friendly and fast.” Examiners can’t award a tick for a wish.","id":657},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ Confusing constraint with non-functional","text":"Listing “must use free software” as a non-functional requirement.","id":658},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ Scope written as requirements","text":"Just re-listing the functional requirements when asked for scope.","id":659},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ Inventing requirements not in the brief","text":"Adding “and it logs players in with Google” because it sounds impressive.","id":660},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"✕ One-word answers to “explain” questions","text":"Answering a 3-mark “explain” with a label and nothing else.","id":661},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Command words & the P·E·L move","text":"Half of “losing marks” isn’t not knowing — it’s under-writing. Match your answer length to the command word :","id":662},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"State / List / Identify","text":"Just name it. One line. No explanation needed.","id":663},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Describe","text":"Name it and add detail — what it is, what it covers.","id":664},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Explain","text":"Say why / how — give a reason and connect it to the case.","id":665},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Justify / Compare","text":"Make a case with evidence, or weigh two options against each other. For “describe / explain” marks, the reliable structure is P·E·L : P Point — name the concept clearly. E Evidence — tie it to the specific case study. L Link — connect back to the question or its impact.","id":666},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Exam questions — see the weak vs strong answer","text":"Each question shows a weak response with examiner annotations, a strong model answer, and the marking guide . Try it yourself first, then reveal. 1 mark: definition identifies a function/action/behaviour the software does . 1 mark: a correct, behaviour-based example tied to PixelBoard (e.g. sort scores, store a score, display top ten). 1 mark: correct definition of non-functional requirement (a quality/standard of the product). 1 mark: correct definition of constraint (an imposed limitation on development). 1 mark: a valid, distinct PixelBoard example of each. 1 mark: an explicit point of difference (product target vs build limitation).","id":667},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"Exam questions — see the weak vs strong answer","text":"1 mark: identifies that scope defines an in/out boundary. 1 mark: explains it prevents scope creep / uncontrolled feature growth. 1 mark: links the benefit to PixelBoard’s context (shared understanding / meeting the week-8 deadline). 1 mark each for two correct functional requirements (behaviours: save score, show top ten). 1 mark each for two correct non-functional requirements (qualities: reliability, usability). No mark if a quality is listed as functional or vice-versa. 1 mark: functional requirements correct and complete (incl. daily total). 1 mark: at least one genuine non-functional requirement. 1 mark: identifies the technical (printer) constraint. 1 mark: identifies time and/or legal constraint. 1 mark: scope states both in and out (refunds out of scope).","id":668},{"file":"u1o2-kk04.html","nav":"u1o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Programming","title":"Requirements, Constraints & Scope","head":"The whole dotpoint in four lines","text":"FUNC Functional = what it must do . A behaviour you can tick yes/no. Written as a verb on data (sort, store, display). NON-F Non-functional = how well . A quality bar — usually an “-ility” (usability, reliability, security). Make it measurable. CONST Constraint = an imposed limit (economic, technical, legal, social, time). A fence around how you build. SCOPE Scope = the boundary . State what’s in and what’s out. Guards against scope creep.","id":669},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","text":"Every game, app and website is built from created things : code, artwork, music, fonts, fragments of other people's libraries. The moment you make something original, the law treats it as yours . The moment you reach for someone else's work, the law asks one question — do you have permission? This module is the rulebook for both sides of that line.","id":670},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"“Echo Run” — Kai ships a game","text":"Kai is a Year 11 student building Echo Run , a neon endless-runner he wants to publish on an app store and sell for $1.99. To finish it, Kai has to make five decisions that have nothing to do with code working — and everything to do with the law: 1 the runner sprite — draw it, or grab one from another game? 2 the background music — what can he legally play under a paid game? 3 the jump-physics library — open-source code has strings attached 4 the title font — yes, fonts are licensed too 5 his own source code — what licence should he release Echo Run under?","id":671},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"“Echo Run” — Kai ships a game","text":"We follow Kai through every fork. By the end you'll be able to make the same calls — and write them up the way a VCAA examiner wants to read them. “Key legal requirements relating to intellectual property and copyright when designing and developing software.” The support material anchors this to the Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth) and to Creative Commons licences and the restrictions that can still apply to them.","id":672},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Intellectual property: the big umbrella","text":"When you create something with your mind — a tune, a drawing, an invention, a brand name — that creation is intellectual property (IP) . You can't hold it like a phone, but the law still lets you own it, control it and earn from it. “IP” is not one law; it's a family of protections, and software touches several of them at once.","id":673},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Copyright","text":"Protects original expression — code, artwork, music, writing, the look of a UI. Automatic and free. This is the heavyweight for software.","id":674},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Trademark","text":"Protects brand identity — a name, logo or slogan that tells customers who made it. Must be registered to get the ® symbol.","id":675},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Patent","text":"Protects a genuinely new invention or process — how something works. Expensive, must be applied for, rare for student software.","id":676},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Registered design","text":"Protects the visual appearance of a product — its shape or pattern. Occasionally relevant to distinctive device or icon designs. Copyright protects how an idea is expressed ; a patent protects the idea / invention itself . You can copyright the code that sorts a list, but you can't copyright the idea of sorting. For Unit 1 software, copyright does the heavy lifting — so the rest of this module focuses there.","id":677},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The copyright moment","text":"Here's the part students get wrong on exams: copyright is automatic . You don't apply, register or pay. It springs into existence the instant an original work is fixed in a material form — saved to disk, written down, recorded. Before that moment, an idea in your head is not protected. After it, the expression is. Kai is imagining the runner sprite. It only exists in his head — a swirl of possibility. Copyright protects nothing yet, because there is no fixed expression to protect. ↑ Toggle the lab. Watch the loose “idea” cloud condense into a solid, sealed work the moment Kai saves the file.","id":678},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The copyright moment","text":"The © shield appears by itself — no paperwork. The sprite PNG Kai drew and saved His Echo Run source code on disk A level theme he recorded as an MP3 The wording of his game's description “A game where you dodge stuff” — an idea A genre, mechanic or rule on its own A fact (e.g. high score = 9,000) A title or single word (that's trademark territory)","id":679},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"What copyright covers inside a piece of software","text":"A finished app is a bundle of separately-copyrighted works . Pull Echo Run apart and almost every layer is owned by someone — usually whoever created it. The default rule: the creator is the first owner (unless they made it as an employee, or signed the rights away). Literary work under the Act. The way Kai wrote his functions and classes is protected — even if the underlying logic is common. Sprites, backgrounds, icons, button styling. Each is an artistic work with its own copyright. Music tracks and sound effects are protected.","id":680},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"What copyright covers inside a piece of software","text":"A track usually carries two rights — the composition and the recording. Typeface files are licensed software. “Free to download” does not always mean “free to ship in a paid app”. Tutorial copy, store description, in-game dialogue — written works, all protected. “I found it on Google Images, so it's free.” Being able to download something is not permission to use it. Search results, screenshots and “free” asset packs are full of copyrighted work. Use without a licence = infringement, even if you never charged a cent.","id":681},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The licence spectrum","text":"A licence is permission, with conditions, granted by the owner. Licences sit on a spectrum from “all rights reserved” (you may do nothing without asking) to public domain (do anything). Slide along it — the further right you go, the more freedom you get, and usually the fewer strings attached. ↑ Drag the slider. The marker glides from the locked red end to the open green end; the permission chips show exactly what each licence lets Kai do with someone else's work.","id":682},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The licence types you must know","text":"For the exam, you need to recognise the main families of licence and what each one signals about cost and freedom. A royalty-free asset means you pay once and owe no per-use fee afterwards — you might still pay an upfront price and still must follow the licence. Don't confuse it with “free of charge”.","id":683},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Creative Commons, decoded","text":"Creative Commons (CC) lets a creator keep copyright but pre-grant permission on their own terms. A CC licence is built from up to four condition blocks . Read the blocks and you instantly know what you're allowed to do — this is exactly the “restrictions that can still apply” the study design wants you to understand. Credit the creator. Present in every CC licence. If you remix it, release your version under the same licence. No making money from it. Kills a paid game. Use as-is. No editing, cropping or remixing.","id":684},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Back to Echo Run · the music decision","text":"Kai finds a perfect track licensed CC BY-NC . Decode it: BY = he must credit the artist; NC = non-commercial only. But Kai wants to sell Echo Run for $1.99 — that's commercial use. Verdict: he can't use it. He needs a track that is CC BY (commercial OK), CC0, royalty-free with a commercial licence, or one he makes himself. Assuming “Creative Commons” means “free for anything”. It doesn't. NC blocks commercial use and ND blocks editing. Always read the suffix before you build a paid product on top of it.","id":685},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Permissive vs copyleft — the chain reaction","text":"Open-source code is free to use, but the licence on a library can reach into your whole project . This is the difference between permissive licences (like MIT) and copyleft licences (like the GPL). For Echo Run, Kai needs a jump-physics library — and his choice decides whether he can keep his own code private. ↑ “Add GPL library” triggers a copyleft wave: the obligation spreads up through Kai's stack until everything turns copyleft-purple. MIT leaves his cubes blue and free. A developer who drops a GPL library into a closed-source paid product and ships it has breached the licence — a legal problem, not just an ethical one.","id":686},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Permissive vs copyleft — the chain reaction","text":"Knowing the difference between permissive and copyleft is a genuine professional skill, and a favourite VCAA distinguishing question. A sprite ripped from a popular console game A music track licensed CC BY (for a paid game) A music track licensed CC BY-NC (for a paid game) An MIT-licensed jump-physics library A sprite Kai drew himself in Aseprite A 'free' font with no licence stated anywhere","id":687},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Infringement, plagiarism & consequences","text":"Two words students mix up — and an examiner loves to test the difference.","id":688},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Copyright infringement","text":"Using a protected work without permission — copying, sharing, performing or adapting it. This is a breach of the law . It happens even if you credit the creator, because crediting is not the same as having a licence.","id":689},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Plagiarism","text":"Passing off someone else's work as your own — failing to credit. This is mainly an ethical / academic wrong (and against school rules). You can plagiarise something that is not even under copyright. You can infringe without plagiarising (use a licensed song in a video and credit it, but never get the licence) and plagiarise without infringing (copy a public-domain poem and claim you wrote it). Different problems, different fixes: a licence fixes infringement; attribution fixes plagiarism.","id":690},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"What actually happens when you get it wrong","text":"The app store or platform removes your product, often without warning. Repeat strikes can close your developer or channel account entirely. The owner can demand damages or an account of profits. Legal costs dwarf any sales. “The dev who stole assets” follows you. In a small industry, that matters.","id":691},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Kai's release checklist","text":"Here's how Kai legally ships Echo Run. This is the practical workflow examiners want you to be able to recommend. Make or license every asset. Original art & code, or assets whose licence allows commercial use. Keep proof. Read the full licence, not the headline. Decode CC suffixes; check MIT vs GPL on every library. Attribute where required. A credits screen listing CC BY assets, libraries and fonts. Keep your own licence notices intact. Don't strip the MIT notice from a library you reused. Check the font. Confirm the font licence permits embedding in a commercial app.","id":692},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Kai's release checklist","text":"Choose a licence for your code. Proprietary to keep it closed and sell it, or open source to share it. Mark your ownership. Add a copyright notice (© 2026 Kai) — not required for protection, but good practice. Tick them off as you read — your progress saves automatically.","id":693},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"These are written in VCAA style. For each: read the command word, attempt your own answer, then reveal a weak response, a strong response and the marking guide . Use the self-mark dial to bank what you'd score yourself. Define the term intellectual property and give one example relevant to developing software. Intellectual property is stuff you own on a computer like files and programs. Intellectual property is a creation of the mind — such as a work, invention or brand — that the law lets a person own and control.","id":694},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"Example: the original source code a developer writes for a game is their intellectual property, protected by copyright. 1 mark — a correct definition: a creation of the mind that can be legally owned/controlled. 1 mark — a relevant software example (e.g. original source code, game artwork, a track). Explain how the Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth) protects a student's original game code, including when that protection begins and what it covers. Copyright protects your work after you register it with the government so no one can copy your code. Under the Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth), original source code is protected as a literary work.","id":695},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"Protection is automatic and free — it begins the moment the code is fixed in material form (e.g. saved to disk), with no registration required. It protects the student's particular expression of the code, not the underlying idea or algorithm, so others may not copy or adapt that code without permission. 1 mark — protection is automatic, no registration needed. 1 mark — begins when the work is fixed in material form. 1 mark — protects the expression (the code as written), not the idea. A developer wants to use a music track licensed under CC BY-NC in a game they intend to sell.","id":696},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"Explain two conditions this licence places on the developer and the consequence for this project. They have to say thanks to the person and it's free so they can use it in the game. The 'BY' condition requires the developer to attribute (credit) the original creator wherever the track is used. The 'NC' condition restricts use to non-commercial purposes only. Because the developer intends to sell the game, their use is commercial and therefore falls outside what the licence permits — so they cannot legally use this track and would need a commercially-licensed or self-made alternative.","id":697},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"1 mark — BY = attribution required. 1 mark — NC = non-commercial use only. 1 mark — selling the game is commercial use. 1 mark — therefore the track cannot be used / licence would be breached. Distinguish between a permissive open-source licence (e.g. MIT) and a copyleft licence (e.g. GPL), with reference to the obligations each places on a derivative work. MIT and GPL are both free open source licences so you can use them in any project without rules. Both publish source code for reuse, but they differ in the obligations on derivative works.","id":698},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"A permissive licence such as MIT lets a developer reuse the code, keep their own code closed/private and release the larger project under any licence they choose, provided they retain the original notice. A copyleft licence such as the GPL requires that any derivative work which includes the GPL code must also be released as open source under the same (GPL) licence — so a developer cannot keep their project closed if they build on GPL code. 1 mark — both make source available for reuse (shared trait). 1 mark — MIT:","id":699},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"permissive, code can stay closed / any licence (retain notice). 1 mark — GPL: copyleft, derivative must be open source. 1 mark — under the same/GPL licence (clear contrast on derivative obligation). Kai is about to publish Echo Run (a paid game). He has used: a sprite he drew himself, a music track licensed CC BY-SA , and an MIT -licensed physics library. Recommend and justify the steps Kai must take to release the game legally, and recommend a licence for his own code. Kai should just publish it because he made most of it himself and credit everyone in the description to be safe.","id":700},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"Kai owns the sprite he drew, so he may use it freely. The MIT library is permissive: he may include it and keep his own code private, as long as he retains the MIT licence notice in the project. The CC BY-SA track allows commercial use, so selling the game is fine — but he must (a) attribute the artist, and (b) note that the Share-Alike condition requires anything he distributes that adapts the track to carry the same CC BY-SA licence; if he only plays it unchanged he must still credit it.","id":701},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"He should add a credits screen listing the track and the MIT library, confirm the title font's licence allows commercial embedding, and add a copyright notice for his own work. For his own code, a proprietary licence is appropriate because he wants to sell a closed-source game and the MIT library permits that — this keeps his source private while meeting every other licence's conditions. 1 mark — own sprite: he owns it, use freely. 1 mark — MIT library: permissive, keep code closed, retain notice. 1 mark — CC BY-SA allows commercial sale (so a paid game is OK).","id":702},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Exam questions — with weak & strong responses","text":"1 mark — BY-SA still requires attribution AND share-alike on adaptations. 1 mark — practical steps: credits screen / check font / © notice. 1 mark — justified licence for own code (proprietary/closed) consistent with selling + MIT allowing it.","id":703},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Most marks are lost not because students don't know the content, but because they don't structure the answer. For “explain” and “justify” questions, write in P·E·L : Point · Explain · Link . Build one below. P Kai cannot legally use the CC BY-NC track in Echo Run. E The “NC” block means the licence permits non-commercial use only; because Kai intends to sell the game for $1.99, his use is commercial and falls outside what the licence grants. L Using it anyway would be copyright infringement — exposing him to a store takedown — so he must source a track licensed for commercial use or create his own.","id":704},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"The verb in the question tells you how much to write. Match the command word to the move — and the marks usually match the depth. Give a fact or name — no explanation needed. Give the precise meaning of a term. Give the features or characteristics — what it is and looks like. Say how or why — show cause, effect and reasoning. Show the difference(s) between two things, point by point. Make a choice and defend it with reasons that beat the alternatives.","id":705},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Five traps that cost marks","text":"Wrong in Australia. Copyright is automatic on fixation. Registration belongs to trademarks and patents . Attribution fixes plagiarism, not infringement. You still need a licence to use protected work. NC blocks selling; ND blocks editing. Always decode the suffix. Open source still has a licence. GPL (copyleft) can force your whole project open. Copyright = the expression (the code as written). Patent = the invention/idea (a novel process).","id":706},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Key-term flip cards","text":"Tap a card to flip. Say the definition out loud before you check. 1 When does copyright protection of original software begin in Australia? 2 A track is licensed CC BY-NC. Kai wants to sell his game. Can he use it? 3 What is the key obligation a GPL (copyleft) library places on a derivative work? 4 Which best distinguishes infringement from plagiarism? 5 Copyright protects ___, while a patent protects ___. 6 A font is 'free to download' but states no licence. The safest action is to:","id":707},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"The five must-knows","text":"IP = copyright + trademark + patent + design. Copyright is automatic, free, protects expression fixed in material form . Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth) is the law. Licence = permission with conditions from the owner. Creator is first owner by default.","id":708},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Licence spectrum","text":"© All rights reserved → ask first. Proprietary / EULA → buy a use licence. Freeware / shareware → free use, closed source. Open source → MIT (permissive) vs GPL (copyleft). CC0 / public domain → do anything.","id":709},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Creative Commons blocks","text":"BY — credit the creator (always). SA — share remixes under the same licence. NC — no commercial use (kills a paid app). ND — no edits or remixes.","id":710},{"file":"u1o2-kk06.html","nav":"u1o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Programming","title":"Who owns what you make — and what you use ?","head":"Don't mix these up","text":"Infringement = no licence (legal). Fix: get a licence. Plagiarism = no credit (ethical). Fix: attribute. Copyright = expression. Patent = invention. Royalty-free ≠ free of charge. Download ≠ permission. That's KK06. You can now define IP, explain how copyright protects software, decode any licence, and recommend a legal release path — and write it up in P·E·L.","id":711},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The two ideas that tame complexity","text":"Object-oriented programming rests on two foundations: abstraction — showing only what matters — and encapsulation — bundling data with the methods that guard it. Master both and big programs stop being scary.","id":712},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"What KK07 actually asks of you","text":"This is dot point 7 of the Programming chapter. The study design lists the examinable principles in one line — read it carefully, because the wording is the marking key. \" the principles of object-oriented programming: abstraction and encapsulation \" That's the whole dot point. Two words do the heavy lifting, and the examiner expects you to be able to define each one, describe how it works, and apply it to a scenario you've never seen before. You won't be asked to write a full class — you'll be asked to reason about why a class is built the way it is.","id":713},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"What KK07 actually asks of you","text":"For Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 the OOP principles are only abstraction and encapsulation . Inheritance and generalisation are NOT in this dot point — they belong to Software Development Units 3 & 4 . If you list four pillars here, you've answered a different course's question. Stick to two.","id":714},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"◐ Abstraction","text":"Show only the essential details and hide the rest. You drive a car without knowing how fuel injection works. The simple controls are the abstraction.","id":715},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"🔒 Encapsulation","text":"Bundle the data with the methods that act on it inside one object, and only let the outside world touch it through controlled doors.","id":716},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Complexity is the enemy. These are the weapons.","text":"A real app has thousands of moving parts. Nobody can hold all of it in their head at once. OOP's trick is to break the system into objects — self-contained units that each look after one thing — so you only ever think about a small piece at a time.","id":717},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Meet our running example: BeatBox","text":"Maya (Year 11) is building BeatBox , a music app, for her programming SAT. Inside it lives a Player object that holds the current song, the volume, and the play position — and knows how to play() , pause() and skip() . We'll use this one object to see both principles in action. Think of an object as a tiny appliance . From the outside it has a few buttons. Inside it has wiring you never see and never touch. Abstraction is the decision about which buttons to put on the outside.","id":718},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Meet our running example: BeatBox","text":"Encapsulation is the case that seals the wiring in and forces everyone to use those buttons. Same appliance, two different jobs. Abstraction = hide complexity (the \"what\", not the \"how\"). · Encapsulation = hide data and control access (the \"case\" around the object).","id":719},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Abstraction — show the buttons, hide the engine","text":"Abstraction means representing something by its essential features only, and leaving out the detail that doesn't matter to the person using it. It lets you work at a high level without drowning in how things actually happen underneath.","id":720},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"What you keep","text":"The essential stuff: a song has a title , an artist , a duration . The Player offers play() and pause() . That's all anyone needs to use it.","id":721},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"What you hide","text":"The messy \"how\" : decoding the audio file, filling the playback buffer, talking to the sound card. Real, necessary — and completely irrelevant to someone pressing ▶.","id":722},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The classic car analogy","text":"You start a car with a key or a button. You steer, brake, accelerate. You do not need to understand combustion, the gearbox or the ECU. The dashboard is an abstraction of a hugely complex machine — it exposes only the controls you need. A Player object does the same for audio playback. In code, abstraction shows up as method names and the public interface of a class. When Maya writes player.skip() , she's using an abstraction: one short call stands in for dozens of hidden steps. If she ever rewrites the guts of skip() , every part of her app that calls it keeps working — because the interface didn't change, only the hidden implementation did.","id":723},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The classic car analogy","text":"\"Abstraction is the principle of representing a real-world entity in software by its essential characteristics and behaviours only, hiding unnecessary implementation detail so the solution is simpler to understand and use.\"","id":724},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The BeatBox controls — abstraction you can touch","text":"Press the buttons on the player. They're simple. Now hit Peek inside to lift the case and watch the hidden machinery that every press actually triggers. That gap — simple outside, complex inside — is abstraction. With the case closed, you'd never guess how much happens per press. That's the point: the interface (buttons) is deliberately tiny so the user isn't burdened with the implementation (the churning parts). Good abstraction means you could swap the whole engine and the buttons wouldn't change.","id":725},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Encapsulation — seal the data, guard the doors","text":"Encapsulation means bundling an object's data (its attributes) together with the methods that operate on that data into a single unit — the object — and restricting direct outside access to the data. The outside world can only change things through methods you allow. It has two halves, and strong answers name both:","id":726},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"1 · Bundling","text":"The volume , currentSong and position live inside the Player object, right next to play() and setVolume() . Data and the code that uses it travel together as one capsule.","id":727},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"2 · Information hiding","text":"Those fields are marked private . Outside code can't write player.volume = 9000 . It must call player.setVolume(80) , which can check and clamp the value first.","id":728},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The capsule analogy","text":"Encapsulation literally means \"to put in a capsule\". A medicine capsule holds the contents together and protects them from the outside. An object does both: it keeps related data and methods together, and shields the data behind a controlled surface so it can't be set to a nonsense value by accident. Why bother? Because if any part of a program could reach in and change volume directly, a single typo could set it to -50 or 9000 and break playback — and you'd have no idea which line did it.","id":729},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The capsule analogy","text":"With encapsulation there's one door ( setVolume() ), so there's one place to validate, one place to fix, and one place to look when something goes wrong. \"Encapsulation is the principle of combining an object's data with the methods that operate on it into a single unit, and restricting direct access to that data so it can only be changed through controlled methods, protecting it from invalid or unintended modification.\"","id":730},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The volume vault — watch the guard work","text":"The volume field is sealed inside the object (valid range 0–100). Try to slam a rogue value straight at the data — it bounces off the private wall. Then send it through the setVolume() door and watch it get checked and clamped before it's allowed in. Flip the route to through setVolume() and the same rogue value is no longer dangerous: the method validates it (range check), clamps 120→100 and −30→0, and only then updates the field. The door is the single safe entry point — that's information hiding doing its job.","id":731},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Class vs object — blueprint vs the real thing","text":"Abstraction and encapsulation are both expressed through classes and objects , so you have to keep these two terms straight — examiners love to test the difference.","id":732},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Class = the blueprint","text":"A template that defines what every Player will have (its data) and do (its methods). Written once. You can't \"play\" a blueprint — it's the plan, not the appliance.","id":733},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Object = the instance","text":"A real, working Player created from the class, living in memory with its own actual volume and current song. One class, as many objects as you like.","id":734},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Cookie-cutter and cookies","text":"The class is the cookie cutter: one shape, defining every cookie's outline. Each object is a cookie you stamp out — same shape, but its own dough, its own sprinkles, eaten independently. Change the cutter and future cookies change; the cookies already made are separate. In the hero animation at the top, the glowing panel is the class ; the little units budding off it and drifting away are objects — instances stamped from the same plan.","id":735},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Abstraction vs encapsulation — not the same thing","text":"They work together so closely that students blur them. They both involve \"hiding\", but they hide different things for different reasons . This table is the difference that wins marks. Question Abstraction ◐ Encapsulation 🔒 What does it hide? Complexity — the implementation detail (\"how\"). Data — the internal state, behind private access. Why? So the solution is simpler to understand and use . So data can't be changed invalidly or by accident. Level it works at Design — deciding what the interface should be. Implementation — controlling access to the data.","id":736},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Abstraction vs encapsulation — not the same thing","text":"Shows up as Method names & the public interface of a class. Private fields + getter/setter methods bundled in. BeatBox example player.skip() hides all the playback steps. volume is private; only setVolume() can change it. They're two sides of the same coin. Abstraction is the architect drawing simple plans; encapsulation is the builder sealing the walls so nobody can mess with the wiring. You design with abstraction and protect with encapsulation.","id":737},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Both principles, highlighted","text":"Here's a trimmed Player class. Blue marks abstraction (a simple public method hiding detail). Amber marks encapsulation (private data + a guarded door). You don't have to write this in the exam — you have to recognise and explain it. The blue play() is abstraction: the caller writes one line; three hidden helpers do the work. The amber __volume + set_volume() is encapsulation: the field is private (double underscore), and the setter validates before storing. You can describe both without writing a line of Python.","id":738},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Drag each statement into the right principle","text":"Eight statements. Drop each into Abstraction or Encapsulation . Correct drops turn green and add to your score; wrong drops turn red so you can rethink. (On touch screens, tap a chip then tap a bin.)","id":739},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Four fast questions","text":"Instant feedback. Each correct answer adds a point to your dock. These mirror the multiple-choice style of Section A.","id":740},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Six traps that cost students marks","text":"Every one of these is a real, repeated mistake. Learn the fix and you've already beaten most of the cohort.","id":741},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Swapping the two definitions","text":"Writing \"abstraction hides the data\" — that's encapsulation. Abstraction hides complexity .","id":742},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Listing four pillars","text":"Adding inheritance and generalisation. Those are Units 3 & 4 (Software Development), not this dot point.","id":743},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Encapsulation = \"make it private\"","text":"Private fields are only half of it. You also have to mention bundling data with its methods.","id":744},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"No example from the scenario","text":"A textbook definition with nothing tied to the case study caps your marks on \"describe/explain\" questions.","id":745},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Confusing class and object","text":"Calling the blueprint an \"object\" or vice-versa. The class is the template ; the object is the instance .","id":746},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Stating what , never why","text":"\"Encapsulation makes data private.\" True, but \"explain/justify\" wants the benefit.","id":747},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks are won with structure. P·E·L — Point, Example, Link — turns a vague sentence into a full-mark one. First, match the command word to what it's really asking.","id":748},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"State the principle","text":"Name it and give the precise definition. \"Encapsulation bundles data with its methods and restricts direct access.\"","id":749},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Then comes evidence","text":"Switch to the example tab to see how to anchor it to BeatBox.","id":750},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Then the link","text":"Switch to the link tab to see how to tie it to a benefit.","id":751},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Give a concrete example","text":"Pull a real element from the scenario. \"In BeatBox the volume field is private and can only be changed via setVolume() .\"","id":752},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Then the link","text":"One more tab — connect it to why it matters.","id":753},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Link to the benefit","text":"State the payoff. \"…so the volume can't be set to an invalid value, protecting playback from errors and making the code easier to maintain.\" \"BeatBox uses encapsulation (P) : the volume field is kept private inside the Player object and can only be changed through the setVolume() method (E) , so the value is always validated and can't be set to something invalid like 9000, which protects playback and makes the program easier to maintain (L) .\" Your turn. Write an explain -level answer for abstraction in BeatBox. The detector below lights up as you include each P·E·L element and a scenario anchor.","id":754},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Five questions · good vs bad responses","text":"A fresh scenario, so you have to transfer the idea — not just recall BeatBox. Each question shows a weak and a strong response with examiner annotations and a marking guide. Read both, then self-mark honestly. Your running total sits in the dock. FitTrack is a fitness app built by Sam. It has a Member object that stores a private restingHeartRate (valid 30–220 bpm) and a private name . Members are updated through methods like recordHeartRate() . A simple member.startWorkout() call kicks off logging, GPS tracking and timing behind the scenes.","id":755},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Five questions · good vs bad responses","text":"1 mark for: representing an entity by its essential characteristics only / hiding unnecessary detail or complexity . Do not award if the answer hides \"data\" or \"code\" — that's encapsulation. 1 mark — the field is private / access is restricted (information hiding). 1 mark — it can only be changed through a method (controlled access), ideally naming recordHeartRate() . Anchoring to the scenario (the actual field/method) is expected at \"describe\". 1 mark — identifies abstraction hiding the implementation steps behind startWorkout() . 1 mark — links to the scenario (Sam / FitTrack uses the simple call).","id":756},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Five questions · good vs bad responses","text":"1 mark — explains a genuine benefit: reuse , simpler to use , or easier to maintain because the interface stays stable when internals change. 1 mark — abstraction = hiding complexity / implementation detail (the \"how\"). 1 mark — encapsulation = bundling + hiding data, controlled access (the internal state). 1 mark — valid abstraction example ( startWorkout() ). 1 mark — valid encapsulation example (private restingHeartRate via a method). Up to 2 marks — abstraction: breaking the system into objects with simple interfaces so the programmer reasons about one piece at a time (reuse / simpler).","id":757},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"Five questions · good vs bad responses","text":"Up to 2 marks — encapsulation: private data + controlled access isolates and protects each object's state; single point to validate/fix. 1 mark — explicit link to managing complexity / maintainability as the program grows. Best answers are anchored to FitTrack objects, not generic.","id":758},{"file":"u1o2-kk07.html","nav":"u1o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Programming","title":"The two ideas that tame complexity","head":"The whole dot point on one card","text":"If you revise nothing else the night before, revise this. Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 Programming · U1·O2 · KK07 — Principles of OOP (Abstraction & Encapsulation) · Study Design 2025–2028 · en-AU","id":759},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"The four building blocks every program is made from","text":"A computer can only ever do a handful of truly different things: store a value, decide between paths, repeat work, calculate with operators, and reuse a named block of code. Master these and you can read or write any object-oriented program ever written.","id":760},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"📋 What the study design actually asks","text":"The VCAA wording for this dot point lists the features of an object-oriented programming language you must be able to use and describe: Feature family Examinable items Variables named storage for a value that can change while the program runs Control structures sequence · selection · iteration / repetition Operators arithmetic · logical (AND/OR/NOT) · conditional / relational Reusable blocks procedures · functions · methods ⏱️ Work top-to-bottom for a full lesson, or jump via the rail. Interactive checks feed the score ring (bottom-right). Everything is saved in your browser — close the tab and come back later.","id":761},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"01 · The Control-Flow Engine","text":"A running program is a single point of attention — the program counter — moving through your instructions. The three control structures are the only three shapes that path can take. Press play and watch the glowing token travel. The fork is a selection (member → discount branch, guest → straight on). The circular return path is an iteration that runs once per topping layer. Change the toggles and replay to see the path physically re-route.","id":762},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Sequence","text":"Steps run one after another, top to bottom. The default — no keyword needed.","id":763},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Selection","text":"A condition picks one branch. if / elif / else .","id":764},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Iteration","text":"A block repeats. for (counted) or while (condition).","id":765},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"02 · Variables — labelled boxes in memory","text":"A variable is a named box that holds one value at a time. The name is the label on the box; the value inside can be swapped out as the program runs. The kind of value it holds (its data type — text, number, Boolean) was KK02; here we care about using it. Think of the kiosk’s order screen. Each thing it remembers is a variable: An assignment uses = meaning “put the value on the right into the box on the left”. It is not the maths “equals”.","id":766},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"🔎 Step the value through","text":"Watch one box, total , change as three lines run. Tap Next line .","id":767},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"03 · Control structures up close","text":"The engine showed the shapes; here is the code and the analogy for each. Examiners love asking you to name the structure and justify why it suits the task.","id":768},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"① Sequence — “follow the recipe in order”","text":"Instructions execute one after another, exactly as written. Order matters: pour tea before adding the lid.","id":769},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"② Selection — “the fork in the road”","text":"A condition decides which branch runs. Use if for one test, elif for more, else for the catch-all.","id":770},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"③ Iteration — “keep going until done”","text":"A block repeats. A counted loop ( for ) runs a known number of times; a conditional loop ( while ) runs until something becomes false.","id":771},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"04 · Operators — the verbs of code","text":"Operators combine or compare values. The study design names three families. Mixing them up is one of the most common dropped marks, so nail the categories.","id":772},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Arithmetic","text":"Do maths, give a number . + − * / // % **","id":773},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Conditional / relational","text":"Compare two values, give True/False . == != < > <= >=","id":774},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"Logical","text":"Join True/False values. and · or · not Priya’s discount rule needs all three at once — arithmetic to build the total, relational to test it, logical to combine conditions:","id":775},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"🧪 Operator playground","text":"Pick two values and an operator. Arithmetic returns a number; relational and logical return True / False . Try 9.10 > 8.00 , then True and False . This is a relational operator → returns True/False.","id":776},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"05 · The Function Factory","text":"A procedure , function and method are all named, reusable blocks — but the exam wants you to tell them apart. Watch the machine and the difference clicks: it’s about what comes back and who it belongs to . Block Returns a value? Belongs to an object? BobaBot example Function ✅ Yes — that’s the point calculateTotal(base, n) → returns 9.10 Procedure ❌ No — it just does something makeDrink() → pours & builds, returns nothing Method Either ✅ Yes — called on an object drink.addTopping(\"pearls\")","id":777},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"06 · Trace the loop","text":"“Desk-checking” — running code by hand and recording each variable — is a guaranteed exam skill. Fill the table for this counted loop, then check it. (3 marks to the ring.) Pass total after line","id":778},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"07 · Name that feature","text":"Drag each snippet into the family it belongs to. On a phone, tap a snippet then tap a bin. (6 marks to the ring.)","id":779},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"08 · Decode the command word","text":"VCAA marks the verb . “Identify” is worth less effort than “explain”; “justify” needs a reason. Match your answer length to the word. Name it. One word or short phrase. “Selection (an if-statement).” Say what it is and a feature of it. Two sentences. Say what and why/how it works in this context. Cause → effect. Give a similarity and a difference — both, explicitly, side by side. Make a choice and defend it with a reason tied to the scenario. Produce actual code or pseudocode . Syntax must be plausible and correct.","id":780},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"10 · Write it the P·E·L way","text":"For “explain / justify” questions, structure beats waffle. P oint (name it) → E xample (from the scenario) → L ink (back to the question). Toggle a worked answer, then write your own and watch the meter.","id":781},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"POINT Name the feature precisely","text":"“BobaBot should use a selection control structure (an if/elif/else ) to choose the base price.” Your turn. Q: Explain why BobaBot needs a selection control structure to set the cup price. Aim to hit all three P·E·L pips. Type at least 12 words to score it.","id":782},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"11 · Quick six","text":"Instant feedback. Each correct answer adds to the ring.","id":783},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"12 · VCE-style exam practice","text":"Five questions, 20 marks . Try each before revealing. Read the weak answer to see how marks slip, the strong answer for full marks, then self-mark — it feeds the ring. “Loops and if statements.” Only two ideas, both vaguely worded. “Loops” is informal for iteration; sequence is missing entirely. Caps at 1 mark. 1 mark per correctly named structure, to a max of 2 here (full list = 3 names). Accept ‘repetition’ for iteration. ‘Sequence’ must appear — most-missed item. “It uses an if statement to check the member.","id":784},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"12 · VCE-style exam practice","text":"It is true.” Names the control structure, not the operators asked for. Doesn’t identify ‘and’ (logical) or ‘>’ (relational). No working shown → 1 mark of 3. 1 mark: relational/conditional identified for >. 1 mark: logical identified for and. 1 mark: correct overall result True with brief working. “A function does something and a procedure also does something. Like makeDrink and calculateTotal.” States they’re similar but never gives the distinguishing feature (return value). Examples aren’t tied to which is which. Around 1–2 marks. 1 mark: function returns a value. 1 mark:","id":785},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"12 · VCE-style exam practice","text":"procedure performs an action / no return. 1 mark each for a correct, matched BobaBot example (2). “total = cupSize + toppings” No selection structure — ignores the three size cases. Adds text to a number (type error). Misses the per-topping arithmetic. ~1 mark. 1: correct if/elif/else selection. 1: all three prices correct incl. else default. 1: arithmetic total = base + toppings*0.80. 1: plausible syntax (colons/indentation). 1: returns or sets total clearly. “Use a for loop 10 times because 100/10 is 10.” Reaches the right count but doesn’t justify why while suits an ‘until full’ goal.","id":786},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"12 · VCE-style exam practice","text":"No trace of the changing level. Misses the justification marks → ~2–3. 1: identifies while (or for) as iteration. 2: justification references repeat-until-condition vs counted. 2: correct trace of level changing by 10. 1: correct final count of 10 pours.","id":787},{"file":"u1o2-kk08.html","nav":"u1o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Programming","title":"The four building blocks every program is made from","head":"13 · One-screen cheat sheet","text":"Named box holding a value that can change = is assignment , not maths equals Type comes from the value: text, number, Boolean Sequence — top-to-bottom, order matters Selection — if/elif/else , picks one branch Iteration — for (counted) / while (condition) Arithmetic → number: + - * / % ** Relational → T/F: == != < > <= >= Logical join T/F: and · or · not Function — return s a value Procedure — does an action, no return Method — written object.name() = assign vs == compare if = selection (structure), > = operator logical ( and ) vs relational ( > ) Match points to marks Use P·E·L for explain/justify “Function” → always say “returns”","id":788},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Naming conventions for solution elements","text":"A name is the smallest design decision in your program — and the one you make most often. Get it right and your code reads like plain English. Get it wrong and your own project, six weeks later, reads like a stranger's handwriting. This dot point names two conventions you must know: Hungarian notation and camelCase . \"Solution elements\" = the things you give names to: variables, constants, functions/methods, objects/classes, GUI controls (text boxes, buttons, labels) and files. This dot point is examinable. Eight identical grey boxes — the same variable, button and method, with no identity.","id":789},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Naming conventions for solution elements","text":"Watch the name-tags arrive and snap each box into its convention's colour. That tag is the whole idea: a good name tells you what a thing is the instant you read it.","id":790},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Code is read far more than it is written","text":"You type a line of code once. You — plus your teammates, your teacher, the marker of your SAT, and \"future you\" debugging at 11 pm — will read it dozens of times. The name is the part you read. A computer does not care what you call things; x , a1 and intHighScore all run identically. Names are written entirely for humans .","id":791},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"🧳 The airport-luggage analogy","text":"Imagine a baggage carousel where every suitcase is the same plain black bag with no tag. They all work as luggage — but finding yours means opening every single one. Now add tags: a colour for the airline, your name, your destination. You spot yours in a second. A naming convention is the agreed system for those tags, so everyone on the team reads them the same way.","id":792},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Readability","text":"A name should reveal purpose. playerScore beats x every time.","id":793},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Consistency","text":"One agreed system across the whole solution, so the team isn't reading five different styles.","id":794},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Maintainability","text":"Good names mean fewer comments, faster debugging, and cheaper changes months later. In the exam, \"purpose\" answers nearly always come back to these three words: readability , consistency , maintainability . Lock them in.","id":795},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"What counts as a \"solution element\"?","text":"The study design says naming conventions distinguish solution elements . So first — what are they? Meet ArcadeBox , a tiny retro arcade high-score app we'll use all the way through. Every kind of named thing appears in it. Notice the prefixes already: txt btn lbl int bool . Those are Hungarian notation. The way each name runs words together with a capital — playerName , startGame — that's camelCase. They work together . We'll pull them apart next.","id":796},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"The Name-Tag Inspector","text":"Pick a raw idea — say \"player score\" — then flip between conventions and watch the same element get re-tagged live. This is the single most useful drill for this dot point: see how one purpose is dressed in each style. Hungarian: a type/control prefix is bolted on the front, then the rest is camel-cased. Best for telling similar elements apart.","id":797},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Hungarian notation — a prefix that says what a thing is","text":"Hungarian notation adds a short lowercase prefix to the front of a name to flag what kind of thing it is — its type or its purpose . The rest of the name describes what it's for. The combination of type + purpose in one name is the heart of the idea.","id":798},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"GUI control prefixes","text":"txt text box → txtPlayerName btn button → btnStart lbl label → lblScore cbo combo box → cboDifficulty chk checkbox → chkSound","id":799},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Data-type prefixes","text":"int integer → intScore str string → strPlayerName bool boolean → boolGameOver dbl double → dblAvgScore arr array → arrHighScores","id":800},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"🧠 The backstory — why \"Hungarian\"?","text":"It's named after Charles Simonyi , a Hungarian-born programmer who created the style at Xerox PARC and brought it to Microsoft in the 1980s, where it shaped early Word and Excel. The nickname is a small joke: Hungarian names are written surname first (family name, then given name) — and Simonyi's prefixes put the \"type\" first, before the descriptive part. So a name like strPlayerName reads \"type-first\", just like a Hungarian name. (Simonyi later became wealthy enough to fly to the International Space Station — twice — but that's a story for another lesson.)","id":801},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Two flavours (worth a mark in extended answers)","text":"Prefix shows the data type : intScore , strName . This is the version VCE uses and the one in most VB textbooks. Prefix shows the purpose/role , not the raw type — e.g. rwPosition (row), cbWidth (count of bytes). Simonyi's original intent.","id":802},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"camelCase — humps where the words join","text":"A name can't contain spaces, so we need a way to glue words together and still read them. camelCase keeps the first word lowercase, then capitalises the start of every word after it. The capitals stick up like a camel's humps — hence the name (coined in 1995, but in use since the 1970s). two words → player score → playerScore high score → highScore start game → startGame","id":803},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Where you'll see it","text":"camelCase is the standard for variables and methods in Visual Basic, Java, C#, JavaScript and many others. It also sits inside Hungarian names: in txtPlayerName , the txt is Hungarian and the PlayerName part is camel-cased.","id":804},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Don't confuse it with its cousins","text":"PascalCase is just camelCase with the first letter also capitalised. The exam tell: classes and objects ( Player , ScoreBoard ) use PascalCase; the variables and methods inside them use camelCase.","id":805},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Live convention converter","text":"Type any idea in plain words — \"final boss health bar\" , \"is paused\" , \"max attempts\" — and see it rendered in every convention at once. This is exactly the transformation an exam question expects you to do by hand. Hungarian here uses a sensible default prefix; in real code you'd pick the prefix that matches the element's actual type or control.","id":806},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Sort the names into the right convention","text":"Drag each name into the bin for the convention it follows (or tap a chip, then tap a bin on touch devices). You'll get instant feedback and a score.","id":807},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Spot the element → name it","text":"Tap a card. Front: an ArcadeBox element. Back: a well-named version and why.","id":808},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"The P·E·L technique","text":"Short-answer marks are won with structure, not waffle. Use P·E·L : Point (name it), Explain (how/why it works), Link (tie it to the scenario or a benefit). Draft an answer below to: \"Explain one benefit of using Hungarian notation when naming ArcadeBox's GUI controls.\" The meter lights up as your answer hits the ideas a marker looks for.","id":809},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Model answer","text":"Point. A Hungarian prefix shows the type of each control directly in its name. Explain. Naming the start button btnStart and the score label lblScore means a reader can tell a button apart from a label without opening the form designer. Link. This improves readability and maintainability — anyone who later edits ArcadeBox can find and change the right control quickly, with less chance of wiring code to the wrong element.","id":810},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"VCE-style practice · 18 marks","text":"Each question has a weak answer (with the marker's notes), a strong answer , and a marking guide . Try it on paper first, reveal, then self-mark — your total tracks in the dock below. Define the term naming convention and state one reason a software team would agree on one. ArcadeBox stores the player's current score and whether the round has ended. Using Hungarian notation , name these two variables and justify each prefix. A student names a class player and a variable PlayerScore . Identify the convention error in each and give the corrected name.","id":811},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"VCE-style practice · 18 marks","text":"ArcadeBox's interface has a text box for the player's name and a label that displays it. Explain why naming conventions are especially important when two controls relate to the same thing, and give suitable names for both. A teammate sends you this snippet from ArcadeBox. Identify three separate naming problems and rewrite the three names to follow good convention, then state the overall benefit your changes deliver.","id":812},{"file":"u1o2-kk09.html","nav":"u1o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Programming","title":"Naming conventions for solution elements","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"Names are for humans. Good ones buy readability, consistency and maintainability. Variables, constants, functions/methods, objects/classes, GUI controls, files — anything you name. Lowercase prefix = type/purpose ( int str bool txt btn lbl ) + descriptive body. Charles Simonyi, Microsoft, 1980s. firstWordLowerThenHumps. Standard for variables & methods. Lives inside Hungarian names too. PascalCase classes/objects · snake_case (Python) · SCREAMING constants. Name a convention → always pair it with a purpose . Prefixes must not lie. Stay consistent.","id":813},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","text":"Code tells the computer what to do . Internal documentation tells a human what the code is doing, and why it was built that way — written right inside the source file as comments and clean layout. This is the dot point examiners love, because it separates students who can write code from students who can write code someone else can maintain .","id":814},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Meet CourtBook — and the bug Mia inherited","text":"Kai, a Year 12 student, built CourtBook : a small app that lets students book the school gym's basketball courts at lunch. It worked. Then Kai graduated and left. Three weeks later, courts are being double-booked. The job of fixing it lands on Mia , a Year 11 who has never seen this code before . She opens the file. Whether she fixes the bug in ten minutes or loses a whole afternoon depends almost entirely on one thing: did Kai leave internal documentation? That last clause matters. A comment changes nothing about what the program outputs.","id":815},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Meet CourtBook — and the bug Mia inherited","text":"It exists purely to make the code understandable to a human reader — which is exactly why a beginner is tempted to skip it, and exactly why examiners ask about it.","id":816},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Internal vs external documentation","text":"Don't mix these up — it's a classic trap.","id":817},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"The pieces of internal documentation","text":"Internal documentation comes in two broad forms: comments (written notes the language ignores) and formatting (how the code is laid out). Comments themselves come in a few recognisable flavours. Click any line below to see what it's doing.","id":818},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"The header / metadata block","text":"A block of comments at the top of a file or module that records who, what, when and why. The first thing Mia reads. Click each line:","id":819},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Warning comments","text":"A comment that flags something surprising or fragile — a place where the obvious change would break things. These earn their keep.","id":820},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"The three purposes of internal documentation","text":"If you remember nothing else, remember these three. They are the answer to almost every \"explain the purpose(s)\" question on this dot point.","id":821},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Explain & justify structures","text":"Describe what the data structures and code structures do, and why they were chosen. A comment notes that bookings are kept in a list of records (not a single array) because each booking carries several fields — court, slot, student — of different types.","id":822},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Support maintenance","text":"Help a future programmer (or future-you) debug, update and extend the solution quickly and safely. Mia reads the comment on is_clash() and instantly sees the double-booking bug: it only checked the court, not the time. The comment told her the intended rule, so the gap was obvious.","id":823},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Describe stubs","text":"Mark and explain unfinished sections — placeholders left for later — so they aren't mistaken for working code. A stub for the future \"email confirmation\" feature is a comment-only placeholder: # STUB: send_email() — returns True for now . It documents intent without pretending to work.","id":824},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Explain vs justify — the distinction that splits the band","text":"Purpose 1 contains two verbs, and students lose marks by treating them as the same word. They are not. Quick test: if your comment could start with \"because…\" , it's a justification . If it starts with \"this…\" or \"loops/checks/sets…\" , it's an explanation . Strong answers in an exam often give one of each.","id":825},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Layout is documentation too","text":"Comments get the attention, but how the code is laid out is internal documentation as well — it shapes how fast a human can read structure. Indentation, blank lines between logical chunks, and meaningful names all communicate without a single comment . Compare these two versions of the same function — identical behaviour, very different readability. The right-hand version barely needs a comment — the meaningful names ( slot_is_free , existing_bookings ) and the indentation document the logic by themselves. This is why naming conventions (KK09) and internal documentation are siblings: good names are documentation you don't have to write twice.","id":826},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Signal vs noise — more comments isn't better","text":"A common misconception is \"good documentation = lots of comments.\" Wrong. A comment that just restates the code adds noise — it clutters the file and goes stale the moment the code changes. Good comments add signal : the why , the gotcha , the intent the code can't show. Rule of thumb to repeat in your head: comment the why, not the what. The code already shows what it does; your comment should capture what the code can't say.","id":827},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"The Maintenance Time Machine","text":"Here's Kai's is_clash() module as a 3D object. Flip the documentation switch and watch two things happen: the comment-tags fade in around the code, and the meter shows roughly how long it takes a brand-new programmer like Mia to understand and safely change it. Drag to rotate.","id":828},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Time-to-understand simulator","text":"The numbers are illustrative, but the relationship is real and well documented in software engineering: developers spend far more time reading existing code than writing new code, so anything that speeds reading pays for itself many times over.","id":829},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Sort it out","text":"Drag each chip into the correct bin. Each sorter saves your score — get them all to all correct .","id":830},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Calling a user manual \"internal documentation\"","text":"User manuals, help guides and technical specs are external . Internal documentation lives inside the source code .","id":831},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Thinking comments change how the program runs","text":"Comments are ignored by the compiler/interpreter . They never affect output, speed or behaviour. They benefit humans, not execution.","id":832},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Treating \"explain\" and \"justify\" as the same thing","text":"Explain = what/how . Justify = why this choice . A \"justify\" comment can usually start with \"because…\".","id":833},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"\"My code works, so comments are a waste\"","text":"Working code and maintainable code are different goals. The cost of missing documentation appears later — when someone else (or future-you) must change it.","id":834},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Equating \"more comments\" with \"better\"","text":"Comments that restate the code are noise — they clutter and go stale. Quality means commenting the why , not the obvious what .","id":835},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Forgetting layout counts","text":"Internal documentation isn't only comments. Indentation, white space and meaningful names document structure too.","id":836},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Saying documentation is \"only for other people\"","text":"The most common reader is future-you , who has forgotten the details. Maintenance includes your own later edits.","id":837},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure, not length. Use Point → Evidence → Link . Draft an answer to the prompt below; the keyword tags light up as you hit the ideas examiners reward.","id":838},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Prompt: \"Explain one purpose of internal documentation in a software solution.\" (2 marks)","text":"State the purpose plainly. e.g. \"One purpose is to support maintenance.\" Show how — name a concrete mechanism (a comment explaining a structure, a header block). Connect to the benefit — a future programmer can debug/update the code faster and more safely.","id":839},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Practice questions","text":"Five VCE-style questions. For each, try it yourself first, then reveal a weak and a strong response with annotations and the marking guide. Self-mark honestly — your score tracks at the top. 1 mark — definition: explanatory notes within the source code , for human readers, not affecting how it runs. 1 mark — a valid internal example (comment, header block, meaningful naming or layout). No mark if the example is external (manual, help guide, spec). 2 marks per purpose (×2): 1 for naming a valid purpose, 1 for explaining how it helps / its benefit.","id":840},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Practice questions","text":"Valid purposes: explain & justify structures · support maintenance/debugging · describe stubs/unfinished sections. The two purposes must be distinct — restating one in different words caps the answer at 2. 1 mark — states the distinction: explain = what/how the code works; justify = why a decision was made. 1 mark — a correct example of each type. 1 mark — stub = placeholder for an unwritten/incomplete part, often returning a fixed value. 1 mark — why documenting helps: signals the code is unfinished so it isn't mistaken for working code / guides future development.","id":841},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Practice questions","text":"1 mark — acknowledges a valid point in the statement (comments don't affect running; over-commenting is noise). 1–2 marks — counter-arguments: code is maintained/read repeatedly; supports debugging, updating, handover; future-you forgets. 1 mark — a justified overall conclusion (a \"discuss\" needs a position, weighed).","id":842},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"What it is","text":"Explanatory notes inside the source code — comments + layout. For humans; ignored at runtime.","id":843},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Internal ≠ external","text":"Internal lives in the code. External = manuals, help guides, specs — separate documents.","id":844},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Three purposes","text":"Explain & justify structures · support maintenance · describe stubs.","id":845},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Explain vs justify","text":"Explain = what/how. Justify = why (often starts with \"because…\").","id":846},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Layout counts","text":"Indentation, white space and meaningful names are documentation too.","id":847},{"file":"u1o2-kk10.html","nav":"u1o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Programming","title":"Internal documentation The notes a programmer leaves inside the code — for the next person, who is often future-you.","head":"Signal not noise","text":"Comment the why , not the obvious what . More comments ≠ better. \"Internal documentation is comments and layout written inside the source code to explain and justify the structures, support maintenance and mark stubs — read by humans and ignored when the program runs.\"","id":848},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Validation techniques","text":"Three quick gates every piece of input has to pass before your program trusts it — does it exist , is it the right type , and is it in range . Master these and you stop \"garbage in, garbage out\" at the front door. The running scenario — “CourtBook”. Aria is a Year 11 student who has built CourtBook , a small app that lets students book the school's sports courts at lunchtime. Every booking is a row of input: a name, a student ID, a court number, a date, a duration and a party size.","id":849},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Validation techniques","text":"If even one field is rubbish, the timetable falls apart — double bookings, blank names, court 99 that doesn't exist. Validation is how CourtBook protects itself before it saves anything. We'll use CourtBook the whole way through, so each idea lands on the same concrete form. Everything is offline and self-marking — your score collects in the dock at the bottom-right.","id":850},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"01 What validation actually is","text":"Validation is an automated check a program runs on input data to confirm it is reasonable, sensible and allowable before that data is processed or stored. It sits in the development stage of the problem-solving methodology, alongside coding, testing and documentation. The key word is reasonable , not correct . Validation can tell that an age of 200 is impossible, or that a blank name is missing, or that the word \"three\" isn't a number. It cannot tell that someone who typed age 17 is actually 16 — that value is perfectly reasonable , just wrong.","id":851},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"01 What validation actually is","text":"Catching wrong-but-reasonable data is a different job (verification — section 06). Airport gate analogy. Validation is the gate agent who checks your boarding pass is filled in (existence), is a boarding pass and not a receipt (type), and is for a flight that exists today (range). They wave through anyone whose pass looks plausible. They do not check whether you're the actual person named on it — that's a different desk. A plausible pass can still belong to the wrong traveller. Why bother? Computers follow the principle GIGO — garbage in, garbage out .","id":852},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"01 What validation actually is","text":"If you let nonsense into the program, every calculation, sort and report built on it is also nonsense. Validation is the cheapest place to stop that: at the moment of input, before the bad data spreads. It improves data integrity and makes the solution more reliable — but it reduces errors, it never eliminates them.","id":853},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"3D Lab A · The Validation Gauntlet","text":"A booking request travels along a conveyor toward CourtBook's database. It must clear Existence , then Type , then Range . Pick what the user typed in the court number field and watch which gate catches it. Order matters — the first failing gate stops it.","id":854},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Confirms a required value has been entered and the field is not blank.","text":"It says nothing about whether the value is the right type or sensible — only that something is there. Used on every field a record cannot do without. In CourtBook: the name and student ID fields both need an existence check — a booking with no name is useless to the teacher reading the timetable. The check passes the moment any character is present and fails only on blank/whitespace.","id":855},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Confirms the data entered matches the expected data type.","text":"Numbers where a number is expected, a valid date where a date is expected, text where text is expected. Stops a word being treated as a number, which would crash a calculation. In CourtBook: the court number , duration and party size fields all expect integers; the date field expects a valid calendar date. Typing G4 or \"half an hour\" fails the type check before any maths happens.","id":856},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Confirms a value falls between an acceptable minimum and maximum (or within a limit).","text":"Applies to numbers and dates. The value has already passed type checking — now we ask whether it's inside the sensible boundaries for this field. In CourtBook: court number 1–6 , duration 15–60 minutes, party size 1–10 , and the booking date must be today or later (a date range). A range check is the only one of the three that needs you to know the real-world limits of the problem.","id":857},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"05 All three, side by side","text":"Check Question it answers CourtBook example Rejects Existence Is anything there? Court number field not blank (blank) Type Is it the right kind of data? Court number is a whole number Range Is it within allowable limits? Court number is 1–6 Notice the order is also a logical pipeline: there's no point type-checking a blank, and no point range-checking text. Run them existence → type → range and each check can assume the previous one passed.","id":858},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"right kind","text":"\"Is it a number / date / text?\"","id":859},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"3D Lab B · Valid but wrong","text":"CourtBook's student ID field wants a 5-digit number. The value 99999 exists, is the right type, and is in range — so it passes validation . But no student is enrolled with that ID, so it is wrong . Think of validation as throwing a dart at a board: landing on the board means plausible; hitting the bullseye means actually correct. Validation only checks the board.","id":860},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"06 Validation vs verification vs testing","text":"Term Question it answers When CourtBook example Validation Is the input reasonable / allowable? As data is entered Court number is 1–6 and not blank Verification Is the data accurate / the true value? Against a real source That student ID really belongs to Aria — checked against the enrolment list, or typed twice and compared Testing Does the solution itself work ? After coding, by the developer Feed court 0 and court 7 as test data; check the program rejects both (expected vs actual)","id":861},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"07 Live form validator","text":"Every field below runs existence, type and range checks as you type. Watch the message under each field name the check that fails. Then hit Save booking to see whether the whole record is accepted.","id":862},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"08 Sort-the-check","text":"Click a scenario, then click the bin it belongs in. Six scenarios, three bins. Correct placements score a point in the dock; wrong ones turn red so you can rethink.","id":863},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"State / Name 1 mark","text":"Give the answer only. \"Name the validation check that confirms a field is not blank.\" → Existence check. No explanation needed.","id":864},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Describe 2 marks","text":"Say what it is and show it in context. \"Describe a range check for the duration field.\" → it confirms the value is between a min and max; here, 15–60 minutes.","id":865},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Explain 2–3 marks","text":"Give the reason / how it works / why it matters. \"Explain why validation can't guarantee correct data.\" → it tests plausibility, not truth; a reasonable value may still be wrong.","id":866},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"Distinguish / Compare 2–4 marks","text":"Make the difference explicit with \"whereas\". \"Validation checks input is reasonable, whereas verification checks it is accurate against the true source.\"","id":867},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"11 P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Draft a 3-mark answer to the prompt below. As you type, the keyword chips light up when you use the language an examiner rewards. Then reveal the model answer to compare.","id":868},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"12 VCE-style practice questions","text":"Try each one on paper first. Then read the annotated weak answer, the full-mark answer, and the marking guide. Mark yourself honestly with the buttons — it feeds the dock. 1 mark — validation = automated reasonableness/allowability check on input (not “correct”). 1 mark — performed before the data is processed/stored. 1 mark — names all three: existence, type, range (all three required for the mark). 1 mark — existence described + a blank rejected. 1 mark — type described + a non-numeric value rejected. 1 mark — range described as between 15 and 60.","id":869},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"12 VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 mark — a value outside 15–60 rejected (e.g. 5 or 90). 1 mark — validation = reasonableness of input, with example. 1 mark — verification = accuracy vs a true source, with example. 1 mark — clear contrast drawn between validation and verification (e.g. “whereas”). 1 mark — testing = developer checks the solution works (expected vs actual), distinct from validating input. 1 mark — identifies the field as a derived/calculated value. 1 mark — explains it is already numeric so a type check is redundant. 1 mark — names range check as the correct technique.","id":870},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"12 VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 mark — contextualises it to the 200-minute cap. 1 mark — first distinct problem clearly stated in context. 1 mark — correct technique paired with problem 1. 1 mark — second distinct problem, genuinely different from the first. 1 mark — correct technique paired with problem 2.","id":871},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"● Existence check","text":"Confirms a value has been entered (not blank). Also called presence / required check. if name == \"\" then reject Says nothing about whether it's correct.","id":872},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"● Type check","text":"Confirms the data is the expected data type . Number / date / text / Boolean. if not isInteger(x) then reject Stops \"G4\" being treated as a number.","id":873},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"● Range check","text":"Confirms a value is between min and max / within a limit. Numbers and dates. if x < 1 or x > 6 then reject Derived values need range , not type.","id":874},{"file":"u1o2-kk11.html","nav":"u1o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Programming","title":"Validation techniques","head":"● The three V's + T","text":"Validation = input is reasonable (as entered). Verification = input is accurate vs a true source. Testing = the program works (expected vs actual). Always contextualise : name field + boundaries.","id":875},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Debugging & Testing","text":"Writing code that runs is the easy half. Proving it does the right thing — and tracking down why it doesn't — is the skill examiners reward. This module covers test tables, constructing test data, and the debugging techniques every VCE programmer is expected to name and use.","id":876},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Testing finds the bug. Debugging removes it.","text":"These two words get swapped all the time, and examiners love punishing it. They are different jobs done in a different order with different tools.","id":877},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"🔍 Testing","text":"Running the solution with chosen test data and comparing the actual result against the expected result you worked out beforehand. Testing detects whether a fault exists — it doesn't fix anything. Main tool: the test table .","id":878},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"🛠️ Debugging","text":"The process of locating and correcting the cause of a fault that testing has revealed. Debugging diagnoses and repairs . Main tools: breakpoints , debugging output statements , and desk checking / trace tables . Testing is the thermometer and the blood test — measurements that tell you something is wrong. Debugging is the diagnosis and the treatment — finding the cause and fixing it. You can take someone's temperature all day; that never cures them. Test data is the symptom you provoke on purpose so the illness shows up.","id":879},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"The three kinds of error","text":"Every fault you'll ever test or debug falls into one of three families. Naming the family correctly is half the battle, because each one is caught a different way.","id":880},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Syntax error","text":"You broke the grammar rules of the language — a missing colon, an unclosed bracket, a misspelled keyword. The program won't run at all ; the interpreter/compiler refuses. prnit(\"hi\") · if x > 5 (no colon) Caught by: the editor / interpreter, instantly.","id":881},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Logic error","text":"The code runs happily and produces an answer — just the wrong answer . The grammar is fine; the thinking is faulty. The sneakiest of the three. Using < where you needed <= ; adding when you meant to multiply. Caught by: a test table — nothing else flags it.","id":882},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Run-time error","text":"The program starts fine, then crashes part-way when it hits something impossible — dividing by zero, reading a file that isn't there, an index past the end of an array. total / count when count = 0 Caught by: an error/exception while running.","id":883},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Error triage","text":"Drag each fault into the bin you think it belongs in. The dock keeps your score. Placed correctly: 0 / 8 . A program that runs never has a syntax error.","id":884},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"The Boundary Bug Hunter","text":"Here is Zoe's ParkPass pricing module on a 3D age axis . Drag the slider to set a customer's age and watch the execution token fall into a price band. The boundaries between bands — the exact ages 4, 16 and 65 — are where logic bugs hide. Flip between her buggy code and the fixed code and watch what happens right at age 15.","id":885},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Anatomy of a test table","text":"A test table (testing table) is the structured record of testing. The non-negotiable idea is the expected result is worked out by hand before you run the code — with a calculator, pen and paper, your brain — and only then do you record what the program actually produced. What it tests Test data (input) Expected result Actual result Pass / Fail Adult, normal age = 30 $89 $89 PASS Junior, normal age = 8 $45 $45 PASS Junior boundary (top) age = 15 $45 $89 FAIL ←","id":886},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Must-have columns","text":"Test number · what it checks · test data · expected result · actual result · pass/fail . Some teachers add a \"corrective action\" column for what you'll change when it fails.","id":887},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"The golden rule","text":"Expected ≠ Actual ⇒ FAIL ⇒ now you debug. Expected = Actual ⇒ PASS for that input only . One pass never proves the whole module works.","id":888},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Constructing test data","text":"Good testing lives or dies on the data you choose to feed in . Random numbers won't do it. You deliberately construct three types so that, together, they exercise every path through the code and every edge of every range.","id":889},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"NORMAL","text":"Typical, valid, \"middle of the range\" values the program should obviously accept. Proves the everyday case works. ParkPass: age = 30 → $89.","id":890},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"BOUNDARY","text":"Values right on the edge of a range and one either side — the cut-offs where a wrong < vs <= shows up. The single highest-value test data you can write. ParkPass: 3, 4 · 15, 16 · 64, 65.","id":891},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"ABNORMAL","text":"Invalid / unexpected input the program should reject or handle — negatives, letters, blanks. Proves validation holds and the program won't crash. ParkPass: age = −5, age = \"old\", blank. Before opening a bridge, engineers don't just drive one normal car across ( normal data ). They park a fully loaded truck right at the rated weight limit ( boundary data ), and they imagine a flood or an earthquake ( abnormal data ). The boundary test — exactly at the limit — is the one that reveals whether the safety margin was calculated with < or <= . Same logic in code.","id":892},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Live test-table builder","text":"Add test rows for the buggy ParkPass module below. Type an age, predict the expected price, then press Run — the real buggy function executes and fills the actual result, marking pass/fail for you. Your job: find an age where it fails . (Hint: the buggy version uses age < 15 for the junior cut-off instead of age < 16 .) Age Expected Actual Result No tests yet — add one above.","id":893},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Debugging techniques: stepping the code","text":"Testing told us that ParkPass is wrong. Debugging finds where . The two techniques VCE expects you to name are breakpoints and debugging output statements — plus the old-school desk check / trace . Step the execution token line by line and watch the variables update in the watch panel. Reset. age = 15. Step through and watch line 4 ( age < 15 ) evaluate false , skipping the junior price on line 5.","id":894},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"● Breakpoint","text":"A marker that pauses execution at a chosen line so you can inspect the current value of every variable at that moment . You watch age = 15 reach line 4, see age < 15 is false, and realise it wrongly skips to the adult band. No code is changed to use one.","id":895},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"🖨️ Debugging output statement","text":"A temporary print() line you insert into the code to display a variable's value as the program runs — e.g. print(\"age=\", age, \"price=\", price) . Cheap, works anywhere, but you must remember to remove them before release.","id":896},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"The pay-calculator worked example","text":"VCAA's own teaching activity for this dot point asks students to test a pay calculator : enter hours worked and hourly rate; gross pay is calculated; 12% is removed for superannuation and 30% for tax ; net pay is shown. You compute the expected result with pen and calculator, run the program, and compare. Here it is as a finished test table. Worked by hand for 10 hours @ $20/hr : gross = 10 × 20 = $200 ; super = 12% = $24; tax = 30% = $60; net = 200 − 24 − 60 = $116 .","id":897},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"The pay-calculator worked example","text":"Hours Rate Type Expected net Actual net Result $20 NORMAL $116.00 $116.00 PASS $20 BOUNDARY $0.00 $0.00 PASS $55.50 NORMAL $1,212.12 $1,212.12 PASS $20 ABNORMAL error / rejected −$58.00 FAIL ←","id":898},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"1 · Mixing up the two words","text":"Giving a debugging tool (breakpoint) when the question asked for a testing technique (test table), or vice versa. Read the command word.","id":899},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"2 · No boundary data","text":"A test table of three \"normal\" rows that all pass. It demonstrates nothing. Always include boundary and abnormal rows.","id":900},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"3 · Forgetting \"expected ≠ actual\"","text":"Describing a test table without naming both an expected and an actual column. The comparison is the technique.","id":901},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"4 · \"I'd just run it and see\"","text":"Expected results must be calculated by hand first . If you read the answer off the program, you're testing the program against itself.","id":902},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"5 · Naming an error type wrong","text":"Calling a wrong-answer-but-runs fault a \"syntax error\". A program that runs has no syntax error — it's a logic error .","id":903},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"6 · One example, no link","text":"Higher-mark questions want the technique plus why it suits this scenario. Always close the loop back to the case study.","id":904},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Short-answer marks come from structure, not length. Make a Point , give Evidence from the scenario, then Link it to the consequence. Tab through a model, then try your own — keyword hits light up.","id":905},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Your turn","text":"Prompt: Zoe's ParkPass module runs but charges 16-year-olds the wrong price. Explain one testing technique she could use to detect this fault.","id":906},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total. Attempt each in your head or on paper, reveal the weak vs strong responses, then self-mark — the dock tallies your score.","id":907},{"file":"u1o2-kk12.html","nav":"u1o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Programming","title":"Debugging & Testing","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"Testing = detect a fault (test table) Debugging = locate + fix it Test → find → debug → re-test Test # · what it checks Test data (input) Expected (worked by hand first) Actual · Pass/Fail NORMAL typical valid value BOUNDARY on the edge ±1 ABNORMAL invalid / rejected Syntax — won't run (grammar) Logic — runs, wrong answer Run-time — crashes mid-run Breakpoint — pause & inspect variables Output statement — temp print() of a value Desk check / trace table — hand-execute on paper Always include a boundary row Name expected AND actual Link the fault to the scenario Tie abnormal tests to validation That's KK12 — the final dot point of the Programming outcome. 🎉 Test deliberately, debug methodically, and always write the expected result first. More modules at digitalvector.com.au","id":908},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"What makes someone build something new?","text":"Every digital solution you'll ever study started as a spark in someone's head. This dot point is about that spark — the factors that inspire and drive innovation . Get this right and the rest of the Innovative Solutions outcome clicks into place. “Factors that may inspire and drive innovation, such as curiosity , ingenuity and the United Nations' Sustainable Development Goals .” The study design uses the words such as , so curiosity, ingenuity and the UN SDGs are the named examples you must be able to explain — but they aren't the only things that can drive innovation.","id":909},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"What makes someone build something new?","text":"Examiners reward students who name the big three confidently and show they understand other supporting drivers (an emerging technology becoming feasible, a real user need, competition). We'll cover both. Throughout this module we follow one running team so the abstract ideas stay concrete: Mia , a Year 11 student, helps stack shelves at her local IGA on weekends. She keeps noticing crates of slightly bruised or near-date fruit and veg getting binned — while a community pantry two suburbs over runs short every week. With three classmates she builds SecondServe :","id":910},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"What makes someone build something new?","text":"a cheap shelf sensor plus an app that flags surplus produce and routes it to the pantry before it spoils. We'll use SecondServe to make curiosity, ingenuity and the SDGs visible in action.","id":911},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"◈ In scope for KK01","text":"What curiosity, ingenuity and the UN SDGs are How each one inspires or drives innovation How the factors combine (and why one alone rarely ships) The difference between innovation, invention and creativity Recognising drivers in an unseen scenario","id":912},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"◇ Deferred to later dot points","text":"What makes a solution creative/innovative → KK04 Capabilities of digital systems → KK02 Impact & economic effects of tech → KK03 Solution specifications & design tools → KK05–07 Ethics & legislation → KK11–13","id":913},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Creativity → Invention → Innovation","text":"Students lose easy marks by swapping these three words. They're a chain, not synonyms. Tap each card to see the exam-ready definition and where SecondServe sits.","id":914},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Creativity","text":"Generating novel, original ideas — imagining what could be. It happens in your head; nothing is built yet.","id":915},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Invention","text":"Turning an idea into a brand-new thing that didn't exist before — the first working version of it.","id":916},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Innovation","text":"Putting an idea or invention into real use so it creates value — improving something new or existing until people actually adopt it. Invention creates something new; innovation creates value . You can innovate without inventing — combining or improving existing things in a new, useful way (Uber didn't invent cars or phones) absolutely counts as innovation.","id":917},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Curiosity","text":"Curiosity is the desire to understand or explore — to ask “why is it like this?” and “what if it were different?” . In innovation it's the starting fuel : it makes someone notice a problem everyone else walks past, and refuse to accept “that's just how it is.” Curiosity drives innovation by surfacing problems and opportunities that aren't obvious. The bin full of edible produce is invisible to most staff — Mia's curiosity (“why are we throwing this out?”) is what turns a background annoyance into a question worth solving.","id":918},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Curiosity","text":"Without that first question, there's nothing to build. Curiosity is the match , not the engine. It lights the spark — but a match on its own can't move a car. That's why curiosity needs the next two drivers to actually go somewhere.","id":919},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Ingenuity","text":"Ingenuity is cleverness and resourcefulness — the skill of working out an inventive solution using the means available , often within tight limits of money, time or technology. If curiosity finds the problem, ingenuity figures out a way to actually solve it. Ingenuity drives innovation by turning a question into something workable. Mia's team can't afford industrial cold-chain tracking, so they improvise : a $6 gas sensor reads the ethylene that ripening fruit gives off, a Raspberry Pi logs it, and free mapping routes a volunteer to the pantry. That resourceful “make it work with what we have” thinking is ingenuity — and it's exactly what keeps a good idea from dying as “too expensive.” Curiosity finds and frames the problem;","id":920},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Ingenuity","text":"ingenuity solves it. A common exam slip is describing both as “thinking of ideas.” Keep the split sharp: curiosity = the question , ingenuity = the clever answer .","id":921},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"UN Sustainable Development Goals","text":"The Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) are a set of 17 global goals adopted by all UN member states in 2015 as part of the 2030 Agenda . They cover issues like ending hunger, clean water, quality education, climate action and reduced inequality — a shared “to-do list for the planet” to be reached by 2030. The SDGs drive innovation by giving it purpose and direction . They tell innovators which problems are worth solving and provide a recognised, measurable target to aim at. SecondServe maps straight onto SDG 2 — Zero Hunger and SDG 12 — Responsible Consumption & Production ;","id":922},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"UN Sustainable Development Goals","text":"that framing helps the team justify the project, apply for a grant, and measure success (kilograms rescued, families fed). The goal turns “a nice idea” into “a solution to a problem the world has agreed matters.”","id":923},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Spin the goals — pick a target for an innovation","text":"This is the 17 SDGs as an interactive globe. Drag to rotate , then click a goal tile to see how an innovation might target it. Notice how the same curiosity + ingenuity could be pointed at very different goals.","id":924},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"The Spark Reactor — why one driver alone won't ship","text":"Three energy sources feed a central innovation core : Curiosity , Ingenuity and Purpose (SDGs) . Toggle them on and off and watch the core. Only when all three are active does it ignite into sustained innovation — the whole point of this dot point made physical. Curiosity only → endless questions, nothing built. Ingenuity only → clever tinkering with no problem worth solving. Purpose only → good intentions, no spark or method. The drivers are complementary : each covers a gap the others leave. That single sentence is worth marks on a “discuss” question.","id":925},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Together they ship — plus the supporting cast","text":"The named three rarely act alone, and they're rarely enough by themselves. Here's the combination logic, then the other drivers worth a mention in an extended response.","id":926},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Missing curiosity","text":"Skilled team, worthy goal — but no one spotted a fresh problem. You rebuild what exists.","id":927},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Missing ingenuity","text":"Great question and cause, but no workable way to solve it within the budget. The idea stalls.","id":928},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Missing purpose","text":"Curious and clever, but aimed at nothing that matters. Effort with no direction or measure of success.","id":929},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"◈ All three → innovation","text":"Curiosity finds the bin of wasted food, ingenuity builds a $6-sensor workaround, and SDG 2/12 give it a purpose and a yardstick. That's when a solution actually gets used and creates value.","id":930},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Drag each clue into the driver it shows","text":"Sort these nine clues. On touch screens, tap a clue then tap a bin . Drag works on desktop.","id":931},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Supporting drivers worth naming","text":"Emerging technology becoming feasible — the “why now?” factor. Cheap sensors, fast mobile data and free mapping mean SecondServe is buildable today but wouldn't have been a decade ago. A real user need or pain point , competition and market pressure , collaboration (diverse teams spark more ideas), and constraints or necessity (“necessity is the mother of invention”) all push innovation along. Name one or two of these in an extended answer to show breadth beyond the core three.","id":932},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"SecondServe, start to finish","text":"Follow how the three factors show up at each stage. This is exactly the kind of scenario the exam hands you and asks you to label.","id":933},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"curiosity Notice the problem","text":"Mia keeps asking why edible produce is binned while a pantry runs short. The question reframes a daily annoyance as an opportunity.","id":934},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"SDGs Frame the purpose","text":"The team aligns the project to SDG 2 (Zero Hunger) and SDG 12 (Responsible Consumption). Now they have a clear “why,” a recognised cause, and measurable targets.","id":935},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"ingenuity Engineer a cheap fix","text":"No budget for cold-chain tech, so they improvise: a $6 ethylene sensor + Raspberry Pi flags produce nearing spoilage; an app routes a volunteer driver to the pantry.","id":936},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"all three Innovation lands","text":"The app is adopted by two IGAs. 40 kg/week that used to be binned now reaches families. An idea became value used by real people — the definition of innovation.","id":937},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Command words — what they're really asking","text":"The verb sets the depth. Match your answer to it or you'll over- or under-write.","id":938},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"Build a full-mark answer with P · E · L","text":"A reliable structure for “explain/analyse” answers: P oint (name the factor) → E xplain (how it drives innovation) → L ink (tie it to the scenario). Write below — the trainer lights up each part as it detects it.","id":939},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Try each in your head or on paper first. Then reveal the weak answer (and why it loses marks), the strong answer, and the marking guide . Award yourself marks — your total fills the dock. “Innovation is when you invent something new and creative.” ← treats the two words as the same thing; gives no real distinction, so neither mark is earned. Innovation is putting an idea or invention into use so that it creates value, by improving something new or existing until it is adopted. Invention differs because it is the creation of something entirely new for the first time — you can innovate by improving existing things without inventing anything.","id":940},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 mark — correct definition of innovation (use/value, not just “something new”). 1 mark — clear point of difference (invention = first creation of something new). “Mia was curious so she made an app. Curiosity is good for innovation.” ← names curiosity but never explains the mechanism (how it drives innovation) and barely uses the scenario. Curiosity is the urge to question and explore. It drove innovation by leading Mia to notice a problem others overlooked — edible food being thrown away — and to ask why it couldn't be redirected.","id":941},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"This question reframed an everyday annoyance as an opportunity, providing the starting point and direction for the whole SecondServe solution. Without that curiosity the problem would never have been identified. 1 — defines/identifies curiosity (questioning, exploring, noticing). 1 — explains the mechanism: surfaces an overlooked problem / reframes it as an opportunity. 1 — applies to the scenario with a specific detail (binned produce / Mia's question). “Curiosity and ingenuity both help you think of new ideas for innovation.” ← states a similarity, not a distinction; the words “distinguish between” require the difference.","id":942},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Curiosity is the desire to question and explore, which finds and frames the problem worth solving. Ingenuity is resourceful cleverness, which produces a workable solution to that problem — often within tight constraints. In short, curiosity identifies the problem while ingenuity solves it. 1 — correct sense of curiosity (questioning/finding the problem). 1 — correct sense of ingenuity (resourceful solving) with the contrast made explicit. “They were curious and clever and wanted to help the world, so they made BrightBus. All three factors helped them innovate.” ← lists the factors generically with no analysis of how each one specifically operated;","id":943},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"no SDG named. Curiosity likely surfaced the problem — the team questioned why some families lack reliable power and what a cheap fix might look like, identifying the opportunity. Ingenuity shaped the solution — resourcefully combining low-cost solar panels, a battery and a charger into an affordable kit that works within a tight budget and without mains power. The UN SDGs gave purpose and a measurable target — aligning to SDG 7 (Affordable & Clean Energy) framed the work around an agreed global priority and a way to measure impact (households reached).","id":944},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Together, the question, the clever build and the clear goal turned an idea into a solution people actually use. 1 — curiosity analysed (identifying/framing the problem or opportunity). 1 — ingenuity analysed (resourceful, constrained solution-building). 1 — SDGs analysed (purpose/direction; naming a relevant goal, e.g. SDG 7 strengthens it). 1 — shows how the factors connect/combine to produce the innovation. “Yes the SDGs are the most important because helping the world is good. SecondServe helped with hunger so the SDGs are the best driver.” ← one-sided, no counter-argument, no real weighing, and no judgement that acknowledges the other drivers “discuss” demands.","id":945},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"For the claim: the SDGs gave SecondServe purpose and direction — aligning to SDG 2 and SDG 12 told the team which problem was worth solving and provided measurable targets (kg rescued), which helped justify and sustain the project. Against the claim: a goal alone ships nothing. Without curiosity , Mia would never have noticed the binned produce, so the project wouldn't exist; without ingenuity , the team couldn't have built the cheap sensor workaround that made it feasible. An enabling technology (cheap sensors, free mapping) also mattered — the same goal a decade ago might not have been achievable.","id":946},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Judgement: the SDGs are a powerful driver of direction , but they are not automatically “most important.” The factors are complementary — curiosity finds the problem, ingenuity solves it, and the SDGs give it purpose. In SecondServe, no single factor was sufficient alone; innovation emerged from their combination. 1–2 — case for : SDGs provide purpose/direction/measurable targets, applied to SecondServe. 1–2 — case against : at least one other driver (curiosity, ingenuity or enabling tech) shown to be necessary, applied to the scenario. 1 — explicit weighing of importance (not just two lists). 1 — clear judgement: factors are complementary / no one factor sufficient alone.","id":947},{"file":"u2o1-kk01.html","nav":"u2o1-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Factors that inspire & drive innovation","head":"◆ KK01 · Factors that inspire & drive innovation","text":"Curiosity — questioning & exploring; finds/frames the problem. Ingenuity — resourceful cleverness; solves it under constraints. UN SDGs — 17 goals (2015, by 2030); give purpose & direction . Creativity = the idea. Invention = first build of something new. Innovation = put to use to create value . You can innovate without inventing. One driver alone rarely ships. They're complementary — each fills the others' gap. All three → a used, valued solution. Name the factor → say how it drives innovation → link to scenario. Quote a stimulus detail every time. Name a specific SDG when relevant. Match depth to the command word .","id":948},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","text":"Before you can design something innovative , you need a clear-eyed picture of what today's digital systems already do — and how much they are already able to do . This dot point is the map of the territory you're about to push past.","id":949},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"What counts as a digital system ?","text":"A digital system is never just \"the app\" or \"the gadget\". It's a combination of parts working together to carry out an information-processing job. Tarni's contactless payment isn't \"the card reader\". It's the reader (hardware) plus the bank's software, plus your account data, plus the payment network linking the shop to your bank, plus the people and rules that set it up. Pull any one out and the \"system\" stops being a system.","id":950},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Hardware","text":"The physical parts — sensors, chips, readers, satellites, robot arms.","id":951},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Software","text":"The instructions that tell the hardware what to do and when.","id":952},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Data","text":"The raw material it acts on — locations, balances, traffic counts.","id":953},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Network & people","text":"The links that connect parts, and the humans/processes giving it purpose.","id":954},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Function vs capability","text":"This is the one idea the whole dot point turns on — and the one students most often blur. Get it crisp and the rest is straightforward.","id":955},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"What it does · what it's for","text":"The task or role the system is designed to perform. Answers \"what's its job?\" — usually one clear verb: locate, pay, listen, lift, control.","id":956},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"What it's able to do","text":"The extent of what it can achieve — its scale, speed, accuracy, reach or autonomy. Answers \"how much / how well / how far?\" — usually a measure. Function = your job description: \"make coffees, serve customers.\" Capability = what you can actually deliver: \"180 cups an hour at peak, latte art, remembers thirty regulars' orders.\" The job is the same; the capability is what makes you good at it. Both share one function — give off light. Their capability is worlds apart: a torch lights a footpath; a lighthouse throws a beam 40 km out to sea, all night, in fog. Same job, different capability. Flip these to test yourself — the front is a system, the back splits its function from a capability.","id":957},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"GPS navigation","text":"Function: locate the device and give directions. Capability: pinpoints to within ~3 m, anywhere on Earth, in real time, for billions of devices at once.","id":958},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Contactless payment","text":"Function: transfer money to pay for goods. Capability: clears a tap in under a second, 24/7, while screening it for fraud against millions of patterns.","id":959},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Warehouse robot","text":"Function: pick and move stock to pack orders. Capability: runs 24 h with no fatigue, places items to the millimetre, lifts loads people can't, never loses count.","id":960},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Smart hearing aid","text":"Function: amplify sound for a person with hearing loss. Capability: separates speech from background noise live, auto-adjusts per room, streams calls straight to the ear.","id":961},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The Capability Amplifier","text":"Here's the distinction made physical. The function stays locked — this system does exactly one thing: locate . The dials below only change its capability . Watch the globe respond.","id":962},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The five-systems tour","text":"VCAA's five example domains, as a rotating hub. Click a pod to focus it — each plays a small animation and reveals its function, its capability, and the opportunity a designer could chase. Help people with disability do tasks they'd otherwise find hard — e.g. a hearing aid amplifies sound, a screen reader voices on-screen text. Separates speech from noise in real time, auto-tunes per environment, describes images with AI, and streams audio straight to the device.","id":963},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The five domains, on paper","text":"The same five, in a table you can revise from. Remember: these are examples of the function-vs-capability idea, not a memorise-list. The skill is doing this split for whatever system an exam hands you.","id":964},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Capability is an emergent property","text":"Capabilities don't live in one part — they emerge when the parts work together . Switch components off below and watch a navigation system's capability collapse. Tap each row to toggle it. Notice you can't point to a single \"capability part\" — knock out the network and you lose live rerouting; knock out data and there's no map to route on at all. That's why exam answers should describe the system , not a lone component.","id":965},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"How capability grows — and feeds new ideas","text":"Functions are fairly stable (we've \"located\" and \"paid\" for a long time). It's the capability that keeps climbing — and each climb opens a door for an innovative solution. This is the bridge back to KK01's drivers of innovation. Cheap sensors and phones pour out data. Traffic systems went from a few loop detectors to whole-city, second-by-second sensing — so signals can now adapt instead of running on a fixed timer. Always-on networks let parts that were isolated talk live. Your navigation reroutes around a crash because thousands of phones report speeds back in real time.","id":966},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"How capability grows — and feeds new ideas","text":"Cheaper compute and machine learning add autonomy — fraud detection, speech-from-noise, robots that adapt to what they sense rather than following a fixed script. What filled a room now fits a wristband. That's exactly why FloatMate (KK01) is feasible now — the capability finally fits on the wrist at a price a surf club can afford.","id":967},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Sort it: function or capability ?","text":"Drag each statement into the right bin — or tap it, then tap a bin. Some are deliberately sneaky (a \"benefit\" hiding as a capability).","id":968},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Six named exam traps","text":"These are the recurring ways students bleed marks on this dot point. Name the trap, dodge the trap. Writing \"the function of GPS is that it's very accurate.\" Accuracy isn't a function — it's a capability. The function is to locate . \"It has a search bar and a settings menu.\" Those are features, not capabilities. A capability is what the system can achieve , stated with scope. \"A robot arm lifts things.\" That's a component. The system is the arm plus its sensors, control software, data and the people who program and supervise it.","id":969},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Six named exam traps","text":"\"Its capability is that it's convenient.\" Convenient is a benefit to the user , not something the system does. Benefits are the result of a capability. \"It's fast and powerful.\" Examiners can't award that — it could describe almost anything. VCAA wrote \"for example\", so assistive tech / finance / GPS / robotics / traffic are illustrations . A question may hand you a totally different system.","id":970},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"The verb in the question sets how much you write. Tap one to see what it's really asking on this dot point. Just name it — no explanation needed. State the function of a GPS navigation system. → \"To locate a device and provide directions.\"","id":971},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Point → state the function or capability. Evidence → back it with a concrete measure or example. Link → tie it to the question (often: the opportunity it creates). Type an answer and watch the meters react live.","id":972},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Five questions building from 2 to 4 marks. For each: reveal a weak answer (annotated with why it loses marks), a strong answer, and the marking guide . Then mark yourself — your score fills the ring, bottom-right. \"The function is what it does and the capability is also what it does but better.\" No real distinction — \"what it does but better\" is hand-wavy. A distinguish question needs both sides defined against each other, ideally with a contrast word like whereas . \"A function is the task a digital system is designed to perform — what it is for (e.g.","id":973},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"to locate a device), whereas a capability is the extent of what it is able to do — its scale, speed, accuracy or reach (e.g. locating to within ~3 m anywhere on Earth in real time).\" 1 Function correctly defined as the task/purpose — what the system does. 1 Capability correctly defined as the extent/how well it does it, clearly contrasted with function. An example for each is not required for 2 marks but strengthens a borderline answer. \"Its function is to take money. It's really fast and it's safe and convenient.\" Function is acceptable (1).","id":974},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"But \"fast\", \"safe\" and \"convenient\" are vague and \"convenient\" is a benefit, not a capability — no measures, so the two capabilities don't earn their marks. Function: to authorise and transfer payment for a purchase between a customer's account and the merchant. Capability 1: it can complete and settle a tap in under a second, operating 24/7 without a teller. Capability 2: it can screen each transaction against millions of fraud patterns in real time and decline suspicious ones automatically. 1 Function: process/authorise a payment between customer and merchant. 1 One capability described with a measure or scope (e.g.","id":975},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"sub-second, 24/7). 1 A second, distinct capability, also with scope (e.g. real-time fraud screening). Two capabilities that are really the same point (\"fast\" and \"quick\") = 1 mark only. \"GPS helps you find places. People made Uber with it. So it creates opportunities.\" States a function (\"find places\") but never names a capability with scope, and the link to innovation is asserted, not explained. \"Explain\" needs the chain: capability → why it enables something → the opportunity. \"GPS navigation can pinpoint a device to within a few metres, anywhere on Earth, in real time and for billions of devices at once.","id":976},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Because location is now cheap, live and universal, designers can assume a user's position is always known. This makes solutions like real-time ride-share matching, live delivery tracking and geofenced safety alerts feasible — the system supplies precise, continuous location, so the innovation only has to add value on top of it rather than solve locating from scratch.\" 1 Names a genuine capability with scope (precision, real-time, global, scale). 1 Explains why that capability matters (cheap/live/always-available location). 1 Connects it to a concrete opportunity/innovative solution. 1 Reasoning is a clear chain (capability → enabler → opportunity), not just assertion.","id":977},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"\"Traffic lights control cars. If they're smart they'll fix the congestion because they're better than normal lights.\" Names the function (control cars) but the capabilities are missing and the reasoning is circular (\"better… so it fixes it\"). Analyse wants the capability broken down and weighed against the specific need (peak-hour congestion on one corridor). \"An adaptive system can sense traffic volume in real time across the whole corridor (capability), so instead of fixed timers it can lengthen green time in the busy direction during the peak. It can also give priority to trams and buses , moving more people per cycle, and coordinate adjacent intersections into a 'green wave' to keep flow moving.","id":978},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Matched to the council's need, these directly attack peak-hour congestion on that corridor. A limitation to weigh: the gain depends on accurate sensor data and won't help if the road is simply over capacity — so it manages flow rather than removing the underlying demand.\" 1 Identifies a relevant capability (real-time sensing / adaptive timing). 1 A second capability (PT priority or intersection coordination). 1 Links capabilities specifically to reducing peak-hour congestion on the corridor. 1 Weighs it up — a limitation or condition (data dependence / capacity limit) for true \"analyse\".","id":979},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"\"Robots are good because they work hard and don't get tired. But some people don't like them.\" One vague benefit and a vague objection. Discuss wants capabilities stated with scope on the benefit side, a genuine limitation, and a balanced sense of the trade-off — not \"some people don't like them.\" Benefits: warehouse robots can run continuously without fatigue and place items to the millimetre, so throughput and accuracy rise and orders ship faster with fewer picking errors. They can also handle heavy or repetitive loads that risk human injury.","id":980},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Limitation: the system depends on a structured, well-mapped environment and reliable data — an unexpected obstacle or a layout change can stall it, and the upfront cost and maintenance are high. There's also a workforce impact, as roles shift from picking to supervising the robots. On balance, the capability pays off at high, predictable volume but is less suited to small or highly variable operations. 1 A benefit tied to a real capability with scope (continuous run / mm precision). 1 A second distinct benefit (safety on heavy loads / accuracy / speed). 1 A genuine limitation (environment/data dependence, cost, or job impact). 1 A balancing/overall judgement — the mark of \"discuss\".","id":981},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The split","text":"Function = what it does (one verb, its purpose). Capability = what it's able to do (a measure: scale/speed/accuracy/reach/autonomy).","id":982},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The test","text":"Has a verb only? → function. Has a number / \"real-time / 24-7 / global\"? → capability. Describes a user feeling (\"handy\")? → benefit, not capability.","id":983},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"It's a system","text":"Hardware + software + data + network + people. Capability is emergent — name ≥2 parts working together.","id":984},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Five example domains","text":"Assistive tech · financial services · GPS · robotics · traffic management. \"For example\" = not a memorise-list. Apply the method to any system.","id":985},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"Capability climbs via","text":"More data · more connectivity More compute & AI (autonomy) Smaller, cheaper hardware","id":986},{"file":"u2o1-kk02.html","nav":"u2o1-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Functions & capabilities of digital systems","head":"The innovation link","text":"Describe current capability precisely → see the gap between what it can do and what people need → that gap is where the innovative solution lives.","id":987},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"The impact of emerging technologies","text":"Every emerging technology changes the world it lands in — and almost never in just one direction. The same system that lifts one person up can leave another behind. This module is about naming those impacts precisely, the way the exam wants you to.","id":988},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"The one idea that earns marks: impact is double-edged","text":"Weak answers say a technology is “good” or “bad.” Strong answers show the same technology producing a benefit for one stakeholder and a cost for another, at the same time. Automation that gives a company faster, cheaper output is the very same automation that removes a worker’s job. Hold both halves at once and you’re writing at the top band.","id":989},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Meet the scenario: Bellview & the Tran family","text":"Bellview is a regional Victorian town built around one big employer — ParcelHub , a parcel distribution warehouse. This year ParcelHub switched on an automated sorting line, a fleet of warehouse “pick-bots,” and an app-only returns kiosk. We’ll follow the ripple through one family: Spent 12 years on the ParcelHub floor reading labels and sorting parcels. His job is the front line of automation , deskilling and job loss . Banking is now app-only and the shops are self-checkout. She meets the edges of access and the decline of human interaction .","id":990},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Meet the scenario: Bellview & the Tran family","text":"An anonymous “school confessions” app and endless group chats expose her to cyberbullying and a quiet drop in face-to-face interpersonal skills . Sees soaring productivity , cheaper delivery for the whole town, a sustainability win on truck idling — and a misuse /e-waste headache. One town, one family — but the impacts land at three levels: the individual , the organisation , and society . Keep that ladder in mind; the exam loves it.","id":991},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"One technology, three levels of impact","text":"Drop an emerging technology into the centre and watch the impact ripple outward — first to the individual , then the organisation , then society . Tap a technology to switch the source. Notice that no impact stops at one ring.","id":992},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Impact of current & emerging technologies","text":"This strand is about how technology reshapes people and relationships — how we work, communicate and treat each other. Three named impacts you must be able to explain:","id":993},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"automation Automation","text":"Automation means a task is completed without human intervention — a machine, robot or program does what a person used to do. At ParcelHub, pick-bots now move parcels Đức once carried by hand.","id":994},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"cyberbullying Cyberbullying","text":"Cyberbullying is using a digital system to threaten, harass, intimidate or humiliate someone. Emerging tech makes it worse along three axes: it’s scale (one post reaches the whole year level), persistence (it’s saved, screenshotted, resurfaced), and anonymity (Bellview High’s “confessions” app hides who posted).","id":995},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"human interaction Decline of physical interaction & interpersonal skills","text":"When self-checkouts, app banking and messaging replace face-to-face contact, two things slip: the amount of real human interaction, and the skill of doing it well — reading body language, small talk, resolving conflict in person. Bà used to chat with the bank teller every week; now she taps an app and speaks to no one. Mai’s group can text for hours but freezes in a face-to-face disagreement.","id":996},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Economic issues involving emerging technologies","text":"This strand zooms out to money, work and resources — who can afford the tech, what happens to jobs and skills, and what it costs the planet. Five named issues: Who can get and afford the technology? New tools can widen the digital divide — Bà can’t use app-only banking, a low-income family can’t afford the device the school assumes everyone has. When machines take over the skilled part of a job, the human is left doing a narrower, simpler task — and the original expertise fades. Đức went from reading and routing parcels to just clearing jams the bot can’t.","id":997},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Economic issues involving emerging technologies","text":"Roles disappear entirely as automation scales. ParcelHub cut a third of its floor staff. New jobs appear too (bot technicians) — but rarely for the same people in the same town . Technology used for harm or beyond its intended purpose — scams using AI voices, surveillance creep, selling data collected for one purpose to another. ParcelHub’s customer data could be on-sold without consent. The environmental and long-term economic footprint. Both directions again: ParcelHub’s smart routing cuts truck idling and fuel (a win) — but the constant device upgrades and dumped scanners create e-waste , and data centres burn real energy (a cost).","id":998},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"The same technology, weighed from two sides","text":"Here’s the idea that lifts answers into the top band, made physical. Pick a technology, then choose whose eyes you’re looking through. The prism splits the technology into benefit-rays and cost-rays , and the scale tips toward whichever side weighs more for that stakeholder . Switch the lens and watch it re-balance — the technology didn’t change, the stakeholder did.","id":999},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Watch deskilling and job loss happen","text":"Drag the automation level on ParcelHub’s sorting line from manual to fully automated . As bots take over each station, three readouts move together: productivity climbs, headcount falls (job loss), and the workers who remain do narrower tasks (deskilling). This is the economic strand in one motion.","id":1000},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Flip each impact to its other edge","text":"Front = a familiar framing. Tap to flip to the edge people forget . Training your brain to always reach for the second edge is exactly the habit the exam rewards. faster, cheaper, 24/7 output …but the same automation causes deskilling and job loss for the workers it replaces. convenient and quick …but creates an access barrier for people like Bà and removes everyday human interaction. …but anonymity, scale and persistence make them engines for cyberbullying. huge productivity boost …but enables misuse (scams, deepfakes) and carries an energy + e-waste cost.","id":1001},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Flip each impact to its other edge","text":"…but constant device upgrades dump old hardware as e-waste — the other side of sustainability. …but for many it erodes face-to-face contact and interpersonal skills.","id":1002},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Social impact or economic issue?","text":"Drag (or tap) each impact from Bellview into the right bucket. Mixing the two strands is one of the most common ways students lose easy marks.","id":1003},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Six ways students throw away marks here","text":"“Automation is bad because it takes jobs.” One edge only — and no stakeholder. ✓ Fix: Show both edges and name who gains vs loses: a productivity benefit for ParcelHub, a job-loss cost for Đức. Calling Đức’s shrunken role “job loss” when he still has a job, or vice-versa. ✓ Fix: Deskilling = keeps the job, narrower. Job loss = role removed. Use the exact term the case fits. Listing access as a “social impact,” or cyberbullying as an “economic issue.” ✓ Fix: Social strand = automation, cyberbullying, decline of interaction.","id":1004},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Six ways students throw away marks here","text":"Economic = access, deskilling, job loss, misuse, sustainability. “Robots take jobs and people get sad.” No named stakeholder, no concrete instance. ✓ Fix: Anchor it: “ParcelHub’s pick-bots made a third of floor staff redundant.” Specifics earn the mark. Saying bullying always existed, so it isn’t about technology. ✓ Fix: Name the amplifying role: scale, persistence and anonymity that emerging apps add. Listing impacts when asked to analyse , discuss or evaluate . ✓ Fix: Match the verb: analyse = examine cause/effect; discuss = both sides; evaluate = weigh + judge.","id":1005},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Do exactly what the verb asks","text":"The mark is for matching your answer to the command word. Tap one to see what it demands and how it changes a KK03 answer.","id":1006},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Build a top-band paragraph live","text":"A reliable structure for “explain/analyse/discuss the impact” questions: P oint (name the impact + stakeholder) → E vidence (a concrete example, ideally from the scenario) → L ink (back to the question + the other edge). Write below — the meters react to what you include.","id":1007},{"file":"u2o1-kk03.html","nav":"u2o1-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The impact of emerging technologies","head":"Five questions · 18 marks · self-marked","text":"Each question reveals a deliberately weak answer (with why it drops marks), a strong answer, and the marking guide . Mark yourself honestly — your score fills the dock in the corner.","id":1008},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"What makes a solution stand out ?","text":"Anyone can build an app. Far fewer build one people actually adopt. This dot point is about the qualities that separate a forgettable project from a creative and innovative solution — and how to argue, in exam conditions, that a solution has them.","id":1009},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Orientation","text":"Here is the exact slice of the study design this module covers — and the trap that costs the most marks.","id":1010},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"\"Characteristics of creative and innovative solutions\"","text":"It sits inside Unit 2, Outcome 1 — Innovative Solutions , where you and your team identify a problem, need or opportunity and build a solution as a proof of concept, prototype or product . KK04 gives you the vocabulary to judge whether what you built is genuinely creative and innovative , not just finished.","id":1011},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Two words, two ideas","text":"Examiners reward students who can tell creative (the idea is new ) apart from innovative (the new idea is applied and adopted to deliver value ). Treat them as synonyms and you cap yourself at half marks. This module drills exactly that line.","id":1012},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Creative is not the same as innovative","text":"This is the single distinction the dot point hangs on. Get it crisp and the rest follows.","id":1013},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The four-quadrant map","text":"Plot any solution on two axes — how original the idea is, and how much it is adopted and creates impact — and you get four honest categories. Most student projects sit in the bottom-left and need pushing up-and-right.","id":1014},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Forgettable","text":"A to-do list app that copies five others and nobody installs. Neither new nor adopted. Safe, and invisible.","id":1015},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The gimmick","text":"A dazzling, original idea that is impractical, unaffordable or unwanted — so it never gets used. Creative but not innovative.","id":1016},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The quiet game-changer","text":"A small, unoriginal tweak that everyone adopts and that genuinely changes behaviour. Innovative without being especially creative.","id":1017},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The standout","text":"An original idea that is also effective, usable and widely adopted. Creative and innovative — what you are aiming for.","id":1018},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Flip these to lock it in","text":"Tap each card. Front = a claim a student might make; back = whether it shows creativity, innovation, or both.","id":1019},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"\"It uses a brand-new idea no one's tried.\"","text":"Creative. Novelty is established — but creativity alone is not innovation. Until it is built, used and delivers value, it is just a good idea.","id":1020},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"\"Half the year level already uses it every lunch.\"","text":"Innovative (impact + adoption). Strong evidence of uptake and changed behaviour. Pair this with novelty and you have a true standout.","id":1021},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"\"It's a clever concept but costs $4,000 a unit.\"","text":"Creative, not innovative. A gimmick: original yet not feasible or adopted, so it delivers no real value. Novelty without uptake.","id":1022},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"\"It solves a real need, works reliably and people love using it.\"","text":"Both — the standout. Effective + user-centred + adopted. If the idea is also original, this is exactly what KK04 is asking you to recognise.","id":1023},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The characteristics, named","text":"When a question asks you to judge a solution, these are the levers you pull. Four core characteristics carry most marks; two supporting ones round out a strong answer.","id":1024},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Originality","text":"A new idea, a fresh combination, or a novel use of existing tech. The \"creative\" half of the dot point.","id":1025},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Effectiveness","text":"It actually does the job — it solves the real problem reliably and well (functionality).","id":1026},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"User-centred","text":"Designed around real users' needs and abilities, so it is genuinely usable — not just buildable.","id":1027},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Disruptiveness","text":"Changes how things are done — shifting behaviour, a market, or an existing way of working.","id":1028},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Aesthetics & appeal","text":"It looks and feels considered. Appeal isn't decoration — it drives the adoption that makes an idea innovative.","id":1029},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Relevance & feasibility","text":"It targets a genuine need and can realistically be built and run within the constraints. The \"why now / why this\" check.","id":1030},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"🌊 FloatMate","text":"Jade's wearable wristband that buzzes a swimmer when a rip current is detected near them. Original Effective User-centred Disruptive → the standout","id":1031},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"🔮 HoloHomework","text":"A desktop hologram that projects your homework into mid-air in 3D. Dazzling at the pitch; $4,000 a unit and needs a dark room. Very original Not feasible Not adopted → the gimmick (creative, not innovative)","id":1032},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"🥪 QuickQ","text":"A one-tap canteen pre-order — pay before recess, skip the queue. Boring tech; the whole school now uses it. Low novelty Effective Adopted Disruptive → the quiet game-changer (innovative, not very creative)","id":1033},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"3D Lab · The Characteristics Profiler","text":"Toggle each characteristic to extend its spoke and build a solution's innovation profile — the shape it makes is its fingerprint. Switch solutions and watch the shape change. A spiky, lopsided star is a solution strong in some areas and weak in others; a full, even star is a true standout.","id":1034},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"The four core characteristics, up close","text":"Each one: a definition you can quote, the evidence an examiner wants, and how the three pitches stack up. The \"evidence\" line is what turns a vague claim into a marked point.","id":1035},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"① Originality the creative half","text":"The solution introduces something new — a fresh idea, an unexpected combination of existing technologies, or a use no one has applied to this problem before. Evidence examiners reward: what specifically is new, and what it is new compared to . \"Original\" with no comparison is an empty claim.","id":1036},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"② Effectiveness / functionality does the job","text":"The solution works and solves the actual problem reliably. Not \"has features\" — achieves the intended result for the user. Evidence: tie it back to the stated need. Effective = the need is met. Watch the classic mix-up — effective (does it meet the need?) is not efficient (does it use few resources?).","id":1037},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"③ User-centred design built around people","text":"Shaped by the real needs, contexts and abilities of its users — gathered through research, not assumed. A user-centred solution is genuinely usable by the people it is for. Evidence: name the user and the need it was designed around. \"Easy to use\" is a conclusion; the design decision that makes it easy is the mark.","id":1038},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"④ Disruptiveness changes the game","text":"The solution changes how something is done — it shifts behaviour, displaces an existing way of working, or reshapes a market. Disruption is the clearest signal an idea has become an innovation. Evidence: what behaviour or practice changed because the solution exists? Adoption is the proof.","id":1039},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"3D Lab · The Creative × Innovative matrix","text":"The three pitches plotted on a living plane. Pick a solution, then drag the sliders to make design decisions — push the idea to be more original , or push it toward adoption and impact — and watch the marker travel between the four quadrants. The goal is the green corner.","id":1040},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Judge the pitch","text":"Each evidence card below proves one characteristic. Drag it — or tap then tap a bin — into the characteristic it best demonstrates. This is the skill the exam tests: matching evidence to the right quality.","id":1041},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Exam traps","text":"The specific ways students lose marks on this dot point. Open each to see the fix. Writing \"the solution is creative and innovative\" as one fused compliment, with no evidence for either. Claiming a solution is effective because it \"runs fast\" or \"uses little data\". That is efficiency. Saying \"it's original\" with nothing to compare it against. Original compared to what ? Marking the most futuristic idea as the most innovative. HoloHomework is the most original — and the least innovative, because no one uses it. \"It is effective, user-centred and disruptive.\" A list of labels scores almost nothing. Calling a solution user-centred because it \"looks nice\" or \"is easy\", with no named user or need.","id":1042},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Writing trainer · command words & P·E·L","text":"Decode the command word first, then build the answer with the P·E·L spine. The trainer below detects the moves examiners look for as you type.","id":1043},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Point","text":"Name the characteristic and your claim. \"QuickQ is highly disruptive.\"","id":1044},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Evidence","text":"Cite the scenario fact. \"The whole school now pre-orders, emptying the recess queue.\"","id":1045},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Link","text":"Connect back to the question / to innovation. \"This changed behaviour is what makes it innovative, not its novelty.\"","id":1046},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Practice questions","text":"VCE-style. Attempt each in your head or on paper first, then reveal the weak answer (and why it bleeds marks), the strong answer, and the marking guide. Self-mark honestly — it fills the dial in the corner. Total: 18 marks. Distinguish between a creative solution and an innovative solution. Describe three characteristics that make a solution stand out, using QuickQ as your example. HoloHomework is the most original of the three pitches but almost no one uses it. This best shows that… Explain why FloatMate can be described as both creative and innovative.","id":1047},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"Practice questions","text":"Refer to at least two characteristics. A judge says: \"HoloHomework is clearly the most innovative pitch — it's the most futuristic.\" Evaluate this claim, then justify which pitch you would award \"most innovative\" and why.","id":1048},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"One-screen cheat sheet","text":"The whole dot point on one screen. Screenshot it the night before. Creative = new / original idea. Innovative = new idea applied + adopted to deliver value. Creative ⊂ innovative only if it lands. Originality — is it new (vs what)? Effectiveness — does it meet the need? User-centred — built from a real user need. Disruptiveness — what behaviour changed? Aesthetics & appeal — drives adoption. Relevance & feasibility — real need, buildable. Effective (meets need) ≠ efficient (few resources). Original ≠ innovative (needs uptake). Futuristic ≠ innovative.","id":1049},{"file":"u2o1-kk04.html","nav":"u2o1-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"What makes a solution stand out ?","head":"One-screen cheat sheet","text":"FloatMate — standout (creative + innovative). HoloHomework — gimmick (creative only). QuickQ — quiet game-changer (innovative only). Point: name the characteristic + claim. Evidence: a scenario fact. Link: back to creative / innovative.","id":1050},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","text":"An innovative solution that nobody needs is just an expensive hobby. This module is about the two techniques the study design names for finding out what users actually need — surveys and interviews — when to reach for each, and how to turn what people tell you into real requirements. Four Year 11 students — Priya, Liam, Sophie and Noah — are building GrazeGo , an app that lets students pre-order canteen food and skip the lunch queue. Before they design a single screen, they have to find out what students, the canteen manager and people with dietary needs actually want.","id":1051},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","text":"We'll follow their data collection the whole way through. VCAA Key Knowledge: \"techniques for collecting data to determine user needs and requirements, such as interviews and surveys.\" Because the study design uses \"such as\" , interviews and surveys are the named examples you must be able to discuss — observation is a useful related primary-source method, but the two you'll be examined on are surveys and interviews .","id":1052},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Breadth or depth — you can't have both from one method","text":"Every data collection method trades breadth (how many people you hear from) against depth (how much you learn from each one). That single trade-off is the heart of this dot point, and it's why surveys and interviews exist as separate tools.","id":1053},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"The survey net 🕸️","text":"Think of a fishing net dragged across the whole school. It catches a little from everyone — fast, wide, countable. Priya surveys 600 students in a day and learns how many want vegetarian options. What she can't do is ask any one fish, \"wait — why?\"","id":1054},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"The interview spotlight 🔦","text":"Think of a spotlight on one person. It reveals a lot about a few — slow, narrow, rich. Liam interviews the canteen manager for 30 minutes and uncovers the real bottleneck (EFTPOS refunds), something no checkbox would ever have surfaced. A survey reaches many people shallowly and gives quantitative, generalisable data; an interview reaches few people deeply and gives rich, qualitative data. Name the trade-off — breadth vs depth — and you've earned the marks. Use the 3D scene above to see it: switch the instrument and watch how many people light up versus how much each one reveals.","id":1055},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Surveys — wide and countable","text":"A survey is a fixed set of questions sent to many people, usually online (Google Forms, Microsoft Forms). Everyone answers the same questions, so the responses are easy to count, chart and compare. Surveys are the go-to when you need to know how many , how often , or which option is most popular across a large group. Breadth — reach hundreds or thousands quickly and cheaply. Quantitative — closed questions produce numbers you can graph and compare. Consistent — everyone gets identical questions, so results are comparable. Anonymous — people answer honestly about sensitive topics.","id":1056},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Surveys — wide and countable","text":"Fast to analyse — forms tools auto-tally and chart results. Shallow — you can't ask \"why?\" or follow an interesting answer. No clarification — a confusing question stays confusing; you get junk data. Low response rate — many ignore it, which can bias results. Rigid — you only learn about things you thought to ask. Misreads — people rush, click randomly, or misunderstand. Priya posts a 6-question Google Form to all year levels. In two days, 612 students respond. She learns: 71% would use a pre-order app, the worst queue is 12:55–1:05pm , the most-wanted feature is \"see when my order is ready\" , and 18% need allergen labelling. That's a clear, countable picture of what most students want — exactly what a survey is for.","id":1057},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Interviews — narrow and rich","text":"An interview is a guided conversation with one person (or a small group) where the interviewer can probe , follow up, and read tone and body language. You learn why , not just how many . Interviews shine when you need depth: the workflow of an expert, the lived experience of a user with specific needs, or the messy reasons behind a behaviour.","id":1058},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Structured","text":"Fixed questions, same order, no improvising. Closest to a spoken survey — consistent and easy to compare, but rigid.","id":1059},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Semi-structured","text":"A planned set of questions plus freedom to follow up. The sweet spot for gathering needs — most school projects use this.","id":1060},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Unstructured","text":"A free-flowing chat around a topic. Great for early discovery, hard to compare across people. Depth — probe with \"why?\", \"tell me more\", \"what happens when…\". Qualitative richness — stories, reasons, edge cases and emotions. Adaptive — chase unexpected answers a survey would miss. Clarify on the spot — fix misunderstandings immediately. Empathy — read tone and body language; build rapport. Slow & costly — minutes per person; you can only do a few. Small sample — can't generalise to the whole population. Interviewer bias — leading questions or tone sway answers.","id":1061},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Unstructured","text":"Hard to analyse — transcripts must be read and coded by hand. Less anonymous — people may hold back face-to-face. Liam runs four semi-structured interviews : the canteen manager (Mrs Tran) and three students with food allergies. From Mrs Tran he learns the till can't easily refund a cancelled order — a hidden non-functional constraint. From a student with a severe nut allergy he learns that \"vegetarian\" labels aren't enough; she needs per-ingredient allergen info. No survey checkbox would have caught either. Four people, but each answer reshaped the design.","id":1062},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Side by side — and why you usually want both","text":"Flip each card to reveal the contrast. The pattern is always the same: where a survey is strong, an interview is weak, and vice-versa. That's exactly why pairing them — survey for breadth, interview for depth — beats either alone. Researchers call this triangulation : two methods checking each other.","id":1063},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"When to choose it","text":"Dimension Survey Interview Sample size Large (100s–1000s) Small (a handful) Depth per person Shallow Deep Data produced Mostly quantitative Mostly qualitative Can follow up? Yes — probe freely Speed & cost Fast, cheap Slow, resource-heavy Analysis effort Low (auto-charted) High (coded by hand) Generalisable? Yes, if sample is representative No — too few people Best question word How many / which Why / how / what's it like","id":1064},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"The method is only as good as the questions","text":"You can pick the perfect method and still collect garbage if the questions are badly written. Two ideas to master: the open vs closed distinction, and the common question faults that quietly ruin your data.","id":1065},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Closed questions","text":"Fixed choices — yes/no, multiple choice, a 1–5 rating. They produce quantitative data that's quick to count. Perfect for surveys. \"How often do you buy from the canteen each week? ○ 0 ○ 1–2 ○ 3–4 ○ 5+\"","id":1066},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Open questions","text":"Free text or free speech — the person answers in their own words. They produce qualitative data: rich, but slow to analyse. The lifeblood of interviews. \"What's the most frustrating part of buying lunch at school?\"","id":1067},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Spot & fix the faulty questions","text":"Each question below is broken in a classic way. Tap to reveal what's wrong and how Priya's team fixed it.","id":1068},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Quick check — open or closed?","text":"Tap the label you think is correct. Green = right, red = try again.","id":1069},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Who you ask decides what you learn","text":"Collecting data isn't just choosing a method — it's choosing who answers . Two ideas decide whether your data is trustworthy: the sample (the slice of the population you actually reach) and the response rate (how many of them reply). Get these wrong and even a huge survey can mislead you. Survey: confidence in ‘how many’ climbs as the sample grows (66 responses) — but every data point stays shallow. Great for breadth and numbers. If GrazeGo only surveys the queue at the canteen , they miss every student who gave up and brings lunch from home — exactly the people the app could win back. A sample that doesn't represent the whole population produces biased data, no matter how many respond. Always ask: who is missing from my sample?","id":1070},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Which method fits the goal?","text":"Drag each goal into the method you'd choose (or tap a chip then tap a bin on mobile). Some genuinely need both . When you're done, hit Check . Tip on mobile: tap a chip to select it, then tap a bin.","id":1071},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Turning answers into requirements","text":"Collecting data is step one. The point is to convert what users said into solution requirements — the bridge to KK05. A raw quote isn't a requirement; you have to translate it. Notice how each requirement traces back to a real piece of collected data.","id":1072},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"From GrazeGo's data to its spec","text":"Survey data tends to become functional requirements and measurable non-functional targets (numbers, popularity, thresholds). Interview data tends to surface hidden constraints and edge-case requirements that no checkbox would reveal. You need both kinds to write a complete specification.","id":1073},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Collecting data responsibly","text":"The moment you collect data from real people, you take on responsibilities. Examiners love a question that asks you to weave an ethical or legal point into a data collection answer — so know these.","id":1074},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Informed consent","text":"Tell people what the data is for, that taking part is voluntary, and that they can stop. For under-18s, you may need parent/guardian consent.","id":1075},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Anonymity & privacy","text":"Don't collect names or identifying detail you don't need. This links to the Privacy Act 1988 and the Australian Privacy Principles you met in Data Analysis.","id":1076},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Honesty & no harm","text":"Don't deceive participants or pressure them. Store responses securely and use them only for the stated purpose.","id":1077},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Avoid bias by design","text":"Neutral, non-leading questions and a representative sample aren't just \"good practice\" — biased collection produces unfair, misleading conclusions. VCAA tie-in: the study design even asks \"how can the coordinator be sure every student submitted their survey — or that one student didn't submit 20?\" Data integrity (one response per person, verified) is part of collecting trustworthy data.","id":1078},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Decode what the question is really asking","text":"Marks are lost when students describe for an analyse question. Tap each command word to see what it demands and roughly how many marks it signals.","id":1079},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Listing strengths with no trade-off","text":"Writing \"surveys reach lots of people\" and stopping. Strengths only earn full marks when paired with a limitation or a comparison. ↳ Always answer breadth-vs-depth: more reach but less depth.","id":1080},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Ignoring the scenario","text":"Giving a generic textbook answer when the question describes a specific situation (an expert's workflow, a whole student body). ↳ Name the actual users and pick the method that fits them .","id":1081},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Confusing qualitative and quantitative","text":"Saying surveys give \"detailed reasons\" or interviews give \"percentages of the whole school\". You've swapped their data types. ↳ Survey = quantitative/breadth · Interview = qualitative/depth.","id":1082},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Forgetting sample & bias","text":"Recommending a survey but never mentioning who is sampled. A biased sample undermines the whole method. ↳ Add one line on a representative sample / response rate.","id":1083},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Treating raw data as the answer","text":"Stopping at \"they collected the data\" without converting it into requirements or a design decision. ↳ Show the link: this data → this requirement.","id":1084},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"One method when the question rewards two","text":"An \"analyse\" or \"recommend\" question often wants you to justify combining methods. Picking only one caps your marks. ↳ Survey for breadth + interview for depth = triangulation.","id":1085},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Write answers that actually score","text":"High-band answers follow a simple shape. P·E·L : make your Point , support it with Evidence from the scenario , then Link back to the user's need or the question. Try it below — the trainer watches for the moves examiners reward. State which method and why, directly. Cite the scenario — the users, the goal, the numbers. Tie it to the need: breadth/depth, requirement, bias. Practice prompt: \"GrazeGo wants to know how many students would use a pre-order app. Recommend a data collection method and justify your choice.\" (3 marks)","id":1086},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"VCAA-style questions · weak vs strong answers","text":"Five questions, 19 marks total. Read each, attempt it yourself, then open the weak answer (and why it loses marks), the strong answer, and the marking guide. Mark your own attempt — the dial bottom-right tracks your total. Distinguish between a survey and an interview as techniques for collecting user needs. The GrazeGo team needs to know how many students across the school would use a pre-order app, and which features are most wanted. Recommend a data collection method and justify your choice. Liam wants to understand the canteen manager's refund workflow and a nut-allergy student's experience reading food labels.","id":1087},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"VCAA-style questions · weak vs strong answers","text":"Explain why an interview is more appropriate than a survey for these two goals, referring to the type of data each method produces. A different team is building RoamSafe , an app to help international students find culturally familiar food near campus. They plan to survey only students queuing at the campus food court. Analyse two problems with this data collection plan and suggest how to improve it. GrazeGo has three weeks and four team members. Propose a complete data collection plan that uses both a survey and interviews to determine user needs and requirements. Justify each method's role, and explain how the team would ensure the data they collect is trustworthy .","id":1088},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"The two named methods","text":"Survey — same fixed questions to many people; breadth , quantitative , fast, cheap, anonymous; can't probe. Interview — guided conversation with a few; depth , qualitative , can probe, builds empathy; slow, small sample, hard to analyse.","id":1089},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Choosing fast","text":"\"How many / which / how often\" → survey. \"Why / how exactly / what's it like\" → interview. Need the full picture / check a design → both (triangulation).","id":1090},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Question quality","text":"Avoid leading , double-barrelled , ambiguous , jargon/loaded questions. Closed = quantitative (surveys); open = qualitative (interviews).","id":1091},{"file":"u2o1-kk06.html","nav":"u2o1-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Before you build it, ask the people who'll use it.","head":"Trust the data","text":"Representative sample (who's missing?), decent response rate , watch bias (self-selection, convenience), ensure integrity (one response each), gain consent , keep it private . Surveys buy you breadth and numbers; interviews buy you depth and reasons — match the method to whether the question asks \"how many\" or \"why\", sample fairly, and turn what you hear into requirements.","id":1092},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","text":"Four ways to put a design on paper — mock-ups , sitemaps , storyboards and pseudocode . Same solution, four different lenses. Knowing which lens shows what is the whole game in the exam.","id":1093},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"📌 The exact dot point","text":"From the VCE Applied Computing Study Design (Unit 2, Outcome 1, Key Knowledge): “design tools and techniques for representing solution designs, such as mock-ups, pseudocode, sitemaps and storyboards”","id":1094},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Jade’s team designs the FloatMate app","text":"You met Jade earlier in this unit — the Year 11 Nippers volunteer who invented FloatMate , a wearable wristband that warns swimmers when they drift into a rip current. The wristband works. Now her team has to design the companion phone app that pairs with it: a screen for beach status, push alerts, settings, and a help guide. Because Outcome 1 is a collaborative task, Jade can’t just build the app in her head — she has to show her teammates and her mentor what she means. That’s exactly what design tools are for: representing the design so other people can see it, question it, and improve it before a single line of code is written.","id":1095},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"The band","text":"Detects drift, buzzes the wearer (built in KK01–KK04).","id":1096},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"The app (now)","text":"Beach status, alerts, settings, help — needs designing.","id":1097},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"The team","text":"Jade + 3 students + a surf-club mentor. They need shared blueprints.","id":1098},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"One design, four lenses","text":"Here’s the FloatMate app as a stack of screens. Switch the lens to see how each design tool represents the same app in a completely different way. Notice: nothing about the app changes — only what the tool chooses to show . Same content, four questions: Mock-up what does it look like? · Sitemap how do the screens connect? · Storyboard what happens, in what order? · Pseudocode what logic runs underneath?","id":1099},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Mock-up","text":"A picture of one screen’s layout & look. A visual draft of a single screen showing the position, size and style of every component (buttons, text, images, colours, fonts).","id":1100},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Sitemap","text":"A tree of all pages and their links. A hierarchical diagram of every page/screen and how they are organised and linked — the navigation map of the whole solution.","id":1101},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Storyboard","text":"Frames in order showing a journey. A series of frames in time order showing the path a user takes through screens for one task — this, then this, then this.","id":1102},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Pseudocode","text":"Plain-English steps of the logic. Structured plain-English steps of an algorithm’s logic — sequence, selection and iteration — without being tied to any one programming language.","id":1103},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Mock-up What the screen looks like","text":"A mock-up is a visual draft of one screen . It shows where each component sits, how big it is, and how it’s styled — the layout, fonts, colours, icons and labels. It deliberately says nothing about navigation or logic; it answers a single question: “what will the user see?”","id":1104},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Low-fidelity vs high-fidelity","text":"A low-fidelity mock-up (a wireframe) is a quick boxes-and-lines sketch to test layout fast. A high-fidelity mock-up looks close to the finished product — real colours, real fonts. Early in design you sketch low-fi; later you polish to high-fi.","id":1105},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Annotated mock-ups","text":"An annotated mock-up adds callout labels explaining each component — its data, its formatting, what happens when tapped. Annotations turn a pretty picture into a buildable specification the developer can follow. Examiners reward annotation.","id":1106},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Try it — tap a component to read its annotation","text":"This is the FloatMate Beach Status screen. Each dashed region is an annotatable component. Tap one. App title, centred. Font: Inter Bold 18pt, white on dark-teal (#1d2b45). Fixed at top on every screen for branding & orientation. Largest element — draws the eye first. Status word pulled live from the band feed ( SAFE green / CAUTION amber / RIP red). Beach name + timestamp above; plain-English sub-line below. Secondary info, two label–value rows. Smaller, dimmed text so it doesn’t compete with the status card. Values refresh every 30 s.","id":1107},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Try it — tap a component to read its annotation","text":"Full-width, accent fill, high contrast. On tap → sends a test buzz to the paired band and shows a confirmation toast. The only tappable control on this screen.","id":1108},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Sitemap How the screens connect","text":"A sitemap zooms out . Instead of one screen, it shows all of them as a hierarchy — a tree with the home screen at the top and branches to each section and subpage. Lines mean “you can navigate from here to there.” It answers: “how is the whole thing organised, and what links to what?”","id":1109},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"What a sitemap shows","text":"Every page/screen in the solution The hierarchy — top-level vs sub-pages The links between pages (navigation paths) How deep the structure goes (how many taps to anything)","id":1110},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"What it deliberately leaves out","text":"What any single page looks like (that’s a mock-up) The order a user moves through for a task (that’s a storyboard) Any processing or logic (that’s pseudocode)","id":1111},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Storyboard What happens, in what order","text":"A storyboard borrows its name from film. It’s a row of frames in time order showing the journey a user takes through screens to complete one task. Arrows between frames mean “next.” It answers: “walk me through what the user actually does, step by step.” Below are the five frames of FloatMate’s most important journey — “a rip is detected while Sam is swimming.” They’ve been shuffled . Tap them into the right order. When the sequence is correct, the storyboard plays.","id":1112},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Pseudocode The logic underneath","text":"The first three tools are about the interface . Pseudocode is the odd one out — it represents the processing logic : the algorithm. It’s written in structured plain English using the three control structures — sequence , selection and iteration — so any developer can read it and code it in any language. It is not real code and a computer can’t run it. Here’s the logic behind FloatMate’s alert — the brains the mock-up button and storyboard are sitting on top of:","id":1113},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Pseudocode conventions to show off","text":"Sequence — steps run top to bottom Selection — IF … THEN … ELSE … END IF Iteration — WHILE … END WHILE / FOR … END FOR Keywords in CAPS, meaningful names, indentation, one action per line","id":1114},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Why pseudocode, not real code?","text":"It’s language-independent and readable by non-programmers on the team, so the design can be discussed and checked before committing to syntax. It captures the logic without drowning it in semicolons and brackets.","id":1115},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Which tool for which job?","text":"This is where most marks live. The exam describes a need; you pick the right tool and justify it . Use the keyword in the question as your signal. Tool Represents Answers the question Question keywords Mock-up Appearance of one screen What will it look like? layout, interface, appearance, screen design, fonts/colours Sitemap Structure of all screens How is it organised / linked? navigation, structure, pages, hierarchy, how it’s organised Storyboard Sequence over time What order does it happen in? flow, journey, sequence, steps, walkthrough, process the user follows Pseudocode Logic / processing What does the program decide/calculate? algorithm, logic, decision, calculate, IF/condition, processing","id":1116},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Drill — match the job to the tool","text":"Pick the best design tool for each request from Jade’s team. Immediate feedback.","id":1117},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"The architect analogy","text":"Imagine designing a house instead of an app. The same four tools appear — and the analogy is worth quoting in an extended-response answer because it shows you understand why each tool exists .","id":1118},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Mock-up","text":"The interior render of one room — what it looks like, finishes and all.","id":1119},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Sitemap","text":"The floor plan — which rooms exist and which doors connect them.","id":1120},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Storyboard","text":"The walkthrough — front door → hallway → kitchen, in the order a guest moves.","id":1121},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Pseudocode","text":"The wiring logic — IF the switch is flipped THEN the light turns on.","id":1122},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Command words → what to actually do","text":"Give the tool, nothing more. 1 mark. “A storyboard.” Say what the tool is and what it represents. “A sitemap is a hierarchical diagram showing all pages and how they link.” Describe plus why/how it works in the context. Add the reason it suits the job. Make the difference explicit in one sentence. “Whereas a mock-up shows one screen’s look, a storyboard shows the sequence across screens.” Pick a tool and defend it against the scenario’s needs. This is where the architect analogy and “communicate to the team” lines pay off. Actually produce the artefact — a labelled mock-up, a tree sitemap, ordered frames, or indented pseudocode. Use the conventions.","id":1123},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"High-mark responses follow P·E·L — Point, Evidence/Example, Link . Pick a prompt, write your answer, and watch the keyword tracker light up as you hit the ideas examiners reward. Distinguish between a mock-up and a storyboard as design tools, using FloatMate as an example. (Aim: Point → Evidence → Link.)","id":1124},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"VCE-style questions with model answers","text":"Attempt each in your head or on paper first. Then reveal the weak answer (and why it loses marks), the strong answer, and the marking guide . Mark yourself — your score feeds the dial in the corner.","id":1125},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"Visual draft of one screen Shows layout, size, fonts, colours, icons Annotate components for marks Low-fi sketch → high-fi polished Hierarchy of all pages Shows organisation + links (navigation) Non-linear map of options No look, no order, no logic Frames in time order Shows the user’s journey/flow for one task Several screens, low detail, arrows = next Sequence, not structure Structured plain-English logic Sequence · selection · iteration Language-independent, not executable The only one for processing/decisions Name the tool → say what it represents → justify against the scenario’s need (often:","id":1126},{"file":"u2o1-kk07.html","nav":"u2o1-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Design tools: drawing the solution before you build it","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"“so the team can review the design before building”). Keyword cheat: look →mock-up · link/structure →sitemap · order/flow →storyboard · logic/decision →pseudocode. Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1&2 · U2·O1 Innovative Solutions · KK07 Design Tools Built for presentation & exam revision · Australian English · fully offline","id":1127},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","text":"Developing an innovative solution isn't waiting for a lightning-bolt of genius. It's a repeatable process: get inside your user's head, blow the problem wide open with dozens of ideas, then narrow ruthlessly to the one worth building. This is design thinking , and it's examinable.","id":1128},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Developing a solution is a process, not a moment","text":"Meet Team Vector — Jade, Marcus, Priya and Tom, four Year 11 students at a Melbourne school. They've spotted an opportunity : new Year 7 students arrive lost, anxious, and afraid to ask for help in their first weeks. Team Vector decides to develop an innovative digital solution. The question is how — and \"we'll just think of something good\" is not a method. VCAA describes the thinking behind this stage precisely. Design thinking is \"a way of thinking critically and creatively to generate and evaluate innovative ideas, and precisely define the preferred solution.\" It runs on two engines you must be able to name and tell apart:","id":1129},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Developing a solution is a process, not a moment","text":"Divergent thinking opens the problem up — it generates a wide range of ideas (quantity, variety, creativity). Convergent thinking closes it down — it evaluates options and selects the preferred idea to develop. You diverge first, then converge. Mixing them up — or doing only one — is the classic mistake.","id":1130},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Think of a film's casting call","text":"A director doesn't hire the first actor through the door. They diverge — audition dozens, encouraging wild range — then converge , comparing every audition against the role's real requirements until one stands out. Developing a solution works the same way: many auditions, one cast lead, then weeks of rehearsal to develop the performance.","id":1131},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Get inside the user's head before you touch an idea","text":"Empathising means deliberately understanding the end user — what they say, think, do and feel — so your ideas solve their real problem, not the one you assumed. Team Vector interviews Sam , a quiet Year 7 who started mid-year and got lost three times in week one.","id":1132},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Build an empathy map","text":"An empathy map sorts what you learn into four quadrants. It's the most exam-friendly empathise tool because it forces you past surface wants. Drag Sam's interview snippets into the right quadrant.","id":1133},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"The same problem looks different through every set of eyes","text":"\"Ideating across perspectives\" means deliberately viewing the problem from each stakeholder's point of view before you brainstorm. The new-student problem isn't only Sam's — it touches buddies, teachers and parents, and each lens unlocks different ideas.","id":1134},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Go wide: generate far more ideas than you'll ever use","text":"Divergent thinking is about quantity and range . The single rule that makes it work: defer judgement. No \"that's silly,\" no \"we can't afford that\" — yet. Criticism in the diverge phase kills the wild ideas that often become the best ones.","id":1135},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Brainstorming","text":"Rapid-fire ideas out loud or on sticky notes. Build on others' ideas (\"yes, and…\"). Aim for volume.","id":1136},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Mind mapping","text":"Start with the problem in the centre; branch outward into themes, then sub-ideas. Shows connections.","id":1137},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"SCAMPER & \"How might we…\"","text":"Prompts that force new angles — Substitute, Combine, Adapt… Each prompt is a fresh idea engine. Team Vector runs a ten-minute brainstorm and fills the wall. Some ideas are obvious, some are wild, a few are terrible — and that's exactly right. Flip each note to see the idea.","id":1138},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Casting a wide net","text":"A fisher who drops one line catches one fish. Divergent thinking casts a wide net so there's something worth keeping when you haul it in. You throw most of it back — but you can't keep what you never caught.","id":1139},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Go narrow: evaluate, then choose with reasons","text":"Now flip the engine. Convergent thinking clusters related ideas, evaluates them against criteria , and selects a preferred idea . The discipline here is choosing on evidence — feasibility, user fit, originality — not on whose idea it was. Left edge = full divergence: ideas explode outward, many and varied. Slide right and convergent thinking pulls them together, dimming the weak ones until a single preferred idea glows at the funnel's neck. That neck is the moment you commit.","id":1140},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Affinity clustering","text":"Group similar sticky notes into themes so 30 ideas become 5 directions.","id":1141},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Dot voting","text":"Each team member spends a few dots on the directions they back. Fast, democratic shortlist.","id":1142},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Scoring matrix","text":"Rate each shortlisted idea against the criteria (feasibility, user fit, originality). Highest total wins — and you can justify it.","id":1143},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Tell the two engines apart","text":"This is the single most-tested distinction in this dotpoint. Sort each technique by the thinking it uses.","id":1144},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Turn the chosen concept into something real","text":"Picking the preferred idea isn't the finish line — it's the start of development . Now Team Vector adds detail, resolves the unknowns, and builds a proof of concept so they can test whether Compass actually helps Sam.","id":1145},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"From idea to proof-of-concept","text":"Developing means making the abstract concrete: defining each feature, sketching screens, deciding how a buddy gets paired, and building enough of it to demonstrate the core promise. VCAA accepts the developed solution as a proof of concept, prototype or product .","id":1146},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Test the risky assumption first","text":"The riskiest assumption in Compass: will a shy Year 7 actually message an older buddy? Team Vector builds that one flow first and tests it with Sam — because if that fails, nothing else matters. Develop what's uncertain, not what's easy.","id":1147},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Command words decoded","text":"Command What the examiner wants For this dotpoint Identify Name it — no explanation. \"Identify one divergent thinking technique.\" → Brainstorming. Describe Name + what it is / how it works. Say what the technique is and how it's used to develop the solution. Explain Make a link clear — show the why / how with cause and effect. Explain how empathising leads to a better preferred idea. Justify Give reasons for a choice; weigh it up. Justify selecting one idea as the preferred idea over another. Compare Similarities and differences, both sides. Compare divergent and convergent thinking.","id":1148},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong short answers follow Point · Evidence · Link : state the point, back it with evidence from the scenario, then link it to the question. Write a real answer below and watch the live coaching.","id":1149},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Read each question, draft your answer, then reveal a weak attempt, a strong one, and the marking guide. Self-mark honestly — your total feeds the dock. Divergent thinking is when you think of ideas and convergent thinking is when you think harder about them. Divergent thinking generates a wide range of varied ideas for the solution (e.g. brainstorming many options, deferring judgement), whereas convergent thinking evaluates those ideas against criteria to select a single preferred idea to develop. 1 mark — divergent = generating a range/variety of ideas. 1 mark — convergent = evaluating/selecting the preferred idea.","id":1150},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Must show the contrast (go wide vs go narrow), not just define one. Empathising is good because you understand the user better, so you can make a better app that they will like more. Asking Sam what app to build only captures a surface want (a map). Empathising reveals the deeper need — Sam feels anxious and embarrassed asking older students for help , which Sam never states directly. This reframes the brief, so the preferred idea can target confidence (private, discreet directions), not just navigation — making it more likely to actually solve Sam's real problem.","id":1151},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"1 mark — identifies that asking directly gives only a stated/surface want. 1 mark — empathising surfaces an unstated need/feeling (anxiety, embarrassment) using the scenario. 1 mark — links this to a better-targeted preferred idea. They could use brainstorming and mind mapping. Perspectives are good because more people means more ideas and that is better for the team. Brainstorming — the team rapidly calls out as many ideas as possible without judging them , building on each other to maximise volume. Mind mapping — they place the new-student problem at the centre and branch outward into themes (wayfinding, social, safety), revealing connections and gaps.","id":1152},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Ideating across perspectives (Sam, a buddy, a teacher, IT) strengthens the solution because each lens surfaces different needs and constraints — e.g. a teacher needs it not to distract class, IT needs it to run on the school network — leading to a more user-centred , robust preferred idea. 1 mark each — two divergent techniques described, not just named (max 2). 1 mark — perspectives surface differing stakeholder needs/constraints. 1 mark — links to a stronger, user-centred solution. They should just pick the buddy app because it is the best idea and everyone in the team liked it the most.","id":1153},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Choosing by criteria is good because criteria help you choose. Team Vector should first cluster the 14 ideas (affinity grouping) into themes — e.g. wayfinding, social support, broadcast — so they're comparing directions, not noise. They then build a scoring matrix, rating each shortlisted direction against agreed criteria: feasibility on the school network, fit to Sam's real need (confidence), originality, and scope within Unit 2. The highest-scoring idea — a buddy-pairing + discreet wayfinding app (Compass) — becomes the preferred idea. Choosing against criteria rather than preference matters because it makes the decision justifiable and traceable — the team can defend why Compass beat AR arrows (lower cost, better fit to the anxiety need) — and it guards against picking the loudest voice's idea over the one that best serves the user.","id":1154},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Preference alone can't be evidenced in evaluation later. 1–2 marks — a convergent method described (clustering and/or scoring matrix / dot voting). 1 mark — criteria named (e.g. feasibility, user fit, originality, scope). 1 mark — criteria applied to the scenario to reach a preferred idea. 1–2 marks — justification: criteria make the choice evidenced/justifiable and traceable to later evaluation, avoiding preference bias. Developing the idea means making the app. They should develop the home screen first because every app needs a home screen and it is easy to do.","id":1155},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"Developing the preferred idea means turning the chosen concept into something concrete and testable — defining each feature, designing the screens, and building a proof of concept that demonstrates Compass's core promise, rather than just coding randomly. They should develop and test the buddy-message flow first, because it carries the riskiest assumption : that a shy student like Sam will actually reach out to an older buddy. If that assumption fails, the whole concept fails, so testing it early is the highest-value development. It also loops straight back to the empathy insight — Sam feels watched — so building a private, discreet version of that flow tests both feasibility and user fit at once.","id":1156},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"VCE-style questions with weak vs strong answers","text":"1–2 marks — developing = making the concept concrete and testable (proof of concept / prototype), defining features & designs. 1 mark — identifies a sensible first feature. 1–2 marks — justifies it by risk / riskiest assumption (test the uncertain thing first). 1 mark — links the choice back to the user need / empathy insight.","id":1157},{"file":"u2o1-kk08.html","nav":"u2o1-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"One great idea is the last idea you keep — not the first you have.","head":"Developing solutions — everything in one place","text":"Empathise — know the user (says/thinks/does/feels) Ideate across perspectives — many lenses, many ideas Diverge — generate a wide range, defer judgement Converge — evaluate vs criteria, select the preferred idea Develop — build a tested proof of concept Divergent = go wide, generate a range Convergent = go narrow, select the preferred idea Diverge then converge — never mix them Brainstorming · mind mapping SCAMPER · \"How might we…\" Rule: defer judgement Affinity clustering · dot voting Scoring matrix against criteria Choose with reasons, not preference Tie every technique to its job + stage Develop = whole arc, not just \"build it\" Justify the preferred idea against criteria range / variety · defer judgement evaluate · criteria · preferred idea user-centred · proof of concept","id":1158},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"What this dot point actually asks of you","text":"Straight from the VCAA Applied Computing Study Design (Unit 2, Area of Study 1), the examinable wording is: “techniques for documenting the development of solutions, including the tools and techniques for coordinating and monitoring projects, such as Gantt charts .” That one sentence hides three jobs you must be able to do and explain. Across this module you will master each, see them on Jade's real team build, and practise the exact wording examiners reward.","id":1159},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Coordinate & monitor","text":"Use a Gantt chart to plan tasks, sequence them, set durations, milestones and dependencies — then track slippage.","id":1160},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Record the journey","text":"Keep a project journal / log of decisions, ideas, problems and modifications as they happen.","id":1161},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Protect the work","text":"Use version control to save dated copies so you can roll back and prove the work is your own. FloatMate is a wearable wristband that buzzes a swimmer when they drift into a rip current. Year 11 student Jade — a Nippers volunteer — leads a four-person team building it across a 10-week term. From here on, every example is their build. Documentation is what stops four enthusiastic people from quietly building four different projects.","id":1162},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Why document at all? Four reasons that matter in the exam","text":"“Because the teacher said so” earns zero marks. Examiners want the purpose . Documentation exists to solve four real problems on a team project.","id":1163},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"🤝 Delegation","text":"A clear plan lets the team split work so no two people unknowingly build the same thing — and nobody sits idle. Jade can assign the buzzer code to Sam while Priya designs the 3D enclosure, because the Gantt chart shows those tasks don't depend on each other.","id":1164},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"📡 Monitoring","text":"Plans drift. A living Gantt chart and journal let the team see this week whether they're ahead, on time, or sliding — early enough to act, not the night before submission.","id":1165},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"🛟 Recovery","text":"When today's code breaks, version control lets you return to Friday's working copy in seconds instead of rebuilding from memory. Documentation is a safety net.","id":1166},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"✅ Authentication","text":"A dated journal and version history prove the solution grew over time and is genuinely the team's own work — the basis of academic integrity in a SAT/SAC. Think of building FloatMate as a four-car road trip. The Gantt chart is the route map and timetable — who drives which leg, by when. The project journal is the travel diary — where you stopped, what went wrong, the detour you chose and why. Version control is the set of save-points: if you take a wrong turn, you can drive back to the last good fork instead of restarting in Melbourne.","id":1167},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Three techniques — and the one-line difference between them","text":"The single most common exam mistake is blurring these three. Lock the distinction now. Tap a card to flip it.","id":1168},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"A timeline of tasks","text":"A horizontal bar chart of every task against time. Shows sequencing, durations, dependencies, milestones and the critical path. It plans and monitors the schedule . Forward-looking.","id":1169},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"A diary of decisions","text":"A dated log of ideas generated, choices made, problems hit and modifications applied — and the reasoning behind them . It records the story . Backward-looking.","id":1170},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Dated save-points","text":"Keeping numbered/dated copies of the work-in-progress so you can roll back , compare, and prove authorship. It protects the files . Reversible.","id":1171},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Anatomy of a Gantt chart","text":"A Gantt chart is a bar chart on its side: each task is a horizontal bar whose position is its start, and whose length is its duration. Six features carry marks — learn every one.","id":1172},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Tasks","text":"The individual jobs that make up the project, listed down the left (e.g. “Write GPS code”, “Print enclosure”, “ User testing ”).","id":1173},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Time allocation (duration)","text":"How long each task is expected to take — shown by the bar's length along the time axis (days/weeks across the top).","id":1174},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Sequencing","text":"The order tasks run in. Some run in parallel (overlapping bars); some must run one after another.","id":1175},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Dependencies","text":"An arrow/link meaning “this task can't start until that one finishes.” Testing depends on a printed enclosure existing.","id":1176},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Milestones","text":"A key checkpoint with zero duration, drawn as a diamond ◆ — e.g. “Prototype complete”, “Submission”. Markers you steer toward.","id":1177},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Critical path","text":"The chain of dependent tasks that takes the longest to complete. It sets the minimum project length. If any task on it slips, the whole project finishes late. Tasks off it have slack (float) — they can slip a little without hurting the deadline. It tells the project manager exactly which tasks to protect . Jade doesn't have to micromanage everyone equally — she watches the critical-path tasks like a hawk, because those are the only ones that can blow the deadline. The next lab lets you feel this directly.","id":1178},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Critical-path explorer","text":"FloatMate's build as a live 3D Gantt chart. Each bar is a task; arrows are dependencies; the diamond is the “Prototype complete” milestone. Drag a task to make it slip and watch what happens to the milestone — then learn why some slips hurt and some don't.","id":1179},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"A Gantt chart you never update is useless","text":"Drawing the chart in Week 1 is planning . The marks are in monitoring — comparing planned vs actual every week and annotating the changes. Examiners love the three-column change record.","id":1180},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Change made","text":"What you altered on the plan — e.g. “extended testing by 3 days.”","id":1181},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Reason","text":"Why it was necessary — e.g. “GPS drifted indoors; needed outdoor retests.”","id":1182},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Impact","text":"Effect on the schedule — e.g. “pushed submission rehearsal to Wk 9; documentation task shortened.”","id":1183},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"🔧 Build a change-record entry","text":"Pick what happened on Jade's project and generate the annotation an assessor wants to see.","id":1184},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Project journals & logs","text":"A project journal (often kept in OneNote, a Google Doc or a shared wiki) is a running, dated record of the build. A Gantt chart says when ; the journal says what happened and why .","id":1185},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"What goes in a strong entry","text":"Date · who did what · ideas generated · decisions made and the reasoning · problems hit and how they were solved · modifications to the solution · next steps. Evidence of thinking, not just activity.","id":1186},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Why it earns marks","text":"It captures design decisions the final product can't show, supports delegation (everyone sees the latest state), and is core authentication evidence that the work developed over time.","id":1187},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"🔍 Spot the strong journal entries","text":"Tap each entry. A strong entry is dated , names a decision , and gives a reason . A weak one just says work happened. A Gantt chart is the recipe's timing (“simmer 20 min, then add the rice”). The journal is the cook's notes in the margin (“used less chilli this time — last batch was too hot for the family”). Both matter; only the second explains your choices .","id":1188},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Version control","text":"Version control means deliberately keeping separate dated copies of the work as it develops — so a later mistake never destroys earlier good work, and you can always show how the solution evolved.","id":1189},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"📁 Naming convention","text":"A consistent, sortable pattern: floatmate_v0.3_2026-05-08.py . Include a version number and date; flag the last known-good copy as _working . Never just “final”, “final2”, “realfinal”.","id":1190},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"☁️ Where copies live","text":"Keep copies in more than one place — a network drive, an external drive, or secure cloud storage — so one failure can't wipe the project. Backups and versioning work together. Rollback: a broken change can be undone by returning to the last working version. Collaboration: the team always knows which copy is current, avoiding two people overwriting each other. Authentication: a trail of dated versions evidences genuine, progressive development. Professional teams use tools like Git/GitHub that automate this, but the examinable idea is the principle : keep recoverable, dated copies of work in progress.","id":1191},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Version time-machine","text":"Each glowing slab is a saved version of FloatMate's code, stacked oldest-to-newest. Version v0.4 introduced a bug that broke GPS. Use the controls to roll back to the last working version — exactly what version control buys you.","id":1192},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"How the three tools drive delegation & monitoring","text":"The dot point ends with the purpose: for delegation and monitoring . Here's the full loop on Jade's team.","id":1193},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"The weekly loop","text":"1 · Delegate (Gantt): the chart's parallel, non-dependent tasks are split across the four members by their strengths — Sam (code), Priya (3D/print), Noah (testing), Jade (coordination + journal). 2 · Do & record (Journal + versions): as each person works, they log decisions in the journal and save dated versions of their files. 3 · Monitor (Gantt + journal): every Friday the team compares planned vs actual, annotates slippage (change/reason/impact), and re-checks the critical path. 4 · Recover when needed (versions): a broken build rolls back to the last working copy, and the loop continues.","id":1194},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"The weekly loop","text":"Examiners often ask about coordination via roles and responsibilities . The point: clear ownership (who is responsible for which task) plus shared visibility (everyone can see the plan, journal and current versions) is what turns four individuals into one functioning team.","id":1195},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Confusing a Gantt chart with a project journal","text":"“The Gantt chart records the team's decisions and reasons.” Fix: the Gantt chart schedules tasks/time; the journal records decisions and reasoning.","id":1196},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Defining critical path as “the most important tasks”","text":"It isn't about importance. Fix: it's the longest chain of dependent tasks — the sequence that sets the minimum project duration.","id":1197},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Treating the Gantt chart as a one-off","text":"Drawing it once = planning only. Fix: stress it's a living document — monitored and annotated (change/reason/impact) throughout.","id":1198},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Forgetting milestones have zero duration","text":"A milestone is not a task. Fix: it's a checkpoint marker (◆) — “prototype complete”, “submission” — with no length.","id":1199},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Saying version control = “saving your file”","text":"Too thin for full marks. Fix: it's keeping multiple dated, named copies so you can roll back, compare, collaborate and authenticate.","id":1200},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Listing tools without stating purpose","text":"Naming “Gantt, journal, version control” alone is a low-band answer. Fix: always tie each tool to delegation, monitoring, recovery or authentication.","id":1201},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"The verb in a question tells you how much to write. Tap one.","id":1202},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong short-answers follow Point · Explain · Link : make the point, explain it, link it back to the scenario. Write an answer to the prompt below and watch the meters respond to your keywords. Prompt: Jade's team is building FloatMate over a 10-week term. Explain how a Gantt chart would help them coordinate and monitor the project. (3 marks)","id":1203},{"file":"u2o1-kk09.html","nav":"u2o1-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Documenting progress","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Each question has a deliberately weak answer, a strong answer, and a marking guide. Attempt it first, reveal the models, then self-mark — your scores fill the dock. Total self-marked: 0 / 17 — keep the dock open (bottom-right) to track your running tally.","id":1204},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","text":"You built the thing. It runs. Now the hardest question in the whole project: does it actually work, and is it actually any good? Those are two different questions — and mixing them up is the single most common way to lose marks in this outcome.","id":1205},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"📦 The scenario: GrazeGo","text":"Back in KK06 you met GrazeGo — four Year 11 students (Aiden, Priya, Mason and Lily) building a canteen pre-order app so the lunch rush stops being a 200-person crush. They surveyed users, designed it, and built a working prototype. The app lets a student pick a meal before recess, pay, and collect from a fast lane at lunch. It's built . The demo works on Priya's phone. The team is ready to call it done. This module is about everything that has to happen before they're allowed to.","id":1206},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Testing ≠ Evaluating","text":"VCAA examiners ask this every year, and students throw away marks by treating the two words as synonyms. They are not. They happen at different times , ask different questions , and compare against different things . Does it work? Checking that each part of the solution does what it's supposed to do — that it meets the requirements / specifications . Done during and at the end of development , usually with a testing table . How well does it do the job? Judging how efficient and effective the solution is in real use, against evaluation criteria written back in the design stage. Done after the solution has been in use for a period of time .","id":1207},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Analogy — making a pizza for a friend","text":"Testing is tasting a slice straight out of the oven: is it cooked, is it the right size, did the cheese melt? You're checking it matches the recipe (the requirements). Evaluating is asking your friend a week later: \"Would you order that again? Was it actually good value? Did it fill you up?\" That's judging how well it met their real need — and you can only answer it after they've actually lived with it. The timeline below shows the two living in different places. Drag the scrubber to move through GrazeGo's project.","id":1208},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Analogy — making a pizza for a friend","text":"Notice testing sits at the tail of development , while evaluation only switches on after the app has been used in the canteen for a few weeks.","id":1209},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"The trap","text":"\"The team evaluated the app by checking each button worked.\" — No. Checking buttons work is testing . Evaluation would be judging whether GrazeGo actually reduced the lunch queue and how efficiently students could order. Swap those two words and you've answered the wrong question.","id":1210},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"User testing","text":"You hand the solution to real intended users and watch them use it — without coaching them. Their stumbles, confusion and feedback reveal problems the makers are blind to, because the makers already know how it's \"supposed\" to work.","id":1211},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"How GrazeGo runs a user test","text":"They grab five Year 8 students (real canteen users, not friends from their own class) and give each a realistic task : \"Order a chicken wrap and an apple juice, and pay, before the timer hits 60 seconds.\" Then the team does three things:","id":1212},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"👀 Observe","text":"Watch silently. Where do they hesitate? What do they tap by mistake? Did they finish the task at all?","id":1213},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"🗣️ Think-aloud","text":"Ask users to narrate their thoughts: \"I can't find the pay button…\" This exposes why they're stuck, not just that they are.","id":1214},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"📋 Gather feedback","text":"A short post-task survey or interview: what was confusing, what was easy, would they use it for real?","id":1215},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"What good user testing finds","text":"When GrazeGo tested, 4 of 5 students missed the \"Pay\" button because it was the same grey as the background. The team knew where it was, so they'd never noticed. That's a usability problem only a real user would surface — and it directly improves the solution.","id":1216},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Analogy — the \"push\" door you pull","text":"Ever yank a door that says PUSH? You're not stupid — the door is badly designed. The designer knew how it worked, so they couldn't see the problem. User testing is hiring strangers to walk into your doors so you find out which ones are confusing before you ship them.","id":1217},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Strengths","text":"Reveals real-world usability issues; uncovers needs the team can't see; feedback comes from the actual audience; builds confidence the solution suits its users.","id":1218},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Limitations","text":"Time-consuming to organise; users may be polite rather than honest; a tiny sample may not represent everyone; users spot symptoms but rarely the technical cause .","id":1219},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Expert review","text":"Someone with specialist knowledge — a professional developer, a UX/accessibility expert, an experienced teacher — inspects the solution against best practice and established standards . They catch things ordinary users never could.","id":1220},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Who's an \"expert\" for GrazeGo?","text":"Their teacher invites Mr Tan , a software developer who builds payment apps for a living. He spends 20 minutes with GrazeGo and writes up findings against professional standards: Expert finding Why a user wouldn't catch it Payment data isn't encrypted in transit It \"works\" for the user, but it's a serious security flaw they can't see. No error handling if the canteen runs out of an item Users only hit it occasionally; an expert knows to check edge cases. Buttons too small for accessibility guidelines An expert checks against WCAG standards most users have never heard of.","id":1221},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"The combo","text":"User testing tells you where people struggle . Expert review tells you what's wrong underneath — security, performance, accessibility, code quality. Strong projects use both , because each sees what the other misses.","id":1222},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Strengths","text":"Catches deep technical, security and accessibility issues; fast (no need to recruit a crowd); measures against recognised standards; spots problems before they reach users.","id":1223},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Limitations","text":"Experts can be hard to find or costly; one expert's opinion may be biased; they may miss real-user behaviour because they're not the target audience; advice can be over-technical for a school project.","id":1224},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"The testing table","text":"A testing table is how you prove you tested — methodically, not just \"I clicked around and it seemed fine.\" Each row is one test with a clear expected result and a recorded actual result, so anyone can see exactly what passed, what failed, and what you did about it.","id":1225},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Anatomy of a row","text":"A complete row answers six questions. Click any hidden cell below to reveal the worked GrazeGo example. What is tested Test data / action Expected result Actual result Pass / fail Correction Order total updates when items added Add wrap ($5) + juice ($2) Total shows $7.00 Reject order after cut-off time Order at 11:05 (cut-off 11:00) Show \"ordering closed\" message Block payment with $0 balance Pay with empty account Show \"insufficient funds\"","id":1226},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Why \"expected vs actual\" matters","text":"A test with no expected result isn't a test — it's just poking the app. You only know something failed if you decided beforehand what success looks like. Row 2 above is the gold: a fail , a clear cause , a correction , and (critically) a note to re-test . Examiners reward the full loop.","id":1227},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"What makes test data good?","text":"Strong testing tables don't only test the \"happy path\". They deliberately include boundary and invalid data:","id":1228},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Evaluation: efficiency & effectiveness","text":"Testing is over. The app works. Weeks later, GrazeGo asks the real question: was it worth it? Evaluation judges the solution against the evaluation criteria written in the design stage , and almost always splits into two ideas you must keep separate. Does it do the job well? How completely and accurately it meets the user's need. Measures: completeness, accuracy, readability, usability, accessibility, clarity, error-tolerance, relevance. Does it do it with little waste? How well it uses time, cost and effort. Measures: speed, time to complete a task, processing/data cost, money saved, labour saved.","id":1229},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"The classic mix-up: effective ≠ efficient","text":"A solution can be effective but not efficient (GrazeGo cuts the queue beautifully, but the app takes 40 seconds to load each order). Or efficient but not effective (it's lightning fast, but students still queue because only 10% bothered to use it). You must judge them separately . Plot GrazeGo on the map below. Drag the two sliders to set how effective and how efficient it turned out — the marker moves into a quadrant and tells the team what to do next.","id":1230},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Timing rule of thumb","text":"If the question says \"after the app had been used for three weeks…\" it's asking you to evaluate . If it says \"check that the order total calculates correctly…\" it's asking you to test . The verb the question uses tells you which world you're in.","id":1231},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Sort it yourself","text":"Drag each activity into the right bucket. Is it a testing activity, or an evaluating activity? Get them all green to prove you've nailed the distinction.","id":1232},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Command words","text":"The verb in an exam question tells you exactly how much to write. Tap each card to see what examiners want — and how it links to this topic.","id":1233},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Six exam traps","text":"These are the mistakes that quietly cost marks every year. Tap to see the fix. They are assessed as different concepts . Testing = checking against requirements (does it work). Evaluating = judging efficiency & effectiveness against criteria (how well, after use). Without a predicted result, there's no way to say a test passed or failed — so it isn't really a test. Testing only valid, typical data misses where solutions actually break. \"It works really fast\" is efficiency ; \"it solves the user's problem fully\" is effectiveness . They're separate.","id":1234},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"Six exam traps","text":"Vague claims earn nothing. Examiners want a technique named (user testing / expert review) and how it was carried out . You can't evaluate fairly against criteria you invent afterwards. The evaluation criteria are written in the design stage , before development.","id":1235},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"High-scoring extended answers follow Point → Evidence → Link . Write a response to the prompt below and watch the live meters detect whether you've hit all three — plus the key terms examiners reward. Prompt (4 marks): The GrazeGo team is deciding how to check their app before launch. Recommend a combination of user testing and expert review , and justify why using both is better than using one alone.","id":1236},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Five questions in the real VCAA style. Try each on paper first, then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide . Self-mark to fill your score ring. Distinguish between testing and evaluating an innovative solution. 1 mark — testing = checks it works / against requirements (during development). 1 mark — evaluating = judges efficiency & effectiveness / against criteria (after use). Describe how the GrazeGo team could carry out user testing on their canteen pre-order app. 1 mark — uses real/intended users given a realistic task.","id":1237},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 mark — observe / think-aloud during the task. 1 mark — collect feedback and use it to improve the solution. Compare user testing with expert review as techniques for testing an innovative solution. Refer to one strength of each. 1 mark — a genuine similarity (both find problems / improve the solution). 1 mark — user testing described (real users, tasks). 1 mark — expert review described (specialist, standards). 1 mark — a clear strength stated for each. GrazeGo must stop orders after the 11:00 am cut-off. Construct one row of a testing table to test this, including a suitable piece of test data , the expected result , and explain why your chosen test data is appropriate.","id":1238},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"What is tested Test data Expected Pass/Fail Orders rejected after cut-off Submit order at 11:01 am \"Ordering closed\" message; no order created test it 1 mark — relevant \"what is tested\" tied to the cut-off rule. 1 mark — appropriate invalid/boundary test data (a time after 11:00). 1 mark — clear expected result (rejected / message shown). 1 mark — justification that the data is invalid/boundary, testing the rule not the happy path. After three weeks of real use, the GrazeGo team wants to evaluate their app. Explain how they could evaluate its efficiency and effectiveness , and justify why evaluation criteria set during the design stage are essential to a fair evaluation.","id":1239},{"file":"u2o1-kk10.html","nav":"u2o1-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Testing & evaluating an innovative solution","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1–2 marks — effectiveness explained with a relevant measure (queue reduced / task completion / accuracy). 1–2 marks — efficiency explained with a relevant measure (time per order / staff time / cost). 1 mark — criteria were set in the design stage (before development). 1 mark — justification: pre-set criteria make the evaluation fair/objective and prevent moving the goalposts.","id":1240},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Legislation & frameworks","text":"Every great idea has to survive contact with the law. This module is about the five instruments that shape how emerging technology can be built, sold and used in Australia — and how to write about them like an examiner wants. Jade and her Year 11 team built FloatMate — a waterproof wristband and phone app that watches a swimmer's heart rate and movement and alerts a guardian if it thinks the swimmer is in distress. It uses a small AI model to tell \"thrashing in trouble\" apart from \"having fun.\" Their council wants to pilot FloatMate at the local public pool . Suddenly FloatMate isn't a school project — it's a product handling other people's health data. Five different rulebooks now apply. Let's meet them.","id":1241},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Rules don't kill innovation — they make it trustable","text":"It's tempting to think of legislation as a handbrake on creativity. The opposite is closer to the truth: rules are what let a clever prototype become something people will actually trust with their data, their health and their kids.","id":1242},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The road-rules analogy","text":"Speed limits, lane markings and traffic lights don't exist to stop you driving — they're the reason you're willing to drive at all. Without them, nobody would share the road. Tech legislation is the same: it's the shared \"road rules\" that make it safe for strangers to use FloatMate. Break them and you don't just get a fine — people stop trusting the whole product. For VCAA, KK11 sits in the Analysis and Evaluation stages of the problem-solving methodology. When you analyse a problem you must identify which laws constrain the solution;","id":1243},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The road-rules analogy","text":"when you evaluate, you judge whether the solution actually meets its legal obligations. So legislation is both a constraint on your design and a criterion you're judged against.","id":1244},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Two are hard law","text":"The Copyright Act 1968 and the privacy Acts create legal obligations . Break them and there are real consequences.","id":1245},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"One is a compass","text":"The AI Ethics Principles are voluntary — guidance, not law. They shape good practice and are becoming the blueprint for future regulation.","id":1246},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Jurisdiction matters","text":"Some Acts are federal (all of Australia); others are Victorian (this state only). Knowing which is which earns marks.","id":1247},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The five instruments, stacked","text":"FloatMate's data has to pass through five checkpoints before it can flow safely from a swimmer's wrist to a guardian's phone. Think of them as a compliance stack — a packet of data dropping through five layers, each asking a different question. Drag the slider to send a packet through, and click any layer to see what it checks.","id":1248},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The Compliance Stack","text":"A FloatMate data packet (heart-rate + distress alert) falls through all five instruments. Each layer guards a different concern.","id":1249},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"AI Ethics Principles","text":"Eight voluntary principles for designing, building and using AI responsibly. Not enforceable, but the moral baseline for FloatMate's distress-detection model.","id":1250},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Privacy Act 1988","text":"13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) governing how personal information is collected, used, stored and disclosed across Australia.","id":1251},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Privacy & Data Protection Act 2014","text":"10 Information Privacy Principles (IPPs) for the Victorian public sector — which the council pool is. Plus rules for protective data security.","id":1252},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Health Records Act 2001","text":"11 Health Privacy Principles (HPPs) covering health information in Victoria — exactly what heart-rate and distress data is. Voluntary vs legal and federal vs Victorian . The AI Ethics Principles are the only voluntary one — calling them \"a law\" loses marks. Copyright and Privacy Acts are federal ; the PDP Act and Health Records Act are Victorian . Get the jurisdiction right and you've already banked a mark.","id":1253},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Australia's AI Ethics Principles","text":"Eight voluntary principles released by the Australian Government in 2019 to guide the responsible design, development and use of AI. They're a compass , not a cage — but they're rapidly becoming the template for future AI law. FloatMate's distress detector is AI — a model trained to classify \"in trouble\" vs \"fine.\" That makes these principles directly relevant. Click any node on the wheel to see how it applies to FloatMate.","id":1254},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The Principle Wheel","text":"Eight principles orbiting FloatMate's AI core. Click a node — or use the buttons — to see the principle and a FloatMate example. Three principles trip students up most. Transparency & explainability = people should know AI is involved and roughly how it decides. Contestability = if AI's decision affects you, you can challenge it. Accountability = a real human is responsible for the outcome. If FloatMate falsely flags a child as drowning and clears the pool, the family deserves to know why (transparency), to dispute it (contestability), and someone at FloatMate must own it (accountability).","id":1255},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth)","text":"Protects the rights of people who create original works — text, images, music, video, and software code — by giving the creator control over how their work is copied, shared and adapted. Protection is automatic the moment a work is created; there's no need to register it. FloatMate's team wants the app to feel polished: a water-safety video , some poster graphics , calming background music , and a set of icons . Every one of those is somebody's copyright. You can't just download and embed them.","id":1256},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"What it protects","text":"Original literary, artistic, musical and dramatic works, plus film, sound recordings and computer programs. FloatMate's own code and logo are protected too.","id":1257},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Fair dealing exceptions","text":"Limited free uses — including research or study , criticism/review, and news reporting. A school assignment may qualify; a commercial pilot at a public pool generally does not .","id":1258},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Creative Commons","text":"Creators can pre-license work under CC. But restrictions still apply — e.g. attribution required, or NonCommercial (NC) which blocks the paid pilot.","id":1259},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"AI & copyright","text":"Generating content from copyrighted material, or training on it without permission, raises live copyright questions. Citing AI use (APA) is now expected in student work.","id":1260},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"The \"borrowed song\" trap","text":"Putting a chart song under FloatMate's promo clip feels harmless — but it's exactly what the Act exists to stop. The artist owns that recording. FloatMate's safe options: license it, commission original music, or use a clearly-licensed Creative Commons track that allows commercial use and credit the creator.","id":1261},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth)","text":"The national law governing how personal information is handled. It contains the 13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) covering the whole life-cycle of data: collection, use, storage, accuracy, access and disclosure. Personal information is anything that identifies a person or could reasonably identify them — names, emergency contacts, swim logs tied to an account, even a device ID. FloatMate collects loads of it.","id":1262},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 2 · Anonymity","text":"Where practical, individuals must be able to deal with you anonymously or with a pseudonym. Could a casual swimmer use FloatMate without an account?","id":1263},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 3 · Collection","text":"Only collect personal information you actually need for your function. FloatMate doesn't need a swimmer's home address to detect distress.","id":1264},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 5 · Notification","text":"Tell people what you're collecting and why, at the time you collect it — a clear privacy notice, not buried fine print.","id":1265},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 6 · Use & disclosure","text":"Only use information for the primary purpose it was collected for. Distress data collected for safety can't be quietly sold to an insurer.","id":1266},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 11 · Security","text":"Take reasonable steps to protect information from misuse, loss and unauthorised access — encryption , access controls, secure servers.","id":1267},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"APP 12 · Access","text":"Give individuals access to the personal information you hold about them when they ask. Bolted onto the Privacy Act, the NDB scheme means that if FloatMate suffers a serious data breach likely to cause harm, it must notify both the affected individuals and the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC) . The notice must describe the breach, the kinds of information involved, and the steps people should take to protect themselves. \"Hope nobody notices\" is not a strategy — it's a second offence.","id":1268},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Privacy and Data Protection Act 2014 (Vic)","text":"Victoria's own privacy law for the Victorian public sector — state government departments, agencies, local councils and the organisations that work for them. It contains the 10 Information Privacy Principles (IPPs) , which closely mirror the federal APPs, plus a protective data security framework.","id":1269},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Why FloatMate suddenly cares","text":"As a school project, FloatMate was only really touched by the federal Privacy Act. But the moment the council runs the pilot at its public pool, the council is a Victorian public-sector body — so the PDP Act and its IPPs now govern how that swimmer data is handled. Same data, extra rulebook, because of who is operating it.","id":1270},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Information Privacy Principles","text":"Ten IPPs covering collection, use, disclosure, data quality, security, access and identifiers — Victoria's version of the APPs for public-sector data.","id":1271},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Protective Data Security","text":"The Act sets a security framework (the VPDSF) requiring public bodies to manage information-security risk to the data they hold. Privacy Act 1988 is federal → APPs → applies to Commonwealth agencies and most businesses. PDP Act 2014 is Victorian → IPPs → applies to the Victorian public sector. They rhyme on purpose, but mixing up \"APP\" and \"IPP\", or \"federal\" and \"Victorian\", is a classic mark-loser.","id":1272},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Health Records Act 2001 (Vic)","text":"Victoria's law specifically for health information — held by anyone in Victoria, public or private. It contains the 11 Health Privacy Principles (HPPs) . Health data gets its own Act because it's some of the most sensitive information about a person. FloatMate's bread and butter — heart rate , movement patterns, and logged distress events — is health information. That pulls the Health Records Act squarely into play, on top of the general privacy laws.","id":1273},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Purpose limitation","text":"Collect health information only for the stated purpose, and don't use it for anything else unless the person separately consents. Safety monitoring ≠ marketing.","id":1274},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Security & retention","text":"Keep health information secure, accurate and only as long as needed. Heart-rate logs shouldn't live on a server forever.","id":1275},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Right of access","text":"Individuals can access and seek correction of their own health records — a swimmer can ask to see their distress log.","id":1276},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Careful disclosure","text":"Strict limits on sharing health information with third parties. Sending a distress alert to a nominated guardian is fine; selling patterns to an insurer is not. If the data is health information in Victoria → Health Records Act 2001 . If it's general personal information held by a business or federal agency → Privacy Act 1988 . If a Victorian public-sector body holds general personal information → PDP Act 2014 . FloatMate at the council pool can trigger all three at once — and saying so is exactly the kind of detail that scores top marks.","id":1277},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Three sets of principles, one shared spine","text":"The APPs (federal), IPPs (Victorian public sector) and HPPs (Victorian health) deliberately echo each other. Once you see the shared concerns — collect fairly, use for the right purpose, keep it secure, allow access — you don't have to memorise three lists. You memorise one spine and three jurisdictions. Shared concern Privacy Act 1988 APP PDP Act 2014 IPP Health Records Act 2001 HPP Collect only what's needed, fairly APP 3 — Collection IPP 1 — Collection HPP 1 — Collection Tell people what & why APP 5 — Notification IPP 1.3 — Notice HPP 1.4 — Notice Use only for the primary purpose APP 6 — Use & disclosure IPP 2 — Use & disclosure HPP 2 — Use & disclosure Keep it accurate APP 10 — Quality IPP 3 — Data quality HPP 3 — Data quality Keep it secure APP 11 — Security IPP 4 — Data security HPP 4 — Data security Let people see their data APP 12 — Access IPP 6 — Access & correction HPP 6 — Access & correction Principle numbers are indicative groupings to show the parallel structure — the exam rewards you for naming the right Act and the right concern , not for reciting clause numbers.","id":1278},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Three sets of principles, one shared spine","text":"Privacy Act 1988 : federal · applies across Australia · agencies & businesses. PDP Act 2014 : Victorian · applies to the Victorian public sector. Health Records Act 2001 : Victorian · applies to anyone handling health information in Victoria. Same idea of \"protect the individual,\" three different reaches.","id":1279},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Which instrument applies?","text":"Each card below is a FloatMate situation. Click a card, then drop it into the instrument you think governs it. Some situations trigger more than one — pick the most specific one. You'll get instant feedback and a one-line reason.","id":1280},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Situation sorter","text":"Tap a situation to select it, then tap the instrument bin it belongs in.","id":1281},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Command words for legislation questions","text":"Legislation questions live and die on the command word. \"Identify\" wants a name; \"explain\" wants the why and the so-what . Matching your depth to the verb (and the marks) is half the battle. State the relevant Act or principle. No explanation needed. \"The Health Records Act 2001.\" Name it and say what it does or requires, in context. Two ideas. Name, describe, and link to the scenario — why it applies and the consequence if breached. Make a judgement and defend it with legislation as evidence. Weigh the obligation against the design choice.","id":1282},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Command words for legislation questions","text":"A 1-mark \"identify\" answered with a paragraph wastes time; a 4-mark \"explain\" answered with three words throws away marks. Read the number in the margin before you write.","id":1283},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Six exam traps that cost real marks","text":"These are the slips examiners report year after year. Click each to see the fix. The principles are voluntary guidance , not legislation. Writing \"FloatMate broke the AI Ethics law\" is wrong and loses the mark. Say FloatMate \"should follow\" or \"is guided by\" the AI Ethics Principles. Contrast with the Acts, which create binding obligations. Saying the Health Records Act is federal, or the Privacy Act is Victorian, signals you don't know the jurisdictions. Federal: Copyright Act 1968, Privacy Act 1988. Victorian: PDP Act 2014, Health Records Act 2001.","id":1284},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Six exam traps that cost real marks","text":"Tag each Act with (Cwlth) or (Vic). Heart-rate and distress logs are health information ; an email address is general personal information . They invoke different Acts. Classify the data first. Health → Health Records Act. General personal info → Privacy Act (or PDP Act if a public body holds it). \"The Privacy Act applies\" with no connection to FloatMate is a generic answer. Examiner reports flag a lack of specific detail every year. Always tie it back: \"...so FloatMate must encrypt the swim logs it stores on its server (APP 11).\" Writing \"they'll go to jail\" for a privacy breach is the exact error VCAA's report calls out.","id":1285},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Six exam traps that cost real marks","text":"Most breaches lead to investigation, orders and penalties — not prison. Talk about realistic consequences: OAIC investigation, mandatory breach notification, fines, reputational damage and loss of user trust. Students remember privacy but forget that the safety video, music and posters FloatMate adds are someone else's copyright . Whenever a solution includes media , ask: who made it, and do we have permission or a licence (including Creative Commons terms)?","id":1286},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Top legislation answers follow a simple shape: Point (name the Act/principle) → Evidence (what it requires, tied to the scenario) → Link (the consequence or judgement). Write a response below and watch the three bars respond to your keywords in real time.","id":1287},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total, in rising difficulty. Try each one cold, then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer, and the marking guide. Mark yourself honestly — the dial bottom-right tracks your total. FloatMate collects swimmers' heart-rate and distress data. Identify two pieces of legislation that govern how this data must be handled, and state the jurisdiction (federal or Victorian) of each. FloatMate wants to add a popular chart song to its promotional video. Describe how the Copyright Act 1968 applies, and outline one lawful way the team could include music.","id":1288},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"When the local council runs the FloatMate pilot at its public pool, an extra piece of legislation applies that did not apply to the school prototype. Explain which Act this is, why it now applies, and one obligation it places on the council. FloatMate's AI sometimes falsely flags a strong swimmer as \"in distress,\" clearing the pool and embarrassing them. Using two of Australia's AI Ethics Principles, explain how FloatMate should respond to this problem. FloatMate proposes selling anonymised \"distress pattern\" insights to a health-insurance company to fund the app. Evaluate this proposal with reference to at least two pieces of legislation and the AI Ethics Principles. Make a clear recommendation.","id":1289},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"AI Ethics Principles","text":"Voluntary · national 8 principles (wellbeing, human-centred, fairness, privacy & security, reliability & safety, transparency, contestability, accountability) Guidance for responsible AI","id":1290},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Copyright Act 1968 (Cwlth)","text":"Federal · hard law Protects original works automatically Fair dealing & Creative Commons exceptions","id":1291},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth)","text":"Federal · 13 APPs Personal information life-cycle Notifiable Data Breaches scheme","id":1292},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"PDP Act 2014 (Vic)","text":"Victorian · 10 IPPs Victorian public sector Protective data security","id":1293},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Health Records Act 2001 (Vic)","text":"Victorian · 11 HPPs Health information in Victoria Purpose limit + access rights","id":1294},{"file":"u2o1-kk11.html","nav":"u2o1-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Legislation & frameworks","head":"Decision shortcut","text":"Health data in Vic → Health Records Act Vic public body → PDP Act Business / federal → Privacy Act Someone's creative work → Copyright AI behaviour → AI Principles","id":1295},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"The ethics of emerging technology","text":"When new tech can do something, should it? This dot point is about the line between can and should — through cyber-security threats, biometric data, and the jobs machines replace. The study design lists this key knowledge as: “ethical issues arising from emerging technologies, including cyber security threats, the collection and storage of biometric data, and job displacement.” The word including means all three are directly examinable — you must be able to discuss each one.","id":1296},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"PulsePoint — the “frictionless” gym","text":"PulsePoint is a fictional 24/7 gym chain opening near your school. Their pitch is “zero-friction fitness”: no membership cards, no front desk, no queues. You walk up, a camera scans your face to unlock the door, a fingerprint opens your locker, and an AI coach app writes your workout. To make it cheap, PulsePoint has no reception staff and only one roaming trainer per three sites. It’s convenient, modern, and almost everything about it is legal . But three quiet questions follow you onto the gym floor — and they’re the exact three this dot point examines:","id":1297},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Cyber-security threats","text":"PulsePoint now holds a database of everyone’s face. What happens when — not if — it gets breached?","id":1298},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Biometric data","text":"Your face and fingerprint are you . You can change a password — you can’t change your face.","id":1299},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Job displacement","text":"The receptionist who used to greet you is gone. Where did that job go — and whose problem is that? Keep PulsePoint in mind. Every concept below maps back to it, and so do the exam answers at the end.","id":1300},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"02 What is an “ethical” issue?","text":"An emerging technology is one that is new, developing, or being applied in new ways — think AI, facial recognition, drones, wearables, the Internet of Things. Because they’re new, the rules and norms around them often haven’t caught up. That gap is where ethical issues live. A situation that raises questions of right and wrong — what a person or organisation should do — beyond what the law strictly requires . Ethics asks whether an action is fair, honest, and respectful of others, even when no law is broken.","id":1301},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"The line examiners love: legal vs ethical","text":"This is the single most-tested idea in the whole dot point. They are not the same thing :","id":1302},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"03 Strand A — Cyber-security threats","text":"Every emerging technology that collects data also creates a target . The more systems connect (cloud, apps, IoT sensors, smart locks), the bigger the attack surface — the number of ways in for an attacker. The ethical question isn’t “how do firewalls work?” (that’s the Cyber Security outcome). It’s: when an organisation collects data, what do they owe the people it belongs to? When PulsePoint collects your data, it takes on a moral responsibility to protect it. A weak password policy or an un-patched server isn’t just a technical slip — it’s a breach of the trust users placed in the organisation.","id":1303},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"04 Strand B — Biometric data","text":"Biometric data is information about your body or behaviour used to identify you. It splits into two kinds:","id":1304},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Why biometrics are different from a password","text":"This is the heart of the strand, and the best 3-mark answer in any exam. A password is a secret you choose . A biometric is a permanent fact about your body . That one difference changes everything:","id":1305},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"The ethical issues with collecting & storing biometrics","text":"Did the person really agree? It’s forever. Collected for X, used for Y. It’s not perfect. Always watching. Where does it live?","id":1306},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"05 Strand C — Job displacement","text":"Job displacement happens when emerging technology — automation, robotics, AI — takes over tasks that people used to be paid to do. PulsePoint’s missing receptionist is the everyday face of it; supermarket self-checkouts, automated warehouses, and AI customer-service bots are others. Displacement = the job disappears. Deskilling = the job remains but needs less skill (so it’s lower-paid and the skill is lost). Reskilling / upskilling = workers learn new skills to move into the jobs technology creates.","id":1307},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"It’s a balance, not a verdict","text":"Top-band answers refuse the lazy “robots = bad” take. Technology displaces some jobs and creates others . The ethical question is about who wins, who loses, and who is responsible for the people left behind. Move the automation slider and watch the trade-off:","id":1308},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"06 How to analyse any ethical issue","text":"Examiners don’t want a rant. They want a structured analysis . Use this 4-step frame for every “discuss / analyse the ethical issues” question — it works for all three strands and any new tech they invent on the day.","id":1309},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Decode the command word first","text":"The verb tells you how much to write and what shape your answer takes. Tap a command word to see exactly what the examiner expects.","id":1310},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"The P·E·L structure for ethics answers","text":"For 3+ mark ethics questions, build each idea as Point → Explain → Link . Make a point (name the ethical issue), explain the benefit and the harm, then link back to the scenario and the people in it. Write an answer below and the trainer checks whether you hit the moves examiners reward.","id":1311},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Six traps that cost marks","text":"Quoting an Act for an ethics question. Only listing harms. “It’s bad for society.” Generic textbook answer. Missing the permanence point. Lists points, never decides.","id":1312},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"08 Practice exam questions","text":"Five VCAA-style questions — 17 marks total . Have a go on paper first, then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer, and the marking guide. Use the self-mark buttons to track your score in the dock.","id":1313},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Nine things to remember","text":"The dot point: ethical issues of emerging tech — cyber threats, biometric data, job displacement. All three examinable. Ethical ≠ legal. Legal = what you can do; ethical = what you should do. The classic trap. Cyber threats: collecting data creates a duty of care ; AI, deepfakes and IoT widen the attack surface. Biometrics = physiological or behavioural traits used to identify you. The crux: a password can be reset, a biometric cannot — breaches are permanent. Biometric ethics: consent, permanence, function creep, accuracy/bias, surveillance, storage. Job displacement ≠ automatically bad — it’s about how the transition is managed.","id":1314},{"file":"u2o1-kk12.html","nav":"u2o1-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of emerging technology","head":"Nine things to remember","text":"Always two-sided: pair a benefit with a harm, name real stakeholders, then conclude. Structure: Name the issue → stakeholders → weigh perspectives → reasoned position.","id":1315},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","text":"AI doesn't follow rules a person wrote line-by-line — it learns patterns from oceans of data, then generates something new. That power is exactly what makes its ethics so slippery. This module unpacks the three issues VCAA wants you to argue about. Four Year 11 students — Priya, Dev, Mara and Sam — build MuseBot for their Unit 2 innovative-solution project: a free AI assistant for Brookvale Secondary that drafts event posters, summarises class notes and answers homework questions. It's wrapped around a large generative AI model. Launch week, the whole school is hooked.","id":1316},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","text":"Then three things happen in three days. Each one is a different ethical fault line — and each one is exactly what the study design wants you to be able to analyse.","id":1317},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The poster problem","text":"Ask MuseBot to \"draw a school captain\" and it keeps drawing the same kind of student. Ask for health tips and it gives advice that could hurt someone.","id":1318},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The fake email","text":"A student talks MuseBot into writing a flawless email pretending to be the Principal, asking staff to \"confirm your login.\"","id":1319},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The borrowed style","text":"A poster MuseBot generated is unmistakably in a living illustrator's style — and a \"summary\" turns out to be lifted almost word-for-word from a textbook. Same tool. Three different ethical problems. Keep Priya's team in mind — every concept below maps onto something that happened to MuseBot.","id":1320},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"What we actually mean by \"ethics of AI\"","text":"Ordinary software is deterministic : a programmer writes the rules, so if it behaves badly you can usually point to the line that did it. Generative AI is different. It is trained , not hand-coded — it absorbs statistical patterns from enormous datasets and then produces fresh text, images, audio or code that no one wrote directly. That creates a gap between what the makers intended and what the system actually does . Ethics of AI is the study of the moral questions that live in that gap: who could be harmed, who is responsible, and what we owe the people whose data trained the model and the people who use its output.","id":1321},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"What we actually mean by \"ethics of AI\"","text":"VCAA narrows \"ethics of AI\" to three examinable issues . Memorise them as a set — most questions ask you to pick one and reason about it for a specific scenario:","id":1322},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Biased or harmful content","text":"AI output that is discriminatory, unsafe, false or distressing — because of what it learned or how it's used.","id":1323},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Usable for cyber attacks","text":"AI that lowers the skill needed to write phishing, malware , scams or deepfakes — arming people who couldn't before.","id":1324},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"From copyright material","text":"AI trained on protected works that then reproduces or imitates them, raising ownership and consent questions. Think of a generative model as an apprentice who learned by copying millions of examples in a workshop. They become brilliantly skilled — but they also pick up the workshop's bad habits (bias), they'll happily forge a document if you ask the right way (cyber misuse), and their \"original\" work is stitched from everything they ever studied, including pieces they had no permission to copy (copyright). The apprentice isn't evil. The ethics live in how they were trained and how we let them be used.","id":1325},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Biased or harmful content","text":"A model only knows the world its training data showed it. If that data over-represents one group, era or viewpoint, the model treats that as \"normal\" — and quietly bakes the imbalance into everything it makes. This is algorithmic bias : unfair, systematic skew in a system's outputs that traces back to its data or design, not to a single typo. Two flavours show up in the exam: Bias doesn't just pass through a model — it can get amplified . If 60% of \"doctor\" photos in the data show one group, the model often outputs that group far more than 60% of the time, because it learns to play the safest bet. Mildly skewed data in, strongly skewed world out. Try it below.","id":1326},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Why it matters ethically","text":"Biased and harmful output isn't just embarrassing — it can entrench discrimination at scale (a screening tool that quietly down-ranks certain names), spread unsafe information faster than any human could, or destroy a real person's reputation through a deepfake. Because AI runs at scale, a single skewed pattern can touch millions of decisions. That's why Australia's AI Ethics Principles put fairness , reliability & safety , and human wellbeing right at the front.","id":1327},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Content usable for cyber attacks","text":"Generative AI is a brilliant writer, coder and impersonator. Those same talents make it a force-multiplier for attackers. The core ethical concern is lowered barriers : tasks that once needed real skill — fluent phishing in perfect English, working malware, a cloned voice — are now a well-phrased request away.","id":1328},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Phishing & social engineering","text":"Flawless, personalised scam emails and texts — like MuseBot's fake \"Principal\" message — at massive volume.","id":1329},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Malicious code","text":"Draft malware, exploit scripts or password-cracking helpers for someone who couldn't write them alone.","id":1330},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Deepfakes & voice clones","text":"Impersonate a real person in audio or video to authorise a transfer or trick a victim. Responsible AI products fit guardrails — filters and refusals that block obvious misuse. The catch is the jailbreak (or prompt injection ): wrapping a banned request in a story, role-play or \"for a security class\" framing so the filter waves it through. The MuseBot team learned this the hard way when a student dressed up \"write a phishing email\" as \"write an example email for our cyber-safety poster.\" Capability (the AI can write a phishing email) is not the same as a cyber attack (someone sends it to steal logins).","id":1331},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Deepfakes & voice clones","text":"In an answer, name the AI capability and the attack it enables — \"MuseBot can generate convincing, error-free phishing emails, which lets an attacker run a credential-harvesting scam against staff at a scale they couldn't manage by hand.\"","id":1332},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Generating content from copyright material","text":"To learn, generative models are fed staggering amounts of human work — books, art, articles, music, code — much of it protected by copyright and used without the creator's permission or payment . The output can then reproduce a source almost verbatim, or imitate a living artist's style so closely it competes with them. Three ethical knots: Copyright is the creator's automatic legal right to control copying of their original work (in Australia, the Copyright Act 1968 ). A derivative work builds on an existing work. Plagiarism is passing off someone's work as your own — an ethical/academic breach that can happen even when no copyright is broken. A strong answer keeps \"illegal\" and \"unethical\" separate: AI imitation can be unethical and harmful to creators even where the legal position is murky.","id":1333},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"So who is actually responsible?","text":"\"The AI did it\" is never a complete answer — and examiners pounce on students who stop there. Responsibility is shared along a chain, and a top-band answer names where it sits: When a question says \"evaluate\" or \"discuss,\" brace your judgement against named principles — it instantly lifts your response. Australia's 8 voluntary AI Ethics Principles include: Fairness (no unfair discrimination) · Reliability & safety (works as intended without harm) · Transparency & explainability (people know AI is involved and roughly how) · Privacy protection & security · Contestability (you can challenge an AI decision) · Accountability (a human is answerable) · Human-centred values · Human, societal & environmental wellbeing .","id":1334},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"So who is actually responsible?","text":"For KK13, fairness , safety , transparency and accountability do most of the work. MuseBot must not discriminate — it should produce equitable results across genders, backgrounds and accents. It must work as intended without causing harm — no unsafe advice, no dangerous output. Users should know they're dealing with AI and roughly how it reached an output. Priya's team and the school stay answerable for what MuseBot does — responsibility can't be offloaded to 'the algorithm'. A student affected by an unfair AI decision must be able to challenge it and reach a human. Data students feed MuseBot must be protected, and the tool must resist misuse for attacks.","id":1335},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Key terms — tap to flip","text":"These are the words that turn a vague answer into a precise one. If you can deploy them correctly, you're writing at a band-5+ level. A systematic, unfair skew in an AI system's outputs that traces back to its training data or design — not a one-off error. The large body of examples a model learns patterns from. Its gaps and imbalances become the model's blind spots. AI that produces new content — text, images, audio, code — by predicting likely patterns, rather than retrieving a fixed answer. When a model states something false or invented with total confidence, because it predicts plausible-sounding text, not verified fact.","id":1336},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Key terms — tap to flip","text":"Synthetic media — image, audio or video — that convincingly impersonates a real person, often used to deceive or harm. A built-in filter or refusal that stops a model producing disallowed content, such as malware or hate speech. A prompt crafted to slip past guardrails — disguising a banned request as fiction, role-play or 'an example'. Also called prompt injection. A creator's automatic legal right (Copyright Act 1968) to control copying of their original work. A new work built on an existing one. AI output trained on protected works can blur into derivative territory. The principle that a human or organisation — not 'the AI' — is answerable for an AI system's outcomes.","id":1337},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Read the command word, then aim your answer","text":"Half of all lost marks in this topic come from answering the wrong question — describing when you were asked to evaluate, or listing when you were asked to justify. Decode the verb first. Name it. A word or short phrase — no explanation needed. Say what it is and add detail or features. Still no judgement. Show how or why — give the cause-and-effect, not just the what. Weigh more than one side or angle; show the tensions before any conclusion. Make a judgement and back it with reasons — strengths vs limitations, then a verdict.","id":1338},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"Read the command word, then aim your answer","text":"Give the reasons a choice is the right one; defend it against the alternative. Propose a course of action and say why it suits this specific situation. Draw out similarities and differences explicitly — use 'whereas', 'both', 'unlike'.","id":1339},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"The P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Most ethics answers are graded on structure as much as content. Use P·E·L : make a Point (name the issue), give Evidence (tie it to the scenario), then Link back to impact, a principle or a who's-responsible judgement. Write a response below — the trainer checks for all three moves.","id":1340},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"Attempt each in your head or on paper first. Then reveal the weak answer (to see the trap), the strong answer (to see the standard), and the marking guide. Self-mark honestly — your score builds in the dock. Definition: Algorithmic bias is a systematic, unfair skew in an AI system's outputs that comes from imbalances in its training data or design. Example: If MuseBot's image data shows mostly one gender as “leaders,” it will keep drawing school captains as that gender — an unfair pattern produced by the data, not a random error.","id":1341},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"1 mark — a correct definition referencing systematic/unfair skew from data or design. 1 mark — a relevant MuseBot example that is genuinely bias (a skewed pattern), not just an error or a different issue. MuseBot can generate fluent, error-free, personalised text on demand — a capability attackers exploit. This lets someone produce a convincing phishing email impersonating the Principal far faster and more believably than they could alone, enabling a credential-harvesting attack against staff. Because the AI lowers the skill and time needed, attacks can be run at scale, and guardrails can be bypassed with a jailbreak (e.g.","id":1342},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"framing it as “an example for a poster”). The same ability extends to drafting malicious scripts or cloning a voice for impersonation. 1 mark — identifies a relevant AI capability (e.g. generating fluent/personalised text or code). 1 mark — links it to a specific attack (phishing / malware / impersonation). 1 mark — explains the mechanism of harm: lowered barrier, scale, or believability. 1 mark — depth: jailbreak/guardrail bypass, or a second attack vector. MuseBot learns from protected works, so its output can imitate a creator's style closely enough to compete with them.","id":1343},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"Consent: the illustrator likely never agreed to their work training the model — an ethical breach even where copying a style isn't clearly illegal. Compensation & fairness: the creator earns nothing while the tool profits from their visual language, breaching the fairness principle. Ownership is unsettled: it's unclear whether the student, the team or the original artists hold rights to the output — so a careful answer separates what is unethical from what is definitely illegal. 1 mark — recognises training on / imitation of protected creative work. 1 mark — raises consent OR compensation for the original creator.","id":1344},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"1 mark — addresses ownership/rights uncertainty of AI output. 1 mark — discusses more than one angle and distinguishes legal vs ethical. The team chose to release MuseBot to students, so under accountability they — not “the AI” — are answerable for foreseeable harm. Shipping a health feature without safety filtering breaches reliability & safety : the tool caused harm rather than working safely as intended. There is also a transparency failure if students weren't warned the advice was AI-generated and possibly wrong. Judgement: their responsibility is high — they had a duty to test for harmful output, add guardrails and disclaimers, and provide a human to contest results;","id":1345},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"the student's choice reduces but does not remove that duty. A balanced answer notes the model maker shares responsibility for the underlying training, but the deployers remain primarily accountable. 1 mark — identifies the team's responsibility as developers/deployers. 1 mark each — correctly applies TWO named AI Ethics Principles to the scenario (max 2). 1 mark — reaches a clear, reasoned judgement about the level of responsibility. 1 mark — balance: acknowledges shared responsibility (model maker / user) without excusing the team. Strategy 1 — Strengthen guardrails + human review:","id":1346},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"add filters that block phishing/malware and unsafe health output, plus human checking of risky requests. Justification: directly targets the cyber-misuse and harmful-content issues and supports reliability & safety. Strategy 2 — Source attribution + bias testing: require MuseBot to cite sources and avoid imitating named living artists, and test outputs across groups before release. Justification: tackles copyright (consent/credit) and fairness, reducing discrimination and creator harm. Add transparency: label outputs as AI-generated with a “may be wrong” warning, so users can contest and verify — covering transparency and contestability. 1 mark each — TWO clearly described, relevant strategies (max 2).","id":1347},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"VCAA-style questions","text":"1 mark each — a valid justification tied to a specific ethical issue or principle for each strategy (max 2). 1 mark — strategies between them address more than one of the three issues (breadth).","id":1348},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"If you remember six things","text":"Three issues: biased/harmful content · content usable for cyber attacks · generating from copyright material. Bias comes from data and gets amplified — the model can output more skew than it was fed. Cyber risk = lowered barriers: name the AI capability and the attack it enables; guardrails help but jailbreaks bypass them. Copyright: separate consent, compensation and ownership — and keep \"illegal\" apart from \"unethical.\" \"The AI did it\" is never enough — pin responsibility on developers, makers, users or deployers. Anchor judgements to the AI Ethics Principles: fairness, safety, transparency, accountability.","id":1349},{"file":"u2o1-kk13.html","nav":"u2o1-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"The ethics of artificial intelligence","head":"If you remember six things","text":"Next door in this chapter: KK14 — Evaluation criteria (judging an innovative solution's efficiency and effectiveness). The ethical reasoning you just practised becomes part of how you evaluate whether a solution is actually good . Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · U2·O1 Innovative Solutions · KK13 Ethics of AI. Built as a single offline file. MuseBot, Brookvale Secondary and all named students are fictional teaching scenarios and can be renamed. Aligned to the VCAA Applied Computing Study Design 2025–2028; this is a teaching resource, not a VCAA publication.","id":1350},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","text":"Unit 2 · Outcome 1 · Key Knowledge 14 — the last dot point Building a solution proves you can . Evaluating it answers the harder question: was it worth it? This module is about judging a finished solution on two separate scales — effectiveness (how well it does the job) and efficiency (how little it wastes doing it) — using criteria you wrote before you built, and evidence you gather after real people have used it.","id":1351},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"The dot point, in plain English","text":"Unit 2 Outcome 1 walks the whole problem-solving methodology — Analysis → Design → Development → Evaluation — to build one innovative solution. This dot point is the finish line . After your solution has been out in the world being used, you step back and judge it. Two things are examinable here, and the exam loves to test whether you can keep them apart: The questions you ask to decide if the solution succeeded — written as specific, measurable statements during design , covering both efficiency and effectiveness. The methods you use to gather evidence against each criterion after real use — interviews, surveys, observation, and analysing the solution's own logged data.","id":1352},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Back where the chapter began","text":"This chapter opened with FloatMate — the wearable rip-current alert wristband that Jade , a Year 11 Nippers volunteer, dreamed up at her surf club. We watched the idea form (KK01), get analysed and designed, then developed. Now it's the end of summer. FloatMate wristbands have been worn by junior swimmers through a full season of patrols . The club committee wants one thing from Jade: tell us, honestly, whether this was a good solution. That word — honestly — is the whole game. Jade can't just say \"I worked really hard and it looks great.\" She has to measure it against the criteria she wrote during design , using evidence she collected once kids actually wore it in the surf.","id":1353},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Back where the chapter began","text":"That's evaluation. Detect when a wearer drifts into a rip Alert that child clearly and immediately Cut the number of dangerous drifts and rescues Be comfortable enough that kids keep wearing it A battery that lasts a whole patrol shift An alert that fires within a second or two A unit price the club can actually afford Setup that doesn't eat a volunteer's whole morning The left column is about effectiveness — hitting the goal. The right column is about efficiency — not wasting time, money, battery or effort getting there. Hold that split in your head; the rest of the module sharpens it.","id":1354},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"The distinction examiners bait you with","text":"Students lose easy marks every year by treating testing and evaluation as the same thing. They are different jobs, at different times, answering different questions. Question: does it work the way I built it to? Happens while you're still coding the solution Uses test data and test cases (expected vs actual) Finds and fixes faults before release You run it yourself, in the workshop Question: was it a success for the people who use it? Happens weeks/months after release, in the real world Measures against evaluation criteria using real evidence Judges whether it met the original need You gather data from users, not just yourself","id":1355},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"When each thing happens on the methodology timeline","text":"Slide through the stages. Notice where the criteria are written, where testing lives, and how far away evaluation sits.","id":1356},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Effectiveness — how well it does the job","text":"Think of a chef cooking dinner for a hungry crowd. Effectiveness is whether everyone leaves full and the food tastes great — the goal got hit. It says nothing yet about how long it took or how much was wasted. A meal can be wonderfully effective and a total disaster on resources.","id":1357},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Common effectiveness measures","text":"Right outputs, no errors. FloatMate: does it flag a real rip and not cry wolf? Does it do all of the job, not just part? Every required feature present. Can a young Nipper understand the alert and act on it instantly? Works for the range of users it's meant for, not just the easy cases. Solves the actual need — fewer dangerous drifts — not a tidier near-miss. Delivers the message or outcome the functional requirements demanded. Quick test: if a measure describes how good the result is for the user , it's effectiveness.","id":1358},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Efficiency — how little it wastes","text":"Back to the chef. Efficiency is whether that great meal took 30 minutes or 5 hours, used half the pantry or just what was needed, ran the oven all day or barely at all. Same delicious result, wildly different efficiency. This is exactly why you must measure the two separately.","id":1359},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Common efficiency measures","text":"Speed to produce a result. FloatMate: seconds from rip-entry to alert. Money to build, buy or run. The price per wristband the club must pay. Human work to set up and maintain — minutes of volunteer time each patrol. Battery, data, processing, materials — what the solution consumes to run. Output per unit of input — more swimmers covered per charged band. How quickly the system computes/handles its workload under load.","id":1360},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Why a solution needs both scales","text":"Effective and efficient are independent axes, so a solution lands in one of four quadrants. Picture a delivery drone dropping a parcel on a target pad. Effectiveness is how close the parcel lands to the centre of the pad. Efficiency is how much battery the drone had left when it got there. Drive both sliders and watch the verdict change. Notice the bottom-right: a drone that nails the target but lands on empty is still a problem — it can't do the next run. Effectiveness without efficiency isn't \"good enough\", and a cheap, fast solution that misses the target is worthless. Evaluation reports on both, separately, then weighs them.","id":1361},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"What makes a criterion examinable","text":"An evaluation criterion is a single, specific, measurable statement (often phrased as a question) you use to judge success. A good set of criteria shares four traits: You could collect a number or a clear yes/no. \"FloatMate is good\" fails. \"What % of real rip events triggered an alert?\" works. Set before building, so the result can't be bent to flatter them. They flow from the solution requirements. Each criterion checks something the solution actually needed to do or be — not a random nice-to-have. Some criteria probe effectiveness , others efficiency . A set that's all one kind is incomplete.","id":1362},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Anatomy of a strong criterion","text":"effectiveness Criterion: Does FloatMate alert the wearer for at least 95% of genuine rip events? Measure / target: count alerts vs logged rip events over the season; target ≥ 95%.","id":1363},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Every criterion needs a way to measure it","text":"A criterion is only useful if you can gather evidence for it. So each one is paired with a technique . Prefer an objective method (a hard number anyone would read the same way) and fall back to a subjective method (people's opinions) only when no number exists. Analysing the band's logged data : alerts fired, response times, battery drain Timing the alert delay across many events Comparing incident reports before vs after the trial Measuring cost per unit against the budget Interviews with lifesavers and Nippers Surveys / questionnaires on comfort and clarity Observation of how kids respond to an alert on patrol User ratings of how easy the alert was to understand \"Was the alert clear?\" can't be read off a sensor — that's a job for a survey or interview (subjective). \"How fast did it fire?\" is a stopwatch job (objective). Match the method to what the criterion is actually asking.","id":1364},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Match each criterion to a sensible method","text":"Pick the best evaluation technique for each. Choices update live.","id":1365},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Effectiveness or efficiency?","text":"Drag each measure into the right bucket — or tap a chip then tap a bucket. Then check your answers.","id":1366},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"From vague to measurable","text":"These criteria would lose marks. Tap each to reveal a stronger version and why it's better. ✓ \"What percentage of genuine rip events did FloatMate alert on across the season? (target ≥ 95%)\" \"Reliable\" can't be measured. The fix names a number, a source of evidence and a target — and it's clearly an effectiveness criterion. ✓ Split into three: alert delay (seconds), unit cost ($ vs budget), and alert-clarity rating — each measured separately. One criterion should test one thing. Bundling three makes it impossible to say which part passed or failed.","id":1367},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"From vague to measurable","text":"✓ \"After a season of use, did logged rescue/near-miss counts fall compared with the previous season?\" Testing ≠ evaluation. A real evaluation criterion looks at outcomes after real use , with evidence gathered from the world, not the workshop. ✓ \"How much volunteer time did set-up take per patrol?\" (an efficiency measure) — and keep \"liked the colour\" as a separate effectiveness/appeal note. Liking the colour is about the result/appeal, not resource use. Efficiency is time, cost, effort and resources.","id":1368},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Read the verb before you write","text":"Command word What it wants FloatMate example State / List Name it, no explanation. State one criterion for evaluating FloatMate's effectiveness. Describe Say what it is, with some detail. Describe one technique Jade could use to evaluate efficiency. Explain Give the why / how it works, with a reason. Explain why evaluation criteria are written during the design stage. Distinguish Make the difference between two ideas clear. Distinguish between testing and evaluation. Justify Give reasons that defend a choice. Justify choosing logged data over a survey for measuring alert speed. Evaluate Weigh strengths and weaknesses; reach a judgement. Evaluate FloatMate's efficiency and effectiveness after the trial.","id":1369},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Write a response that scores","text":"Strong KK14 answers tend to follow P·E·L : make a Point , Explain it with reasoning, and Link back to the solution/scenario. Draft an answer to the prompt below; the trainer highlights the key ideas it detects. It's a guide, not a marker.","id":1370},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Five questions · 18 marks · mark yourself","text":"Have a real go first. Then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide, and award yourself a score — it feeds the dock in the corner.","id":1371},{"file":"u2o1-kk14.html","nav":"u2o1-kk14.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK14","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Did it actually work? Evaluating an innovative solution.","head":"Everything KK14, on a postcard","text":"Effectiveness = how well it does the job (accuracy, completeness, clarity, meets the need). Efficiency = how little it wastes (time, cost, effort, resources). Testing = during development, \"does it work?\". Evaluation = after a period of real use, \"was it a success against criteria?\". Specific, measurable, from the requirements, covering both scales — written before building so the verdict stays honest. Objective first (logs, timing, comparing records, costs); subjective fallback (interviews, surveys, observation). On-target but flat battery = effective, not efficient. Cheap and fast but off-pad = efficient, not effective. Report both, then weigh. Anchor evaluation to \"after real use\". Give every criterion a measure. Always cover both scales + a judgement.","id":1372},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Emerging trends in cyber security","text":"The walls that used to protect a network have basically dissolved. This dot point is about the five ideas the whole industry is shifting toward — and why \"keep the bad guys outside\" is no longer a plan. Clutch is a Melbourne-built app for learner drivers. You book lessons with a driving instructor, the app logs your supervised hours toward the 120 you need, and it stores… a lot: your learner permit number , your home address (it's the pickup point), a parent or guardian contact , a saved payment card , and your live GPS location during a lesson.","id":1373},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Emerging trends in cyber security","text":"Most of its 40,000 users are 16–18. Every example on this page comes back to Clutch, because every one of these trends exists to stop that data ending up in the wrong hands.","id":1374},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The castle had one wall. That wall is gone.","text":"For decades, network security worked like a medieval castle. You built one big wall — a firewall — around your network. Anyone outside was a stranger to be checked. Anyone inside was trusted. Get past the wall once, and you could wander freely. That model quietly broke. People now work from home, from phones, from cafés. Data lives in the cloud, not in a server room you can lock. Clutch's instructors log in from their cars; its database sits on rented cloud servers in another state. There is no longer a single \"inside\" to defend.","id":1375},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The castle had one wall. That wall is gone.","text":"So the field has shifted from perimeter security (\"guard the wall\") to a set of newer ideas that assume the attacker is already in, and check everything, all the time. VCAA lists these under \" emerging trends in cyber security.\" When a question asks you to describe or explain a trend, it wants two things: what it is , and what problem it solves compared with the old approach. A definition alone rarely gets full marks.","id":1376},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"One job each","text":"Each trend attacks a different weak spot. Read them as a set: together they replace the single castle wall with many small, constant checks.","id":1377},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Multi-factor authentication","text":"Proving who you are with more than just a password.","id":1378},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Zero Trust Architecture","text":"Never trust, always verify — even inside the network.","id":1379},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"AI threat detection","text":"Machine learning spots the attack a fixed rule would miss.","id":1380},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Regulatory compliance","text":"Laws forcing organisations to actually do the above.","id":1381},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Multi-factor authentication","text":"Multi-factor authentication (MFA) means proving your identity using two or more independent factors from different categories. The three categories are easy to remember: The whole point is independence . An attacker in another country can buy a leaked Clutch password, but they don't have the student's phone . That's why the second factor stops them. Try the breach below.","id":1382},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"MFA breach simulator — Clutch instructor login","text":"An attacker has phished an instructor's password. Watch what each defence does when the password falls. A password and a security question is not MFA — both are \"something you know.\" MFA needs factors from different categories . Examiners deliberately test this.","id":1383},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Zero Trust Architecture","text":"Zero Trust Architecture (ZTA) throws out the idea of a trusted \"inside.\" Its motto is \"never trust, always verify.\" Every request — even from a device already on the network — must prove who it is, and gets only the minimum access it needs ( least privilege ). Crucially, the network is broken into small zones ( micro-segmentation ) so a break-in can't spread. The scene below is the heart of this dot point. Compromise one machine and watch what happens under each model. In Castle & Moat , one breach owns everything. In Zero Trust , every hop hits a checkpoint, so the damage is contained.","id":1384},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Zero Trust lab — lateral movement on the Clutch network","text":"Pick a model, then click a node. The breach tries to spread to every connected machine. Never trust, always verify (re-check every request) · Least privilege (give the smallest access that still works — a Clutch instructor sees their learners, never the whole database) · Micro-segmentation (wall the network into zones so one breach is trapped). Name these three and you've covered the dot point. Zero Trust is not a product you install and it's not \"a really strong firewall.\" It's an architecture / approach built from verification, least privilege and segmentation. Calling it \"better antivirus\" loses the mark.","id":1385},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"AI threat detection","text":"Old defences used fixed rules : \"block any login from outside Australia,\" \"alert if more than 5 failed passwords.\" Attackers learn the rules and slip under them. AI threat detection instead uses machine learning to learn what normal traffic looks like, then flags anything anomalous — even a pattern no one wrote a rule for. On Clutch, a real instructor opens a handful of student profiles a day. The graph below shows one account's profile-views per minute. At 14:30 it spikes — someone is scraping every learner's home address. A fixed threshold set at 50 never trips. The model, which learned this account's normal rhythm, flags it instantly.","id":1386},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Rule vs. AI — catching the data scrape","text":"AI detection catches novel, unknown attacks and adapts as behaviour changes — but it can raise false positives (flagging harmless oddities) and needs lots of clean data to learn from. A good answer names both the strength and a limitation.","id":1387},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Cryptographic protection","text":"Cryptography scrambles readable data ( plaintext ) into unreadable ciphertext using a key . Without the key, a stolen file is gibberish. Modern systems encrypt data in two places: in transit (moving across the network, e.g. HTTPS) and at rest (sitting in the database). If an attacker stole Clutch's database but the permit numbers were encrypted, they'd get nothing usable. The simplest cipher is the Caesar cipher — shift every letter by a fixed amount. Play with it to feel how a key works, then read why this exact idea is hopeless today.","id":1388},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Caesar cipher — shift Clutch's secret","text":"A Caesar cipher has only 25 possible keys — a computer cracks it instantly by trying them all (a brute-force attack). Real encryption like AES-256 has more keys than there are atoms in the observable universe. Don't confuse \"a cipher\" with \"secure encryption.\"","id":1389},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Regulatory compliance","text":"The first four trends are technical . This one is the reason organisations bother . Regulatory compliance means following the laws and standards that govern how data must be protected. It turns \"we should secure data\" into \"we are legally required to.\" Because Clutch stores minors' personal data and location, several Australian rules apply: Set the baseline: only collect data you need, keep it secure (APP 11), and let people access their own data. Clutch must protect those permit numbers and addresses by law. If a breach is likely to cause serious harm, Clutch must notify affected users and the Information Commissioner.","id":1390},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Regulatory compliance","text":"Hiding a breach is itself illegal. A government baseline of eight practical strategies — patching, MFA, restricting admin rights, backups — that organisations are assessed against. MFA from Trend 01 is one of the eight. Governs how Victorian public bodies handle personal data; relevant if Clutch ever partners with VicRoads or a public school. Compliance is an emerging trend because regulation keeps tightening — the NDB scheme is recent, fines have grown, and \"we didn't know\" is no longer a defence. Security is shifting from optional to mandatory.","id":1391},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The ATM","text":"An ATM needs your card (have) and your PIN (know). Steal one, you still can't withdraw. That's two factors from two categories — textbook MFA.","id":1392},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The airport","text":"Inside the terminal you're still checked at every gate, lounge and boarding pass scan. Being \"past security\" once doesn't let you board any plane. Verify every time.","id":1393},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The bank text","text":"Your bank texts \"was this you?\" after an odd purchase. It learned your normal spending, so an unusual one stands out — no fixed rule needed. That's anomaly detection.","id":1394},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The locked diary","text":"A diary written in a code only you can read is useless if stolen. Encryption is that code — the data is there, but meaningless without the key.","id":1395},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Fire safety law","text":"Buildings have smoke alarms because the law demands it, not just because it's nice. Compliance makes good security non-optional — with penalties if you skip it.","id":1396},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"VCAA marks against the command word . Same topic, different verb, completely different answer. Match your effort to the word. Name it. \"Multi-factor authentication.\" No explanation expected. Say what it is and a defining feature. \"MFA requires two or more factors from different categories, e.g. a password and a phone code.\" Say how/why it works. Show cause and effect — why the trend solves the problem. Give both sides, on the same criteria. \"Unlike a firewall, Zero Trust verifies inside traffic too…\" Make a choice and defend it with reasons tied to the scenario. Link to Clutch's actual data and users. Weigh strengths against limitations, then give a judgement. Both sides, then a verdict.","id":1397},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"The traps that cost marks","text":"Two things you know is one factor twice. MFA needs different categories : know + have + are. It's an architecture — verify everything, least privilege, micro-segmentation. A firewall is just one component. Mention a limitation — false positives and the need for training data — or you'll miss the evaluate marks. Encryption doesn't block access — it makes stolen data unreadable . It protects data, not the door. In a case study, naming the trend isn't enough. Tie it to the scenario — which Clutch data, which user, which threat.","id":1398},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"VCAA answers reward a simple shape: Point (name it) → Explain (how/why it works) → Link (tie it to the scenario). Write a response below — the keyword meter lights up as you hit the ideas examiners look for. Under Zero Trust, the compromised laptop is not automatically trusted just because it's on the network — every request it makes must still be verified (Point/Explain). Because of least privilege , that instructor account can only reach its own learners' records, not the full database, and micro-segmentation walls the network into zones so the attacker can't move laterally to other systems (Explain).","id":1399},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"This means the breach is contained to one instructor's small set of Clutch data rather than exposing all 40,000 users' permit numbers and home addresses (Link).","id":1400},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total, building from Identify to Evaluate . Each shows a weak and a strong response, a marking guide, then mark your own — your score feeds the dial in the corner. \"It's when you use more than one password to log in so it's more secure.\" \"MFA requires a user to verify their identity with two or more factors from different categories — something you know (password), something you have (a phone code) and/or something you are (a fingerprint).\" 1 mark: two or more factors required to authenticate.","id":1401},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 mark: factors come from different categories (know / have / are), ideally with an example. \"Zero Trust is more secure because it doesn't trust anyone, so hackers can't get in. A firewall is old technology.\" \"A firewall only checks traffic at the network edge, so once an attacker is inside — say via a stolen instructor login — they're trusted and can roam. 'Never trust, always verify' re-checks every request and grants least privilege, so a compromised instructor account can only reach its own learners, not Clutch's whole database of 40,000 permit numbers and addresses.\" 1 mark:","id":1402},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"firewall trusts everything once inside the perimeter. 1 mark: Zero Trust verifies each request / applies least privilege. 1 mark: linked to Clutch's data being contained / not fully exposed. \"AI is better than rules because AI is smart and modern. Rules are simple and don't work as well.\" \"Rule-based detection uses fixed thresholds (e.g. alert after 50 profile views), so it's predictable and cheap but misses any attack designed to stay under the limit, like a slow scrape of learner addresses. AI detection learns each account's normal behaviour and flags anomalies even without a matching rule, catching novel attacks — but it can produce false positives and needs large amounts of clean training data.","id":1403},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"AI adapts; rules don't, but rules are simpler to audit.\" 1 mark: rule-based = fixed thresholds/signatures; predictable but evadable. 1 mark: AI = learns normal, flags anomalies / novel attacks. 1 mark: a limitation of AI (false positives / training data). 1 mark: genuine comparison on shared criteria, linked to Clutch. \"They should use encryption and a strong password. That will keep hackers out and make it safe.\" \"First, encrypt the data at rest with AES so that if the database is stolen, the permit numbers and addresses are unreadable without the key — turning a catastrophic breach into a non-event.","id":1404},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Second, enforce MFA on all instructor and admin accounts, so a phished password alone can't unlock access to that data. Together they protect the data on two fronts: encryption limits the impact of a breach, while MFA reduces the chance of one. Given Clutch holds minors' home addresses, this also helps meet its obligations under the Privacy Act (APP 11).\" 1 mark each: two appropriate strategies (encryption at rest, MFA, Zero Trust, AI monitoring…). 1 mark each: a justification tied to a consequence for Clutch's data. 1 mark: depth — e.g.","id":1405},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"distinguishing \"reduce likelihood\" vs \"reduce impact,\" or a compliance link. \"AI threat detection is a good idea because it's modern and catches hackers automatically, so Clutch should definitely use it as their main defence.\" \"AI detection is a strong asset: it learns Clutch's normal traffic and flags novel anomalies — like the slow address scrape — that fixed rules miss, and it monitors in real time across 40,000 users. However, relying on it as the primary defence is risky. It produces false positives that could overwhelm a small team, it needs large volumes of clean data to train, and it's detective, not preventive — it spots an attack in progress rather than stopping the initial break-in.","id":1406},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"A sound strategy uses AI detection as one layer alongside preventive controls: MFA to stop stolen logins, encryption to protect the data if detection fails, and Zero Trust to contain anything that gets through. Overall, AI detection is valuable but should complement, not replace, a defence-in-depth approach.\" 2 marks: strengths (learns normal, catches novel/anomalous, real-time). 2 marks: limitations (false positives, training data, detective not preventive). 1 mark: linked to Clutch's scale/data. 1 mark: a clear, reasoned judgement (complement, not sole defence).","id":1407},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"Quick quiz","text":"Six rapid questions to test recall. Pick an answer to see why it's right or wrong.","id":1408},{"file":"u2o2-kk01.html","nav":"u2o2-kk01.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK01","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Emerging trends in cyber security","head":"If you remember nothing else","text":"The field moved from \"guard the wall\" (perimeter) to \"verify everything, all the time, and assume you'll be breached\" . Every trend is one piece of that shift. In a case study: name the trend, explain the mechanism, link it to the specific data and users.","id":1409},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","text":"Every cyber security incident in this course happens on a network . Before you can defend one, you need to know the gear inside it — what each box does, and which ones are actually there to keep attackers out.","id":1410},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"You can't protect a network you can't picture","text":"This dot point is the vocabulary and the map for the whole Cyber Security outcome. The VCAA wording is short — \"key hardware and software components of networks\" — but it underpins everything that follows: threats (KK06–KK08), risk reduction (KK09), encryption (KK10) and the legislation (KK13). In the SAC you'll be handed a case study about a real-ish organisation's network and asked to name components, explain what they do, and say which ones reduce risk . If you mix up a router and a switch, or a firewall and antivirus, you lose easy marks.","id":1411},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"You can't protect a network you can't picture","text":"Clutch is a Melbourne-built learner-driver app: it matches L-platers with driving instructors, logs the 120 supervised hours, and processes lesson payments. It holds permit numbers, home pick-up addresses, parent contacts, payment cards and live GPS for roughly 40,000 16–18-year-olds. Clutch runs a small office network plus cloud servers — the perfect place to spot every component in this dot point doing its job. We'll keep using Clutch through KK02–KK13. Quick orientation: components in a network fall into two buckets the examiner cares about — things that move traffic (routers, switches) and things that protect data (firewalls, security software, IDS/IPS, backups). Keep that split in your head and most questions sort themselves out.","id":1412},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Meet the gear inside Clutch HQ","text":"Here are the six components named in the study design. Tap any card to flip it for the one-line job, a plain-English analogy, and where it sits at Clutch. We'll then take each in turn.","id":1413},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"A post office sorting hub between suburbs . It reads the destination on each parcel and sends it down the right road toward another network.","id":1414},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"An office receptionist who knows every desk . A parcel for desk 14 goes straight to desk 14 — not shouted across the whole floor.","id":1415},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"A nightclub bouncer with a guest list . On the list, you're in; not on it, you're turned away at the door.","id":1416},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"Storage is your working filing cabinet ; a backup is the photocopy kept off-site in a safe . Lose the original, you still have the copy.","id":1417},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"A personal bodyguard for each device . The firewall guards the building's front gate; this guards the individual people inside.","id":1418},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Analogy","text":"IDS = a security camera + alarm (it tells you). IPS = a guard who slams the gate (it acts). One watches, one stops. Think of Clutch HQ as a house . The router is the front door to the street (other networks). The switch is the hallway connecting the rooms inside. The firewall is the security gate at the boundary. Storage & backup is the safe (and the copy at grandma's house). Security software is each person's own caution. IDS/IPS is the camera-and-guard combo watching for intruders.","id":1419},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Routers vs switches — the #1 thing students confuse","text":"Both move data, so they look similar — but they work at different levels and the examiner loves to test the difference. The one-line rule: A switch connects devices within a single network (a LAN). A router connects different networks together (e.g. your LAN to the internet). Switch = inside. Router = between.","id":1420},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Router — the path-finder","text":"A router sits at the boundary of a network and decides where traffic goes next . It reads the destination IP address on each packet and forwards it toward the right network, choosing an efficient path. Home/office routers usually also run DHCP (handing out IP addresses to devices) and NAT (letting many devices share one public address). Because all traffic to and from the internet passes through it, the router is a natural place to attach a firewall.","id":1421},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Switch — the precise deliverer","text":"A switch connects the devices on one LAN — PCs, printers, servers — and forwards each frame only to the port of the device it's addressed to, using MAC addresses it has learned. That precision is why a switch beats an older hub , which blindly copied every frame to every port (noisy, slow and a security risk, because everyone could see everyone's traffic). No. A switch has no idea what the internet is — it only knows devices on its own network by MAC address. The router is what reaches other networks using IP addresses.","id":1422},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Switch — the precise deliverer","text":"If a question asks which component \"directs traffic between the office network and the internet\", the answer is the router . Feature Switch Router Connects… devices within one network (LAN) different networks together (LAN ↔ internet) Addresses used MAC addresses IP addresses Unit of data frames packets Clutch example links staff PCs & office server links the office to the cloud & internet","id":1423},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Firewalls — the gatekeeper with a rulebook","text":"A firewall inspects traffic crossing a boundary and decides to allow or block it based on rules. Rules can match the source/destination IP address, the port (which service is being reached), and the protocol. Default-deny is the safe posture: block everything, then open only what's needed. A stateful firewall also remembers active connections, so it can tell the difference between a reply you asked for and an unsolicited probe from a stranger. That's how Clutch's firewall lets staff browse out to the web, while silently dropping random connection attempts coming in from the internet toward the payment server.","id":1424},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Firewalls — the gatekeeper with a rulebook","text":"A hardware firewall is a dedicated device (often built into the router) guarding the whole network at its edge — one checkpoint for everyone. A software firewall runs on an individual computer (e.g. the one built into Windows), protecting just that device. Most organisations use both : perimeter device + per-machine software. (Note the overlap — a software firewall is also a form of \"security software\" in the next section.) A firewall filters network traffic by rules; it is not designed to scan files for malware. If a staff member downloads an infected attachment through an allowed connection, the firewall waves it through — that's the job of anti-malware security software . Don't write \"the firewall removes the virus.\" Different tools, different jobs.","id":1425},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Storage & backup — survive the worst day","text":"Storage is where data normally lives: file servers, a NAS (network-attached storage box) on the LAN, or cloud storage. Backup is a separate, recoverable copy kept so data survives a disaster — hardware failure, theft, accidental deletion or a ransomware attack that encrypts the originals. The distinction is the whole point of the dot point: a second live copy on the same server is storage , not a backup, because the same incident can take out both.","id":1426},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"The 3-2-1 rule — build it below","text":"The industry shorthand for a backup that actually saves you: keep 3 copies of the data, on 2 different types of media, with 1 copy kept off-site (or offline). Toggle the pieces and then hit a ransomware strike to see what survives.","id":1427},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"3-2-1 Backup builder","text":"can Clutch recover? Imagine Clutch keeps its only backup on a second drive in the same office. A burst pipe, a fire, a theft — or ransomware spreading across the LAN — takes the original and the copy. The off-site (or offline) copy is the one the attacker and the disaster can't reach. That's the copy that gets the company back online without paying a ransom.","id":1428},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Security software — protection that runs on the device","text":"Not every defence is a box in a rack. Security software is the protective programs running on each computer and server. The examinable families: Anti-malware / antivirus — scans files and running programs for viruses, worms, spyware and ransomware, and quarantines or removes them. Encryption software — scrambles stored data (e.g. the lesson database) and traffic so a thief who copies the files still can't read them. Patch & update management — keeps the operating system and applications current, closing the known holes attackers rely on (links straight to KK09).","id":1429},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Security software — protection that runs on the device","text":"Endpoint monitoring / software firewall — watches each device's behaviour and filters its traffic locally. Write the type of software and what it does (\"anti-malware software that scans and removes malicious programs\"), not just a brand name. \"We'd install [Brand]\" with no explanation earns little. Examiners mark the function, not the logo. Hardware or software? A quick gut-check: if you could uninstall it, it's security software; if you could trip over it in the server room , it's hardware. (A software firewall lives in both worlds — it's software that does a firewall's job.)","id":1430},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"IDS vs IPS — watch, or stop?","text":"This pairing is the single most tested distinction in the dot point. Both inspect traffic for signs of an attack — using signatures (known attack patterns) and/or anomaly detection (anything that strays from normal behaviour). The difference is what they do when they find something.","id":1431},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"🎥 IDS Intrusion Detection System","text":"Detects suspicious activity and raises an alert / log for the security team. Usually sits out of line (monitoring a copy of traffic) — it watches, it doesn't touch. The malicious packet still gets through ; a human has to respond.","id":1432},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"🛡 IPS Intrusion Prevention System","text":"Detects and automatically blocks / drops the malicious traffic. Sits inline (traffic flows through it) so it can stop attacks in real time. The malicious packet is stopped before it lands — no human needed for the block. Saying an IPS \"detects threats\" is only half the answer and often costs the mark. The defining word for IPS is prevent / block ; the defining word for IDS is detect / alert . In a Distinguish question, your sentence must contrast those verbs: \"An IDS only alerts staff, whereas an IPS actively blocks the traffic.\" You can prove this to yourself in the lab below — send a stealth attack with only the IDS on and watch it reach the server with an alert, then switch the IPS on and watch the same attack get dropped.","id":1433},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Defence-in-Depth Lab","text":"This is the whole dot point in one moving picture. Traffic flows left → right through Clutch's network: Internet → Router → Firewall → IDS/IPS sensor → Switch → Server (with a backup branch). Toggle each defence, then fire different packets and watch which layer catches what . Notice how no single box stops everything — that's defence in depth .","id":1434},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Clutch network — layered defence","text":"toggle defences · fire packets The firewall stops obvious, rule-breaking traffic at the edge. A stealth/zero-day attack that looks legitimate sails straight past it — that's exactly why you also need an IPS to block what the firewall missed, an IDS to alert on what gets through, security software on the endpoint, and a clean backup for when something still lands. Layers cover each other's gaps.","id":1435},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Match the component to its job","text":"Tap a component on the left, then tap its correct job on the right. Get all six and you've nailed the core of KK02.","id":1436},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Quick quiz — 6 questions","text":"Multiple choice, instant feedback. These mirror the Section A style of the exam.","id":1437},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"Five questions, 22 marks , climbing the command-word ladder from Identify to Evaluate . Read the question, have a real go in your head or on paper , then reveal a weak and a strong sample answer, the marking guide, and mark yourself. Your score feeds the dock in the corner. A router and a switch. A switch connects the staff PCs to one another within the office LAN. A router connects the office network to the internet — that is, it links two different networks. 1 — switch identified as connecting devices within the LAN 1 — router identified as connecting the office to the internet / different networks A firewall keeps hackers and viruses out of the network.","id":1438},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"There are different kinds you can buy. A firewall inspects traffic at the network boundary and allows or blocks it against rules. For Clutch it could apply a rule to deny all inbound connections to the payment server's port except from the application servers , so strangers on the internet can't reach it. A hardware firewall is a dedicated device at the network edge protecting every device behind it; a software firewall runs on an individual computer, protecting only that machine. 1 — firewall allows/blocks traffic by rules at the boundary 1 — a valid, specific rule example (port/IP/protocol) 1 — hardware = dedicated edge device for whole network 1 — software = runs on one device, protects that device An IDS and an IPS both detect intrusions and threats on the network to keep it safe.","id":1439},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"When a threat is detected, an IDS only raises an alert / log for staff and the traffic continues, whereas an IPS automatically blocks or drops the traffic. An IDS typically sits out of line , monitoring a copy of traffic, while an IPS sits inline so traffic must pass through it and can be stopped in real time. 1 — IDS detects and alerts only 1 — IPS detects and automatically blocks 1 — IDS out of line / monitors a copy 1 — IPS inline / traffic passes through it They should back up their data so if something goes wrong they have a copy.","id":1440},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"Backups are important for safety. Storage holds only the live copy, so a single event — hardware failure, theft, or ransomware encrypting the files — destroys the data with no way back. A 3-2-1 strategy keeps 3 copies, on 2 different media, with 1 off-site/offline . When ransomware encrypts everything reachable on Clutch's LAN, the off-site/offline copy is out of its reach , so Clutch restores the lesson records from that copy and resumes operating without paying the ransom . 1 — storage is the live/only copy → one event destroys it 1 — names ransomware risk (encryption of reachable files) 1 — 3 copies on 2 media 1 — 1 copy off-site/offline 1 — off-site copy enables recovery without paying ransom This is a bad idea because one firewall is not enough.","id":1441},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"They need more security like antivirus and backups to be safe. Defence in depth means having lots of security. The claim is partly true but dangerously incomplete . A firewall does valuable work — filtering traffic by rules at the boundary — but it only inspects what crosses the perimeter and judges traffic by rules, so it cannot catch a stealth/zero-day attack that looks legitimate , nor malware in a file a staff member downloads through an allowed connection, nor an insider. To cover those gaps Clutch needs layers: an IPS inline to block malicious traffic the firewall passed, an IDS to alert staff to anything suspicious that still gets through, security software (anti-malware + patching) on each endpoint to stop malware on the devices, and off-site backups so that if an attack still succeeds the payment and student data can be restored.","id":1442},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"VCE-style questions — weak vs strong responses","text":"This layering is defence in depth : each control covers another's blind spot. Overall the consultant is wrong — given Clutch holds minors' data and payment cards, a single firewall is not adequate; a layered design is required. 1 — acknowledges the firewall's genuine role 1–2 — identifies specific limits (rule-based, perimeter-only, misses stealth/insider/downloaded malware) 1–3 — three+ other components with correct roles (IPS, IDS, security software, backup) 1 — applies defence in depth (layers cover gaps) 1 — clear justified overall judgement referencing the data at stake","id":1443},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"P·E·L — build a full-mark sentence","text":"High-band responses follow Point → Evidence → Link : make the point, back it with a specific detail or example, then link it to the question or scenario. Write an answer to the prompt and watch the three meters fill as the keywords appear.","id":1444},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Command words & the traps that cost marks","text":"Match your answer's depth to the verb. Under-answering a Compare with a one-word \"Identify\" answer is the most common way to leave marks behind. Command word What the examiner wants For KK02, that means… Identify / State Name it. No explanation. \"A router.\" Describe Name + key features / how it works. \"A switch connects devices on a LAN and forwards each frame to the correct device by MAC address.\" Explain Describe and give the reason / how it achieves the effect. \"…so traffic only reaches the intended device, reducing congestion and exposure.\" Compare / Distinguish Explicit points of difference, both sides in one sentence.","id":1445},{"file":"u2o2-kk02.html","nav":"u2o2-kk02.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK02","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"The hardware & software that hold a network together","head":"Command words & the traps that cost marks","text":"\"An IDS only alerts, whereas an IPS blocks the traffic inline.\" Justify / Evaluate Make a judgement and defend it with reasons / trade-offs. \"An IPS is the better choice for the payment server because automatic blocking stops attacks faster than waiting for a human, though it risks blocking legitimate traffic.\" ① Router ≠ switch — between networks vs within a network. ② Firewall ≠ antivirus — filters traffic vs scans files. ③ IDS ≠ IPS — alert vs block. ④ Storage ≠ backup — live data vs a separate recoverable copy (off-site matters). ⑤ Hardware vs software — know which family each component belongs to, and that a software firewall straddles both.","id":1446},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","text":"Every network has to make the same bargain: speed and safety, or freedom to move. This module shows you how to weigh wired , wireless and mobile against the four things examiners care about — and how to justify a choice instead of just naming one.","id":1447},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"One company, three networks","text":"Meet Clutch — a Melbourne start-up whose app helps about 40,000 learner drivers aged 16–18 book lessons, log their 120 supervised hours, and pay instructors. Clutch never thinks of itself as having \"a network\". It runs three different kinds at once , because each part of the business needs something different.","id":1448},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Server room","text":"In the Carlton office: servers holding learner records, payment data and nightly backups. Needs maximum speed, reliability and security. It never moves.","id":1449},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Staff laptops","text":"Twenty staff move between desks, meeting rooms and the kitchen with laptops. They need to roam freely without plugging in — but still reach the servers.","id":1450},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"The in-car app","text":"The actual app, used by a learner and instructor in a moving car on a country road. It has to work anywhere — which rules out everything tethered to a building. The strengths and limitations of wired, wireless and mobile network technologies, measured by cost , data storage , reliability and security . Translation: you must be able to compare the three connection types and justify which suits a given situation, using those four criteria as your yardstick. Throughout this module Clutch's three needs — server room , staff laptops and in-car app — map almost perfectly onto wired, wireless and mobile. Keep them in mind; the exam loves \"which would you choose, and why?\"","id":1451},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Three ways to move data","text":"Before comparing them, be crystal clear on what physically carries the data in each case. This is where careless answers lose marks.","id":1452},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"🔌 Wired","text":"Data travels as electrical signals down copper cables (Ethernet) or as light down fibre-optic cables. A physical wire runs from each device to a switch. Think of it as a private tunnel.","id":1453},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"📶 Wireless (Wi-Fi)","text":"Data travels as radio waves through the air between a device and a nearby wireless access point . No cable to the device. Range is a room or a building. This is a WLAN .","id":1454},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"📱 Mobile (cellular)","text":"Data travels as radio waves to cell towers run by a carrier (Telstra, Optus…) over 4G/5G . Range is a whole country. Your device hops between towers as it moves. Wired is a string-and-tin-can line between two rooms: private and clear, but you can't leave the spot. Wireless is talking out loud across the lounge: easy and free to wander, but anyone in the room can overhear and noise gets in the way. Mobile is phoning someone across the city: works almost anywhere, but you're paying a carrier and you're trusting their lines.","id":1455},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"📱 Mobile (cellular)","text":"\"Wireless\" and \"mobile\" are not the same word for the same thing. Wireless (Wi-Fi) is short-range radio to your own access point inside a building. Mobile (cellular) is long-range radio to a carrier's towers across a region. The in-car app uses mobile, not Wi-Fi — there's no Wi-Fi on a country road.","id":1456},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"The four lenses examiners use","text":"VCAA doesn't want \"wired is good\". It wants a comparison along set criteria. Memorise these four and apply each one in your answers. A neat memory hook: C–D–R–S — “Cables Don't Run Slowly.” Lens The question it asks What a good answer mentions Cost What does it cost to set up and keep running? Cabling/installation vs access points vs ongoing SIM/data plans. Data storage How much data can it carry and how steadily? Where does data sit? Bandwidth/throughput, consistency, data caps, on-site vs cloud. Reliability Will the connection stay up and stable?","id":1457},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"The four lenses examiners use","text":"Interference, walls, distance, congestion, coverage, weather. Security How easily could the data be intercepted or the network breached? Physical access vs over-the-air interception, encryption , who controls it. For a \"compare\" or \"justify\" question, walk the lenses one at a time. Even a short answer that says \"On reliability… On security… On cost…\" reads as deliberate and scores far better than a vague paragraph. The lenses are your scaffold.","id":1458},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"🔌 Wired networks","text":"A physical cable runs from every device to a switch. For Clutch, this is the server room : servers and backups bolted to a rack, wired with fibre and Ethernet. Nothing here ever needs to move, so wired is the obvious win.","id":1459},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Strengths","text":"Reliability: the gold standard. No interference, no walls in the way, stable low latency. The cable does the same thing every time. Data: highest, most consistent bandwidth — fibre handles huge backups and many users at once without slowing. Security: hardest to attack. To tap the data an attacker needs physical access to the cable or a port inside the building.","id":1460},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Limitations","text":"Cost: high upfront — cabling, ports, labour, and disruption to install or re-route walls and floors. No mobility: devices are tethered. You can't carry a wired laptop to a meeting room without a cable. Inflexible: adding or moving a device means running new cable, not just connecting. Wired is a private underground rail line between two stations. Expensive to dig, impossible to move — but once it's there it's fast, predictable, and nobody on the street can jump on board.","id":1461},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"📶 Wireless networks (Wi-Fi)","text":"Radio waves connect devices to an access point. For Clutch, this is the staff laptops : people roam the Carlton office and still reach the servers — no cable per desk.","id":1462},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Strengths","text":"Mobility: move freely anywhere the signal reaches — desk, kitchen, meeting room. Cost: one access point serves many devices; no cabling to each one, cheap to add a new laptop or phone. Convenience: visitors and new devices join in seconds.","id":1463},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Limitations","text":"Reliability: walls, distance, microwaves and other networks cause interference and drop-outs. Bandwidth is shared — more users, slower for everyone. Data: lower and more variable throughput than wired. Security: the signal radiates beyond the walls . Without strong encryption (WPA2/WPA3) it can be intercepted from the car park. Rogue/\"evil-twin\" access points and weak passwords are real risks. Wireless is talking out loud in a café . Wonderfully free — you can move around and anyone can join the chat. But your voice carries to the next table, so if it's private you'd better speak in code (that's encryption). And if the café is packed, you struggle to be heard (that's congestion).","id":1464},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"📱 Mobile networks (4G / 5G)","text":"Radio waves connect to a carrier's cell towers across the whole country. For Clutch, this is the in-car app : a learner and instructor driving a country road. No building means no Wi-Fi — mobile is the only option for something that moves that far.","id":1465},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Strengths","text":"Reach: works almost anywhere there's coverage — the only realistic choice for a moving vehicle. No infrastructure: the carrier owns and maintains the towers; Clutch builds nothing. Data & speed: 5G can be very fast, and the device hands off between towers automatically as the car moves.","id":1466},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Limitations","text":"Cost: ongoing and recurring — every device needs a SIM and data plan; caps and overage charges add up at scale. Reliability: coverage gaps in tunnels, basements and remote roads; congestion at peak times. Security: traffic is encrypted over the air by the carrier, but it's a public, shared network Clutch doesn't control — risks include SIM-swapping and fake-tower interception. Mobile is the national postal service . You can send from almost anywhere and it reaches almost anywhere — but you pay per use, you're trusting someone else's whole system, and out in the bush the van sometimes can't get through.","id":1467},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Connection Trade-off Lab","text":"Pick one of Clutch's three real needs, then try each connection type on it. Watch the 4-lens scorecard change and see the physical reality in 3D — a solid cable, radio through walls, or a car handing off between towers. The exam skill here is reading the trade-off and justifying the fit.","id":1468},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Clutch · Connection Trade-off Lab","text":"The verdict line under the scorecard is exactly the kind of one-sentence justification examiners reward: a choice, tied to the criteria, with the trade-off named.","id":1469},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Head-to-head","text":"No connection type \"wins\" outright — each is best for a purpose . That phrase, \"it depends on the purpose\", is the single most useful thing you can write. Lens 🔌 Wired 📶 Wireless 📱 Mobile Cost High setup, low to run Low — one AP, many devices Recurring SIM/data per device Data storage Highest , most consistent Good but shared/variable Good (5G), but data caps Reliability Best — stable, no interference Walls, range, congestion Coverage gaps, peak congestion Security Strongest — needs physical access Radiates out; needs encryption Carrier-encrypted but public/shared Mobility None — tethered Within a building Anywhere with coverage Clutch fit Server room ✓ Staff laptops ✓ In-car app ✓ \"There is no single best network;","id":1470},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Head-to-head","text":"the right choice depends on the purpose. For a fixed, data-heavy, security-critical server room, wired is best; for staff who must roam an office cheaply, wireless; for an app used in a moving car, mobile is the only viable option.\" — Now you've shown you can weigh , not just list.","id":1471},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Why security tracks how data travels","text":"The security difference between the three comes down to one idea: how easy is it to get between the sender and the data? The more the signal travels through open air or shared networks, the more chances an attacker has. This is why an unsecured café Wi-Fi is dangerous and a wired server room is not: the café broadcasts your data to the room. For Clutch, staff laptops on Wi-Fi must use WPA3 plus a VPN , and the in-car app must encrypt its own traffic on top of the carrier's, because Clutch can't trust a network it doesn't own.","id":1472},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Why security tracks how data travels","text":"Sending an unencrypted password over open Wi-Fi is like writing it on a postcard and reading it aloud in a crowded train. Encrypting it is sealing it in a locked box only the recipient can open — anyone can still grab the box, but the contents are useless to them.","id":1473},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Match the need to the network","text":"Drag (or tap) each real situation into the connection you'd recommend. Think purpose first, then check it against the four lenses.","id":1474},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Flip cards","text":"Tap a card to reveal the one fact that most often earns or loses a mark.","id":1475},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Wired","text":"Best reliability, data capacity and security — but high install cost and zero mobility. Suits a fixed server room.","id":1476},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Wireless (Wi-Fi)","text":"Cheap, mobile within a building, easy to add devices — but signal radiates out, so it needs WPA2/WPA3 encryption.","id":1477},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Mobile (4G/5G)","text":"Works anywhere with coverage — the only option for a moving car. Recurring data cost; coverage gaps; public network.","id":1478},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"The four lenses","text":"Cost · Data storage · Reliability · Security. Apply each — never answer on speed alone.","id":1479},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Why wireless is riskier","text":"The signal travels through open air beyond the walls, so it can be intercepted without physical entry — hence encryption is essential.","id":1480},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"The golden line","text":"\"No single best network — it depends on the purpose.\" Then pick one and defend it against the named criteria.","id":1481},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Six traps that cost marks","text":"Calling the in-car app \"Wi-Fi\". Wi-Fi is your own short-range network in a building; mobile is a carrier's cellular network across a region. A moving car uses mobile. Writing three separate paragraphs that never touch. \"Compare\" means putting them against each other on the same lens: \"Wired is more reliable than wireless because…\". Wired is great but expensive to install and can't move . Naming a real limitation shows balanced judgement — markers look for it. Answering only on speed. A full answer touches cost, data, reliability and security — at least the ones the question names.","id":1482},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Six traps that cost marks","text":"Too absolute. Wireless is less secure by default because the signal radiates , but strong encryption (WPA3) closes most of the gap. Explain why , don't just label. A \"justify\" or \"recommend\" question needs you to actually pick one and defend it against the criteria. Sitting on the fence scores low.","id":1483},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Command words","text":"The command word tells you how much to write and what shape the answer takes. Tap to expand.","id":1484},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Quick quiz","text":"Six multiple-choice questions. Pick an answer to see instant feedback.","id":1485},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong extended answers follow Point → Evidence → Link . Make your Point (your choice/claim), give Evidence (the criteria and facts), then Link back to the scenario. Type below and watch the meters detect each move.","id":1486},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Live P·E·L detector","text":"Aim to light all three meters. The keyword hints show what each move sounds like.","id":1487},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total, building from Identify to Evaluate . Try each in your head or on paper first, then reveal the weak answer, the strong answer and the marking guide. Use the self-mark buttons — your total appears in the dock. 1 mark: identifies mobile / cellular (4G/5G) . 1 mark: a valid reason — works while moving / wide coverage / only option for a vehicle away from buildings. No mark for \"Wi-Fi\" or \"wireless\" alone (that's a building network). Reliability compared (up to 2): wired stable / no interference vs wireless affected by walls, range, congestion.","id":1488},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Security compared (up to 2): wired needs physical access vs wireless radiates and needs encryption. Must compare (use vs/whereas), not list two separate descriptions, for full marks. 1 mark: wired data is enclosed in a cable / needs physical access. 1 mark: wireless data radiates through open air beyond the building. 1 mark: links this to easier interception / the need for encryption. Choice stated and defended (not just named). Criterion 1 applied with a reason (e.g. reliability — stable/no interference). Criterion 2 applied with a reason (e.g. security — physical access;","id":1489},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"or data — high bandwidth). Top answers note the limitations don't apply here (fixed location). Cost weighed both ways (recurring per-device vs existing shared AP): up to 2. Reliability weighed (5G coverage/congestion vs stable indoor Wi-Fi/wired): up to 2. Security weighed (carrier-encrypted but public/uncontrolled vs controlled office): up to 2. 1 mark: a clear, reasoned recommendation that follows from the analysis. Best answers note mobile still suits the in-car app — the right tool for that purpose.","id":1490},{"file":"u2o2-kk03.html","nav":"u2o2-kk03.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK03","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Wired, wireless & mobile networks","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · U2·O2 Cyber Security · KK03 — Wired, wireless & mobile networks","id":1491},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","text":"The study design asks you to explain the technical underpinnings of the intranet , the internet and virtual private networks (VPNs) . They are easy to confuse — until you see them as three different trade-offs between trust and reach .","id":1492},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Running scenario — SwiftPaws","text":"SwiftPaws is a small Melbourne dog-walking & pet-sitting startup. Customers book walks on a public website. Behind the scenes, an internal staff system stores something genuinely dangerous if leaked: customers' home addresses, gate codes and house-key locations . Walkers are out on the street all day and need to pull up the next address from their phones. That one business creates a textbook need for all three networks — we'll follow it the whole way through. The internet gives you reach (anywhere on Earth) but no trust (it's public). The intranet gives you trust (private, staff-only) but no reach (only inside the building).","id":1493},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Running scenario — SwiftPaws","text":"A VPN hands you both — internet reach with intranet trust — by digging an encrypted tunnel through the public internet. Lock that one sentence in and most KK04 questions answer themselves.","id":1494},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"A global network of networks — public by design","text":"The internet is the worldwide, public system that connects billions of independently-owned networks so they can exchange data using one shared set of rules. Technical underpinnings you must be able to explain: It's a \"network of networks.\" No single owner. Each organisation runs its own network; Internet Service Providers (ISPs) and backbone links join them together so any device can reach any other. Packet switching. A message is broken into small packets . Each packet is routed independently and may take a different path; they are reassembled in order at the destination.","id":1495},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"A global network of networks — public by design","text":"This is what makes the internet resilient — if one link fails, packets reroute around it. The TCP/IP protocol suite. Shared rules every device obeys. IP handles addressing and routing (which device, which path). TCP handles reliable delivery — numbering packets, checking nothing is lost, requesting re-sends, and reassembling them in the right order. IP addresses + routers. Every device has an IP address. Routers read each packet's destination IP and forward it one hop closer, over and over, until it arrives. DNS (Domain Name System). Translates a human name like swiftpaws.com.au into the numeric IP address machines actually use — the internet's \"phone book.\"","id":1496},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Security consequence (this is why it's in a Cyber Security course)","text":"Because internet traffic crosses shared, public infrastructure owned by strangers, it is an untrusted environment. Anything sent unencrypted can potentially be read or altered by whoever handles the packets along the way. That single fact is the reason intranets and VPNs exist. For SwiftPaws, the internet is what lets a customer in Brunswick book a walk, and what lets a walker's phone in Coburg talk to the company's systems at all. It's the reach . The catch is that it offers no built-in privacy.","id":1497},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Lab · Packet switching across the internet","text":"Notice three things: packets take different paths (packet switching), they can arrive out of order and TCP re-orders them, and a lost packet is re-sent rather than failing the whole message.","id":1498},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"A private internet, walled off for one organisation","text":"An intranet uses the same technologies as the internet — TCP/IP, web browsers, web servers, links — but it is private : restricted to the authorised members of a single organisation. Technical underpinnings: Same toolkit, closed audience. Staff open a browser and visit internal sites (rosters, policies, the customer database) exactly as they'd browse the web — but those sites live on internal servers and aren't published to the world. Private addressing behind a firewall . The intranet sits behind a firewall that blocks unsolicited traffic from the public internet.","id":1499},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"A private internet, walled off for one organisation","text":"Internal devices typically use private IP addresses that aren't reachable from outside. Authentication & access control. You must log in with an authorised account; non-staff simply have no way in. Bounded = trusted. Because membership is controlled and traffic stays inside the organisation, the intranet is treated as a trusted zone. This is the opposite trade-off to the internet. SwiftPaws' intranet is where the dangerous data lives — the addresses, gate codes and key locations . Keeping that on a private, firewalled intranet rather than the open web is the first line of defence.","id":1500},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"A private internet, walled off for one organisation","text":"The intranet is the trust . Its limitation: by default you can only reach it from inside the office network — useless to a walker standing in someone's driveway. An intranet is not \"a different internet.\" It's the same internet technology deployed privately for one organisation. Think of it as the internet's rules and tools, used inside a locked building.","id":1501},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"The secure tunnel that joins the two","text":"A VPN creates a private, encrypted connection — a \"tunnel\" — across the public internet , so a remote device can reach a private intranet safely, as if it were physically plugged in at the office. Technical underpinnings: Tunnelling ( encapsulation ). The VPN wraps each of your normal packets inside another packet — like sealing a letter inside an opaque, locked outer envelope before it goes through the public post. Encryption . The contents of the tunnel are encrypted, so anyone intercepting the traffic on the internet sees only scrambled, meaningless data — not the address or gate code inside.","id":1502},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"The secure tunnel that joins the two","text":"Authentication of endpoints. Both ends prove who they are before the tunnel forms, so an outsider can't just connect to the intranet by pretending to be staff. Secure remote access. The result: a SwiftPaws walker on café Wi-Fi or 4G can connect to the company VPN and then reach the internal customer database as though they were in the office — across the untrusted internet, but protected. Virtual — there's no real dedicated cable to the office; the private link is simulated over the shared internet. Private — encryption + authentication make that simulated link behave like a private, trusted connection. A VPN is how SwiftPaws gets reach and trust at the same time.","id":1503},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"👁 What the eavesdropper on the Wi-Fi captures","text":"Same internet, same café, same eavesdropper. The only change is the encrypted VPN tunnel — and that's the difference between leaking a customer's home address & gate code and leaking nothing usable at all.","id":1504},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Compare the three — then sort them yourself","text":"If you can fill this table from memory, you can answer almost any KK04 comparison question. Characteristic Internet Intranet VPN Scope / reach Global, anyone One organisation, internal Remote user → that organisation's intranet Who can access The public Authorised members only Authenticated remote staff Ownership No single owner (ISPs + many networks) The organisation Provided/configured by the organisation Trust level Untrusted (public) Trusted (private) Makes an untrusted path behave as trusted Encryption built in? No (unless added, e.g. HTTPS) Not inherently — relies on being closed Yes — encryption is the whole point Core technique Packet switching + TCP/IP Same tech, firewalled & private Tunnelling (encapsulation) + encryption SwiftPaws role Public booking site; the carrier for everything Internal store of addresses & gate codes Lets walkers reach that store safely from the field","id":1505},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Sort it: which network does each statement describe?","text":"Drag each card into the matching bin. On a touch screen, tap a card then tap a bin.","id":1506},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"One analogy, three roles — tap to flip","text":"The public-mail analogy carries all three concepts at once. Tap each card to reveal how it maps back to the technology.","id":1507},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🌐 Internet = the public postal system","text":"Anyone can post anything anywhere. Cheap, global, reliable delivery — but a postcard can be read by every postie who handles it.","id":1508},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"↳ The technology","text":"Shared public infrastructure + packet switching. Huge reach, zero built-in privacy — unencrypted data is a readable postcard.","id":1509},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🏢 Intranet = a members-only building","text":"Locked doors, a staff pass at reception. Documents pinned to the wall inside can't be seen from the street — but you must be physically in the building .","id":1510},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"↳ The technology","text":"Private, firewalled network with logins. Trusted because it's closed — but only reachable from inside.","id":1511},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🛡 VPN = an armoured security van","text":"Your parcel still drives the public roads , but sealed inside a locked, opaque van only the destination can open. Thieves see a van, not the contents.","id":1512},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"↳ The technology","text":"Tunnelling + encryption over the public internet. You get the road network's reach with a private, trusted ride.","id":1513},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Trap 1 · \"An intranet is a smaller internet\"","text":"Wrong framing. Don't define it by size. Define it by access: a private network for one organisation, using the same technologies as the internet but restricted to authorised users.","id":1514},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Trap 2 · Saying a VPN \"hides your identity\" and stopping there","text":"In this course the examinable point is secure remote access via an encrypted tunnel — it lets remote staff reach a private intranet safely across the public internet. Lead with tunnelling + encryption, not vague \"anonymity.\"","id":1515},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Trap 3 · Confusing the VPN with the intranet","text":"The VPN is not the destination — it's the secure path to the destination. Walkers connect through the VPN to the intranet. The VPN protects the journey; the intranet holds the data.","id":1516},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Trap 4 · Treating the internet as automatically secure","text":"The internet's design goal is reach and resilience, not privacy . Always name it as untrusted/public. That's the springboard for justifying a VPN.","id":1517},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Trap 5 · Listing features with no link to the scenario","text":"\"Explain\" and \"justify\" questions want the consequence . Don't just say \"a VPN encrypts data.\" Say why it matters here : without it, an eavesdropper on public Wi-Fi could capture a customer's home address and gate code.","id":1518},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"Build a full-mark answer, live","text":"Strong VCE responses follow P·E·L — Point, Evidence/Explain, Link. Type your answer below; the trainer lights up each key idea an examiner is hunting for. Aim to light them all.","id":1519},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"VCE-style questions — with weak vs strong responses","text":"Try each one in your head (or on paper) first. Then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide. Mark your own attempt — your score builds in the dock. Define the term intranet . Distinguish between the internet and an intranet. A SwiftPaws walker uses café Wi-Fi to look up a customer's address. Explain how a VPN lets them reach the company intranet securely over the internet. A SwiftPaws manager claims: “We send everything over the internet, so our customers' data is already protected.” Evaluate this claim.","id":1520},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"VCE-style questions — with weak vs strong responses","text":"SwiftPaws wants walkers to read customers' addresses and gate codes from their phones while out on the street. Recommend a network solution and justify it, referring to the internet, the intranet and a VPN.","id":1521},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🌐 Internet","text":"Global, public network of networks. Packet switching + TCP/IP. Massive reach, untrusted by default.","id":1522},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🏢 Intranet","text":"Same tech, deployed privately for one organisation behind a firewall. Trusted, but only reachable from inside.","id":1523},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🛡 VPN","text":"An encrypted tunnel across the internet. Gives remote staff secure access to the intranet — reach and trust.","id":1524},{"file":"u2o2-kk04.html","nav":"u2o2-kk04.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK04","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Three networks, one question: who do you trust, and how far can you reach?","head":"🔑 The link","text":"Internet = reach, no trust. Intranet = trust, no reach. VPN = both, via tunnelling + encryption.","id":1525},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","text":"Three letters in front of \"AN\" decide how far a network reaches, how fast it runs, who owns it, and how exposed your data is. This dot point is about matching the right network type to the right job — and being able to defend that choice in an exam. The letter L , W , or WP tells you the geographic scale of the network. Scale then drives every capability examiners ask about: range, speed, ownership, cost, number of devices, and security exposure . Answer with those words and you're answering the dot point — not just naming a gadget.","id":1526},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","text":"We'll keep following Clutch , the Melbourne learner-driver app from KK01–KK04 (~40,000 teenage users). One company touches all three network types at once: a head office in Carlton, the internet reaching every learner's phone, and the gear inside a learner's car . Same company, three scales.","id":1527},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"01 The big idea: it's about scale, not cables","text":"Students lose marks here by sorting networks into \"wired\" and \"wireless.\" That's the wrong axis. LAN, WAN and WPAN are sorted by geographic reach — how much physical space the network covers. Cables vs radio is a separate question (and a LAN can be either). Think about how far your voice carries. A WPAN is a whisper — only someone right next to you hears it (your earbuds, your watch). A LAN is talking across a room or a building — everyone in the house hears, no one outside does.","id":1528},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"01 The big idea: it's about scale, not cables","text":"A WAN is a phone call to another city — your words travel across infrastructure you don't own to reach someone far away. The technology differs, but what really changes is how far it reaches . Picture the three scales as nested rings. Each ring out means more distance, more devices, more shared infrastructure — and a bigger surface for an attacker to reach.","id":1529},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"02 LAN — Local Area Network one site","text":"A LAN connects devices within a single physical location — a home, an office floor, a school, a hospital wing. One organisation (or person) owns and manages all the equipment: the switches, the cabling, the Wi-Fi access points, the local servers.","id":1530},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Clutch in real life","text":"Clutch's Carlton head office is a textbook LAN. About 30 staff plug their desktops into wall sockets that run to a switch in a comms cupboard; a couple of Wi-Fi access points cover the meeting rooms; a local file server holds project files. Everything lives in one building and Clutch owns all of it, so an internal Figma export moves between two designers at full gigabit speed without ever touching the internet. A LAN is like an intercom system inside one building . Press a button and your voice is instantly in the next room — fast, free, private.","id":1531},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Clutch in real life","text":"But the intercom stops at the front door. To reach the Geelong office you need a different system entirely: a phone line out (that's the WAN). Wired or wireless? A LAN that uses Wi-Fi instead of cables is called a WLAN (Wireless LAN). It's still a LAN — same site, same owner — just delivered over radio. Don't confuse a WLAN with a WPAN: the WLAN covers the building ; the WPAN covers the person .","id":1532},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"03 WAN — Wide Area Network global","text":"A WAN spans a large geographic area — between cities, states, or right around the globe. A WAN's job is to join separate LANs together so they act like one network. Crucially, no single organisation owns the whole path: you lease connectivity from telcos and your data crosses infrastructure other people control. The internet is a WAN — in fact it's the world's largest one: a \"network of networks\" linking millions of LANs. Whenever an exam scenario mentions \"over the internet,\" \"to the cloud,\" or \"between branches in different cities,\" you're looking at a WAN.","id":1533},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Clutch in real life","text":"Clutch is a WAN business. Its app reaches 40,000 phones spread across the whole state — and the only thing that can carry data that far is the internet (a WAN). The Carlton LAN talks to Clutch's cloud servers over a WAN link, and a small Geelong support office joins the company network across the same WAN. Because that traffic leaves the building and crosses networks Clutch doesn't own, it must be encrypted — which is exactly why KK04 covered VPNs. A LAN is your driveway: short, private, yours. A WAN is the public road system — it'll take you anywhere in the country, but you share it with everyone, you don't own it, you pay tolls and rego, and it's slower and riskier than your own driveway. So you lock the car (encryption) before driving on it.","id":1534},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"04 WPAN — Wireless Personal Area Network ~10 m","text":"A WPAN is the smallest network type: a short-range wireless bubble — usually only a few metres — around one person and their devices. It's built for low power and convenience , not for speed or distance. The classic technologies are Bluetooth , NFC (tap-to-pay, ~4 cm) and Zigbee (smart-home sensors).","id":1535},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Clutch in real life","text":"The WPAN lives inside the learner's car . The student's phone runs the Clutch app and pairs over Bluetooth to a hands-free car kit so route prompts play through the speakers; a paired smartwatch buzzes a gentle alert at hazard zones so the learner never looks down; an optional OBD-II Bluetooth dongle streams live speed to the app. All of that is one person's bubble of devices — a textbook WPAN — and none of it reaches past the car. A WPAN is the arm's-length bubble around you. Your earbuds, watch and phone gossip among themselves, but the conversation can't be overheard from across the street.","id":1536},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Clutch in real life","text":"That tiny range is the whole point: it keeps power use and interference low, and it keeps the chatter personal. Turn on your phone's Bluetooth tethering or pair it to a wireless speaker — you've just stood up a working WPAN. Tap your card on an EFTPOS terminal and that's NFC, a WPAN too. The study design literally suggests building one with a phone or an old wireless router to feel how short the range is.","id":1537},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"05 Network Scale Lab","text":"Pick a network type below and watch Clutch's data appear at that scale. The scorecard on the right shows the capabilities examiners reward — range, speed, cost and devices — so you can see how each one trades off against the others. As you step WPAN → LAN → WAN , the range meter fills and the data travels further — but speed drops and cost climbs once traffic leaves the building. Flip on Show attack surface and watch how many more points an attacker can reach as the network widens. That growing exposure is the reason this dot point sits inside Cyber Security .","id":1538},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"06 Capabilities side by side","text":"This is the table to know cold. In a \"compare\" question, pick two or three of these rows and contrast them — never answer on a single dimension like speed alone. Capability WPAN LAN WAN Geographic range ~10 m (one person) One site (≤ ~1 km) Unlimited (global) Typical speed Low Very high Moderate, higher latency Who owns it The individual One organisation No single owner Cost to run Near zero Low (no carrier fees) High (ongoing fees) Number of devices A few personal gadgets Tens to hundreds Effectively limitless Core technology Bluetooth, NFC, Zigbee Ethernet + Wi-Fi (WLAN) Leased lines, fibre, internet Clutch example Phone ↔ watch in the car Carlton office network App → 40,000 phones Security focus Pairing / PIN Physical + access control Encrypt in transit (VPN/TLS) Memory hook — read the meters left to right: WPAN = smallest everything; LAN = fastest, cheapest to run, one owner; WAN = biggest reach but slowest, priciest and most exposed.","id":1539},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"07 Sort the scenarios","text":"Tap a chip, then tap the bin where it belongs. Each one is a real situation an exam might describe — decide the network type by how far it reaches .","id":1540},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"08 Flip cards — lock in the definitions","text":"Tap a card to check yourself. Front = the prompt; back = the answer an examiner wants.","id":1541},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"What is a LAN?","text":"A network covering a single site (building/campus), owned and managed by one organisation. High speed, low running cost. e.g. Clutch's Carlton office.","id":1542},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"What is a WAN?","text":"A network spanning a large area (cities → globe) that joins many LANs. No single owner; uses leased lines/the internet. e.g. Clutch's app reaching 40,000 phones.","id":1543},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"What is a WPAN?","text":"A short-range wireless network (~10 m) around one person's devices. Bluetooth/NFC/Zigbee, low power. e.g. phone ↔ watch ↔ car kit.","id":1544},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"WLAN vs WPAN?","text":"WLAN = a wireless LAN (Wi-Fi) covering a building . WPAN = Bluetooth/NFC covering a person (~10 m). Different scale entirely.","id":1545},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"What kind of network is the internet?","text":"A WAN — the largest one. It's a 'network of networks'. If a scenario says 'over the internet', it's a WAN.","id":1546},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Which has the highest typical speed?","text":"The LAN . Data stays local over short cables (often 1–10 Gbps), so there's no carrier link or long-distance latency to slow it down.","id":1547},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Which costs the most to run, and why?","text":"The WAN — you pay ongoing fees to telcos for leased lines and data because you don't own the long-distance infrastructure.","id":1548},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"Why is 'scale' a security issue?","text":"Wider reach = bigger attack surface . WPAN is small/local; the WAN crosses untrusted networks, so data must be encrypted in transit (TLS/VPN).","id":1549},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"09 Why this lives in Cyber Security","text":"It can feel like a networking-trivia dot point, but it's in the Cyber Security outcome for a real reason: scale is risk . The wider a network reaches and the more shared infrastructure it crosses, the larger its attack surface — the number of places an attacker could get in.","id":1550},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"WPAN risk","text":"Short range shrinks the threat, but an attacker within metres can still try bluesnarfing or hijack an unpaired device. Defence: secure pairing, PINs, turn Bluetooth off when unused.","id":1551},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"LAN risk","text":"One breached device sits inside the trust boundary , past the firewall . Defence: physical security, access control, segment the network, secure the Wi-Fi (WPA3).","id":1552},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"WAN risk","text":"Data crosses networks nobody you trust controls — open to interception in transit. Defence: encrypt everything end-to-end with TLS and VPNs . Choosing a network type is also a security decision . Keeping sensitive data on the LAN limits exposure; the moment it must travel over the WAN , encryption stops being optional. Saying that out loud is what separates a top-band answer from a list of definitions.","id":1553},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"10 Decode the command word","text":"The command word tells you what the marker actually wants. Tap each to expand.","id":1554},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"11 Quick quiz","text":"Six multiple-choice checks. Pick an answer to see instant feedback — wrong picks explain the trap.","id":1555},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"12 P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Most network questions are worth 2–4 marks, and the structure that banks them is P·E·L : make your Point , give the Evidence/Explanation , then Link it back to the scenario. Write a response below and watch the keyword tracker light up as you hit the ideas a marker is looking for. Name the network type and the capability you're using to judge it (range, speed, cost…). Say why — give the technical reason that capability is true. Tie it to the actual scenario and what the user needs. P:","id":1556},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"12 P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Use a WAN — specifically the mobile (4G/5G) carrier network — for the car-to-internet link. E: The cars are moving across the whole state, far beyond any single site, and only a WAN has the geographic range to reach head office from anywhere; mobile data is the only WAN access a moving car can use. L: Because that data crosses public infrastructure Clutch doesn't own, it must be encrypted in transit , so Clutch streams it over a secured/VPN connection to protect the learners' footage.","id":1557},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"13 Exam practice — 5 questions · 20 marks","text":"Each question shows a weak and a strong sample answer, then a marking guide. Mark your own attempt honestly — your score builds in the dock in the corner. 1 mark: short-range wireless network around one person (~10 m) / names Bluetooth-type tech 1 mark: a correct device example (earbuds, smartwatch, fitness band, car Bluetooth, NFC tap) 1 mark each (×2) for naming a relevant LAN capability — high speed, low cost, single ownership, easy security, no carrier fees 1 mark each (×2) for explaining WHY that capability follows from the LAN being local/one-site, tied to the office 1 mark:","id":1558},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"13 Exam practice — 5 questions · 20 marks","text":"range contrast (single site vs global) 1 mark: speed contrast (LAN faster / local vs WAN slower / distance + shared links) 1 mark: cost contrast (LAN no carrier fees vs WAN ongoing fees) 1 mark: genuine comparative structure across all three (not three isolated statements) 1 mark: recommends a WAN / mobile (4G/5G) network 1 mark: justifies via range — cars move across the state, beyond any single site 1 mark: rules out alternatives (LAN/WLAN = one site, WPAN = ~10 m) 1 mark: notes the security implication of crossing untrusted networks (encrypt/VPN) 1–2 marks:","id":1559},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"13 Exam practice — 5 questions · 20 marks","text":"explains that the three tasks sit at different scales (WPAN / LAN / WAN) with capabilities 1 mark: shows why one type can't serve all (e.g. WPAN can't span the state; WAN wasteful on one site) 1 mark: fairly notes the upside of the manager's view (simpler management/security) 1 mark: weighs both sides 1 mark: clear, justified judgement (reject the claim, match network to task) Cover the answers, write your own response first, then reveal. Compare against the marking guide, award yourself marks, and tap your score. The weak answers aren't empty — they're the near-misses that lose marks, so learn to spot why.","id":1560},{"file":"u2o2-kk05.html","nav":"u2o2-kk05.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK05","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"LANs, WANs & WPANs","head":"15 One-screen cheat sheet","text":"Digital Vector · VCE Applied Computing Units 1 & 2 · U2·O2 Cyber Security · KK05 — LANs, WANs & WPANs","id":1561},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","text":"Above: PixelPort , run from a bedroom in Melbourne, with players, servers and a payment processor scattered across the globe. Spin the planet and switch on each layer — every line is something that has to stay safe and legal in more than one country at once.","id":1562},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"A local network has walls. A global network has borders.","text":"A network kept inside one building has a clear edge: a handful of doors you can lock and watch. The instant that network reaches across the internet to users, cloud servers and services in other countries, the edge disappears. You are now exposed to everyone, everywhere, all the time — and you are now answerable to the laws of more than one country . The VCAA study design asks you to discuss the risks and benefits of using networks in a global environment . Don't reduce this to \"hackers are bad.\" Examiners want you to see four distinct risk fronts that specifically get worse once a network goes global — and to weigh them honestly against the very real benefits that pushed the organisation global in the first place.","id":1563},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Analogy · the corner shop vs the 24/7 global storefront","text":"A corner shop closes at 6pm, knows its regulars, and only has to obey local council rules. Put that shop online and open it to the world: it never closes, anyone on Earth can walk in, you can be robbed while you sleep by someone you'll never identify, and you suddenly have to obey the consumer and privacy laws of every country your customers live in. Same shop, radically bigger risk surface — and a much bigger market.","id":1564},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Meet PixelPort","text":"PixelPort is an indie-game storefront and community built by Aanya, a Year 12 student in Melbourne. Players around the world create accounts, download games, post on forums and buy in-game items. Players in Australia, the Philippines, Brazil, Germany and the USA — accounts, profiles, chat, ages and locations. Game files & the database live on a cloud provider with data centres in Singapore and Virginia (USA) — chosen because it's cheap and fast. Payments are handled by an overseas payment company , so card details travel offshore. A global CDN (content delivery network) copies game files to servers worldwide so downloads are quick everywhere.","id":1565},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Meet PixelPort","text":"Every convenience in that list is also a doorway. We'll use PixelPort to make each risk concrete — and to ask the real exam question: is going global worth it?","id":1566},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"The four risk fronts of a global network","text":"These are the four risk areas named for this dotpoint. Tap a card to flip it and see how it bites PixelPort specifically.","id":1567},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"When a single packet crosses a border","text":"Follow one player's sign-up. The moment their data leaves Australia, it falls under another country's rules — and Australian privacy law still follows it. Watch the packet travel from Melbourne to the overseas data centre. This is the heart of the privacy and compliance risk. Under the Australian Privacy Principles , APP 8 (cross-border disclosure) says that before you send personal information overseas you must take reasonable steps to ensure the overseas recipient handles it the way Australian law requires — and you can stay accountable for what happens to it there.","id":1568},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"When a single packet crosses a border","text":"APP 11 still requires you to keep it secure. So \"the cloud provider's data centre is overseas\" is never an excuse: the obligation travels with the data. Students write \"the data is in another country so Australian law doesn't apply.\" Wrong. If an Australian organisation collects the data, Australian privacy obligations follow it across the border. Going global adds legal duties, it doesn't remove them.","id":1569},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Risks vs benefits — weigh them honestly","text":"The dotpoint says risks and benefits . A top-band answer never lists only the scary half. Aanya didn't go global to be reckless — she went global because the upside is enormous. Examiners reward students who can hold both sides and then make a judgement .","id":1570},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"● Benefits of going global","text":"Global market. A bedroom project can reach millions of players in dozens of countries — impossible from a local-only network. 24/7 availability. The store never closes; someone is always able to buy and play. Cheap, scalable cloud. Pay only for what you use; handle a launch-day spike without owning servers. Speed & reliability via CDN. Files are copied worldwide, so downloads are fast and one server failing doesn't take the store down. Access to global services & talent. Overseas payment, hosting and collaborators are a click away.","id":1571},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"● Risks of going global","text":"Bigger attack surface. Reachable by every attacker on Earth, all day, every day. Loss of data control. Personal data sits in countries with different (sometimes weaker) protections. Tangled compliance. Must satisfy several countries' laws at once; mistakes mean heavy fines. Harder to investigate. Attackers in other jurisdictions are difficult to trace and prosecute. Dependency on others. An overseas provider's outage or breach instantly becomes your outage or breach.","id":1572},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Sort the incident","text":"Five headlines hit PixelPort. For each, pick which of the four risk fronts it best illustrates. Instant feedback explains why.","id":1573},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Exam traps that cost easy marks","text":"\"DDoS is a risk\" earns little. Say what happens and why global makes it worse : \"a globally-distributed botnet floods the login server, and because attackers are overseas they're hard to trace.\" Cause → effect → the global twist. If the command word is discuss / evaluate and you only list risks, you've answered half the question. Always weigh both sides, then judge. The opposite is true. Storing data offshore adds obligations (APP 8 cross-border disclosure) — it never cancels Australian privacy law. A DDoS is a threat/attack ; an account takeover is unauthorised access .","id":1574},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Exam traps that cost easy marks","text":"Answer the front the question actually names. If asked for a mitigation, name it and link it to the specific risk: \"multi-factor authentication stops credential stuffing because a stolen password alone is no longer enough to log in.\"","id":1575},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Most short-answer marks are won with a simple spine: make a Point , ground it in an Example (use PixelPort), then Link back to the question. Try it below — the tracker lights up as your answer hits each move.","id":1576},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"Practice prompt","text":"\"Explain one data-privacy risk that arises because PixelPort stores player data on overseas servers, and describe one strategy to reduce it.\" (3 marks)","id":1577},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"Each question shows a weak and a strong response so you can see exactly what separates the bands. Read the marking guide, then mark your own attempt — your score builds in the dock. 1 mark — names a specific, relevant threat (e.g. DDoS, malware, phishing). 1 mark — explains how the global network makes it worse (reachable worldwide / 24-7 / distributed / hard to trace). 1 — identifies a genuine privacy risk (loss of control / foreign access / unclear who can read it). 1 — explains the mechanism — why storing offshore causes it.","id":1578},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1 — applies it to PixelPort with a consequence (minors' data, cross-border disclosure / APP 8). 2 marks — one benefit, described and applied to PixelPort (market reach / 24-7 / scalable cloud / CDN speed-reliability). 2 marks — one risk, described and applied to PixelPort (attack surface / compliance / loss of control). 2 marks — explains a mechanism of unauthorised access (credential stuffing / account takeover / man-in-the-middle interception on the long link). 2 marks — names a strategy (MFA / encryption in transit / rate-limiting) and links it to that mechanism.","id":1579},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"VCE-style practice questions","text":"1–2 — benefits of global operation, applied to PixelPort. 1–2 — risks of global operation, applied to PixelPort (across more than one front). 1 — considers the alternative (single Australian server) and its trade-offs. 1 — a clear, justified recommendation (a conditional judgement scores top).","id":1580},{"file":"u2o2-kk06.html","nav":"u2o2-kk06.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK06","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Risks & benefits of networks in a global environment","head":"The five things to walk into the exam with","text":"Four risk fronts: cyber security threats · data privacy · legal compliance · unauthorised access — each gets worse when a network goes global. Always weigh benefits too: global market, 24/7 uptime, scalable cloud, CDN speed/resilience, global services. Cause → effect → global twist is the recipe for a full-mark risk explanation. Offshore ≠ off the hook: Australian privacy duties (APP 8 cross-border disclosure, APP 11 security) follow the data overseas. Finish with a judgement on discuss/evaluate questions — ideally a conditional one (\"stay global provided …\").","id":1581},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Malware","text":"The technical underpinnings of spyware , viruses , worms and ransomware — what each one actually is , how it gets in, and how it behaves once it’s there.","id":1582},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Running scenario · PixelPit Esports Lounge","text":"PixelPit is a suburban Melbourne gaming café. Its small network has 16 gaming rigs on a LAN, a counter PC that runs bookings, payroll and card payments, a public booking website , and a NAS (network storage) holding the membership database and tournament videos. Over one chaotic month, PixelPit gets hit by all four malware types. We’ll use each incident to unpack how that malware works. VCAA lists this dot point as the “technical underpinnings of spyware, viruses, worms and ransomware.” The examiner’s word here is underpinnings — they want the mechanism , not just “it’s bad software.” By the end you should be able to say, for any of the four, how it spreads , whether it needs a user to do something , and what it’s trying to achieve .","id":1583},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"What is malware?","text":"Malware (short for malicious software ) is any program written to harm, exploit or gain unauthorised access to a device, network or its data. It’s an umbrella term — spyware, viruses, worms and ransomware are all kinds of malware, the way “sedan” and “ute” are kinds of car. In everyday speech people call every infection a “virus.” In a VCE answer that costs marks. A virus is one specific type with specific behaviour. If a question asks you to identify a malware type, name the precise one (worm, ransomware, spyware…) and justify it from how it behaves.","id":1584},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"What is malware?","text":"Three questions separate the four types. Keep them in your head — they are the spine of almost every malware answer: Does it need a host? Must it attach to another file/program to exist, or is it standalone? Does it need a user to act? Must someone open, run or click something for it to spread — or does it spread by itself? What’s the goal? Spy and steal information, damage/replicate, spread and consume resources, or lock data for a ransom?","id":1585},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Spyware","text":"Spyware hides on a device and secretly monitors activity , gathering information — keystrokes, screenshots, browsing history, login details — and transmits it to a third party without the user’s knowledge or consent. Its goal is surveillance and data theft , not destruction. It usually doesn’t need to replicate; it just needs to stay hidden and keep reporting back.","id":1586},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"How it works — step by step","text":"1 Delivery. Usually bundled with something that looks legitimate — a “free” download, a cracked game, a dodgy browser extension — so the user installs it themselves (a trojan delivery). 2 Hide & persist. Runs quietly as a background process, often disguised, and sets itself to start with the system. 3 Collect. A keylogger records every keystroke; other variants capture screens, webcam, clipboard or browser data. 4 Exfiltrate. Periodically sends the harvested data over the network to the attacker’s server.","id":1587},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"PixelPit incident","text":"A regular installs a “free aim-trainer” on rig 7. Bundled inside is a keylogger . It does nothing visible — no crashes, no pop-ups. But every time a staff member logs into the booking system or types a customer’s card number at the counter PC, the keystrokes are quietly captured and posted to an overseas server. Nobody notices for weeks because nothing breaks — that silence is the whole point. Spyware is a hidden CCTV camera a burglar installs in your house . It doesn’t smash anything or steal furniture — it just watches, and quietly streams the footage out. You’re robbed of information , and you may never see a broken window.","id":1588},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Virus","text":"A virus is malicious code that attaches itself to a legitimate host file or program . It stays dormant until that host is opened or run by a user — that user action is what activates it. Once active it replicates by inserting copies of itself into other files, and may run a payload that corrupts or deletes data.","id":1589},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"How it works — step by step","text":"1 Attach. The virus embeds itself inside a host — an .exe , a macro inside a document/spreadsheet, a script. 2 Wait. It stays inert. Copying the infected file around does not trigger it. 3 Trigger (user action!). A user opens or runs the host . Only now does the virus code execute. 4 Replicate. It writes copies of itself into other files on that machine. 5 Payload. It may corrupt files, delete data, or open a backdoor.","id":1590},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"PixelPit incident","text":"A “sponsor” emails tournament_bracket.xlsm . It carries a macro virus . Sitting in the inbox it’s harmless. The moment a staff member opens it and enables macros , the virus runs, copies itself into other spreadsheets on the counter PC, and scrambles the cells in the takings file. The key detail for the exam: nothing happened until a human clicked . Like a biological virus : it can’t do anything floating in the air. It needs to get inside a host cell (the file) and have that cell become active before it can hijack the machinery and make copies of itself.","id":1591},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Worm","text":"A worm is standalone malware — it doesn’t need a host file. It self-replicates and spreads across networks automatically , with no user action required , by exploiting vulnerabilities (e.g. unpatched software). As it multiplies it consumes bandwidth and system resources , slowing or crashing the network, and it can carry a payload such as installing a backdoor or dropping ransomware.","id":1592},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"How it works — step by step","text":"1 Entry. Slips onto one machine through an unpatched vulnerability or open network port. 2 Scan. Automatically scans the network for other reachable, vulnerable devices. 3 Self-replicate. Copies itself to each one without anyone clicking anything . 4 Repeat. Each newly infected machine becomes a new launch point — spread is exponential . 5 Impact / payload. Bandwidth and CPU get eaten alive; an optional payload does further damage.","id":1593},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"PixelPit incident","text":"One rig is months behind on updates. A worm exploits that hole at 2am. By open the next morning it has copied itself across all 16 rigs and the counter PC — nobody touched a thing overnight . The rigs are crawling because the worm is hammering the network scanning for more targets. This is the line students must hold: a worm needs neither a host file nor a user . That’s exactly what separates it from a virus. A worm is a chain letter that posts itself . A virus needs you to lick the stamp and mail it on. A worm finds every address in the building and sends itself to all of them while you sleep.","id":1594},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Ransomware","text":"Ransomware encrypts the victim’s files (or locks the whole device) using cryptography , then demands a ransom — usually in cryptocurrency — in exchange for the decryption key. Its goal is extortion through denial of access : the data is still there, you just can’t read it. It’s often delivered by phishing or by a worm, and modern variants steal a copy of the data first and threaten to leak it (“double extortion”).","id":1595},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"How it works — step by step","text":"1 Delivery. Arrives via a phishing attachment, a malicious download, or as a worm’s payload. 2 (Optional) exfiltrate. Quietly copies sensitive data out first — leverage for “pay or we publish.” 3 Encrypt. Uses strong encryption to scramble files; the key is held only by the attacker. 4 Demand. Displays a ransom note with a deadline and a cryptocurrency wallet address. 5 Pressure. A countdown threatens permanent loss or a price rise to force a fast decision.","id":1596},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"PixelPit incident","text":"The worm’s payload was ransomware. It reaches the NAS and encrypts the membership database and every tournament video. A note appears: “Your files are encrypted. Pay 0.4 BTC in 72 hours or lose them forever.” PixelPit can’t take bookings, can’t prove who’s a member, and the footage for the regional final is locked. The fix that would have saved them isn’t paying — it’s an offline backup (KK09). Ransomware is a thief who puts their own padlock on your locker and slides a note through the vent: pay up for the key.","id":1597},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"PixelPit incident","text":"Your stuff is still inside — you just can’t get to it. And a spare key kept at home (your backup) makes the whole threat collapse. Notice how the types combine : a worm delivered the ransomware, and spyware-style exfiltration powered the double-extortion threat. Real incidents blend mechanisms — examiners love a scenario where you have to untangle which type did what.","id":1598},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Compare & contrast","text":"This table is the single most exam-useful thing on the page. The virus-vs-worm row in particular comes up again and again. Type Needs a host file? Needs user action to spread? Self-replicates? Primary goal Spyware No (installed once, then runs) No (usually) Covertly gather & steal information Virus Yes Yes — user opens/runs the host Yes Replicate & damage/corrupt files Worm No — spreads by itself Yes Spread fast; consume resources; carry payload Ransomware Often (phishing) — or none if worm-delivered No (it’s the payload) Encrypt data & extort payment Spyware watches. Virus needs a host and a click. Worm needs neither — it crawls the network alone. Ransomware locks your data and asks for money.","id":1599},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Infection Spread Simulator","text":"This is PixelPit’s network in 3D: the counter PC (front), 16 gaming rigs , the NAS , and an external attacker server . Pick a malware type, hit Release , and watch how each one behaves differently . The point isn’t the animation — it’s seeing why a worm turns the whole room red on its own while a virus only moves when you click. In Virus mode the infection only moves when you click an infected machine to “share a file” . In Worm mode you click Release once and then sit back — it spreads with zero further clicks. That difference is worth marks in “distinguish a virus from a worm” questions.","id":1600},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Exam practice","text":"Short-answer style modelled on VCAA Applied Computing questions. Read the question, attempt it on paper, then open the responses and self-mark honestly — your marks feed the score dock in the corner. Identify the category of malware and explain how it operates to steal the card details. Explain the technical underpinnings of ransomware (2 marks) and describe one reason it is especially damaging to PixelPit, and the single control that would best protect it (2 marks). Identify the most likely malware type and justify your choice using two pieces of evidence from the scenario.","id":1601},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Writing trainer","text":"VCAA answers reward structure . Use P·E·L : make a Point , give Evidence (a technical detail or scenario example), then Link back to the question. Type a response below — the chips light up as you hit the technical terms an examiner looks for. P: “A virus and a worm differ mainly in…” · E: “Specifically, a virus… whereas a worm…” · L: “This matters for PixelPit because…”","id":1602},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Spyware","text":"Covertly monitors and gathers information (e.g. a keylogger) and transmits it to a third party. Goal: silent data theft. No symptoms by design.","id":1603},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Virus","text":"Attaches to a host file; dormant until a user opens/runs it ; then replicates into other files and may corrupt data.","id":1604},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Worm","text":"Standalone; self-replicates across networks with no user action by exploiting vulnerabilities; consumes resources; can carry a payload.","id":1605},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Ransomware","text":"Encrypts data and demands a ransom (usually cryptocurrency) for the key. Best defence: offline backups.","id":1606},{"file":"u2o2-kk07.html","nav":"u2o2-kk07.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK07","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Malware","head":"Glossary — examiner wording","text":"KK07 names the threats; KK08 sets them among the wider security threats, and KK09 (reducing risk — patching, MFA, backups, updates) is where you explain how PixelPit stops each one. Quote backups against ransomware and patching against worms and you’re connecting dot points the way top responses do.","id":1607},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Security threats","text":"Clutch is a Melbourne-built learner-driver app used by about 40,000 teenagers across Victoria. It logs driving hours, books lessons, stores licence details and pings parents when a session ends. Its servers live in a Carlton data-centre rack; staff work off laptops from home; the app talks to the cloud from inside moving cars. That makes Clutch a juicy target — and a perfect lab for spotting where threats actually land. A security threat is any potential cause of an unwanted event that could harm a network, its data, or the people who rely on it.","id":1608},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Security threats","text":"This dot point names five of them. Your job in the exam is not just to define each one — it's to recognise it inside a case study and explain the damage it does. Let's get the vocabulary straight first, because examiners punish students who blur it.","id":1609},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Threat vs vulnerability vs risk","text":"These three words are not synonyms, and a case-study question will often hand you all three in the same paragraph to see whether you can tell them apart. Lock this in now: The threat is a burglar in your neighbourhood. The vulnerability is your unlocked back window. The risk is how likely the burglar is to try your house and how much you'd lose if they did. Fixing the window (the vulnerability) is usually the only thing you control — you can't make the burglar disappear. If a question says \" identify a security threat in this scenario \", it wants the thing that could go wrong (e.g.","id":1610},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Threat vs vulnerability vs risk","text":"\"a denial-of-service attack\"), not the weakness (\"the server is slow\") and not the consequence (\"users can't log in\"). Name the threat using the study-design vocabulary, then explain the weakness it exploits and the harm it causes.","id":1611},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Denial-of-service (DoS & DDoS) attacks","text":"A denial-of-service (DoS) attack deliberately overwhelms a server, service or network with so much traffic or so many bogus requests that it can no longer respond to legitimate users. The attacker isn't usually stealing data — they're making the service unavailable . When the flood comes from one machine it's a DoS; when it comes from thousands of hijacked devices at once (a botnet ), it's a distributed denial-of-service — DDoS , which is far harder to block because there's no single source to switch off. Imagine 50,000 prank callers ringing a pizza shop's only phone at once.","id":1612},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Denial-of-service (DoS & DDoS) attacks","text":"The line is never broken — but no real customer can get through to order. That's a DoS. Now imagine the prank callers are spread across thousands of phones in different cities so you can't just block one number. That's a DDoS. For Clutch, a DDoS at 7 pm on a school night — peak lesson-booking time — means thousands of learners staring at a spinning wheel, instructors unpaid, and parents not getting their \"lesson finished\" alert. No data is stolen, but the business reputation takes the hit. Use the lab below to feel how the attack scales and why mitigation matters.","id":1613},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"DDoS Flood Lab","text":"Mitigation filters the bot traffic at the edge so real learners get through again — exactly what a scrubbing service / firewall rule does in real life. Rate-limiting, traffic scrubbing services (e.g. Cloudflare-style filtering), firewalls and auto-scaling capacity all reduce DoS impact. You'll meet these properly in KK09 — Reducing risk ; here you only need to identify and explain the threat.","id":1614},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Poor credential management","text":"Credentials are the keys to a system: usernames, passwords, API keys, access tokens and certificates. Credential management is the whole process of creating, storing, sharing, rotating and revoking those keys. When that process is sloppy — that's poor credential management , and it's one of the most common ways real organisations get breached.","id":1615},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"👥 Shared accounts","text":"Clutch's three developers all log in as the same admin account. When something goes wrong, no one knows who did it, and you can't disable one person without locking out everyone.","id":1616},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"📋 Plain-text storage","text":"Passwords saved in a shared Google Sheet or hard-coded inside the app's source code. Anyone who sees the file — or the public GitHub repo — owns the system.","id":1617},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"🚪 No off-boarding","text":"A casual instructor leaves, but their login is never disabled. Months later that dormant account is the door an attacker walks through.","id":1618},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"🔁 No rotation / no MFA","text":"The same admin password since 2021, no multi-factor authentication , and it's reused on the founder's personal email too. Poor credential management is like cutting twenty copies of the building master key, lending them to anyone who asks, never collecting them back when someone quits, and taping a spare under the welcome mat. The locks are fine — it's the handling of the keys that's broken. Weak passwords are about the password being easy to crack ( clutch123 ). Poor credential management is about the practices around handling credentials — sharing, storing, rotating, revoking.","id":1619},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"🔁 No rotation / no MFA","text":"A 40-character random password that's emailed around the whole team and never changed is a strong password with poor credential management . Examiners love this distinction.","id":1620},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Malicious software (malware)","text":"Malicious software — malware — is any program written to damage, disrupt or gain unauthorised access to a system. As a threat in this dot point, what matters is that it's an attacker's tool that runs code on a machine it shouldn't : it can steal Clutch's licence data, encrypt files for ransom, log keystrokes, or quietly turn staff laptops into part of someone else's botnet. The detailed mechanics of spyware , viruses, worms and ransomware are KK07 — Malware . Here in KK08, malware is one threat among five — so be able to name it as a threat, say how it typically gets in, and describe the harm. Don't re-write the whole KK07 taxonomy in a KK08 answer; spend your marks on identification and impact.","id":1621},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Outdated software","text":"Outdated software is any operating system, application, library or firmware running an old version that's missing security patches . Every time vendors fix a security hole, they publish it (often with a CVE identifier). The moment that fix is public, every unpatched machine becomes a known, documented, copy-paste target — attackers literally scan the internet for systems still running the vulnerable version. It's like a locksmith publicly announcing \"every Brand-X lock made before March can be opened with a bent paperclip.\" Brand-X releases a free replacement lock the same day.","id":1622},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Outdated software","text":"If Clutch never swaps theirs out, every burglar in town now has the instructions — and knows exactly which door to try. For Clutch this could be an unpatched web server, an old version of the database with a known exploit, or staff laptops still on an end-of-life operating system that no longer receives updates at all. The danger isn't theoretical — outdated software is behind a large share of real-world breaches precisely because the exploit is already written and freely available. The security problem with outdated software is the missing patches and known vulnerabilities , not that it \"runs slowly\" or \"looks dated\".","id":1623},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Outdated software","text":"If you only write \"the software is old so it's bad\", you've missed the marks. Say: unpatched → known vulnerability → attackers exploit a published flaw.","id":1624},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Weak passwords","text":"A weak password is one that's easy for an attacker to guess or crack: short, common ( password , 123456 ), based on personal info, a dictionary word, or reused across multiple sites. Attackers crack them with brute-force (trying every combination), dictionary attacks (trying known common passwords), and credential stuffing (trying username/password pairs leaked from other breaches — which works because people reuse passwords). Length and unpredictability are what make a password strong, because each extra character multiplies the number of combinations an attacker must try. Try a few in the estimator below — it's a teaching model, not a real cracker, but it shows the pattern clearly.","id":1625},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Weak passwords","text":"Be precise. Weak = easy to crack (short/common). Reused = strong but used everywhere, so one leak unlocks all. Poor credential management = the handling process. A scenario can contain all three at once — say which is which and why each matters.","id":1626},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Five threats at a glance","text":"Tap each card to flip it. Front = the threat; back = a one-line definition plus how it shows up at Clutch. Great for last-minute revision.","id":1627},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"DoS / DDoS attack","text":"Floods a service with traffic so legitimate users can’t get through. DDoS uses many hijacked devices (a botnet) at once.","id":1628},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Poor credential management","text":"Sloppy handling of logins & keys: shared accounts, plain-text storage, no rotation, no off-boarding, no MFA.","id":1629},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Malicious software","text":"Attacker’s code that runs on a machine to steal, encrypt, spy or hijack. (Full taxonomy = KK07.)","id":1630},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Outdated software","text":"Unpatched OS / apps / firmware with known, published vulnerabilities that attackers actively scan for.","id":1631},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Weak passwords","text":"Short, common or reused passwords cracked by brute-force, dictionary or credential-stuffing attacks.","id":1632},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Sort it: threat, vulnerability or consequence?","text":"Drag each statement into the right bin. This is exactly the discrimination examiners test — getting the category right is worth marks even before you explain anything.","id":1633},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"Half of exam technique is doing what the command word actually asks. Tap any word to see what it demands and roughly how to spend the marks.","id":1634},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"P·E·L writing trainer","text":"Strong cyber-security responses follow P·E·L : Point (name the threat) → Explain (how it works / the weakness it exploits) → Link (tie it to the scenario and its impact). Pick a threat, write a response, and watch the tracker light up as you hit each part. Keyword detection is a guide, not a marker.","id":1635},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Five questions spanning the command words you'll meet. For each: reveal a weak response, a strong response and the marking guide , then self-mark. Your scores feed the dock in the corner. It’s when a hacker attacks a server and it stops working so people can’t use the website. A denial-of-service attack deliberately floods a server or network with so much traffic or so many bogus requests that it can no longer respond to legitimate users, making the service unavailable . The aim is disruption rather than data theft. 1 Identifies that the service/server is flooded or overwhelmed with traffic/requests.","id":1636},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 States the effect: legitimate users are denied access / the service becomes unavailable. Weak passwords and poor credential management are both about bad passwords. “clutch123” is weak and that’s poor management. They should make it stronger. A weak password is one that is easy to crack — here “clutch123” is short, predictable and dictionary-based, so a brute-force or dictionary attack would break it quickly. Poor credential management is about the practices for handling credentials: at Clutch the account is shared by three developers (so actions can’t be traced to a person), and the password has never been rotated since 2021.","id":1637},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Even a strong password would still be poorly managed if it were shared and never changed — the two problems are separate. 1 Weak password defined (easy to crack: short/common/predictable) + example “clutch123”. 1 Poor credential management defined (handling/process: sharing, rotation, storage, revocation). 1 Clear distinction drawn + scenario example of the management failure (shared / never rotated). 1. The laptops are old. 2. The email might be bad. These could cause problems for the company. 1. Outdated software. The laptops run an OS that no longer receives security updates, so any newly discovered vulnerability will never be patched .","id":1638},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Attackers scan for these known, published flaws, making the devices an easy entry point to Clutch’s data. 2. Malicious software (malware). The attachment “invoice.pdf.exe” is an executable disguised as a document — a classic phishing payload. If run, it could install a keylogger or trojan, capturing the instructor’s Clutch login or giving an attacker remote access to learner records. 1 Outdated software identified (unpatched OS / no updates). 1 Justified: known vulnerabilities remain unfixed → exploited for access. 1 Malicious software identified (disguised executable / phishing payload). 1 Justified: could install malware → steal credentials / data / remote access.","id":1639},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"A DoS is a denial of service and a DDoS is a distributed one. They are both attacks on servers. Similarity: both aim to make a service unavailable to legitimate users by overwhelming it with traffic or requests. Difference: a DoS attack comes from a single source, so it can often be blocked by filtering that one address; a DDoS is distributed across thousands of hijacked devices (a botnet), so there is no single source to block, making it far harder to defend against and capable of generating much greater traffic.","id":1640},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"1 Similarity: both flood a service to deny access to legitimate users. 1 Difference: DoS = single source; DDoS = many distributed sources / botnet. 1 Consequence of the difference: DDoS is harder to block / larger scale. Clutch has lots of threats like weak passwords, no MFA, old software and DDoS. They are all bad and Clutch should fix them all to be safe. The worst one is hackers. Several threats are present. Outdated software (unpatched web server) is high-likelihood: published exploits are scanned for automatically, and the server holds 40,000 sensitive records, so impact is severe — a strong candidate for greatest risk.","id":1641},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Poor credential management + weak password (a shared “clutch123” admin login with no MFA) is also high-likelihood, since a single dictionary attack or credential leak grants full administrative access to everything ; the shared account also removes accountability. DDoS is plausible given a competitor was just hit, but its impact is mainly temporary unavailability rather than data loss. Judgement: the greatest risk is the combination of the unpatched server and the weak, shared admin credentials with no MFA , because both are highly likely to be exploited and both lead to the worst impact — unauthorised access to 40,000 learners’ personal and licence data, a serious privacy breach.","id":1642},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"The DDoS threat, while real, is lower risk because it disrupts availability temporarily without exposing data. I would therefore prioritise patching and fixing credential management ahead of DDoS protection. 2 Identifies at least three relevant threats using correct terminology (outdated software, weak password / poor credential management, DDoS; MFA absence supports these). 2 Applies likelihood to threats (e.g. published exploits scanned automatically; competitor recently hit by DDoS). 2 Applies impact, distinguishing data-breach severity (privacy of 40,000 records) from temporary unavailability. 2 Reaches a justified judgement ranking the greatest risk, supported by the likelihood × impact reasoning.","id":1643},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"VCE-style questions","text":"Self-mark honestly — the value is in spotting the gap between your answer and the strong one. Re-attempt anything under full marks after reading the guide.","id":1644},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ Threat ≠ vulnerability ≠ consequence","text":"The threat is the potential bad event; the vulnerability is the weakness it exploits; the consequence is what results. Questions mix all three to test you.","id":1645},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ Weak password ≠ poor credential management","text":"Weak = easy to crack. Poor management = how credentials are handled (sharing, storage, rotation, revocation, MFA). A strong password can still be poorly managed.","id":1646},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ “Outdated” means unpatched, not slow","text":"The risk is known, published vulnerabilities that go unfixed — not that the software “looks old” or “runs slowly”. Always mention missing patches.","id":1647},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ DoS vs DDoS — one source vs many","text":"A DoS is from a single source; a DDoS is distributed across a botnet of many devices, which is why it’s far harder to block. Don’t use the terms interchangeably.","id":1648},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ Don’t dump the whole malware list","text":"In KK08, malware is one threat of five. Name it, say how it gets in, and state the harm. The full spyware/virus/worm/ransomware taxonomy belongs to KK07.","id":1649},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"⚠ Always link to impact","text":"Identifying a threat earns the first mark; the rest come from explaining the weakness it exploits and the concrete harm to the people/organisation in the scenario.","id":1650},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"KK08 — Security threats, in one place","text":"DoS / DDoS Flood a service so real users can't get in . DDoS = many hijacked devices (botnet) at once → harder to stop. Harm: unavailability , lost trust. Poor credential mgmt Sloppy handling of logins/keys: shared accounts, plain-text storage, no rotation, no off-boarding, no MFA. Not the same as weak passwords. Malicious software Attacker's code runs on your machine (steal / encrypt / spy / enslave). Gets in via phishing, downloads, dependencies, USB. Detail = KK07. Outdated software Unpatched OS/app/firmware with known, published vulnerabilities attackers actively scan for.","id":1651},{"file":"u2o2-kk08.html","nav":"u2o2-kk08.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK08","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Security threats","head":"KK08 — Security threats, in one place","text":"Fix = patch & update. Weak passwords Short / common / reused → cracked by brute-force, dictionary, credential-stuffing. Fix = long, unique, unpredictable + a manager. Golden vocab Threat = the potential bad event · Vulnerability = the weakness it exploits · Risk = likelihood × impact. Answer shape P·E·L : Point (name it) → Explain (how/weakness) → Link (Clutch + impact). Match the command word.","id":1652},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","text":"You can't make a network un -hackable. But you can make it expensive, slow and frustrating to attack — and quick to recover when something slips through. That's what risk reduction means. Clutch is a small Melbourne start-up. Their app matches learner drivers with instructors, tracks logbook hours, stores licence details and takes card payments. Their \"network\" is modest: a router in the office, one server, four staff laptops and a fleet of instructor tablets. In KK06–KK08 you met the threats to a network like this. KK09 is the other half of the story: the controls that lower the risk those threats become a real breach.","id":1653},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Risk is likelihood × impact","text":"Every security control does one of two jobs. It either makes a breach less likely to happen , or it makes the breach less damaging when it does . Knowing which job a control does is the single most useful idea in this whole topic — examiners test it constantly.","id":1654},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Reduce likelihood","text":"Make it harder for an attack to succeed in the first place.","id":1655},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Reduce impact","text":"Limit the damage and recover quickly once something gets through. Defence in depth. No single control is enough. Attackers only need one gap; defenders need every layer to hold. So we stack independent controls so that if one fails, the next still stands. That stack is what the rest of this module builds, one layer at a time.","id":1656},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Clutch's defence stack","text":"Here is Clutch's data core, wrapped in the five layers of KK09. Drag to rotate. Each ring is one risk-reduction method — when they're all closed and glowing emerald, an attacker has to defeat every layer in turn.","id":1657},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Firmware updates","text":"Firmware is the low-level software baked into a device's chip that tells the hardware how to behave — the router, the modem, the office printer, the instructors' dash-cams. It's not an app you open; it runs the moment the device powers on. Why it reduces risk: manufacturers release firmware updates to patch newly-discovered vulnerabilities and to remove insecure defaults. A router running three-year-old firmware often has publicly-listed exploits and ships with default admin passwords that attackers try first. Updating firmware reduces the likelihood of those known attacks landing.","id":1658},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"For Clutch","text":"Clutch's office router is the front door to the whole network. If its firmware is outdated, an attacker can exploit a known flaw to take control of traffic — including learners' licence numbers in transit. A scheduled quarterly firmware check on the router, modem and any smart devices closes that door.","id":1659},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Multi-factor authentication (MFA)","text":"Multi-factor authentication requires two or more independent proofs of identity from different categories before granting access: Password, PIN, passphrase. Phone with an authenticator app, a code by SMS, a hardware key. Fingerprint, face, other biometric . Why it reduces risk: the most common breach starts with a stolen or guessed password. MFA makes a password alone useless — even with the correct password, the attacker is stopped because they don't have the second factor. It directly reduces the likelihood of unauthorised access.","id":1660},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Backups","text":"A backup is a separate copy of data kept so it can be restored after loss — ransomware , a failed hard drive, a fire, or someone deleting the wrong folder. Backups are the one control on this list whose main job is to reduce impact , not likelihood. They don't stop the attack; they make it survivable. The detail examiners want: a backup only helps if it is recent , tested , and kept separate . An untested backup that won't restore is worthless; a backup left plugged into the same network gets encrypted along with everything else.","id":1661},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Operating-system & anti-malware updates","text":"Software ships with flaws nobody has found yet. When a flaw is discovered, the vendor releases a patch . The gap between a flaw becoming public and you installing the patch is the window of vulnerability — the period attackers race to exploit. Keeping operating systems and anti-malware software updated reduces the likelihood of those known exploits working.","id":1662},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"OS updates","text":"Fix security holes in Windows / macOS / Linux. Turn on automatic updates so the window of vulnerability stays short.","id":1663},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Anti-malware updates","text":"Refresh the signature database so the scanner recognises the newest malware. Out-of-date anti-malware misses brand-new threats. A flaw in Clutch's server OS goes public on Day 0. Choose how quickly Clutch patches.","id":1664},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Staff procedures — the human layer","text":"The first four layers are technical controls . This one is different: it's an administrative (procedural) control — the rules, training and habits people follow. It matters because the strongest technology fails the moment a person clicks a phishing link, reuses a password, or props the metaphorical door open.","id":1665},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"What good staff procedures look like at Clutch","text":"Teach staff to spot phishing emails and report them, not click them. Long, unique passphrases in a password manager — no sticky notes, no reuse. Staff get only the access they need; accounts are disabled the day someone leaves. A clear, blame-free way to report a mistake fast — this reduces impact when something slips through.","id":1666},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Defence Stack Lab","text":"Switch Clutch's five controls on and off, then launch real-world attacks at the system. Watch which layer stops each attack — and watch the residual risk gauge move. Notice that backups never stop an attack; they change what happens after one lands.","id":1667},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Flip cards — the five methods","text":"Tap a card to flip it. Recall the method, then check whether it reduces likelihood or impact .","id":1668},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Build a P·E·L answer","text":"Top-band responses follow Point → Explain → Link : name the method, explain how it works, then link it to the scenario. Write each part below — the trainer highlights the key ideas examiners look for and scores your structure live.","id":1669},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Exam traps","text":"No control is total. Write \"reduces the likelihood\" or \"reduces the risk,\" never \"eliminates\" or \"completely prevents.\" Residual risk always remains. Firmware = chip-level software on a device (router, IoT). OS updates = the computer's operating system. They're separate layers — name the right one. Backups don't stop an attack happening — they reduce its impact by letting you recover. Get the likelihood-vs-impact distinction right. \"Use MFA and backups\" earns almost nothing on an Explain or Justify question. You must say how each control reduces the risk, and link it to the scenario.","id":1670},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Exam traps","text":"Students load up on gadgets and forget staff procedures . Naming the administrative control shows balanced understanding and often picks up a mark. A backup that's never tested, or left plugged into the same network, fails when you need it. Strong answers note it must be recent, tested and kept offline/off-site.","id":1671},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Cheat sheet","text":"Method Type How it reduces risk Reduces… Firmware updates Technical Patches known device flaws; removes insecure defaults on routers / IoT. Likelihood Multi-factor auth Technical Adds a second independent factor, so a stolen password alone can't log in. Likelihood Backups Recovery Separate, tested, offline copy lets data be restored after loss/ransomware. Impact OS & malware updates Technical Patches OS holes and refreshes malware signatures; shrinks the window of vulnerability. Likelihood Staff procedures Administrative Training, password policy, least privilege, fast incident reporting. Both","id":1672},{"file":"u2o2-kk09.html","nav":"u2o2-kk09.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK09","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Reducing the risk — five ways to keep a network harder to break.","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"Command word What the examiner wants Identify / State Name it. No explanation needed. 1 mark each. Describe Say what it is and a key feature — a sentence or two. Explain Give the how or why . Show cause and effect. Compare Both similarities and differences, side by side. Justify Give reasons for a choice; say why it's better than the alternative. Evaluate Weigh strengths and limitations, then make a judgement.","id":1673},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","text":"Anything you send across a network can be copied by someone in the middle. Cryptography doesn't stop them grabbing it — it makes what they grab useless . This module walks the whole story, from a 2,000-year-old shift cipher to the encryption protecting your bank login right now.","id":1674},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"scenario PigeonPost","text":"A student-built messaging app at a Melbourne college. Notes “fly” from one phone to another across the shared school Wi-Fi.","id":1675},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"builder Maya","text":"Year 11 developer. She wants every note private — even if a teacher, the IT system, or another student is watching the network.","id":1676},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"eavesdropper Raven","text":"In class, one student role-plays Raven, sitting on the Wi-Fi and copying every packet, to test whether Maya's encryption actually holds.","id":1677},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"01 What cryptography actually is","text":"Cryptography is the practice of transforming readable information into a scrambled form so that only someone with the right secret can read it. It is the tool the study design points to for protecting confidentiality of data on a network. Four words do all the heavy lifting in an exam answer, so get them exact: Plaintext is the original readable message. The cipher (or algorithm) is the method of scrambling. The key is the secret setting that the method uses. Ciphertext is the scrambled output. Encryption goes plaintext→ciphertext; decryption goes back.","id":1678},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"01 What cryptography actually is","text":"The single most examined idea: security comes from keeping the key secret, not from keeping the method secret. A good cipher stays safe even if an attacker knows exactly how it works — they still can't read anything without the key. This is Kerckhoffs's principle , and it's why “we invented our own secret algorithm” is a red flag, not a feature. Sending plaintext is like writing on a postcard : every postie who handles it can read it. Encrypting is like sealing the note in a locked steel box .","id":1679},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"01 What cryptography actually is","text":"Raven can still grab the box off the network, shake it, photograph it — but without the key, what's inside is noise. The rest of this module is really one question: how do Maya and her friend both end up holding the right key?","id":1680},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"02 The Caesar cipher","text":"The oldest trick in the book: shift every letter forward by a fixed number of places. It's a substitution cipher — each letter is swapped for another — and the key is just the shift amount.","id":1681},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"Caesar cipher disk","text":"Drag the shift to rotate the inner ring. The outer ring is the plaintext alphabet; the inner ring is what each letter becomes. Maya's app once used this — watch how few keys there are. Why this is hopeless for real security: there are only 25 useful keys . Raven just tries all of them — that's a brute-force attack , and on 25 options it takes seconds. Worse, even one guess can be skipped: the most common letter in the ciphertext is almost always plain E , so frequency analysis cracks it without trying every key at all.","id":1682},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"03 Vigenère & polyalphabetic ciphers","text":"The fix people reached for next: stop using one shift for the whole message. A polyalphabetic cipher changes the shift letter by letter. The Vigenère cipher does this with a repeating keyword . Each letter of the keyword gives the shift for the matching letter of the message. A =shift 0, B =shift 1, C =shift 2, and so on. The keyword repeats across the whole message.","id":1683},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"Vigenère encoder","text":"Type a keyword and watch the same plaintext letter encrypt to different ciphertext letters depending on where it sits. That's what kills simple frequency analysis. Look at the highlighted letters: the same plaintext letter became two different ciphertext letters. With a keyword, a simple letter count no longer cracks it. Polyalphabetic ciphers were considered “unbreakable” for 300 years. They aren't — if the keyword is short and repeats, the pattern eventually leaks (the Kasiski attack). In WWII, machine ciphers like Enigma pushed this idea to an extreme, and the codebreakers at Bletchley Park — including Alan Turing — broke them anyway.","id":1684},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"Vigenère encoder","text":"The lesson the study design wants you to take: a longer, more random key is harder to break , which is exactly why modern keys are huge random numbers, not English words.","id":1685},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"04 Symmetric encryption — one shared key (AES)","text":"Caesar and Vigenère are both symmetric : the same key encrypts and decrypts. The modern symmetric standard is AES (Advanced Encryption Standard). It does to bits what Vigenère does to letters, but vastly more thoroughly and with an enormous key. AES is fast , runs in hardware on every phone and laptop, and with a 256-bit key the number of possible keys is so large that brute force is physically impossible. The key, not the method, carries all the secrecy — AES's algorithm is fully public.","id":1686},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"Why key length is the whole game","text":"Each extra bit doubles the number of keys. That's why “256-bit” isn't twice as strong as 128-bit — it's 2¹²⁸ times the keyspace. No computer that could ever exist brute-forces AES-256. The fatal catch — key distribution. AES is brilliant, but it has a chicken-and-egg problem. Before Maya and her friend can send encrypted notes, they both need the same secret key. How does Maya get that key to her friend across the network without Raven copying it on the way ? You can't encrypt the key… because you'd need a key to do that. This single problem is what asymmetric encryption was invented to solve.","id":1687},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"05 Asymmetric encryption — two keys (RSA · ECDH · ECDSA)","text":"The breakthrough: give everyone a pair of mathematically linked keys. A public key that anyone may have, and a private key kept secret. What one key locks, only the other can unlock. Maya hands out open padlocks with her name on them (her public key) to anyone who asks — she doesn't care if Raven grabs a hundred of them. To send Maya a private message, you put it in a box and snap one of her padlocks shut. Now only Maya's private key can open it — not the sender, not Raven, not even another one of Maya's own padlocks. The lock can be public because locking and unlocking use different keys .","id":1688},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"🔑 Symmetric 1 shared key","text":"✓ Fast — encrypts large amounts of data with little processing. ✓ Mature, hardware-accelerated (AES everywhere). – Key distribution problem — both sides must already share the secret. – Key count explodes — n people need many separate shared keys.","id":1689},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"🔑🔒 Asymmetric public + private","text":"✓ Solves key distribution — the public key can be shared openly. ✓ Enables digital signatures — proof of who sent something. – Slow — far heavier maths, poor for large data. – Relies on the private key never leaking.","id":1690},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"The three names in the study design","text":"All three are asymmetric, but they're used for different jobs — examiners like you to know what each one is for , not just that it exists. Confidentiality vs authenticity. Encrypting protects confidentiality (nobody can read it). Signing protects authenticity and integrity (you know who sent it and that it wasn't changed). Don't mix these up in an exam — a signature does not hide a message, and encryption alone does not prove the sender.","id":1691},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"06 Lab — how a real connection is built","text":"Real systems don't choose symmetric or asymmetric — they use both , each for what it's good at. This is exactly what happens in the half-second before your bank page loads (TLS / HTTPS). Step through it.","id":1692},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"The hybrid handshake","text":"Maya's phone (left) wants a private channel to the PigeonPost server (right). Raven sits on the wire between them. Press play and watch which key does which job. The exam-grade insight: asymmetric is used once , only to deliver the symmetric key safely; then fast symmetric encryption protects everything after. You get the key-distribution fix of asymmetric and the speed of symmetric. If you can explain why a system uses both, you're answering at the level top responses sit.","id":1693},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"07 Key terms — tap to flip","text":"The exact vocabulary examiners reward. Tap a card to check yourself, then say the definition aloud before you flip. The original, readable message before any encryption is applied. The scrambled, unreadable output of encryption. Useless without the key. The algorithm used to scramble. It can be public — secrecy lives in the key, not the method. The setting the cipher uses. Keeping the key secret is what keeps the message safe. Same key encrypts and decrypts. Fast, but both sides must already share the secret. e.g. AES. A linked key pair:","id":1694},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"07 Key terms — tap to flip","text":"what one key locks, only the other unlocks. Solves key distribution. Advanced Encryption Standard. Modern, fast, hardware-accelerated, with huge keys (128/256-bit). Public-key system. Security rests on how hard it is to factor very large prime products. Elliptic-Curve Diffie–Hellman: agree a shared secret over an open channel without sending it. Elliptic-Curve Digital Signature Algorithm: proves who sent a message and that it wasn't altered. Try every possible key until one works. Hopeless against a large keyspace like AES-256. Exploit letter-frequency patterns (E is most common) to break simple substitution ciphers. A system should stay secure even if the method is fully known.","id":1695},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"07 Key terms — tap to flip","text":"Only the key need be secret. Asymmetric to share a key safely, then fast symmetric for the data. This is how HTTPS works. Sign with a private key; verify with the public key. Proves authenticity and integrity, not secrecy. The challenge of getting a shared symmetric key to both parties without an attacker copying it.","id":1696},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"10 Writing trainer — C·M·E","text":"Crypto questions reward a tight three-move structure. Use it for any “explain / justify” cryptography answer. Name the technique and what it protects (confidentiality / integrity / authenticity). Say how it works in one line — keys, public/private, shift, etc. Link it to the scenario: the benefit or trade-off here . Prompt: Maya wants to send a private message to one friend over the school Wi-Fi. Explain how asymmetric encryption keeps the message confidential even though Raven can see everything on the network. (3 marks) Maya's friend creates a public/private key pair and shares the public key openly — it doesn't matter that Raven copies it (Claim:","id":1697},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"10 Writing trainer — C·M·E","text":"confidentiality via asymmetric encryption) . Maya encrypts the message with that public key , and because of the way the key pair is mathematically linked, the ciphertext can only be decrypted by the matching private key , which never leaves her friend's device (Mechanism: different keys lock and unlock) . So although Raven intercepts the ciphertext on the shared Wi-Fi, she has no private key and the message stays unreadable to her (Evaluation: tied to the scenario) . 1 mark: plaintext = the original/readable message. 1 mark: ciphertext = the scrambled/encrypted, unreadable output (ideally noting it needs the key to reverse).","id":1698},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"10 Writing trainer — C·M·E","text":"1 mark: identifies the very small keyspace (only 25 keys / a single shift). 1 mark: explains brute force — an attacker tries all keys quickly. 1 mark: links to why that means no real security (or cites frequency analysis). 1 mark: symmetric = one shared key; asymmetric = public/private pair. 1 mark: a valid advantage of each (symmetric: fast; asymmetric: solves key distribution / open sharing). 1 mark: a valid disadvantage of each (symmetric: key distribution; asymmetric: slow). 1 mark: genuine comparison (the trade-off is speed vs safe key sharing), not just two separate descriptions.","id":1699},{"file":"u2o2-kk10.html","nav":"u2o2-kk10.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK10","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cryptography: turning a readable note into unreadable noise","head":"10 Writing trainer — C·M·E","text":"1 mark: asymmetric solves safe key exchange over an open channel. 1 mark: recognises asymmetric is too slow for bulk data. 1 mark: AES (symmetric) is fast/efficient for the conversation data. 1 mark: clear justification — the design combines the strengths of both / each used for its best job. 1 mark: what Raven CAN get (captures ciphertext / public key / metadata). 1 mark: what Raven CANNOT do and why (no private key → can't decrypt the session key). 1 mark: identifies a realistic failure (private key leaked, weak key, or fake/substituted public key). 1 mark: analytical conclusion — the maths holds; risk lies in key secrecy / trust, not the cipher.","id":1700},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"AI in Network Security","text":"How machine learning watches the shape of network traffic , learns what \"normal\" looks like, and raises the alarm in real time when something doesn't fit.","id":1701},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"⚡ The 20-second version","text":"Machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns = the AI learns a baseline of normal network behaviour, then flags anomalies that deviate from it. Real-time monitoring & notification = it watches every packet 24/7 at machine speed and alerts a human (or auto-responds) within seconds, not days. It catches new (zero-day) threats that rule-based tools miss — but it can raise false positives , depends on good training data , and still needs human oversight . PulseGrid is a live-streaming platform a Year 12 student built so her school can broadcast sport, drama nights and esports finals.","id":1702},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"⚡ The 20-second version","text":"On a quiet Tuesday it carries a steady trickle of viewers; during a grand final it spikes to thousands. That constantly-changing traffic is exactly the kind of thing a human admin can't watch by hand — so PulseGrid puts an AI on the wire. We'll use it the whole way through.","id":1703},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"The big idea: an AI that knows the regulars","text":"The VCAA study design asks you to understand the use of artificial intelligence in network security — specifically machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns and real-time monitoring and notification . Two ideas, one job: spot trouble fast. Traditional security tools work like a wanted poster . A firewall or a signature-based IDS holds a list of known-bad fingerprints — this virus, that malicious IP — and blocks anything matching the list. Brilliant for threats we've seen before. Useless against an attack nobody has fingerprinted yet. A new bouncer with a wanted poster only stops faces on the poster.","id":1704},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"The big idea: an AI that knows the regulars","text":"A bouncer who has worked the door for years doesn't need a poster — they know the regulars . When someone behaves oddly (casing the till, slipping toward the staff door at 3am), it just feels wrong , even though that exact person was never on any list. AI in network security is the experienced bouncer. It learns the normal rhythm of your network so well that \"weird\" jumps out — even brand-new weird. In machine-learning terms, the AI is trained on huge volumes of network data so it builds an internal model of normal behaviour .","id":1705},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"The big idea: an AI that knows the regulars","text":"Then it compares live traffic against that model. Behaviour that strays too far is an anomaly worth a closer look. This is why the approach is often called anomaly-based or behaviour-based detection. Baseline: the model of normal network behaviour the AI learns from training data (typical volumes, timings, sources, destinations, ports, packet sizes). Anomaly: live traffic that deviates significantly from the baseline — a candidate threat, not a confirmed one. Real-time monitoring: continuously analysing traffic as it happens, so detection and notification occur in seconds.","id":1706},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns","text":"\"Traffic patterns\" means the measurable shape of data moving across the network. The AI doesn't read the content of every message — it studies features of the flow, such as: Volume — how much data, how many connections per second. Timing — when traffic happens (PulseGrid is busy at lunch and after school, dead at 3am). Source & destination — which devices talk to which servers, and where in the world. Ports & protocols — the \"channels\" used (web, video, file transfer). Packet size & frequency — the rhythm of the conversation.","id":1707},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns","text":"The model learns the baseline from this — what a normal Tuesday and a normal grand-final night look like. Two broad learning styles appear in the literature, and you only need the gist: Supervised learning — trained on data labelled \"normal\" or \"attack\", so it learns to classify new traffic. Strong when you have good labelled examples. Unsupervised learning — given unlabelled traffic and left to find the natural clusters of \"normal\", flagging anything that sits outside them as an outlier. Good for spotting threats nobody has labelled yet. A human could write a rule like \"alert if traffic > 5,000 connections/sec\".","id":1708},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns","text":"But on grand-final night legitimate traffic blows past 5,000 — false alarm. On a sleepy Tuesday, an attack of 800 connections/sec is clearly abnormal but slips under the rule. A fixed threshold can't tell the difference. An ML model that has learned context (time of day, day of week, event schedule) can: 5,000 at final time = normal; 800 at 3am = anomaly.","id":1709},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Interactive: the Anomaly Lab","text":"Below is PulseGrid's traffic plotted in a 3-feature space: connection rate , packet size and time of day . Each green dot is a normal sample. Press Train baseline and the AI wraps a \"normal region\" around the cluster it has learned. Then inject anomalies and watch what falls outside.","id":1710},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Anomaly Lab · learned-normal region","text":"Notice the model never sees a label saying \"this is an attack\". It only knows what normal looks like — anything far enough outside the learned region is flagged for a human to judge. That's exactly why an anomaly is a suspect , not a verdict .","id":1711},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Signature-based vs AI/anomaly-based detection","text":"Examiners love this comparison. Drag each statement into the detection method it best describes.","id":1712},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"🧠 AI / anomaly-based","text":"Signature detection matches known fingerprints — fast and precise on old threats, blind to new ones. AI/anomaly detection learns normal behaviour and flags deviations — can catch zero-day threats, but produces more false positives. Most real networks run both : signatures for the known, AI for the unknown.","id":1713},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Real-time monitoring and notification","text":"Detection is only useful if it's fast . The second half of this dot point is about watching continuously and telling someone immediately . Humans cannot watch every packet. PulseGrid moves millions of packets an hour; even a whole security team couldn't eyeball that. An AI monitor: Never sleeps — 24/7 coverage, including 3am when attackers prefer to strike. Works at machine speed and scale — analyses millions of events per second. Notifies automatically — pushes an alert to a dashboard, email, SMS or security console the moment something looks wrong.","id":1714},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Real-time monitoring and notification","text":"Can trigger an automated response — e.g. block an IP or isolate a device — though \"notify\" and \"respond\" are different jobs (see the trap below). A hospital heart monitor doesn't treat the patient — it watches the pulse continuously and screams the instant the rhythm goes wrong , so a human can act. AI network monitoring is the EKG of the network: a steady green line of normal traffic, and a loud alarm the moment the pattern spikes or flatlines. The faster the alarm, the shorter the attacker's dwell time — the window they sit inside undetected.","id":1715},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Real-time monitoring and notification","text":"Dwell time: how long a threat is present in a network before it's detected. Real-time AI monitoring exists to shrink dwell time from weeks (industry average for undetected breaches) toward seconds .","id":1716},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Interactive: PulseGrid Live Monitor","text":"Green packets stream across PulseGrid's wire while the AI watches the pulse line below. Launch an attack and see how fast the model flags the anomaly and fires a notification — and watch the threat meter climb.","id":1717},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Live Monitor · real-time detection","text":"Each attack has a different signature shape : DDoS is a wall of inbound packets, exfiltration is a slow trickle leaving the network, credential stuffing is a rapid burst of login attempts. The model recognises each as \"not normal\" and notifies — that's analysis of traffic patterns plus real-time notification working together.","id":1718},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Strengths & limitations","text":"A \"discuss\" or \"evaluate\" question wants both sides . Flip each card to reveal the point. Green = strengths, red = limitations.","id":1719},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Detects novel threats","text":"Tap to reveal Learns behaviour, so it can flag zero-day attacks that have no known signature — the bouncer who notices 'new weird'.","id":1720},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Machine speed & scale","text":"Tap to reveal Analyses millions of events per second, 24/7, including 3am — far beyond what a human team can watch.","id":1721},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Adapts over time","text":"Tap to reveal Retrains as traffic evolves, so the baseline keeps up with how the network legitimately changes.","id":1722},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Eases analyst load","text":"Tap to reveal When well-tuned, it triages the noise so humans focus on the alerts that actually matter, shrinking dwell time.","id":1723},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"False positives","text":"Tap to reveal An anomaly isn't always an attack. Legit spikes get flagged, causing alert fatigue — staff may start ignoring alarms.","id":1724},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Needs good data","text":"Tap to reveal Garbage in, garbage out. Biased or incomplete training data creates blind spots the model can't see past.","id":1725},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Adversarial evasion","text":"Tap to reveal Attackers can poison the training data or shape traffic to look 'normal', sneaking past the model.","id":1726},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Still needs humans","text":"Tap to reveal It's a detective control, not a decision-maker. A 'black-box' alert still needs a person to investigate and act. AI is a powerful detective control that augments — but does not replace — human analysts and traditional defences. Used well, it cuts dwell time and catches novel threats; used naively, it drowns a team in false positives or can be fooled by attackers who poison its training data or disguise traffic as normal. The mature answer is \"AI and humans\", not \"AI instead of humans\".","id":1727},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Named exam traps","text":"AI augments the security team; it doesn't replace human judgement. Always mention human oversight — someone investigates the alerts. An anomaly is merely unusual , not proven malicious. A legitimate new app or a grand-final spike can be anomalous → false positives . Detection ≠ confirmation. Real-time monitoring and notification is a detective control (it spots and tells). It is not the same as a preventive control (firewall, MFA) that stops the attack happening. No — signatures are the traditional approach. AI's strength is learning patterns/behaviour , letting it catch threats with no known signature (zero-day).","id":1728},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Named exam traps","text":"Alerting an admin is notification . Automatically blocking the IP is response . The dot point names monitoring and notification — be precise about which you mean. Garbage in, garbage out. A model trained on biased or incomplete data has blind spots and can be tricked by adversarial /poisoned traffic. Good data = good model.","id":1729},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Writing trainer · Point · Evidence · Link","text":"VCAA answers reward structure. Write a paragraph answering the prompt below using P-E-L : state your Point , back it with Evidence (a fact/term/example), then Link it back to the question. The trainer lights up the key terms as you include them.","id":1730},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Practice exam questions","text":"Five VCAA-style questions ( 18 marks total). Each has a weak answer, a strong answer and a marking guide . Read them, then self-mark your own attempt — your score feeds the dock. 1 mark learns/models a baseline of normal traffic patterns 1 mark compares live traffic and flags deviations/anomalies as possible threats 1 mark continuously analyses traffic in real time at machine speed/scale 1 mark automatically alerts/notifies an administrator on deviation 1 mark value: handles volume humans can't / reduces dwell time so staff act faster 1 mark 2am baseline is low, so the flood is a large deviation/anomaly 1 mark model recognises the abnormal traffic pattern (volume spike) 1 mark real-time detection → automatic notification/alert to admin 1 mark human (or automated response) then investigates/mitigates, e.g.","id":1731},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Practice exam questions","text":"rate-limit/block 1 mark states a valid benefit (e.g. detects zero-day/novel threats; speed & scale) 1 mark develops the benefit with reasoning 1 mark states a valid limitation (e.g. false positives, poor training data, adversarial evasion) 1 mark develops the limitation with a consequence (e.g. alert fatigue) 1 mark strength: real-time/24-7 monitoring at scale 1 mark strength: detects novel/anomalous threats 1 mark limitation: false positives/negatives, training-data quality or adversarial risk 1 mark need for human oversight / accountability of alerts 1 mark justified judgement: augment rather than replace (reject as stated)","id":1732},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Key terms glossary","text":"Term Exam-ready meaning Baseline The model of normal network behaviour learned from training data; live traffic is compared against it. Anomaly Traffic that deviates significantly from the baseline — a possible threat, not a confirmed one. Anomaly / behaviour-based detection Detection that learns normal patterns and flags deviations; can catch unknown threats. Signature-based detection Traditional detection that matches traffic against known threat fingerprints; blind to new threats. Real-time monitoring Continuously analysing traffic as it happens so detection occurs in seconds. Notification / alerting Automatically informing an administrator (dashboard, email, SMS) when an anomaly is detected.","id":1733},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Key terms glossary","text":"False positive A legitimate event wrongly flagged as a threat — too many cause alert fatigue. False negative A real threat the model fails to flag — a dangerous miss. Zero-day threat An attack with no known signature; AI's behaviour-based approach can still detect it. Dwell time How long a threat is present before detection; real-time AI aims to shrink it. Training data The data a model learns from; biased or poor data creates blind spots ('garbage in, garbage out'). Supervised learning Training on labelled normal/attack data so the model learns to classify new traffic.","id":1734},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"Key terms glossary","text":"Unsupervised learning Finding natural clusters of normal in unlabelled data and flagging outliers. Adversarial attack Crafting or poisoning traffic/data so the model is fooled or misled. Detective vs preventive control Monitoring/notification detects and reports (detective); firewalls /MFA stop attacks (preventive).","id":1735},{"file":"u2o2-kk11.html","nav":"u2o2-kk11.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK11","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"AI in Network Security","head":"✅ Before the exam, you can…","text":"Explain machine-learning analysis of traffic patterns as learning a baseline of normal behaviour and flagging anomalies . Explain real-time monitoring and notification as continuous machine-speed analysis that alerts humans in seconds, shrinking dwell time . Compare signature-based vs anomaly/behaviour-based detection and say why networks use both. Evaluate AI in security: novel-threat detection & speed vs false positives, training-data quality, adversarial risk and the need for human oversight .","id":1736},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","text":"A burglar and a locksmith use the same skills. One ends in handcuffs, the other gets paid. The difference isn't the lock-picking — it's the permission slip . This module is about the people we hire to attack our own networks. Clutch is a Melbourne-built learner-driver app with around 40,000 teenage users . It logs hours behind the wheel, stores licence photos, parent emails and payment details, and syncs to a small network: a public web server, an app server, a user database and a handful of staff laptops. In four weeks Clutch launches \"Test-Ready Mode\" — and the founders are about to make a decision every real company faces: do we pay someone to try to break in before the public can? Follow Clutch through this whole module.","id":1737},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"What ethical hacking actually is","text":"Ethical hacking means using the same tools and techniques a criminal would — but with the owner's written permission, and the goal of fixing weaknesses instead of exploiting them. Ethical hacking is the authorised , legal practice of deliberately attempting to penetrate a network or system on behalf of its owner, in order to identify vulnerabilities and weaknesses before a malicious attacker can find and exploit them. The tester is also called a penetration tester or white-hat hacker , and the engagement is often called a penetration test (pen test). Strip away the drama and ethical hacking has three parts that must all be present:","id":1738},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"1 Authorisation","text":"The owner has given written permission and agreed exactly what may be tested (the scope ). No permission = it's just a crime.","id":1739},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"2 Same techniques","text":"Scanning, probing, password attacks, exploiting bugs — identical to what a real attacker does. The skills are neutral; intent isn't.","id":1740},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"3 Intent to protect","text":"The aim is to report what was found so it can be patched — never to steal, damage or sell. Findings go to the owner, not the dark web. You hire a locksmith to break into your own house. They jimmy the back window, pick the front lock, and hand you a list: \"your laundry window doesn't latch, your deadbolt is a cheap one.\" Same actions as a burglar — but you asked them, they told you, and now you can fix it. A burglar does the same break-in and leaves with your TV.","id":1741},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"3 Intent to protect","text":"The permission slip is the whole difference. If you only remember one thing: authorisation is what makes hacking \"ethical.\" Take the permission away and the exact same activity becomes unauthorised access — a criminal offence. Many marks are won or lost on whether you mention permission / consent / authorisation .","id":1742},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"White, grey & black hats","text":"The \"hat\" colours come from old Western films — heroes wore white, villains wore black. In security they describe a hacker's authorisation and intent , not their skill.","id":1743},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"White hat","text":"Has explicit permission and a defined scope. Finds weaknesses and reports them to the owner . This is the ethical hacker / penetration tester. Fully legal.","id":1744},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Grey hat","text":"Pokes at systems they weren't authorised to test, then tells the owner instead of exploiting. Good intentions, but still illegal — they crossed a line they had no right to cross.","id":1745},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Black hat","text":"No permission and harmful intent — steals data, deploys ransomware , sells access. The criminal attacker ethical hacking is designed to stay ahead of. A grey hat who finds a flaw and \"does the right thing\" by reporting it is still breaking the law — they had no authorisation. Don't write that grey-hat hacking is a type of ethical hacking. Only the white hat is ethical, because only the white hat was given permission first .","id":1746},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"The role: find the holes before the criminals do","text":"The study design is precise: ethical hacking's role is identifying vulnerabilities and weaknesses in networks . It is the network's fire drill — a controlled attack that exposes problems while it's still safe to fix them.","id":1747},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Proactive, not reactive","text":"Most security is reactive — you patch the hole after the breach, once data is already gone and the news has the story. Ethical hacking flips this: it's proactive . You discover the weakness on your terms, in a controlled test, before a real attacker stumbles onto it. Reactive defence Ethical hacking (proactive) When you learn of the hole After the breach Before any attacker Who finds it A criminal (or a customer) A hired professional you trust Cost of the lesson Stolen data, fines, lost trust A test fee and a to-do list You control the timing Yes","id":1748},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"What a pen test actually checks","text":"A good engagement doesn't just rattle the firewall . It probes the whole network for weaknesses across technology, configuration and people :","id":1749},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Unpatched software","text":"Old versions of an operating system, server or app with known, published holes attackers already have tools for.","id":1750},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Misconfigurations","text":"A firewall port left open, default settings never changed, a database reachable from the internet by mistake.","id":1751},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Weak credentials","text":"Guessable, reused or never-changed passwords; missing multi-factor authentication on staff accounts.","id":1752},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Human weakness","text":"Whether staff fall for a phishing email or hand over access — often tested with the owner's consent too. If Clutch launches \"Test-Ready Mode\" and a black hat finds an open database port first, 40,000 teenagers' licence photos end up for sale and the Privacy Act's Notifiable Data Breaches scheme kicks in. If a white hat finds the same open port two weeks earlier, it's a one-line fix and a quiet launch. Same hole — wildly different week. A school doesn't wait for a real fire to discover the back exit is chained shut.","id":1753},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Human weakness","text":"It runs a drill — a controlled, fake emergency — to find the blocked door while everyone's safe . A pen test is a fire drill for the network: a fake attack that reveals the real problems before they matter.","id":1754},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"The White-Hat Lab","text":"Here is Clutch's network. Run the same intrusion two ways. As a white hat (authorised) you stay inside the scope, find the holes and the team patches them. As a black hat (no permission) the identical attack ends with data walking out the door. Watch what changes — and what doesn't. The packet path, the discovered holes and the techniques are identical in both modes. Only two things differ: whether there's a scope boundary the tester respects, and whether the ending is \"patched\" or \"breached.\" That's the whole lesson of this dot point in one animation.","id":1755},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Inside a penetration test","text":"A pen test isn't random button-mashing. It follows recognised stages — the same ones a real attacker would, run in a disciplined order. Tap each phase to see what happens, and what it means for Clutch. \"Scope & authorise\" isn't paperwork to skip — it's the only thing standing between a legal pen test and a crime. The signed agreement (often called rules of engagement ) states exactly which systems can be tested, when, and how far. Step outside the scope and the white hat instantly becomes a black hat in the eyes of the law.","id":1756},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Authorised — or a crime?","text":"In Australia, accessing a computer system without permission is an offence (under the Commonwealth Criminal Code / cybercrime law). The exact same keystrokes are either a paid professional service or a criminal act — and the only thing that decides it is authorisation . The test that decides everything: did the owner give prior, written permission , and did the tester stay within the agreed scope ? If yes to both → ethical hacking. If no to either → unauthorised access, a crime — no matter how good the intentions were.","id":1757},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Bug bounties — ethical hacking, crowdsourced","text":"Big companies (and a few brave start-ups like Clutch) run bug bounty programs : a public invitation that says \"here are the rules — find a flaw within them and we'll pay you.\" That published invitation is the authorisation. It turns thousands of would-be grey hats into legal white hats, because everyone is now testing with permission .","id":1758},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"What ethical hacking can't do","text":"A strong answer doesn't treat pen testing as magic. To reach the top band you have to show you understand its limitations as well as its value — that's what \"evaluate\" questions are fishing for.","id":1759},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"It's a snapshot","text":"A pen test shows weaknesses on the day it ran . New code, new staff or a new bug next month can reopen the door. Security has to be ongoing.","id":1760},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"It finds — it doesn't fix","text":"The tester hands over a report. If the organisation never acts on it ( remediation ), nothing is safer. The list alone protects no one.","id":1761},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Only as good as the scope","text":"A narrow scope can miss the very system that gets breached. Anything ruled \"out of scope\" simply isn't checked.","id":1762},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"It runs on trust","text":"You're handing a skilled hacker the keys. A poor or dishonest tester is a serious risk — reputable, vetted professionals matter.","id":1763},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"It can disrupt","text":"Aggressive testing can crash live services or corrupt data, which is exactly why scope and timing are agreed in advance.","id":1764},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Not a silver bullet","text":"It's one layer. It works alongside firewalls , MFA, patching, backups and staff training — never instead of them. Clutch's pen test finds four holes and the team patches three before launch — but skips \"low priority\" #4 to save time. Six weeks later that exact flaw is exploited. The test did its job: it found the hole. The breach happened because Clutch didn't finish the remediation . Finding isn't fixing.","id":1765},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Named exam traps","text":"These are the specific mistakes that quietly cost students marks on this dot point. Learn the trap, dodge the loss. Writing that all hacking is illegal. Ethical hacking is legal and valuable . Define it by authorisation and intent , not by the word \"hack.\" Describing what a pen tester does without saying it's authorised . Without that word, you've described a criminal. Always state consent/permission/scope. Ethical hacking identifies vulnerabilities — it doesn't repair them. The organisation must then act (remediation). Match the study design's verb: identify . Calling grey-hat hacking ethical.","id":1766},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Named exam traps","text":"Reporting a flaw doesn't undo accessing a system you had no right to. Only the white hat is ethical. Treating a single pen test as permanent protection. It's a snapshot in time ; networks change, so testing must be repeated. \"Evaluate\" answers need both sides — concrete strengths (proactive, controlled, finds real holes) and limits (snapshot, doesn't fix, scope-bound) — then a judgement.","id":1767},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Writing trainer","text":"VCE marks reward structure. Decode the command word first, then use P·E·L — Point , Explain , Link — to make sure every answer earns its marks.","id":1768},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Command-word decoder","text":"Tap a command word to see what the examiner actually wants. The word sets the depth — and the marks.","id":1769},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Five questions, 20 marks total, building from Define to Evaluate . Try each on paper first. Then reveal a weak answer, a strong answer and the marking guide — and self-mark into the score dock. \"Ethical hacking is when someone hacks into a computer to test it and find problems.\" Why it loses marks: no mention of authorisation/permission (the defining feature) and no mention of the purpose (identifying vulnerabilities). It describes any hacker. \"Ethical hacking is the authorised , legal attempt to penetrate a network or system on behalf of its owner, in order to identify vulnerabilities and weaknesses so they can be fixed before a malicious attacker exploits them.\" A definition missing the word \"authorised\" caps at 1 mark, however well-written.","id":1770},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"\"Because they are a grey hat, not a white hat. Grey hats are in between so it's not really ethical.\" Why it loses marks: circular — it labels the hat instead of explaining . No reference to authorisation, and no link to the act being illegal. \"Ethical hacking requires the owner's prior authorisation and an agreed scope. The grey hat accessed Clutch's system without permission , which means the access itself was unauthorised — a criminal offence — regardless of their good intent. Warning Clutch afterwards is responsible, but it doesn't retrospectively make the access legal, so it can't be classed as ethical hacking.\" \"Ethical hackers would hack Clutch and find the problems and then Clutch would be safe.","id":1771},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"This is good because hackers can't get in anymore.\" Why it loses marks: no detail on how (no scanning, no specific weaknesses), overstates the outcome (\"safe\", \"can't get in\"), and ignores that Clutch must still fix what's found. \"With Clutch's written permission and an agreed scope, a penetration tester would use the same techniques as a real attacker — scanning the network and probing the web server, app server, database and staff laptops — to find weaknesses proactively . They might uncover an open firewall port, unpatched server software, or a weak staff password.","id":1772},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Because this happens before launch and in a controlled way , the tester reports each vulnerability to Clutch, who can then patch them — closing the holes on their own terms rather than after a real breach exposes 40,000 users' data.\" \"They should do ethical hacking because it's better than a firewall and finds hackers. A firewall only blocks some things. Ethical hacking is more modern so Clutch should use it.\" Why it loses marks: asserts \"better\" without reasons or evidence, misunderstands a firewall, and never explains the unique value (proactive testing of real weaknesses).","id":1773},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"No genuine justification. \"A firewall and other tools are defensive — they try to block attacks, but you can't be sure they're configured correctly or that they cover every gap. An ethical hacking engagement is proactive and tests the whole system the way a real attacker would , including the firewall itself, the servers, weak passwords and even staff behaviour — revealing weaknesses the tools quietly miss, such as a port the firewall was never set to block.\" \"Critically, it finds these before a criminal does, in a controlled test Clutch can schedule, so Clutch fixes problems on its own terms rather than after a breach triggers Notifiable Data Breach obligations.","id":1774},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"This is why ethical hacking should be used alongside defensive tools, not instead of them: the firewall blocks, and the pen test verifies that the blocking — and everything else — actually works.\" \"Ethical hacking is really good for Clutch. It finds all the vulnerabilities and stops hackers and keeps the data safe. Clutch should definitely do it because it's the best way to be secure. Overall it's very effective.\" Why it loses marks: one-sided cheerleading. No limitations, overstated claims (\"finds all\", \"stops hackers\"), and the \"judgement\" isn't supported by weighing both sides.","id":1775},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"Strengths: \"Ethical hacking is a powerful proactive strategy. Because an authorised tester attacks Clutch's network the way a real criminal would, it exposes genuine weaknesses — open ports, unpatched servers, weak staff passwords — that defensive tools alone can miss, and it does so before a real attacker, in a controlled test Clutch can schedule. The findings let Clutch close holes ahead of launch and avoid a breach of 40,000 users' data.\" Limitations: \"However, a pen test is only a snapshot in time — new code or staff can reopen risks, so it must be repeated.","id":1776},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"VCE-style exam questions","text":"It only identifies weaknesses; Clutch still has to act on the report (remediation), and anything left out of scope isn't tested. It also requires trusting a skilled outsider with access.\" Judgement: \"On balance, ethical hacking is highly valuable for Clutch provided it is one ongoing layer of a wider strategy — combined with firewalls, MFA, patching and staff training, and acted upon — rather than treated as a one-off guarantee of security.\" Full marks need BOTH sides AND a judgement. A one-sided answer caps around 3/6 no matter how long.","id":1777},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Definition","text":"Authorised , legal attempt to penetrate a network On behalf of the owner , within an agreed scope Aka white hat / penetration tester","id":1778},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"The role","text":"Identify vulnerabilities & weaknesses Proactive — before attackers find them Checks software, config, passwords & people","id":1779},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"The hats","text":"White = authorised + reports = ethical Grey = no permission + reports = still illegal Black = no permission + malicious = criminal","id":1780},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"The 5 phases","text":"1 Scope & authorise (the legal step) 2 Recon · 3 Scan · 4 Exploit 5 Report & remediate","id":1781},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Limitations","text":"Snapshot in time — repeat it Finds, doesn't fix — needs remediation Scope-limited · relies on trust · one layer only","id":1782},{"file":"u2o2-kk12.html","nav":"u2o2-kk12.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK12","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Ethical hacking Breaking in — with permission — so the criminals can't.","head":"Exam gold","text":"Always say authorised / permission Use the verb identify , not \"fix\" Evaluate = strengths + limits + judgement","id":1783},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Legislation & Frameworks","text":"The laws every Australian network must obey, and the frameworks that turn \"be secure\" into a real to-do list. We map all five — through the eyes of a Melbourne learner-driver app called Clutch .","id":1784},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Why a network has to obey the law","text":"In KK06–KK12 you learned how attacks happen and how to stop them. KK13 asks a different question: who says you have to? The answer is the law — plus the frameworks that show you exactly how. Clutch is a Melbourne start-up app that helps learner drivers log their 120 hours, book lessons, and track progress. It has grown to about 40,000 users aged 16–25 across Victoria. To do its job, Clutch stores: names, dates of birth, learner-permit numbers, GPS logs of every practice drive, payment details — and, for some users, a medical fitness-to-drive declaration (epilepsy, vision, etc.).","id":1785},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Why a network has to obey the law","text":"That single mix of data is enough to pull Clutch under three different privacy laws at once. This module shows you why. Think of it like the road rules Clutch's own users have to follow. A learner doesn't get to invent their own speed limit — it's set by law, and breaking it has consequences. Networks are the same. If Clutch leaks 40,000 teenagers' data, \"we didn't realise\" is not a defence. The Notifiable Data Breaches (NDB) scheme can compel them to tell every affected user and the regulator, and the regulator can investigate and fine.","id":1786},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Why a network has to obey the law","text":"Laws (Privacy Act, PDP Act, Health Records Act) are like the road rules: mandatory, enforceable, and you can be penalised for breaking them. They tell you what you must achieve. Frameworks (Essential Eight, ISM) are like the structured lessons a learner takes: not a law in themselves, but the practical, step-by-step way to actually become a safe driver. They tell you how to get there.","id":1787},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Laws vs frameworks — the distinction examiners love","text":"A surprising number of marks are lost because students call the Essential Eight \"a law\" or the Privacy Act \"a guideline\". They are fundamentally different, and KK13 lists both deliberately. Legislation (laws) Frameworks (guidance) In KK13 Privacy Act 1988 · PDP Act 2014 · Health Records Act 2001 Essential Eight · ISM Made by Parliament (Commonwealth or Victorian) The Australian Signals Directorate (ASD / ACSC) Status Legally binding — you must comply Best-practice advice — strongly recommended, mandated only for some agencies Tells you What outcomes to achieve (e.g. \"keep data secure\") How to achieve it (specific technical controls) If you breach Investigation, enforceable undertakings, fines, court No direct penalty, but you've likely also breached a law's security duty The laws say \"protect the data\" but don't spell out the technical steps.","id":1788},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Laws vs frameworks — the distinction examiners love","text":"The Essential Eight and ISM are those steps. So following a framework is one of the clearest ways to prove you met a law's security obligation (APP 11). They're two halves of the same answer.","id":1789},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) — the Australian Privacy Principles","text":"The big federal one. It runs the 13 Australian Privacy Principles (APPs) and applies right across Australia to most private businesses (with turnover over $3M) and Australian Government agencies. Because Clutch is a private company operating nationally , the Privacy Act is its baseline. The 13 APPs cover the whole life-cycle of personal information — from collecting it openly, to using it only for the purpose you collected it for, to securing it, to letting people see and correct their own data.","id":1790},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Tell people what you do","text":"A plain-English privacy policy in the app's sign-up flow, not buried in legalese. Says GPS logs are kept and why (lesson verification).","id":1791},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Stick to the purpose","text":"GPS logs collected to verify driving hours cannot be sold to an insurer. That would be using data outside its primary purpose .","id":1792},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Offshore ≠ off the hook","text":"Clutch backs up to a US cloud region — APP 8 still binds Clutch. It must take reasonable steps to ensure the US provider protects the data.","id":1793},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Keep it safe","text":"This is where the Essential Eight & ISM plug in — they're how Clutch meets APP 11. Encryption , MFA, patching, backups = \"reasonable steps\". Bolted onto the Privacy Act, the Notifiable Data Breaches (NDB) scheme means that if Clutch suffers a breach likely to cause serious harm , it must notify both the affected users and the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC) as soon as practicable. Hiding a breach is itself a breach. This is the single most exam-relevant consequence of the Act.","id":1794},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Privacy and Data Protection Act 2014 (Vic) — the IPPs","text":"Victoria's own privacy law. It runs the 10 Information Privacy Principles (IPPs) and applies to the Victorian public sector — state government departments, councils, Victoria Police, public schools, and the contractors who handle their data. So when does a private app like Clutch touch the PDP Act? The moment it works for a Victorian government body . Imagine the Department of Transport hires Clutch to run an official \"Learner Hours\" verification service. Clutch is now handling personal information on behalf of a Victorian public-sector agency — so the IPPs apply to that data, on top of the Privacy Act for everything else.","id":1795},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Privacy and Data Protection Act 2014 (Vic) — the IPPs","text":"The IPPs are deliberately very similar to the APPs (collection, use, security, access). Think of them as the state-level version of the same idea — like how you can hold a national passport and a Victorian driver's licence. Different issuer, overlapping coverage, both valid at once. The key difference is who they cover: APPs = private sector & federal; IPPs = Victorian public sector. Being based in Melbourne does not automatically put a private business under the PDP Act. A private company is governed by the federal Privacy Act . The PDP Act only reaches it through a public-sector relationship (a government contract). State the trigger, don't assume geography.","id":1796},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Health Records Act 2001 (Vic) — the HPPs","text":"Health information is the most sensitive personal data there is, so Victoria gives it its own law: the 11 Health Privacy Principles (HPPs) . This Act covers health information held by both the public and the private sector in Victoria. Remember Clutch's fitness-to-drive medical declarations (epilepsy, vision conditions, medications affecting driving)? That is health information. The instant Clutch stores it, the Health Records Act switches on — regardless of whether Clutch has any government contract at all. This is why the same app can sit under three laws at once.","id":1797},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Health Records Act 2001 (Vic) — the HPPs","text":"A general user with no medical info → governed mainly by the Privacy Act (APPs) . A user who declares epilepsy for fitness-to-drive → that health record is also governed by the Health Records Act (HPPs) . If the Dept of Transport contracts Clutch to verify hours → that slice of data also falls under the PDP Act (IPPs) . One app, three regimes, depending on the data and the relationship. Health information isn't only what a hospital holds. A fitness app, a gym, an employer's first-aid log, or a learner-driver app collecting a medical declaration all hold health information. The HPPs follow the data , not the building.","id":1798},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"The three privacy regimes, side by side","text":"Examiners frequently ask you to compare or distinguish these three. The differences live in just three columns: jurisdiction, who it covers, and its principle set. Privacy Act 1988 PDP Act 2014 Health Records Act 2001 Jurisdiction Commonwealth (national) Victoria (state) Victoria (state) Principle set 13 APPs 10 IPPs 11 HPPs Applies to Private sector (>$3M) & federal agencies Victorian public sector & their contractors Anyone holding health info in Vic (public or private) Data covered Personal information generally Personal information held by Vic gov Health information specifically Regulator OAIC (federal) OVIC (Vic) Health Complaints Commissioner (Vic) Clutch link Its everyday baseline Only via a Dept of Transport contract The moment it stores a medical declaration A PP = A ll of Australia (federal). I PP = I nside Victorian government. H PP = H ealth, anywhere in Victoria. Three letters, three triggers.","id":1799},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Which law applies? — the Compliance Map","text":"This is the skill the exam tests: given a scenario, name the law(s) that apply and justify why . Flip the switches to change what data Clutch handles and who it works for. Watch the shields light up — and read the verdict that explains each one.","id":1800},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Clutch Compliance Map","text":"Scenarios are designed to overlap. If the data includes a health record and there's a government contract, you must name all applicable laws and justify each. \"The Privacy Act applies\" alone would forfeit the marks for the HPPs and IPPs.","id":1801},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"The Essential Eight — turning \"be secure\" into eight jobs","text":"Published by the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD) , the Essential Eight is a set of eight baseline mitigation strategies. It's not a law, but it's the most practical answer to the security duty in APP 11 / HPP 4 / IPP 4. Each strategy has a maturity level (0–3) — raise Clutch's maturity and watch its resilience climb.","id":1802},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Clutch's Essential Eight maturity","text":"Maturity Level 0 is a fresh learner who's never driven. ML1 is supervised L-plates. ML2 is solo P-plates. ML3 is a confident, experienced driver. The Essential Eight gives Clutch the same staged pathway — you don't jump to perfect overnight; you mature each control step by step. Students often name only MFA, backups and patching. The full eight also includes application control , patching operating systems , restricting admin privileges , configuring macro settings , and user application hardening . If a question says \"describe Essential Eight strategies (4 marks)\", you need four distinct ones.","id":1803},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"The ISM — the deep networking rulebook","text":"The Information Security Manual (ISM) , also from the ASD, is a far more detailed cyber-security framework. KK13 specifically points you at its networking guidelines — how to design, segment and harden a network. If the Essential Eight is the \"eight big habits\", the ISM is the full driving handbook — hundreds of specific controls covering network segmentation, gateways, cryptography standards, logging and monitoring. It's primarily mandatory for federal government systems, but private organisations like Clutch use it as a gold-standard reference, especially the parts on isolating sensitive systems. Essential Eight — short, prioritised, \"do these eight first\".","id":1804},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"The ISM — the deep networking rulebook","text":"A great starting baseline. ISM — comprehensive, granular, the complete reference. Its networking guidelines tell Clutch how to segment its learner database away from its public web servers so one breach can't reach everything. Following ISM networking guidance, Clutch puts its 40,000 user records on an isolated, segmented subnet behind a firewall , separate from the public-facing booking website. If an attacker compromises the website, network segmentation stops them reaching the sensitive database — exactly the \"defence in depth\" the ISM is built around.","id":1805},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"Exam technique for legislation questions","text":"These questions reward precision: the exact name of the law, the exact principle, and a clear link to the scenario. Tap a command word to see what the examiner actually wants. N ame the law and its principle set (e.g. \"Privacy Act 1988 — APP 11\"). A nchor it to the scenario data (e.g. \"because Clutch stores 40,000 users' personal information\"). J ustify the link (e.g. \"so it must take reasonable steps to secure that data\"). Name → Anchor → Justify wins full marks.","id":1806},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"Five exam-style questions, 20 marks total. Try each one before revealing the responses. Compare the weak and strong answers, read the marking guide, then self-mark — your score feeds the dock in the corner. Legislation and frameworks are both about cyber security and keeping data safe. The Essential Eight is a law that organisations have to follow to be secure. Legislation (e.g. the Privacy Act 1988) is made by Parliament and is legally binding — it sets out what outcomes an organisation must achieve and can be enforced with penalties.","id":1807},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"A framework such as the Essential Eight is guidance issued by the ASD that recommends how to achieve security; it is best practice rather than law and carries no direct penalty of its own. 1 mark: legislation is mandatory/legally binding ('what') 1 mark: framework is recommended guidance/best practice ('how') Full marks need the contrast made explicit, not two separate definitions The Privacy and Data Protection Act applies because Clutch is in Victoria. Also the Privacy Act applies because they store personal data like names. Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) applies because Clutch is a national private business collecting personal information (names, DOB, permit numbers, GPS logs) from 40,000 users, so it must comply with the 13 APPs.","id":1808},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"Health Records Act 2001 (Vic) also applies because the fitness-to-drive medical declarations are health information held in Victoria, which is governed by the Health Privacy Principles. Each law is triggered by a different category of data Clutch holds. 1 mark each: correctly name Privacy Act 1988 and Health Records Act 2001 1 mark each: justify with the matching data type (personal info → APPs; health info → HPPs) No credit for PDP Act here — there is no government contract in this scenario Clutch has to tell people there was a hack so they can change their passwords.","id":1809},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"They might get in trouble for it. The NDB scheme operates under the Privacy Act 1988 and applies to data breaches likely to result in serious harm to the individuals affected. Because the exposed records contain sensitive personal (and health) data, this threshold is met. Clutch must, as soon as practicable , notify both the affected users and the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner (OAIC), describing the breach, the information involved and the steps users should take. Failing to report would itself breach the Act. 1 mark: NDB sits under the Privacy Act 1988 1 mark:","id":1810},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"applies to breaches likely to cause serious harm 1 mark: must notify affected individuals 1 mark: must also notify the OAIC (regulator) as soon as practicable Clutch should use multi-factor authentication and back up their data. This makes them more secure and follows the Essential Eight. Multi-factor authentication (MFA): requiring a second factor (e.g. a phone code) means a stolen password alone can't unlock an account, directly reducing unauthorised access — exactly the 'reasonable steps' APP 11 demands. Regular backups: keeping tested, isolated backups means that if ransomware encrypts the user database, Clutch can restore the 40,000 records rather than lose them, protecting the data from loss as APP 11 requires.","id":1811},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"Both are concrete ways Clutch proves it took reasonable security steps. 1 mark each: clearly describe two DISTINCT Essential Eight strategies 1 mark each: link each to meeting APP 11's 'reasonable steps to secure data' duty Naming alone (no description or link) caps the answer at 2 marks Clutch broke the law by getting hacked and leaking health data. They should have had better security like firewalls . The Essential Eight would have stopped the hackers completely. Three regimes apply: the Privacy Act 1988 (APPs, as a private business holding personal info), the Health Records Act 2001 (HPPs, because medical declarations are health information), and the PDP Act 2014 (IPPs, because Clutch now handles data for a Victorian government agency).","id":1812},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"Under the NDB scheme Clutch must notify affected users and the OAIC, since a breach of sensitive health data clearly risks serious harm. Evaluation: the Essential Eight would have lowered the likelihood — MFA and restricting admin privileges make account compromise harder, while tested backups limit damage. The ISM's networking guidelines add deeper protection: segmenting the sensitive health database onto an isolated subnet means a breach of the public booking site need not reach the 40,000 records. However, no framework guarantees prevention — they reduce, not eliminate, risk — so Clutch's legal duties to secure data and report breaches remain regardless.","id":1813},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"VCE practice questions","text":"Up to 3 marks (Discuss): names Privacy Act, Health Records Act AND PDP Act with correct triggers, plus the NDB notification duty Up to 2 marks (Evaluate): explains how specific Essential Eight controls and ISM segmentation reduce likelihood/impact 1 mark: a balanced judgement — frameworks reduce but don't eliminate risk; legal duties stand","id":1814},{"file":"u2o2-kk13.html","nav":"u2o2-kk13.html","kind":"kk","code":"KK13","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Legislation & Frameworks","head":"🗂️ KK13 in one glance","text":"Federal · 13 APPs · private sector & federal gov · personal info · regulator OAIC · NDB scheme. Victorian · 10 IPPs · Vic public sector & contractors · regulator OVIC. Victorian · 11 HPPs · health info, public OR private · regulator HCC. ASD framework · 8 baseline strategies · maturity levels 0–3 · the \"how\" for security duties. ASD framework · detailed networking guidelines · segmentation, gateways, crypto · gold-standard reference. Laws = mandatory \"what\", made by Parliament. Frameworks = recommended \"how\", made by ASD. Name the law/principle → Anchor to scenario data → Justify the obligation. APP = All Australia · IPP = Inside Vic gov · HPP = Health anywhere in Vic.","id":1815},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Big picture","text":"This outcome follows one dataset all the way from collection to a finished visualisation. You decide what data you need and whether it is qualitative or quantitative, judge its quality, handle it lawfully under the Australian Privacy Principles, structure it in a database or spreadsheet, manipulate and validate it, summarise it with descriptive statistics, and finally communicate your findings through a clear, well-designed visualisation. Every key knowledge dot point is a stage in that pipeline — so understanding how the stages connect matters as much as knowing each one.","id":1816},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"How it's assessed","text":"School-assessed for Units 1&2, but the skills are examined the same way VCAA examines them in Unit 3&4: precise definitions, correct use of terminology, and applying a concept to the specific scenario in front of you. Expect to be asked to classify data, name and apply a specific Australian Privacy Principle, design a database/spreadsheet structure, choose and justify a validation technique, calculate or interpret a descriptive statistic, and evaluate a visualisation against its purpose and audience. Marks are lost by being vague, naming the wrong principle, or answering in general terms instead of about the scenario.","id":1817},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Qualitative data: Data describing qualities or categories (e.g. opinions, colours) that cannot be meaningfully averaged.","id":1818},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Quantitative data: Numeric data that can be measured and calculated with (e.g. counts, times, scores).","id":1819},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Data integrity: The accuracy, completeness and consistency of data over its whole life cycle.","id":1820},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Australian Privacy Principles (APPs): The 13 principles in the Privacy Act 1988 (Cwlth) governing how personal information is handled.","id":1821},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Primary key: A field (or combination) that uniquely identifies each record in a table.","id":1822},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Foreign key: A field in one table that refers to the primary key of another, forming a relationship.","id":1823},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Validation: Checking that entered data is reasonable and complete (existence, type, range).","id":1824},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Standard deviation: A measure of how spread out values are around the mean.","id":1825},{"file":"ch:u1o1","nav":"u1o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O1","chapter":"Data Analysis","title":"Data Analysis","head":"Glossary","text":"Data visualisation: A graphical representation of data designed to inform, educate, persuade or entertain an audience.","id":1826},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Big picture","text":"This outcome is the full build of a small object-oriented program. You read the requirements, constraints and scope; design with mock-ups, IPO charts and pseudocode; then develop using the language's features — data types, data structures, control structures, and the OOP principles of abstraction and encapsulation. Good practice runs through all of it: meaningful naming conventions, internal documentation, validation, and disciplined debugging and testing. The dot points map onto the problem-solving methodology: analysis, design, development and evaluation.","id":1827},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"How it's assessed","text":"You are assessed on precise programming vocabulary and on reasoning about code, not just writing it. Expect to define data types and structures, trace or complete pseudocode using sequence/selection/iteration, explain abstraction vs encapsulation, justify naming conventions, write or complete a test table with expected vs actual results, and choose validation techniques. Vague answers (\"it makes the code better\") score poorly; tie every point to what the code actually does.","id":1828},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Abstraction: Hiding complexity by exposing only the essential features of an object.","id":1829},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Encapsulation: Bundling data and methods together and restricting direct access to the data.","id":1830},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Data structure: An organised store of related values, e.g. a one-dimensional array, list or record.","id":1831},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Control structure: The flow of a program: sequence, selection (if) and iteration (loops).","id":1832},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Camel case: Naming convention: first word lowercase, each later word capitalised (e.g. totalScore).","id":1833},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Hungarian notation: Naming convention using a type prefix (e.g. strName, intCount).","id":1834},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Internal documentation: Comments and naming inside the code that explain its structure and logic.","id":1835},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Validation: Existence, type and range checking of input before it is used.","id":1836},{"file":"ch:u1o2","nav":"u1o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U1·O2","chapter":"Programming","title":"Programming","head":"Glossary","text":"Test table: A table of test cases listing input, expected output and actual output.","id":1837},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Big picture","text":"This is a team, design-thinking outcome. You start from a driver of innovation — curiosity, ingenuity or a UN Sustainable Development Goal — examine what digital systems can do and how emerging technologies affect people, then run a full design process: collect user needs, ideate, design with mock-ups/storyboards/pseudocode, develop, document progress with Gantt charts and version control, and test and evaluate. Threaded through it is the law and ethics of emerging technology and AI. The emphasis is on collaboration, user-centred design and honest evaluation.","id":1838},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"How it's assessed","text":"Expect scenario questions about what makes a solution innovative, choosing user-need collection methods and justifying them against constraints, naming the right legislation or AI Ethics Principle for a situation, and evaluating a solution's efficiency and effectiveness against criteria. Project-management items (Gantt charts, version control, journals) and ethics items are common. Generic \"it helps people\" answers score poorly — name the method, the law or the criterion.","id":1839},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Innovation: A solution that is original, effective and often disruptive — new value, not just newness.","id":1840},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"User-centred design: Designing around real user needs gathered and tested throughout the process.","id":1841},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Sustainable Development Goals: UN goals that can inspire and drive innovative digital solutions.","id":1842},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Gantt chart: A timeline chart for planning tasks, durations and dependencies in a project.","id":1843},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Version control: Tracking and managing changes to a solution so work can be coordinated and recovered.","id":1844},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"User testing: Having intended users trial a solution to evaluate it.","id":1845},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"AI Ethics Principles: Australia's voluntary principles guiding responsible AI design and use.","id":1846},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Efficiency: How economically a solution uses resources such as time, cost and effort.","id":1847},{"file":"ch:u2o1","nav":"u2o1","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O1","chapter":"Innovative Solutions","title":"Innovative Solutions","head":"Glossary","text":"Effectiveness: How well a solution meets its requirements and the user's need.","id":1848},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Big picture","text":"This outcome is built around a case study. You first understand the network — its hardware and software, the types of network (wired, wireless, mobile; LAN, WAN, WPAN; intranet, internet, VPN) — then analyse the threats (malware, denial-of-service, weak credentials, outdated software) and the risks of operating on global networks. From there you propose protections: multi-factor authentication, backups, updates, staff procedures, cryptography and frameworks such as the Essential Eight. AI's role in detection and the place of ethical hacking and legislation round it out.","id":1849},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"How it's assessed","text":"Case-study analysis is the core skill: read the scenario, identify the specific threat or vulnerability, and propose a protection that actually addresses it. Expect to distinguish malware types, explain how a threat works, recommend and justify risk-reduction measures, explain cryptography (symmetric vs asymmetric, a named cipher), and name relevant legislation or the Essential Eight. Listing generic \"use antivirus\" advice without matching it to the scenario's threat loses marks.","id":1850},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Malware: Malicious software, including viruses, worms, spyware and ransomware.","id":1851},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Ransomware: Malware that encrypts files and demands payment for their release.","id":1852},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Denial-of-service (DoS): An attack that floods a system to make it unavailable to legitimate users.","id":1853},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Multi-factor authentication: Verifying identity with two or more independent factors.","id":1854},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Firewall: Hardware/software that filters network traffic against security rules.","id":1855},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Symmetric encryption: Encryption using one shared key to both encrypt and decrypt (e.g. AES).","id":1856},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Asymmetric encryption: Encryption using a public/private key pair (e.g. RSA, ECDH).","id":1857},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"VPN: A virtual private network providing a secure, encrypted connection over a public network.","id":1858},{"file":"ch:u2o2","nav":"u2o2","kind":"chapter","code":"U2·O2","chapter":"Cyber Security","title":"Cyber Security","head":"Glossary","text":"Essential Eight: A baseline set of mitigation strategies for reducing cyber security risk.","id":1859}];